{"_id":"nfYrCR2c1b1EZ6ng","name":"bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed","pages":[{"_id":"tjQait7p1xDeqtHL","name":"PDF local","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h1>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed</h1><p><strong>Archivo:</strong> bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed [2022-07-01].pdf</p><p><strong>Paginas:</strong> 268</p><p><a href=\"systems/broken-tales/assets/source-pdfs/bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed-2022-07-01.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Abrir PDF dentro de Foundry</a></p>","markdown":""},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241710,"modifiedTime":1783973241710,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"tSiV3vfEjjmnXkRb","name":"Pagina 1","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 1</h2><p><em>Page has no extractable text. Use the local PDF linked on the first Journal page.</em></p>","markdown":""},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241710,"modifiedTime":1783973241710,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"5uqtfrtqUqGsrFu8","name":"Pagina 2","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 2</h2><p>Game Design and Texts: Alberto Tronchi<br>Editing: Natascia Cortesi, Alberto Tronchi, Sean Newton, <br>Tommaso De Benetti, Luca Vanin<br>Translations: Tommaso De Benetti, Y oann Stordeur<br>Graphic, Illustrations, and Map: Daniel Comerci<br>Layout: Daniel Comerci<br>Crowdfunding Manager: Tommaso De Benetti<br>Music: Jane Toikka<br>History Consultant: Stefano Maioli<br>Guest Material for the Kickstarter:  Petter Nallo, <br>Tommaso De Benetti, Chris van der Linden and Chris <br>“Mono” Mahon, Peter Chiykowski, Claudio Serena, Guido <br>Campanini, Francesco Panitti.<br>Playtest and Thanks:  Tommaso De Benetti, Luca <br>Vanin, Daniel Comerci, Giacomo Jack Gordesco, Federico <br>Scattolin, Enrico Ronconi, Fabiana Gasperini, Alberto <br>Lolli, Gianpaolo Benedetti, Attilio Bravi, Fabio Bianchetti, <br>Matteo Mazzoli, Valerio Votadoro, Giorgio Catenacci, <br>Rikch, Fabrizio Infusino, Jane Toikka, Stefano Maioli, <br>Elvis Lupo, Matteo Petrangeli, Gabriele Tacito, Alessandro <br>Prometeo Di Pastena, Marco D’ Ascenzo, Fumble GDR, <br>Tebra Hansing, Y oann Stordeur, Sean Newton, Annalisa <br>Zaniboni, Nix, Eric Verspoor, Jerry Boucher, Ciro Lamberti.<br>Alberto Tronchi Copyright (c) 2022<br>Broken Tales is a work of fiction. Names, characters, locations, <br>and incidents either are products of the author’s imagination <br>or are used fictitiously. Any resemblance to actual events or <br>locales or persons, living or dead, is entirely coincidental.<br>The work, including all its parts, is protected by copyright <br>law. Unless expressly authorized, reproductions are forbidden <br>in any way or form, including photocopying, scanning, and <br>electronic storage. Any violation will be prosecuted to the full <br>extent of the copyright law.<br>Web: theworldanvil.com<br>Discord: bit.ly/discord-twa<br>Facebook: facebook.com/theworldanvil<br>Twitter: twitter.com/theworldanvil<br>Printed in the month of July 2022 in Türkiye at KÜLTÜR SANAT<br>Printing House.<br>Broken Tales Core Book HARDCOVER ENG ISBN: 979-12-80387-04-2<br>Broken Tales Core Book PDF ENG ISBN: 979-12-80387-02-8</p>","markdown":""},"sort":200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"aO8YxQUgytKZOMgC","name":"Pagina 3","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 3</h2><p>“Fairy tales are <br>more than true – <br>not because they <br>tell us dragons <br>exist, but because <br>they tell us <br>dragons can be <br>beaten.” G. K. Chesterton<br>TABLE OF CONTENTS<br>3 The Fairytale of the Child Saviour<br>6 Introduction<br>10 Rules For Hunters<br>12 Rules for the Storyteller<br>17 Further Details on Game Rules<br>35 The Storyteller’s Role<br>41 Dark Presences<br>69 The Hunter’s Creation<br>89 Scenarios<br>91 Scenario Creation<br>103 Broken Europe<br>113 Spoiler<br>114 The Fairytale Of The Child Savior Reprise<br>117 Scenarios<br>118 Red-hood<br>118 Iskra<br>130 Of Flesh and Wood<br>144 The Smile in the Darkness<br>156 A Soldier’s Duty<br>168 Wonderbedlam<br>182  Tuvstarr’s Reflection<br>196 One Thousand and One Nightmares<br>202 The City of Pigs<br>216 Saint George the Dragon Slayer<br>222  OZena the Suffering and Desperate<br>243 Playing a Broken Tales Campaign<br>261 Hunter’s Sheet<br>262 Bookmark<br>263 Scenario Summary Sheet<br>265 Map<br>266 Backers</p>","markdown":""},"sort":300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"RKrXMjJajg7kIgOr","name":"Pagina 4","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 4</h2><p>3<br>The Fairytale of <br>the Child Saviour<br>Once upon a time... the world of fairytales was on the verge of ending, forsaken by <br>children who grew up too fast and forgot the value of old stories. Within the void left by <br>failing stories, darkness and oblivion blossomed. All the inhabitants of fairytales wept with <br>fear at the long-dreaded end.<br>“ All it would take is one last reader. One single young heart willing to believe in us still, ” <br>sighed the weary Fairytale King.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"t95HfdkNqNNDWH1Y","name":"Pagina 5","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 5</h2><p>4<br>But there was a Child who still believed in fairytales. Alone and abandoned by everyone, the <br>Child found shelter in those old stories. Within was protection from the world outside, too real <br>and too cruel. Lost among myths and tales, he forgot the pain of a family unable to give him the <br>childhood he deserved. “I love all fairytales full of heroes and villains to defeat, ” said the Child. <br>“Why doesn’t anyone write new fairytales? If only I knew how, I would do it, ” the little dreamer <br>kept repeating. <br>The Fairytale King noticed the little dreamer, for if even a single reader <br>was ready to believe in fairytales, the whole world would continue to do so. <br>Thus the Child became the Saviour. From his dreams, fairytales drew new life. <br>As a reward, the Fairytale King granted the Child Saviour a wish.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"g2DxgFi0u3QTVpqq","name":"Pagina 6","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 6</h2><p>5<br>“Thanks to you we are remembered. I <br>trust you will find in your heart the <br>proper reward to ask for. ”<br>For a long time, the Child <br>searched his heart for the most <br>beautiful wish he could think <br>of. However, hidden in his <br>heart’s innermost corner, <br>he found his own shadow. <br>The One Who Plots in <br>the Shadows emerged <br>from the future, <br>driven by rejection, <br>But every light needs its shadow.<br>So it was that the villains became good, the heroes became evil.<br>And all fairytales shattered.<br>whispering in the Child Saviour’s <br>mind a malicious intention. The <br>Child Saviour truly believed <br>that it was a good idea. <br>Innocent, he said, “I would give <br>new life to the rogues, a chance at <br>redemption for every character <br>who has been relegated to the <br>role of villain for centuries. ”</p>","markdown":""},"sort":600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"RgV8wfAuXDE9mckg","name":"Pagina 7","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 7</h2><p>6<br>Introduction<br> <br>Broken Tales tells dark stories, reinterpreting <br>fairytales from an upside-down perspective. Players will <br>become part of the Order, a secret group operating on <br>behalf of the Papacy to investigate supernatural events <br>beyond human comprehension. Moving through an 18th <br>century Europe imbued with mysticism and horror, the <br>main characters of Broken Tales are nothing less than the <br>former antagonists of fairytales, thrown into a new world <br>resulting from the wish of the Child Savior.<br>The Game System<br>Broken Tales uses a role-playing rule system called Monad <br>Echo. The system aims to be fast, encourage storytelling, <br>and avoid pauses while playing. All this, while allowing <br>Players a great degree of freedom. <br>This rulebook is based on the Monad System, a universal <br>role-playing system created by The World Anvil collective. <br>Monad Echo is not a lite version of the Monad System, but <br>rather a totally new system that shares terminology and <br>action resolution mechanics with the original system while <br>focusing on a more narrative and cinematic style. <br>Already two other games featuring Monad Echo have <br>been published in Italian: Evolution Pulse Rebirth and  <br>Valraven: The Chronicles of Blood and Iron. If you like the <br>mechanics and dynamics showcased in this manual, know <br>that you will find them in these games as well, adapted to <br>the narrative and gameplay features of each setting. <br>From now on we will refer to Monad Echo as “the Broken <br>Tales system” or more simply “the system” . <br>Glossary of Game <br>Terminologies<br>Additional Successes: Further Successes to be added <br>to the Base Successes, obtained by spending Soma, rolling <br>dice or due to the effect of Gifts. <br>Agenda: Description of an NPC’s purpose and goals.<br>Base Successes:  The number of successes a Hunter <br>starts with when facing a Position or Defense check.<br>Defense Check: The game mechanic by which a Hunter <br>reacts to the actions of an NPC or a Threat, managed by the <br>Storyteller.<br>Dark Presence: NPC related to the world of fairytales <br>and reborn in their “broken” version in the world of Broken <br>Tales.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ELBb2oAzHbr2QktW","name":"Pagina 8","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 8</h2><p>7<br>Descriptor: A short sentence de-<br>scribing a salient characteristic of a <br>Hunter, NPC, or aspect of the world <br>of Broken Tales. <br>Exchange: A short time unit defin-<br>ing the order of actions for each par -<br>ticipant in a conflict situation. <br>Experience Points: Abbreviated as <br>XP, it’s the numerical value that indi-<br>cates the experience gained by a Hunt-<br>er during their adventures. <br>Failure: Indicates that a Hunter’s <br>action has failed because of an unsuc-<br>cessful Position or Defense Check.<br>Gift: A special ability of a Hunter, <br>NPC, or Threat that activates particu-<br>lar effects in the game.<br>Hunter: A classic fairytale villain re-<br>born as an agent of the Order.<br>Interlude: A specific moment <br>during a Session when Hunters catch <br>their breath, spend XP , and recover <br>Soma and Wounds.<br>Keywords: Single-themed words <br>that help Players to focus on narrative <br>details in a direct way, stimulating the <br>imagination and helping everyone in-<br>volved create interesting details on the <br>fly.<br>NPC: Acronym for Non-Player Char-<br>acter. All non-protagonist characters, <br>fantastic creatures, Dark Presences, <br>and in general any character managed <br>by the Storyteller. NPCs are divided <br>into three types: Main, Minor, and <br>Dark Presences.<br>Opposition Level: Shortened as OL, <br>it’s the difficulty value associated with <br>an NPC or Threat.<br>Outcome: Indicates a good result in a <br>Position or Defense check and can be <br>of three types: with Cost, Standard, or <br>with Increment.<br>Player: Any participant in a Session <br>of Broken Tales. One Player must take <br>the role of Storyteller, often the one <br>who has read this book in full. All the <br>other participants will play a Hunter.<br>Position Check: The game mechan-<br>ic by which a Hunter tries to succeed <br>at actions they’ve described in the <br>narrative.<br>Penalty: Value to be subtracted from <br>Base Successes, derived from NPC <br>Gifts.<br>Scene: The time unit during which a <br>Session is played.<br>Scenario: A complete Broken Tales <br>story that reinterprets and “breaks” a <br>classic fairytale.<br>Session: A single evening/afternoon <br>of play.<br>Soma: A value that quantifies the in-<br>ner strength and ability to tap into the <br>inner energies of a Hunter. Spending <br>Soma can grant automatic positive <br>Outcomes during Checks or activate <br>some Gifts.<br>Threat: A generic term for an ob-<br>stacle or complex situation that has <br>its own Descriptor and an OL, which <br>could oppose a Hunter.<br>Wounds: Represents the ability of a <br>creature (Hunter or NPC) to resist any <br>source of adversity, whether physical <br>or mental.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"F4Tl24zTvZlIGpra","name":"Pagina 9","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 9</h2><p>8<br>About Role-<br>Playing Games<br>A role-playing game is a recreational <br>activity where all participants are involved <br>in a conversation aimed at creating a <br>story. In our case, the main characters <br>are the Hunters and the world in which <br>they move is the Broken Europe of Broken <br>Tales. Imagine you are helping to write a <br>screenplay or novel, in which the plot is <br>created in real time by the players at the <br>table, each making contributions.<br>There are two well-defined roles during a <br>game:<br>Player – the one who moves and makes a <br>single Hunter act, equipped with a Sheet. <br>A Player is one of the main characters <br>of the Scenario and the narrated events <br>revolve around them. The narrative <br>authority of a Player is focused on their <br>Hunter. They will have to decide how to <br>act and react to everything the Storyteller <br>will introduce during a Session.<br>Storyteller – this is the role that most <br>closely resembles a film director. The <br>Storyteller brings the Broken Tales <br>Scenarios to life, describing locations and <br>people, as well as reacting to the Hunters’ <br>decisions. The Storyteller has a different <br>set of duties than the other Players but <br>isn’t solely responsible for how a Session <br>unfolds. Simply put, the rules provide <br>them with tools and procedures to manage <br>the conversation from an alternative point <br>of view.<br>To recap<br>The Storyteller introduces the Hunters <br>to scenes and situations from the chosen <br>Scenario. Players narrate the exploits <br>of their Hunters and how they react to <br>situations. When the conversation reaches <br>a point where the outcome is uncertain, <br>it’s time for a Position or Defense Check to <br>determine the Outcome or Failure of the <br>Hunters’ actions. The conversation then <br>resumes its flow until the next Check. <br>This pattern will help create a story in <br>which each Player at the table features <br>as a protagonist. The goals are chosen by <br>the Hunters and the themes are expressed <br>in the Scenarios by the Storyteller. When <br>combined, Players and Storytellers create <br>a unique narrative in the Broken Tales <br>style.<br>Playing materials<br>To play, you will need what we listed <br>below. Some material will need to be <br>printed or procured. Hobby and board <br>game stores might be helpful. Get:<br> ◆ Some common 6-sided dice. Each <br>Player can have their own set for <br>convenience. The Storyteller never <br>rolls dice and doesn’t need a backup. <br> ◆ One Hunter’s Sheet for each Play-<br>er, excluding the Storyteller. Plus, a</p>","markdown":""},"sort":900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"CWqu5Bz35OdE4QtD","name":"Pagina 10","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 10</h2><p>9<br>printout of a Bookmark for each Hunter.<br> ◆ Pencils and erasers to write on the Bookmarks and <br>keep track of the Hunters’ progress throughout the <br>game. <br> ◆ Markers of any kind, such as small colored stones or <br>tokens, are useful to quickly keep track of each Hunter’s <br>Tokens and Soma Points, even if not essential.<br>Reality and fiction<br>The setting of Broken Tales presents an alternative <br>Eighteenth century strongly inspired by historical Europe. <br>Grafted onto this backdrop are several very different <br>realities and fantasies, such as imaginary kingdoms and <br>supernatural creatures, that strongly differentiate Broken <br>Tales from a specific historical context. This game presents <br>not just another time, but an original world, pervaded <br>by darkness, where you can play your Broken Tales. <br>Storytellers and Hunters will be free to sketch details of <br>locations. As a general reference, it may be useful to know <br>that the year 1780 is the starting point of the Core Book <br>Scenarios’ hypothetical timeline.<br>Game Modes<br>Broken Tales is a modular game, and can adapt to the needs <br>of your playgroup. The fastest way to experience the game <br>(useful also for demos and one-shots) is to select one of <br>the ready-made Scenarios and pre-generated Hunters and <br>start playing right away. Each Scenario is designed to be <br>played dynamically. Events will move along in response <br>to the Hunters’ actions, making each Session unique. Y ou <br>won’t find a classic pre-written storyline. The Storyteller <br>can have fun, moving Events and NPCs along, reacting <br>to the Hunters’ actions, and creating an emergent plot. <br>Alternatively, each Scenario offers a Scene Tree structure, <br>allowing the discovery of the Scenario’s plot through a <br>series of linked Scenes, in a more classic, linear fashion. If <br>you or other players are new to the game, you might want <br>to try that first.<br>Of course, it’s also possible to play longer Campaigns <br>through a series of linked Scenarios. Freely moving along <br>the map, Hunters will interact with an interconnected <br>world, deciding at each turning point what to do and which <br>locations to explore.<br>In The Broken Ones expansion, sold separately, you’ll also <br>find the rules for playing as ordinary humans and a variant <br>for solo play.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":1000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"9zYB4NvFhxUXcvUq","name":"Pagina 11","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 11</h2><p>10<br>Rules For Hunters<br>The rules for playing a Hunter are presented entirely on the <br>following pages. These same rules can also be found on the <br>Player’s Sheet. If you plan to be the Storyteller instead, read <br>the dedicated section in this chapter and all the in-depth <br>rules in the following chapters.<br>What’s on the Hunter’s Sheet:<br> ◆ Under the Hunter’s name, a brief history explaining <br>who they are and why they joined the Order.<br> ◆ Descriptors indicate what the Hunter does best and <br>what their flaws are. Incorporating a Descriptor into <br>the narration of a Hunter’s actions allows a Position <br>or Defense Check to start from 3 Base Successes. <br>Getting in trouble during the narrative, thanks to the <br>Descriptor’s Downside, allows you to check them off  <br>and gain XP .<br> ◆ Gifts are powerful special abilities that only Hunters <br>of the Order possess. They can be used whenever the <br>opportunity arises, following the rules and limitations <br>of the Gift itself.<br> ◆ The Dark Ego represents their essence and bond <br>to the fairytale world, what the Hunter was before <br>their Breaking Point. Y ou can activate the Dark Ego <br>whenever the Activator’s condition is triggered, or <br>when the Hunter suffers or decides to inflict 1 Wound <br>on themselves. The effect of the Dark Ego persists <br>throughout the course of the Scene.<br> ◆ The equipment indicates what gear the Hunter <br>possesses and can use in order to perform their mission <br>on behalf of the Order.<br> ◆ The Soma value represents the Hunter’s inner strength <br>and ability to tap into the true essence of a Broken Tale. <br>Spending Soma increases the chances of a positive <br>Outcome in any Position and Defense Check, or allows <br>the activation of certain Gifts. <br>When the Storyteller asks for a Position or <br>Defense Check…<br>Check if one of the Hunter’s Descriptors can help them in <br>the action being performed. If so, the Hunter starts with 3 <br>Base Successes. If no Descriptor is relevant, only 1 Base <br>Success is obtained. It’s possible to obtain Additional <br>Successes (for example, as a result of a Gift) or Penalties  <br>(to be subtracted from the total), to modify the number of <br>Base Successes. Once this is done, the number of Successes <br>is compared with the NPC’s or Threat’s Opposition Level <br>declared by the Storyteller. There are 3 Opposition Levels: <br>EASY 3, MEDIUM 5, and HARD 7. <br>For an action to have a positive Outcome, you must obtain <br>a total number of Successes (given by the sum of Base <br>Successes and Additional Successes) that is at least equal to <br>the Opposition Level you are facing. <br>To Get the Additional Successes you need to...<br> ◆ Spend Soma from the Hunter’s reserve to obtain 1 <br>Additional Success for each point.<br> ◆ Decide to roll one or more 6-sided dice. Y ou gain 1 <br>Additional Success for each die rolled. However, if even <br>a single die rolls a 1, the entire Check fails. All other <br>results (2-6) count as Additional Successes.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":1100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"S6ncBZY0QIRcreqB","name":"Pagina 12","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 12</h2><p>11<br>How many dice can be rolled?<br>Rolling dice is a gamble. Y ou can roll as many dice as you <br>wish to reach the Outcome you desire. However, each <br>additional die rolled increases the chances of rolling a 1, <br>even one of which results in a Failure. Even when aiming <br>for the best Outcome (Outcome with an Increment) the <br>total number of Successes needed will never exceed the <br>Opposition Level + 2. <br>Count total Successes...<br>If it’s a draw with the Opposition Level you’ll get an <br>Outcome with a Cost. The Hunter gets what they want <br>but at a cost chosen by the Storyteller. If it makes sense, <br>the Hunter can also inflict 1 Wound. In a Defense Check <br>the incoming problem is avoided, but with a complication <br>decided by the Storyteller.<br>By scoring 1 point above the Opposition Level you’ll get <br>a Standard Outcome. The Hunter gets what they want. <br>In a Defense Check, the problem is handled without any <br>complications. If it makes sense, the Hunter can also inflict <br>1 Wound.<br>By scoring 2 points above the Opposition Level you’ll <br>get an Outcome with an Increment. The Hunter succeeds <br>better than expected and gains an Increment in addition to <br>what they wanted. The Storyteller decides on the additional <br>effect or, alternatively, the special Increment of one of the <br>Hunter’s Gifts can be activated. In the case of a Defense <br>Check, the problem is avoided perfectly and an Increment <br>is also obtained. If it makes sense, the Hunter can also <br>inflict 1 Wound.<br>A Wound is inflicted…<br>As an effect of a failed Defense Check or as a Cost for an <br>action. Each Wound must be described and annotated on <br>the Bookmark. The Wound narratively affects what the <br>Hunter can do and the Opposition Level of what they face. <br>Whenever you suffer 1 Wound, you can activate your Dark <br>Ego power for the duration of the Scene. A Player may <br>decide to voluntarily inflict a Wound on the Hunter to <br>instantly activate their Dark Ego.<br>When they suffer a third Wound, the Hunter is out of the <br>game or dead. The Storyteller will reveal their fate according <br>to the situation.<br>Once upon a time…<br>If during the Scenario the Hunter gets into trouble and <br>highlights the Downside of one of their Descriptors, the <br>corresponding box must be marked. During an Interlude, <br>each box marked is converted into 1 XP .<br>Declaring an Interlude...<br>If Hunters need to catch their breath, a Player can ask <br>the Storyteller for an Interlude  between Scene changes. <br>During the Interlude, it is possible to recover 1 Wound <br>or, alternatively, recover 2 Soma. Each Hunter can ask a <br>question of another Hunter to learn more about their past.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":1200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"qLY3CDNRbwobSWVS","name":"Pagina 13","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 13</h2><p>12<br>During an Interlude XP may be spent to obtain additional <br>effects:<br> ◆ Recover 2 Soma for each XP spent.<br> ◆ Recover 1 Wound for each XP spent.<br> ◆ Evolve a Descriptor into a Specialization. For the rest of <br>the Scenario, this will grant 1 Additional Success in each <br>Scene in which it is used for the first time (1 XP).<br> ◆ Obtain a Scenario Gift for the duration of the Scenario <br>(1 XP).<br>Each Interlude, however, represents a use of time. Remember <br>that the Scenario, and the NPCs, may continue to act even <br>when the Hunters aren’t paying attention.<br>Rules for the <br>Storyteller<br>Broken Tales is designed to be a modular, easy-to-play role-<br>playing game. For Storytellers who already have experience <br>with role-playing games, all the basic rules are presented <br>in this section. In the section Further Details on Game <br>Rules (page 17) you will find all the rules explained with <br>examples, to clear up doubts about the system and on how to <br>handle a game of Broken Tales.<br>Choose how to play the Scenario<br>Unlike other RPGs, Broken Tales doesn’t have Scenarios <br>with a pre-written plot, but instead cultivates an “emergent” <br>narrative. What happens in the Scene will always be the <br>outcome of the Hunters’ actions and this, combined with <br>the Storyteller’s choices regarding the NPCs, will generate <br>situations with unpredictable outcomes. <br>An emergent narrative means approaching the game with the <br>intention of being surprised by it, reacting on the fly while <br>being guided by the rules of the game and the Scenario’s <br>information.<br>As mentioned earlier, a more classical approach is also <br>possible. Each Scenario comes with a Scene Tree that will <br>allow you to explore one of the possible plots in a more linear <br>fashion. A Scene Tree may include forks and variations, but it <br>will always give the Storyteller clear directions on what clues <br>to bring into play and how to move the plot forward. <br>There is no right or wrong way to play Broken Tales. Each <br>group can decide how to approach it based on their own <br>taste and desire to improvise or, rather, live out a more <br>guided story.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":1300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"hXA1GsNEgQ62S4fo","name":"Pagina 14","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 14</h2><p>13<br>The Storyteller’s Job<br>The Storyteller’s job is to manage the game, the Scenario, <br>and all the NPCs that the Hunters will encounter. Each <br>Broken Tales Scenario provides all the information needed <br>to move a plot forward while adapting continuously to <br>the Hunters’ decisions and the Storyteller’s personal taste <br>in puppeteering the many side NPCs. After the Starting <br>Situation, this outline should be followed to run the Session:<br>1. The Storyteller asks the Hunters where they want to <br>go and what they want to do.<br>2. The NPCs’ Agendas and Scenario Events should be <br>consulted frequently. If something has changed and it <br>makes sense in the narrative, the Storyteller will have <br>“off-stage” NPCs acting or entering the Scene.<br>3. Each new Scene must be contextualized by the Story-<br>teller with a Place, a Time, an Initial Situation, and <br>any further Information.<br>4. After a brief introduction of the Scene, it’s the Hunt-<br>ers’ turn to decide what to do.<br>5. During the Scene, if the outcome of an action is un-<br>certain or collides with an NPC/Threat, the Storytell-<br>er should ask for Position and Defense Checks. Once <br>the Check is resolved, it’s again the Hunters’ turn to <br>describe what they do.<br>6. When the Hunters’ stated goal in the Scene is <br>achieved or can no longer be achieved, the Scene <br>starts over from step 1.<br>NPCs’ Agendas<br>To manage the game flow, each Scenario presents a series of <br>Agendas, goals that the Scenario’s NPCs try to accomplish. <br>An Agenda can progress in two ways: when it makes sense <br>for it to happen in the narrative or during an Interlude <br>(because time continues to pass while the Hunters rest). The <br>Agenda is the most important reference for the Storyteller <br>when deciding how to handle the events of the Scenario. It <br>describes what that specific NPC wants regardless of the <br>Hunters’ actions. Consulting NPC Agendas can lead to <br>spontaneous situations without having to plan Scenes in <br>advance.<br>Scenario’s Events<br>Events are brief descriptions of something that will happen <br>if certain conditions are met. They’re sudden twists in the <br>Scenario, shaking things up for the Hunters. When the <br>conditions described in the Event occur, the Storyteller <br>should include it in the Scenario as soon as possible.<br>Scenes and Interludes<br>Each Scenario is developed through Scenes, which are <br>roughly comparable to scenes in a movie. It is usually clear <br>when one ends and a new one begins. Each Scene must have <br>a Place, a Time, an Initial Situation , and possibly some <br>Information the Storyteller can use as a starting point. It’s <br>the Storyteller’s job to manage Scenes and decide when to <br>move on to the next one.    <br>Interludes are special Scenes that Hunters can ask for <br>between the action to catch their breath. Interludes are calm, <br>restful (such as dinner at the inn), and always take time. In <br>addition to recovering Soma and Wounds, as indicated on <br>the Player’s Sheet, an Interlude has two additional effects <br>on the Scenario:<br> ◆ Hunters can ask another Hunter a question about their <br>past. This is a good way to reveal something and dig <br>deeper into each background story. Players are free to <br>invent whatever they want to characterize their Hunter <br>but their answer should remain relevant to the question <br>they have been asked.<br> ◆ Time doesn’t stop during an Interlude, and the <br>Storyteller must consider how to advance the Scenario’s <br>Agendas. They must point out to the Hunters that the</p>","markdown":""},"sort":1400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"f9wQpOUIMYbcBZqp","name":"Pagina 15","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 15</h2><p>14<br>Scenario goes on without them. Asking for too many <br>Interludes can lead to things getting out of control!<br>Handling the Position Checks<br>When a Hunter performs any kind of action, the Storyteller <br>needs to decide if they want to ask for a Check. In making <br>this decision, it’s vital to keep all relevant Descriptors in <br>mind.<br> ◆ If the Hunter acts to obtain something but might fail <br>due to an NPC or a Threat<br>Then, it’s time for a Position Check. This applies to any <br>action in which the Hunter is the active party. Ideally, the <br>Hunter would narrate a detailed, dynamic action such as, <br>“I run up the wall and leap off, cutting with my sword at <br>the giant’s head.” Not every action requires a Check, just <br>those that face opposition that could prevent the Hunter <br>from succeeding.<br> ◆ If the Storyteller’s narration includes circumstances <br>that may injure or inconvenience the Hunter<br>Call a Defense Check instead. This applies to any reaction <br>in which the Hunter is a passive party. For example: <br>“You’re jumping from roof to roof, but the rain made the <br>tiles slippery, do a Defense Check against OL Medium 5. ” All <br>Defense Checks represent a Hunter’s reactions, attempts to <br>avoid a potential problem. A Defense Check is used when <br>the Storyteller is the one taking the floor, presenting a <br>Threat or an NPC as an obstacle the Hunter must overcome.<br>The Storyteller never rolls dice. Instead, they ask for Position <br>Checks when a Hunter acts. The Storyteller also asks for a <br>Defense Check when Scenario NPCs and Threats attempt <br>to oppose the Hunters. Not every Hunter will find the same <br>situation challenging, so the Storyteller may only ask some <br>Hunters to perform a specific Check, remembering to keep <br>in mind the Descriptors of each Hunter, NPC, or Threat <br>involved. <br>If the Scene evolves into a conflict, you must keep tabs on <br>who has acted and who hasn’t, until all participants in the <br>Session have had a chance to do something. This rotation <br>system is called Exchange.<br>Depending on the outcome of the Position and Defense <br>Checks, a Cost or Increment may be generated. The <br>Storyteller will decide its nature.<br> ◆ A Cost is some kind of narrative disadvantage, such <br>as employing more time to perform the action or <br>consuming a useful resource to do it. Possible Costs are: <br>You retrace your steps or move away from a potential goal <br>you intended to achieve, or you hesitate, avoid danger, <br>but can’t get past what you’re trying to overcome / You <br>get wounded or waste a lot of energy, suffering 1 Wound <br>/ You lose, break, or drop something, or waste more <br>resources than expected / Your opponent can easily move <br>away from you and you can’t do anything to prevent it / <br>You’re forced to make promises to successfully conclude <br>the negotiation / You reveal something important about <br>yourself or an ally / You lose much more time than <br>expected / You let your guard down or are caught off  <br>guard, and receive 1 Penalty on your next Check / What <br>you obtain is not whole or is missing parts.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":1500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241711,"modifiedTime":1783973241711,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"QTXntgXcxLM5DiHE","name":"Pagina 16","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 16</h2><p>15<br>Alternatively, or if no ideas spring to mind, you may assign <br>1 Penalty to the Hunter’s next action, or inflict 1 Wound.<br> ◆ An Increment is some kind of narrative advantage, <br>such as spending less time performing the action or <br>getting into a better position during an attack. Possible <br>Increments are: You can maneuver around your target, <br>stay engaged with it, and move in a direction of your <br>choosing, or you can easily move away from a Threat <br>without impediments / You can catch something on the <br>fly / If an enemy is moving, you can force them to stop <br>by blocking their path / You can provide 1 Additional <br>Success to your next action or that of your ally, to <br>be spent in the immediate future / You get the best of <br>the negotiation, impress or fascinate someone, or are <br>otherwise memorable / You can learn a secret, details of <br>a scandal, or a technique from a subject or situation / <br>You succeed better than expected, it takes you less time, <br>or you get more beneficial results / You succeed and you <br>can also help someone who is facing the same problem as <br>you, benefitting their narrative position.<br>As an alternative, if no ideas spring to mind, you may <br>assign 1 Additional Success to your next action or that of <br>an allied Hunter.<br>The Opposition Level of Opponents <br>and Threats<br>Any element of the Scenario can be an NPC or a Threat (a <br>natural element, a magical effect, or anything other than an <br>NPC). Both are always characterized by a Descriptor and <br>an Opposition Level and, in some cases, by one or more <br>Gifts. NPCs are also divided by Category, which indicates <br>their importance in the game.<br> ◆ The Descriptor: is a short narrative quote describing <br>the NPC or Threat. It is used to handle the narrative <br>and to modify the Opposition Level by +1 if the Hunter <br>is taken by surprise or has no means to oppose what <br>the Descriptor says. If the Hunter uses it to their <br>advantage, it will lower the Opposition Level by 1.<br> ◆ The Opposition Level (OL): is the numerical value <br>to be achieved or surpassed in a Position or Defense <br>Check.<br>EASY 3 / MEDIUM 5 / HARD 7 <br> ◆ Gifts: are special effects and powers. Each Scenario will <br>feature those specific to relevant NPCs and Threats.<br> ◆ The Category: indicates the importance of an NPC in <br>the narration and a sensible range of Wounds they can <br>suffer.<br>Minor NPC: from 1 to 3 Wounds (generally 1).<br>Main NPC: from 1 to 6 Wounds (generally 3).<br>Dark Presence: from 1 to 6 Wounds (generally 3).</p>","markdown":""},"sort":1600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"hM0b5wouIDSM4Nav","name":"Pagina 17","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 17</h2><p>16<br>Managing Information<br>Broken Tales Scenarios will often be investigations <br>that Hunters perform on behalf of the Order. With <br>this in mind, it does not make sense to ask for <br>Position Checks to find clues that, if undiscovered, <br>would stall the situation. In general, when a Hunter <br>is looking for information, ask yourself:<br> ◆ Does one of the Hunter’s Descriptors justify <br>the knowledge of the information? If so, the <br>Hunter will get it.<br> ◆ Does it take time to get the information? <br>The Storyteller communicates this drawback <br>to the Hunter, who will decide what to do.<br> ◆ Is getting the information dangerous for the <br>Hunter? The Storyteller introduces an NPC/<br>Threat into the Scene.<br> ◆ Does the Hunter need external help to get <br>the information? The Storyteller will reveal <br>who can provide it. This can often lead to a <br>new Scene.<br>This is all you need to get started with the game. <br>In the Further Details on Game Rules chapter on <br>page 17, you will find several examples for each <br>mechanic presented in these pages and the rules <br>for creating NPCs and Threats.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":1700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"knOg6PABwDiVOqCc","name":"Pagina 18","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 18</h2><p>17<br>Further Details on <br>Game Rules<br>In this section, we’ll explore further the rules we’ve already briefly discussed in <br>the sections devoted to Hunters and Storytellers. If you’re not familiar with role-<br>playing games, it can be a good idea to read everything at least once. Y ou will better <br>be able to understand the application of rules, after seeing some practical examples <br>explained. For those who already have experience with other games based on Monad <br>Echo, this section is a useful reference when in doubt.<br> <br>The Conversation<br>A game of Broken Tales is structured as a conversation between all <br>Players, in which the Storyteller presents fictional situations and <br>the other Players react with their Hunter’s choices. When the <br>consequences of a Hunter’s choice are uncertain, the Storyteller <br>asks for a Position Check to determine the outcome. At this point, <br>the Hunter’s action either succeeds or fails, and the conversation <br>resumes. The Storyteller narrates the action’s result, together with <br>the Hunter’s Player. Play continues until the next Check and so on <br>throughout the Session.<br>The Storyteller never performs Checks on the <br>behalf of NPCs and Threats.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":1800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"A6yZRq3wHAtbiWny","name":"Pagina 19","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 19</h2><p>18<br>Check Type When is it done? What are the Check <br>criteria?<br>Who <br>narrates the <br>outcome?<br>What are the <br>mechanical <br>consequences?<br>Position <br>Check<br>The Hunter is actively trying <br>to position themselves in a <br>certain way within the story, <br>and the outcome is uncertain.<br>The Storyteller requests the <br>Check, based on the Hunter’s <br>narrative and what they’re <br>trying to achieve. <br>The Storytel-<br>ler describes <br>the outcome.<br>The action continues <br>with one of three possible <br>positive Outcomes or a <br>Failure. The Hunter expe-<br>riences the consequences <br>of the action.<br>Defense <br>Check<br>The Hunter is the target of <br>an action by someone or <br>something (NPC or Threat) <br>attempting to obstruct them.<br>The Storyteller requests the <br>Check based on the actions <br>or triggers of NPCs or <br>Threats. <br>The Hunter <br>narrates the <br>outcome.<br>The Hunter suffers any <br>effects and play continues. <br>The Hunter cannot achie-<br>ve anything that is not <br>related to avoiding danger.<br>Making Decisions While Narrating<br>The game flow is simple and fast. It is interrupted only for <br>Position and Defense Checks. With this in mind, it is very <br>important to have a clear idea of who can determine what, <br>and the duties of the Hunters and the Storyteller in telling <br>the story.<br>How and when does a Hunter act? How much can they <br>risk in terms of resources and consequences in the <br>narrative?<br>This is the domain of the Players. The Storyteller cannot <br>impose actions or make decisions for a Hunter.<br>How dangerous is an action and when is a Position and <br>Defense Check required?<br>Making this decision is up to the Storyteller. A Hunter may <br>try to steer the narrative towards one of their Descriptors <br>to improve their chances of obtaining 3 Base Successes. <br>However, it will always be the Storyteller who decides <br>whether or not to call for a Check. Only the Storyteller <br>knows the Descriptors and other details of NPCs and <br>Threats, and they’re the only one at the table who always <br>knows everything that is happening.<br>When a setting/environmental element acts directly <br>against one or more Hunters, the Storyteller may request <br>a special Position Check called a Defense Check. As <br>with a normal Position Check, the Hunter will always <br>be confronted with the Opposition Level declared <br>by the Storyteller; this time, however, the Player will, <br>with the help of the Storyteller, narrate the outcome.  <br>Once the Check is resolved, the narration resumes as usual.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":1900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"gpwRdow2k0Pm9V5m","name":"Pagina 20","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 20</h2><p>19<br>Which Scenario developments affect the way Hunters <br>behave? What will trigger XP accumulation thanks to a <br>Descriptor’s Downside? <br>Players have authority in these situations. Each of them <br>has Descriptors on their Sheet and can decide when to <br>create a problem for themselves, putting the Downside in <br>the spotlight. Doing so will allow them to check off the <br>Descriptor, which will later translate into XP .<br>The Basic Mechanics<br>The main mechanics of Broken Tales revolve around <br>Position and Defense Checks. But what are they exactly?<br>The Position Check represents an action taken by the <br>Hunter, along with the purpose they are trying to achieve, <br>in order to metaphorically gain a beneficial “position” <br>within the storytelling. Anything a Hunter declares they <br>will do that does not have an obvious outcome may require <br>a Position Check. Defense Checks are a special type of <br>Position Checks. If the Storyteller declares that a Hunter <br>faces a challenge, it will be up to the Player to describe <br>what they will do to avoid it. Their success or failure in a <br>Defense Check determines their new place, or position, in <br>the narrative.<br>Position Check<br>The Storyteller asks for a Position Check when a Player’s <br>narration causes their Hunter to interact with an NPC, <br>another Hunter, or a Threat, and the outcome of that <br>interaction is uncertain.<br>When in doubt, follow the storytelling because the same <br>action can lead to different Checks and outcomes based on <br>the context. <br>Narrating in detail what the Hunter does is essential for the <br>Storyteller who:<br> ◆ Starts with the story when determining what kind of <br>Check is needed (if any).<br> ◆ Will evaluate if one of the Hunter’s Descriptors is <br>relevant to the action.<br> ◆ Will decide the possible consequences of a positive <br>Outcome or how the narrative will proceed in the <br>event of a Failure.<br> ◆ Will determine whether to change an NPC’s Opposition <br>Level or Threat by +1 or -1, answering the question: <br>“Has the NPC/Threat Descriptor been taken advantage <br>of, or countered?”<br> ◆ Will determine if a Player can roll a Position Check to <br>see if their action succeeded, or if a Defense Check is <br>needed first.<br>The Hunter always has the right to review an action before <br>deciding whether to roll the dice or invest Soma. The <br>Storyteller has the duty to clearly explain the consequences <br>of what is about to happen, without stating the unknown <br>Descriptors of the opponents or adversities. What a Hunter <br>knows and what they don’t know can vary in relation to <br>their Descriptors. Some may have the skills to sense threats <br>that others would normally underestimate.<br>In fact, the Hunter’s intentions will often collide with <br>unexpected situations. When changing circumstances <br>might affect a Hunter’s action, a Defense Check may be <br>needed to see how they are affected. If successful, they may <br>be able to then roll the Position Check for their action. <br>Again, it is up to the Storyteller to make the situation clear <br>and ask the Hunter what they intend to do in light of how <br>events are unfolding.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":2000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"hBDdva5hqpcLTIrA","name":"Pagina 21","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 21</h2><p>20<br>Example: <br>Garou the Old Wolf is exploring the area around the town <br>of Durfort. Meanwhile, his companions are having a <br>conversation with the noble Dubois, hoping to get a grasp <br>of what is happening in the Red Hood Iskra Scenario. <br>The Storyteller warns Garou of the presence of a rapidly <br>approaching pack of wolves. No Check is required because <br>it is a piece of information Garou knows (as explained on <br>page 16) and in addition, Garou has the Gift Find Them <br>Forever After, which allows Garou to perceive noises and <br>smells before anyone else. Safely among the foliage, Garou <br>prepares an ambush for the new arrivals, determined to make <br>immediately clear that this is now his territory. The wolves <br>arrive a few meters from the hiding place and Garou decides <br>to attack, jumping on them. However, the Storyteller points <br>out that wolves have a very acute sense of smell (as reported <br>by their Descriptor) and therefore the surprise effect could <br>fade before Garou manages to bite one. At this point, the <br>Storyteller requires a Defense Check to see if the Hunter will <br>really be able to perform the surprise attack. Garou agrees to <br>take the risk and does the Check. If not, Garou would have <br>remained in hiding waiting for a better opportunity.<br>Once the situation is clear and defined, we move on to the <br>resolution sequence.<br>The Storyteller:<br> ◆ Identifies whether to determine the positive <br>Outcome or Failure of an action during the game.<br> ◆ Declares the basic Opposition Level of the Threat/<br>NPC. <br> ◆ Determines whether to raise or lower the Opposition <br>Level by 1 , according to the current narrative and <br>Hunter’s behavior (knowing or not) in relation to <br>what is happening. A Hunter often does not know the <br>Descriptors of a Threat (but can discover them using <br>special Gifts, Descriptors taken advantage of, or as the <br>result of previous actions).<br>For a Check to have a positive Outcome, a Hunter has <br>to accrue a total of Successes equal to or greater than the <br>Opposition Level declared by the Storyteller.<br>The Hunter:<br> ◆ Checks if one of their Descriptors is relevant to the <br>declared action and confirms it with the Storyteller. <br>If so, they start with 3 Base Successes, otherwise with <br>only 1.  <br> ◆ Adds up any Additional Successes and subtracts any <br>Penalties. Each Penalty removes 1 Success.<br> ◆ Decides what kind of Outcome to aim for, depending <br>on the compromises they are willing to make and the <br>expected results of the action. Matching the Opposition <br>Level with Successes leads to an Outcome with a <br>Cost, exceeding it by 1 is a Standard Outcome, and <br>exceeding it by 2 is an Outcome with an Increment <br>(see following pages). It is never possible to aim for a <br>higher result than an Outcome with an Increment.<br> ◆ May decide to spend Soma from their supply to get 1 <br>Additional Success per point spent. <br> ◆ Can roll as many dice as they want, all at once, getting <br>1 Additional Success for each result between 2 and 6.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":2100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"JidXuzOW6iNKp2pZ","name":"Pagina 22","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 22</h2><p>21<br>How to read the dice<br>If 1 is rolled: Failure.<br>Any result between 2-6: Success.<br> A single 1 (Failure) causes the entire Check <br>to fail. <br>Automatic positive Outcome<br>It may happen that the sum of Basic Successes + Additional <br>Successes reaches or exceeds the Opposition Level <br>determined by the Storyteller. In this case, the action <br>is already successful. Which Outcome is reached<br> will be determined as explained in the third point of The Hunter <br>paragraph.  <br>Check example: <br>Continuing with the example on page 20, Garou is facing <br>a pack of four wolves. Through a Defense Check, Garou <br>has approached the enemies from behind, taking them by <br>surprise.<br>Garou’s Descriptors tell us that he is a fierce and powerful <br>predator, and that is definitely relevant to what he is doing. <br>Therefore, Garou receives 3 Base Successes.<br>The Storyteller declares that the Opposition Level of the wolves <br>is Medium, which is equal to 5. However, the Storyteller <br>decides to lower it to 4 because the wolves’ Descriptor specifies <br>that they obey only their Alpha Greskar or Iskra, and neither <br>of them is present in the Scene.<br>Garou has 3 Base Successes and needs at least 1 Additional <br>Success to reach the Opposition Level. This is the minimum to <br>get an Outcome with a Cost.<br>Now the Player can decide if they want 2 Additional Successes <br>to reach a Standard Outcome (1 Success over the Opposition <br>Level) or 3 Additional Successes to aim for an Outcome with <br>an Increment (2 Successes over the Opposition Level). Garou <br>doesn’t mind a Standard Outcome: he now has to choose how <br>to get the 2 missing Additional Successes to achieve it.<br>As the last step, Garou decides to exchange 1 Soma for a <br>Success, and then roll 1 single die. The die comes up a 3: <br>Success. Garou gets a Standard Outcome, which is up to the <br>Storyteller to describe.<br>Let’s see all the possible results of Garou’s Check:<br>Rolling even a single 1 on the dice makes the action fail.<br>In this case, the action fails: if the Hunter’s goal is to <br>somehow avoid a Wound, they will suffer it. The narration, <br>however, goes on anyway. Whether the Hunter wants it or <br>not, something changes, and, in the case of a Failure, it does <br>so in a way that affects them negatively.<br>The Storyteller describes the result: Garou hurries to avoid <br>alerting the wolves, but this makes the attack hasty and <br>inaccurate. The bite misses its mark as the other wolf dodges <br>the attack and turns around, ready to face the threat.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":2200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Gp4GiuEv0CZnhmj5","name":"Pagina 23","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 23</h2><p>22<br>DEFENSE CHECK<br>By obtaining a total of Successes equal to the Opposition <br>Level: the action would result in an Outcome with a Cost.<br>The Hunter gets what they want but at a Cost chosen by the <br>Storyteller from the list (page 14), in line with what is <br>happening. As a result of the Outcome, if the Hunter’s goal <br>is to harm a target in some way, 1 Wound can be inflicted.<br>The Storyteller describes the result: Garou sinks his fangs into <br>the throat of one of the wolves, which, being able to suffer <br>only 1 Wound, is instantly killed. Unfortunately, as the <br>animal falls to the ground, it drags Garou with it, throwing <br>the Hunter off balance. The Storyteller assigns 1 Penalty to <br>Garou’s next Check.<br>By obtaining a total of 1 Success above the Opposition <br>Level: the action would result in a Standard Outcome.<br>In this case, the Hunter gets what they intended and, if <br>consistent, can inflict 1 Wound on one or more targets.<br>The Storyteller describes the result: Garou sinks his fangs into <br>the throat of the enemy, which, being able to suffer a single <br>Wound, is killed instantly.<br>This is exactly what happened in the example on page 20. <br>By obtaining a total of Successes 2 points over the <br>Opposition Level: the outcome is an Outcome with an <br>Increment.<br>The Hunter gets what they have set out to do and an <br>Increment, an additional effect increasing the range of the <br>action itself. The Increment is provided by the Storyteller <br>in relation to the situation and the objectives of the Hunter, <br>choosing from the generic list (page 15). Alternatively, <br>if the Hunter’s Gifts grant special Increments, they may <br>choose to activate them.<br>The Storyteller describes the result: Garou sinks his fangs into <br>the throat of the enemy, which, being able to suffer a single <br>Wound, is killed instantly. Garou sprints past the opponent’s <br>body and pushes the remaining wolves along a narrow path <br>to prevent being surrounded, as stated by the Player at the <br>start of the attack. The Storyteller will therefore neither <br>be able to exploit the narrative advantage of Garou being <br>outnumbered for the wolves’ next action, nor their Gift which <br>confers advantages to them when they outnumber a prey.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":2300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"iF1amvDfgIVv77xV","name":"Pagina 24","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 24</h2><p>23<br>Defense Check<br>A Defense Check is basically a Position Check which <br>represents an obstacle to the Hunter’s intentions. When a <br>Threat or NPC acts on a Hunter, the Storyteller asks the <br>Hunter for a Check to see how well they can handle the <br>problem. Often a Defense Check is self-evident, such as <br>when an enemy responds by attacking a Hunter during a <br>fight. Other times it will be unexpected, for example when <br>a Hunter declares an action and the Storyteller brings into <br>play elements that have been underestimated or hidden.<br>A Hunter’s action may require a Defense Check before a <br>Position Check can be attempted. In that case, the Storyteller <br>decides whether to allow them time to review the action, <br>examining the Descriptors involved and establishing <br>whether the Hunter has the opportunity to become aware <br>of the threat in time.<br>After Garou’s attack, the wolves cannot use their numbers <br>to overwhelm the enemy. Garou recounts how he used the <br>narrow path to force the wolves to face the Hunter one at <br>a time. The Storyteller declares that the Opposition Level <br>drops from 5 to 4 as the opponents fail to use their Descriptor <br>Efficient as a pack. It will always be Garou to make the <br>Defense Check, and once again will be able to count on 3 <br>Base Successes thanks to his Descriptors, deciding what kind <br>of Outcome to aim for. In the same situation, if Garou had <br>declared to dodge the blow rolling away from the enemy, he <br>would have ended up in a small clearing behind his back. In <br>this way, unknowingly, Garou would have put himself in the <br>perfect position for the enemy to bring into play their Gift, <br>which increases their Level of Opposition by 1 when they are <br>numerically superior.<br>The same action and the same situation can have very <br>different outcomes based on the Hunter’s narrative: <br>evaluating whether a threat is perceived or not makes <br>the difference between presenting the Check directly or <br>giving the Hunter the opportunity to review their action. <br>Has Garou seen the enemy pack fight before? Has the <br>Hunter experienced their fighting style and knows how <br>they exploit their numerical superiority? Or does Garou <br>have a Descriptor that indicates the ability to understand <br>the enemy’s strategy? In these cases, the Storyteller should <br>allow Garou to review his action.<br>Other Rules on Position and <br>Defense Checks<br>Let’s discuss some additional elements to consider when <br>calling Position and Defense Checks.<br>A Player describes how the Hunter does <br>something<br>During the game, narration is continuous. Every Hunter <br>must be aware that, if there are no obstacles or a Position <br>Check is successful, they will get exactly what they have <br>set out to do. One’s intent must be clear while narrating, <br>describing what they do concretely and not what they could <br>possibly do. In combat, “I try to hit the enemy” is the wrong <br>way to state intent; “I hit the head of the pirate” is much <br>more precise and useful for fictional positioning.<br>The big difference between the two statements is that <br>the first one is too general and doesn’t tell us anything, <br>making any Outcome bland and leaving all the burden of <br>the consequent narrative to the Storyteller. The Player’s <br>intentions could be misinterpreted and the action would <br>likely lead to a less entertaining narration. The second <br>DEFENSE CHECK</p>","markdown":""},"sort":2400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"edWiJpuUpFwjepjA","name":"Pagina 25","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 25</h2><p>24<br>statement, however, makes the facts clear: for the Storyteller, <br>it will be easy to narrate the result of “hitting a pirate on the <br>head” and also to pick any Cost, Increment, and what type <br>of Wound to inflict in case of success. <br>Everything starts from the narration, <br>everything goes back to the narration<br>The most important question to keep in mind during the <br>game is: what is happening in the Scene? Broken Tales starts <br>with the narrative premise that each Player describes what <br>their Hunter does, while the Storyteller responds through <br>NPCs and situations. There are no subsystems: when an <br>action can have an interesting or uncertain outcome, you <br>make a Check. Take into account what was narrated before <br>asking for the Check. What is happening in the Scene will <br>lead to a whole series of considerations:<br> ◆ What prompted the Check? Are we narrating a violent <br>action towards someone? Or a stealth maneuver to <br>sneak away unseen? Is the action free and unimpeded <br>or does it put the Hunter at risk of having to make <br>a Defense Check first? What is happening in the <br>narration is essential to understanding what will be <br>achieved with the Check. Always remember that if an <br>action is successful and it makes sense in the context, <br>the target could suffer 1 Wound. <br> ◆ How do you manage the Check? Does the Hunter <br>bring into play a relevant Descriptor? Does the NPC <br>or Threat involved bring a Descriptor into play as well? <br>What Gifts are used? It is always through the narrative <br>that we will understand “how” the action is done.<br> ◆ What’s the result? How does the Hunter’s narrative <br>position change after the Check? The result is the <br>most important part because it will always cause some <br>change to the ongoing Scene.<br>Dodging a rifle shot by throwing yourself to the ground <br>is probably the simplest solution, but even in the case of <br>a positive Outcome, it will result in you ending up on the <br>ground. <br>A nearby enemy could take advantage of this and force your <br>Hunter to do a Defense Check while you’re attempting to <br>get up. Blocking the bullet with an improvised shield will be <br>very dangerous and obtaining an Outcome with a Cost could <br>mean suffering a Wound, but will leave your Hunter standing <br>and ready to react.<br>When many subjects are involved in <br>a Scene, it is good to establish turns <br>dynamically<br>When Hunters are alone or in situations where they <br>have full control and time to plan their moves, they can <br>freely decide how and when to act. On the other hand, if <br>there’s a conflict situation involving NPCs, the Storyteller <br>must always divide characters into two factions. After <br>determining the first to act, each faction will then make <br>each of its members act in turn until all of the Hunters and <br>prominent NPCs have acted at least once.<br>This system is called Exchange and it establishes a <br>“narrative order. ” It is used by the Storyteller to keep the <br>spotlight equally divided between the parties but does not <br>have to follow all the contenders in the same way.<br>What matters during an Exchange is that Hunters and <br>prominent NPCs have time to act and turn the tide in <br>their favor, while everything else remains active, but in the <br>background.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":2500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"OkhQsBtBXBcvCGMK","name":"Pagina 26","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 26</h2><p>25<br>After a Position or Defense Check, the <br>narration always continues<br>After a Check, the situation must  evolve in some <br>way, for better or worse. This is a fundamental step. <br>A Position Check always moves the situation forward <br>far enough, even if by just a few moments, to ensure <br>that the previous status is changed. This applies both <br>to any type of positive Outcome, as well as to a Failure. <br>Failing can mean many things. Sometimes, you can <br>get what you want and still fail. The Player narrates <br>how. A Position Check to push someone off a cliff can <br>be resolved in many ways, one of them being that the <br>target is pushed but takes the Hunter down with them!<br>Hunter vs Hunter<br>Broken Tales assumes that a conflict between two <br>Hunters should be resolved mainly between Players, <br>with a spoken mediation between intent and outcome. <br>However, it could happen that one Hunter acts to harm <br>another, generating either a Position or Defense Check. <br>In this case, the Storyteller determines who is acting <br>(the Active Hunter), and who is at the receiving end of <br>the action (the Passive Hunter). The Active Hunter will <br>then have to make a Check against an Opposition Level <br>of either Easy 3 (if the Passive Hunter has no relevant <br>Descriptors) or Medium 5 (if the Passive Hunter has a <br>relevant Descriptor). The Passive Hunter cannot spend <br>Soma to increase their Opposition Level.<br>Dividing storytelling duties<br>Broken Tales puts all the choices in the Storyteller’s <br>hands, who then decides Costs, Increments, and <br>if Wounds are inflicted. This is intended to avoid <br>interruptions in the game flow and avoid delays due to <br>indecision, which can be a frequent problem in some <br>other games. Once you are familiar with the rules, feel <br>free to decide how to divide the duties of narrating Outcomes, <br>Costs, Gifts, choices and Descriptor uses between Storyteller <br>and Hunters to match your playstyle.<br>Descriptors<br>They represent the salient narrative features of a Hunter, an <br>NPC, or any other element of the setting. Descriptors help <br>Players in interpreting the Hunter and the Storyteller in <br>establishing areas of competence during the game. Another <br>effect of the Descriptors is to grant bonus XP if they caused a <br>Hunter trouble during a Scene.<br>Each Hunter Descriptor is made up of two parts. One is positive <br>and describes the Hunter’s abilities and strengths. The second, the <br>Downside, highlights a flaw or weakness.<br>Baba Yaga the Child Witch possesses the Descriptor I am very <br>skilled in reading people. That is why the Order has chosen <br>Strength in numbers?<br>If a group of four Hunters faces a pack of twelve wolves, <br>the Storyteller will not have the enemies act twelve times. <br>Instead, the wolf pack has the same number of actions as the <br>Hunters, four in this example. The purpose of the Exchange <br>isn’t to put pressure on the Hunters with multiple Defense <br>Checks, but to create a tense situation. An overwhelming <br>number of enemies is already a decisive narrative advantage. <br>They can surround the Hunters (forcing them to succeed in <br>a Defense Check to move), take secondary actions, and so <br>on. Some Gifts increase the Opposition Level of opponents <br>based on their number, which can also be a good way to <br>emphasize their superiority.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":2600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"j3GIIOkspQimwqw9","name":"Pagina 27","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 27</h2><p>26<br>me as leader of the Hunters. I love manipulating people <br>and I often do it merely to amuse myself. This Descriptor <br>tells us a lot about our Hunter. Yaga is good at reading others <br>and plays a major role among the Hunters. At the same time, <br>Yaga cannot contain her manipulative nature and will tend <br>to abuse it even without any real need, creating unnecessarily <br>complicated schemes to reach her goal.<br>In this case, there is a noticeable difference between a <br>Hunter, NPCs, and Threats. The protagonist of the game <br>is defined by three complete Descriptors (positive part + <br>Downside), while NPCs and Threats have only one, not <br>necessarily with a Downside.<br>Additional considerations:<br> ◆ For everything that is not a Hunter, a Descriptor is <br>nothing more than a narrative sentence the Storyteller <br>can use to manage that particular story element. The <br>Descriptor of an NPC or a Threat may have a Downside <br>or not. The important thing is that the Descriptor is <br>narrow enough to clearly signal how and when it is <br>relevant in a Check, and what tactics can be applied <br>against it or in its favor.<br> ◆ Some Gifts create a temporary Descriptor. In that case, <br>the Gift description and its importance in the narrative <br>will indicate the Descriptor’s specifics.<br> ◆ Descriptors created by Wounds will be mainly of <br>a negative nature. This doesn’t mean that a Hunter <br>cannot exploit them to their own advantage, but that <br>they will be more of a problem than a resource.<br>Gifts<br>Gifts are special skills and abilities that give Hunters and <br>NPCs depth. Every Gift has a full description of its effect, <br>which clarifies when and why it can be used in the game. As <br>with Descriptors, Hunters and NPCs use Gifts in different <br>ways.<br>On the Hunters’ side, Gifts influence different game <br>situations, from obtaining circumstantial bonuses to <br>recovering Soma.<br>Generally speaking, NPCs and Threats have Gifts that have <br>simpler effects than the Hunters’ . On pages 29, 32 and  <br>73 you’ll find all the expanded rules to create Gifts for <br>Threats, NPCs and Hunters.<br>Gifts are by far the most design-heavy elements to create for <br>Storyteller and Players, as they must be balanced following <br>an often-subjective evaluation.<br>The golden rule when creating a Gift is to start by describing <br>what happens in the narrative when the Gift is used.<br>This means setting aside bonuses and game effects so <br>that you can prioritize a narrative description over the <br>mechanics. It is good to be exhaustive, describing how the <br>Gift is activated, if it requires special precautions, and what <br>happens when the owner shows it off. On page 73 you <br>will find a series of Archetypal Effects and Costs for the <br>Hunters’ Gifts which, when combined, will allow you to <br>build a full-fledged Gift.<br>GIFTS</p>","markdown":""},"sort":2700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"xW21y8FaYXIvc99W","name":"Pagina 28","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 28</h2><p>27<br>Ask yourself:<br> ◆ If you had to describe in simple words what a Gift  <br>does and when it can be used, how would you <br>describe it?<br> ◆ Which of the mechanics available on pages 75 or <br>81 best suit what you described?<br>Always ask yourself the questions in this order!<br>Having a clear understanding of what happens in the <br>narrative is key to deciding which Effects and Costs to <br>apply. In Broken Tales, Hunters and their opponents are <br>often exceptional people. There’s nothing wrong with <br>giving them Gifts that grant incredible abilities. The only <br>real way to create a balanced Gift is to remain consistent <br>with the backstory of the Hunter/NPC.<br>needs to be increased or lowered.<br>It is important to clarify that Wounds represent the NPC’s <br>“plot armor” that keeps them active during the Scenario, not <br>just their physical stamina.<br> ◆ Any NPC who represents a minion or doesn’t have <br>special abilities should have 1 single Wound. Even when <br>facing many of these opponents, Hunters can defeat them <br>with a single hit.<br> ◆ Minor NPCs should have 3 Wounds, so they can <br>withstand some of the Hunters’ attacks and have their say <br>before being knocked out.<br> ◆ Anything between 3 to 6 Wounds is indicated for three <br>categories of NPCs. First, are the Main NPCs of the <br>Scenario, who play a prominent role in the narrative. <br>Dark Presences and particularly dangerous enemies, <br>who even by themselves can be a match for a group of <br>Hunters, can have a larger Wound pool. A single Exchange <br>is probably not enough to defeat an opponent with 5 or <br>6 Wounds, thus giving the Storyteller the opportunity to <br>present an extended challenge.<br>James the Swordsman is engaged in a deadly duel with the <br>Masked Swashbuckler (a Dark Presence inspired by Puss in <br>Boots). After a failed Defense Check, James is slashed in his <br>right leg by his opponent, causing a Wound. The Storyteller <br>gives it the Descriptor: Slash in the leg . As this is the first <br>Wound suffered, James is still in the game, but from now on <br>declaring maneuvers that require quick movements or running <br>away could require a Check.<br>When a target receives its last Wound, its fate is decided by the <br>Player who inflicted the Wound, in accordance with what has <br>been narrated up to that point. This means that suffering the <br>last Wound does not always mean dying or being incapacitated <br>permanently. Wounds can also be psychological trauma such <br>as fear or loss of confidence. They can also be debilitating <br>statuses such as fatigue, confusion, and exhaustion. The result <br>Wounds<br>All creatures have a pool of Wounds, an indicator of their <br>ability to withstand injury and trauma. In terms of play, a <br>subject’s pool determines how many Wounds they can take <br>before being knocked out or, worse, killed. The number of <br>Wounds an NPC can suffer is established according to their <br>type.<br>Every Wound suffered must be outlined with a Descriptor, <br>which represents its effects on the narration. This will <br>become an additional element for the Storyteller to evaluate <br>when, during Checks, the Opposition Level of something <br>GIFTS</p>","markdown":""},"sort":2800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"GBiorGzHtZEUE6q5","name":"Pagina 29","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 29</h2><p>28<br>of a Position or Defense Check may have the additional <br>effect of causing a Wound.<br>The Astonishing Pied Piper Without A Name enters an <br>underground catacomb, where an evil spirit rages and <br>whispers mad words in the ears of mortals. Determined to <br>smother the ravings of the spirit with his music, the Pied <br>Piper brings his flute to his lips and breathes a sweet melody. <br>The Storyteller then asks for a Position Check to determine if <br>the Piper’s melody will really soothe the restless soul. Playing <br>the flute, the Pied Piper hears the ghost’s whispers and is lost <br>in a nightmare of dying, devoured by a mob of hungry rats. <br>This vision shakes the Hunter, who will suffer the Wound <br>Terrified by mice.<br>Recover or exhaust Wounds<br>Although it may not seem like it at first glance, Wounds are <br>a full-fledged resource, useful both for absorbing damage <br>and for activating the effects of various Gifts. A Wound is <br>easy to suffer, but it’s just as easy for a Hunter to recover.<br> ◆ At the discretion of the Storyteller, at the end of each <br>Scene where there is an obvious moment of rest (such <br>as a night of sleep), each Hunter will recover 1 Wound.<br> ◆ During an Interlude, each Hunter can choose to recover <br>1 Wound for free (instead of recovering Soma), and by <br>spending XP , heal additional Wounds.<br> ◆ For the NPCs, on the other hand, the Storyteller simply <br>evaluates whether the subject has had the opportunity <br>to recover from the damage suffered and, if so, restores <br>all their Wounds. <br>Equipment and <br>possessions<br>In Broken Tales, everything a Hunter needs and can be <br>justified by their Descriptors will be in their possession. <br>As a general rule, owning something simply expands the <br>Hunter’s storytelling possibilities, allowing to declare <br>actions that wouldn’t otherwise be possible.<br>The Astonishing Pied Piper Without A Name always has the <br>trusty trained mouse named Hamelin nearby. The Pied Piper <br>can employ his little friend for various tasks, or even complex <br>ones, such as exploiting a crack in the wall to retrieve the key <br>of the Hunters’ jail cell.<br>Weapons and Armors<br>Weapons and armor have no damage modifiers or <br>protection values; this does not make them less effective. <br>The true value of a good weapon is represented by the <br>narrative opportunities that it will give to its owner. In <br>game terms, this means that the Storyteller will evaluate <br>the usefulness of the chosen equipment every time they call <br>for a Check. Whenever possible, it is important to detail <br>an NPC’s weaponry in its Descriptor. A good alternative is <br>to focus on the fighting technique, allowing the Player to <br>decide what equipment is appropriate.<br>Consider the following:<br> ◆ A pack of hungry wolves will be at its strongest when <br>exploiting their numerical superiority, while it will be <br>less effective in the absence of the alpha wolf.<br> ◆ A skilled swordsman will be a relentless foe in single <br>combat but be at a disadvantage if thrown into the <br>chaos of a large-scale confrontation.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":2900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241712,"modifiedTime":1783973241712,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"uYLnVBaXYHouwCcx","name":"Pagina 30","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 30</h2><p>29<br> ◆ The Beast that longs for the flesh of James the <br>Swordsman will be able to crush a peg-legged pirate <br>but will be easy to circle and backstab.<br>These considerations will lead the NPC’s Opposition <br>Level to go up or down by 1, making it more or less lethal <br>depending on the situation and giving a relative meaning <br>to weapons and armor. In addition to the modifier, always <br>keep in mind what leads to a Position and Defense Check <br>during the narrative. Charging an enemy with a loaded <br>pistol will result in a Defense Check for the Hunter before <br>they can attempt a Position Check to conclude the attack.<br>Wealth and Possessions<br>In the Broken Europe of the eighteenth century, trade is <br>highly developed, but most Hunters show no interest in <br>worldly riches. The Broken Tales system does not assign <br>a precise value to every piece of equipment, and for this <br>reason, there is no real need to keep track of treasures <br>or anything else, if not for the weight they can have on a <br>narrative level. When a Hunter is preparing to obtain or <br>seek some material goods, the Storyteller must consider <br>two elements: <br>Are there any Hunter Descriptors that justify that <br>specific possession or that give the Hunter the possibility <br>to obtain it?<br>For Garou, the Old Wolf, getting horses and supplies for a <br>long journey could be tricky. All his Descriptors lead back to <br>a wild wolf who, even when in a human form, possesses no <br>wealth. Regina the Thief of Hearts, on the other hand, will <br>only need to make her requests known to some “friends” in <br>the city and receive what she wants in a short time.<br>Is the object of the search easy to find or is it a rare and <br>precious commodity? <br>In the first case, they get it. In the second case, the Storyteller <br>will reveal information on how to obtain it in the story. The <br>Hunter will then have to actively work to get their hands <br>on it. <br>Threats<br>The term Threats refers to features of the game world such <br>as special places, natural threats, and all those situations in <br>which the Hunters can be in danger but are not directly <br>facing an NPC. A drawbridge of a haunted castle or the <br>illusion of a mighty witch are both excellent examples of <br>a Threat. <br>To create a Threat, the Storyteller must establish three <br>points:<br> ◆ Create a Descriptor that indicates the characteristics of <br>the Threat. <br> ◆ Establish a Threat Opposition Level. <br> ◆ Optional: Give the Threat a Gift to represent a special <br>ability.<br>Threats are a way to formalize potential Position or Defense <br>Checks and a good way for the Storyteller to keep track of <br>what may happen during the Session. Often, a Threat will <br>be created on the fly as a direct result of a Hunter action and <br>will not require additional work for the Storyteller.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":3000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241713,"modifiedTime":1783973241713,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"rQeHm5KsQUIaWrx3","name":"Pagina 31","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 31</h2><p>30<br>NPCS<br>Sun Wukong the Amazing Monkey is chasing a mysterious <br>killer that the Hunters have caught red-handed at the crime <br>scene. The mysterious, black-cloaked figure leaps swiftly <br>across the rooftops of Prague, almost as if it were flying. Sun <br>Wukong runs after them by jumping from roof to roof. It is <br>night and it is raining, so a Defense Check will be needed to <br>keep Wukong from losing track of the target.<br>It is good practice to establish a Descriptor for each Threat, <br>in order to have a narrative reference that describes the <br>possible result of a Hunter’s current course of action.<br>Threat Gifts are simpler than those of the Hunters, as they <br>serve to represent a particular effect that activates when the <br>Hunter interacts with the Threat. The best way to create a <br>Threat Gift is to describe what happens in the story when <br>the Hunter suffers the effects of the Threat. Unlike the <br>Hunters’ Gifts, which are a balancing act, a Threat’s Gift  <br>allows you to have fun creating effects to make the Scenario <br>more interesting.<br>In the wolves’ lair, it will not be easy for the Hunters to move <br>around without being spotted. The Gift Defense Lair  (page <br>124) might be the most suitable because it forces intruders <br>to succeed at a Defense Check every Scene to avoid detection. <br>On the other hand, if the wolves in our story have pups to <br>defend, the Gift Duty Bound  (page 33) will be more <br>relevant to what we imagine could happen in the narrative <br>when the Hunters enter the lair. By describing what we <br>imagine and want to happen in the story, it becomes very <br>easy to detail the full effects of the Gift.<br>Below you will find a list of generic Gifts, to use as a basis <br>for creating Threats on the fly.<br> ◆ The Threat Gifts always must clearly state in the text <br>what activates them.<br> ◆ Unless there are valid narrative justifications, there is <br>no reason why a Threat Gift should not affect NPCs <br>as well.<br>Generic Gifts<br>This list of Gifts represents generic features adaptable to <br>every type of Threat.<br>Adverse: The Threat consumes the power of those who <br>approach. A Hunter loses 1 Soma at the start of each Scene, <br>while an NPC lowers their Opposition Level by 1 on the <br>first action taken. <br>Clock: The Threat accumulates Tokens of a certain type (see <br>page 76), in relation to the actions of the Hunters or the <br>passing of time. Once you have reached a predetermined <br>number of Tokens, activate a Special Event listed in the <br>Gift’s description. This is a good way to give importance to <br>the passage of time, or the accumulation of resources and <br>information during exploration. <br>Create Effect: When the Threat activates, it creates a <br>Descriptor representing how the situation is affected and <br>changed by the Threat.<br>Damage: When the Threat is triggered, it inflicts 1 Wound <br>of a sort linked to the type of Threat. This Wound is in <br>addition to any Wound inflicted on the Hunter because of <br>a Failed Check.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":3100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241713,"modifiedTime":1783973241713,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"h5weK8DuCgYXrAQF","name":"Pagina 32","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 32</h2><p>31<br>Disturbance: The proximity of the Threat weakens a <br>certain ability, such as magic in a holy place. Anyone near <br>the Threat receives 1 Penalty (-1 to the Opposition Level for <br>NPCs) when using abilities that are affected by the Threat’s <br>power. <br>Fulcrum: The proximity of the Threat enhances a certain <br>ability, such as magic in a place charged with arcane energy. <br>Anyone near the Threat receives 1 Additional Success (+1 <br>to the Opposition Level for NPCs) when using abilities that <br>are affected by the Threat’s power.<br>NPCs categories<br>In this part, we will explain how to create NPCs. Broken <br>Tales allows you to come up with NPCs very quickly, <br>defining only a few necessary features. The following are <br>the recommended guidelines. The Storyteller can always <br>decide to change one or more variables to best characterize <br>whoever they have in mind. For example, nothing prevents <br>you from assigning a Major NPC an Opposition Level of <br>Easy 3 to represent a person who is socially influential, but <br>totally unable to handle other situations, despite the rule <br>of thumb stating that a Major NPC will have a Medium 5 <br>Opposition Level.<br>NPCs<br>The first step is to decide what kind of NPC should be <br>created.<br>Main NPCs<br>These are the real antagonists of the Scenario or, more <br>generally, characters with an Agenda who will have a <br>strong impact on events. Main NPCs must have the skill <br>and influence to move the story in their favor or to be an <br>interesting challenge for the Hunters.<br>Minor NPCs<br>These are the people surrounding the Main Scenario NPCs. <br>A Minor NPC is almost never going to be a big challenge <br>for a Hunter and should be considered more of a link <br>between Scenario situations and Major NPCs. Given their <br>varying importance, a Minor NPC may not even have an <br>Agenda. In this way, their actions will be easier to manage <br>and connect to the Main NPCs and Hunters.<br>Dark Presences<br>Dark Presences are NPCs who, like the Hunters, come from <br>the world of fairytales and have been “broken” by the wish <br>of the Child Savior. Dark Presences feature an extra sub-<br>item, called Type, providing a general reason why the Dark <br>Presence is in the Scenario or in the world of Broken Tales. <br>Dark Presences enjoy a slightly more complex creation <br>system, illustrated on page 41. <br>NPCS</p>","markdown":""},"sort":3200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241713,"modifiedTime":1783973241713,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"6cQa8EGYx98ZbFxF","name":"Pagina 33","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 33</h2><p>32<br>NPC Type  Descriptor Agenda Wounds Opposition Level Gifts<br>Main NPC<br>Represents abilities, <br>strengths, and flaws.<br>If carried out, con-<br>siderably changes or <br>resolves the Scenario.<br>From 1 to 6, in <br>relation to their im-<br>portance. 3 Wounds <br>are considered ave-<br>rage for most human <br>NPCs.<br>Normally, Medium 5 <br>represents a solid ability <br>to oppose the Hunters’ <br>actions.<br>1 or 2, useful to give <br>a greater insight into <br>the Main NPCs’    are-<br>as of expertise.<br>Minor <br>NPC<br>Represents abilities, <br>strengths, and flaws.<br>Not mandatory. If <br>present, it’s tied to a <br>Main NPC.<br>From 1 to 3. As a <br>rule, most Minor <br>NPCs should have 1 <br>single Wound. <br>Normally, Easy 3 for <br>common examples or <br>Medium 5 for capable <br>examples.<br>1 or no Gift. Due <br>to their nature as <br>“extras” , most Minor <br>NPCs shouldn’t have <br>a Gift.<br>Dark <br>Presence<br>Represents skills <br>and the characters’ <br>connection with <br>their original <br>fairytale.<br>Representing the <br>essence of the Dark <br>Presence in the world <br>of Broken Tales.<br>From 1 to 6, in re-<br>lation to its impor-<br>tance. 3 Wounds are <br>considered average <br>for most Dark Pre-<br>sences.<br>Normally, Medium 5 to <br>represent a solid ability <br>to oppose the Hunters’ <br>actions.<br>2 Gifts, to give more <br>character to the Dark <br>Presence.<br>NPCs Gifts<br>The Gifts of NPCs are simpler than those of Hunters, as <br>they grant bonus effects in very specific areas and almost <br>never have an activation cost. The best way to create an <br>NPC Gift is to describe what happens in the story when <br>the NPC uses their Gift. Unlike the Hunters’ Gifts, which <br>need a more careful balancing act, with NPC Gifts you can <br>indulge in creating the most imaginative effects to make <br>each NPC unique and interesting.<br>Example: an NPC linked to the Vampire myth could have <br>the Immortal Gift, which makes it impossible to kill except <br>by some specific means described in the Gift itself. How <br>immortality manifests is determined by what we imagine <br>the character to do in the narrative. Will they fall under the <br>blows they have suffered, turning into a cloud of smoke or <br>will they simply ignore any Wound that is not inflicted by <br>something they’re vulnerable to? Or will their body regenerate <br>instantly in front of the incredulous eyes of those present? By <br>describing what we imagine and want to see in the narrative, <br>it becomes easy to detail the full effects of a Gift.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":3300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241713,"modifiedTime":1783973241713,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"oIj2HH2ujIsYQTBJ","name":"Pagina 34","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 34</h2><p>33<br>Below, you will find a list of generic Gifts to use as a basis <br>for creating NPCs on the fly. Y ou can also freely draw from <br>the Hunters’ Gifts and adapt effects to fit the NPC if they are <br>fairly powerful. Often, however, a Gift meant for a Hunter <br>will require some modification to be suitable for an NPC.<br> ◆ NPCs have no Soma, so Gifts that require a Soma cost <br>to activate must change so that their use is limited to <br>one or more times per Scene.<br> ◆ NPCs do not score any Additional Successes or <br>Penalties. These effects must be converted into an <br>equivalent modifier (+1/-1) that can be applied to the <br>NPC’s Opposition Level.<br> ◆ Many NPCs have few Wounds and paying a Wound to <br>activate a Gift can be a difficult cost to bear. In these <br>cases, it is best to make the activation of the Gift free <br>the first time in each Scene the NPC uses it.<br>Generic Gifts<br>This list of Gifts represents generic features adaptable to all <br>types of NPCs and creatures. <br>Ally / Minion: The NPC has a minion, animal, or some <br>kind of servant ready to lay down their lives for them. The <br>Ally / Minion is another NPC who will do their best to help <br>the owner of this Gift and, in case of danger, can shield their <br>patron and take 1 Wound in their place.<br>Armored / Thick-Skinned: The NPC can take 1 addi-<br>tional Wound or ignore a certain type of Wound such as <br>being immune to fire.<br>Destined / Duty Bound:  The NPC will not be easily <br>swayed. Once per Scene, the NPC can ignore or interrupt <br>the effect of a Gift that is used against them.<br>Determined / Devoted: Religious belief or iron determi-<br>nation means the NPC always stays calm. Any attempt to <br>persuade or manipulate the NPC through words or a power <br>related to a Broken Tale receives 2 Penalties.<br>Expert / Skilled:  Whoever possesses this Gift increases <br>their Opposition Level by 1 when they do something they <br>are masterful at. This specialization must be indicated in <br>the Gift description.<br>Foul Play / Poisoner:  Wounds this NPC inflicts are <br>made more serious by a dangerous poison. Wounds <br>inflicted in this way cannot be recovered with an Interlude <br>as usual, but only through the use of a specific antidote / <br>medication or at the end of a Scenario.<br>Gang / Herd: Whoever possesses this Gift increases their <br>Opposition Level by 1 when acting against a target if they <br>have the support of one or more companions.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":3400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241713,"modifiedTime":1783973241713,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"4wdNPcyaRaDrZJUj","name":"Pagina 35","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 35</h2><p>34<br>Intuitive / Persuasive:  The NPC is good at reading <br>whoever they face. During a social interaction, the NPC <br>can understand one of the Descriptors of the person they <br>are talking with. A Hunter can make a Defense Check to <br>avoid revealing anything about themselves.<br>Sworn Enemy / Weapon Master: The NPC is a dan-<br>gerous opponent in combat and, once per Scene, can inflict <br>1 additional Wound when an attack hits.<br>Versatile / Resourceful:  The NPC has a second De-<br>scriptor representing a very useful personal resource, such <br>as great wealth or a special combat technique. The first time <br>this is shown off in a Scene, the NPC can impose 1 Penalty <br>on any Defense Check.<br>Agenda<br>Main NPCs always have an Agenda, which establishes <br>their way of acting and helps the Storyteller manage <br>their behavior during the game. Each time an Agenda is <br>exhausted, either in success or failure, the Storyteller must <br>evaluate whether to write a new one. Agendas are very <br>important, because they give purpose and depth to NPCs <br>in a quick and functional way, suggesting their responses to <br>the Hunters’ actions during the Scenario.<br>On page 93, you will find tables and guidelines for the <br>creation of NPCs Agendas.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":3500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241713,"modifiedTime":1783973241713,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"TnufeEK8WHlb6dgg","name":"Pagina 36","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 36</h2><p>35<br>The Storyteller’s Role<br>This chapter will examine Storyteller’s role, and <br>provide useful tips for managing Sessions and Scenes. The <br>role of the Storyteller differs from that of other Players <br>in terms of duties and narrative authority over the game <br>world. Where the Hunters are the protagonists of Broken <br>Tales’ stories, the Storyteller is responsible for presenting a <br>world that is coherent and managing everything that is not <br>the direct prerogative of a Hunter. The Storyteller makes <br>decisions for NPCs, determines when Scenes open and <br>close, and generally looks at the game with a different eye. <br>The role of the Storyteller is equivalent to that of a movie <br>director, who, however, does not have an immutable script. <br>Instead, they shape what could happen if the Hunters <br>do not intervene, and improvise with a certain degree of <br>freedom. In this way, each Scenario will be unique and <br>tailored to each group.<br>How the Storyteller acts during a <br>Session<br>The game is a conversation where the Storyteller presents <br>various situations and the Players deal with them by <br>narrating how their Hunters act. For a Player, storytelling <br>duties are all related to their Hunter and to some information <br>about their past. For the Storyteller, however, the spectrum <br>of agency is much broader. <br>But how, then, does the Storyteller act during a Session?<br>Giving life to Broken Europe<br>Broken Tales’ setting is a version of eighteenth-century <br>Europe where rural landscapes are still predominant. The <br>Hunters often travel to small villages and abandoned places, <br>where the Broken Tales can find fertile ground in which <br>to act away from the gaze of ordinary people. The Broken <br>Tales’ existence is an anomaly. At the same time, they need <br>contact with people and reality to pursue their goals. This <br>duality will inevitably create conflicts and problems. It is up <br>to the Storyteller to bring out these elements, which form <br>the basis of the events of Broken Tales’ stories, in play. The <br>key principles of the setting are:<br> ◆ The world of Broken Tales, Broken Europe, is <br>a massive fairytale that encompasses all other <br>fairytales within it. This concept will be explained <br>better when we discuss the Campaign (page 243). For <br>now, it is good to keep in mind that Broken Europe <br>is a fictional world that lays its foundations in the <br>real historical context of the era, and then corrupts <br>everything with out-of-the-box characters, magic, and <br>a strong horror vibe.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":3600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241713,"modifiedTime":1783973241713,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"AHB4f58N3P2huKNh","name":"Pagina 37","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 37</h2><p>36<br> ◆ The stories the Hunters live out will almost always <br>take place in a rural setting. The section on Broken <br>Europe on page 103 will provide useful information <br>to manage and present a plausible eighteenth century. <br>In this context, the Storyteller’s prerogative must be <br>to break the fairytales, place them in this plausible <br>context, and give each character a purpose and a reason <br>to use the powers that distinguish them.<br>By choosing or creating a Scenario<br>The Hunters are part of the Order and intervene when <br>there is a cry for help against the darkness. The Storyteller <br>decides which Scenario to present from those found in this <br>book or creates one from scratch. In the case of a Campaign, <br>the Storyteller can manage everything as explained on page <br>243.<br>By shaping the initial situation of each Scene<br>This is a great power: the Storyteller decides how a Scene <br>begins and who will be there. They describe places and <br>situations, and only when the Scene is clearly understood <br>by everyone will they leave the stage to the Hunters. After <br>the first Scene, it will be easier to set up the following <br>ones, because in most cases it will be the Hunters who will <br>specify a new objective. The Storyteller will simply have <br>to decide what happens between one Scene and the next, <br>and how the new situation begins. Between two Scenes, <br>the Storyteller must keep track of what is happening and <br>possibly “move” the NPCs, if they have already appeared <br>in a previous Scene, according to their Agenda. There is <br>no predefined style regarding how to set up a Scene. The <br>Storyteller introduces everything that seems relevant to the <br>situation and goals of the Hunters, asking questions of the <br>Players to understand how the story should unfold.<br>By managing information<br>The Storyteller knows many secrets and will often see all <br>the mysteries of the Scenario clearly from the beginning. <br>Their task is to disclose information according to the <br>questions and actions of the Hunters. Since the Storyteller’s <br>goal is for the Hunters to advance from Scene to Scene <br>towards the conclusion of the Scenario, they should never <br>deny information, as explained on page 16. This does not <br>mean helping the Hunters or offering NPCs with ready-<br>made solutions. Hunters must always be at the center of the <br>Scene, while NPCs must act in response to their actions, <br>with information acting as the glue between the two.<br>Considering when to call a Check<br>The last important responsibility of the Storyteller is <br>to manage the transition from narration to resolution <br>through Position and Defense Checks. As explained in the <br>rules, the Storyteller must always be certain of a Hunter’s <br>intent when evaluating whether to request a Position <br>Check. Broken Tales allows you to act on the granularity <br>of events, “zooming in” on a particularly important scene <br>and splitting it into multiple “close-up shots” , or keep a <br>“wide shot” to solve a macro-situation in one go. The most <br>striking example of this granularity can be found during <br>fight Scenes: all the parties involved will act to harm the <br>opponents on multiple actions and, most likely, failure will <br>have painful consequences. In a conflict, the Hunters will <br>describe action after action and generate many Checks. <br>Conversely, an action to infiltrate a location protected by <br>guards could be resolved with a single Position Check <br>made by the Hunter leading the raid. <br>As a general rule, before requesting a Check, the <br>Storyteller must ask themselves the following question: <br>Does Succeeding or Failing the Check have an interesting <br>narrative outcome? <br>If the answer is yes, then it’s okay to call a Check.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":3700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241713,"modifiedTime":1783973241713,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"RAvwMqftoAqqjEKc","name":"Pagina 38","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 38</h2><p>37<br>By fostering a safe and inclusive gaming <br>environment<br>Role-playing is an activity that can easily expose delicate <br>issues, offending the sensibility of some Players. Broken <br>Tales is no exception and the themes of the Scenarios can <br>be difficult to deal with for some people. Each Scenario <br>includes a series of Keywords useful for getting a quick <br>understanding of the situations that could arise during the <br>game. In this way, the Storyteller will be able to evaluate <br>what to offer to the table and whether or not to list the <br>Keywords to the Players. It must be noted that Keywords <br>might reveal characters and situations, spoiling some <br>aspects of the plot.<br>Another good way to handle difficult issues is to modify <br>the Scenario based on Keywords. If the story includes <br>the Keywords Sect and Manipulation, the Storyteller <br>can modify those elements in the plot, transforming the <br>members of the sect into something else. For example, a <br>gang at the service of the villain. <br>The best advice, however, remains to speak and listen to <br>each Player and be accommodating to their sensitivity. <br>Often, simply hinting at what happened in a given situation <br>and not dwelling on the details is a good way to run the <br>Scenario as it’s written without impacting the fun factor at <br>the table.<br>Finally, even if it may seem trivial, it is good to remember <br>that Broken Tales is a dark horror game with a focus on <br>the distortion of traditional fairytales, switching the roles <br>of hero and villain. Approaching the game with appropriate <br>expectations is essential to avoiding nasty surprises. After <br>all, you wouldn’t go to the movie theater to see a scary <br>movie if you hated the horror genre, right?<br>Tips for proper game <br>management<br>The following is a series of good procedures that can be <br>useful to the Storyteller and clear up any doubts about <br>various game situations.<br>Establish the initial description of the Scene<br>Take into consideration the place, the time of day, and other <br>characters present. The Hunters see the world through the <br>Storyteller, who filters what has yet to be discovered from <br>what has already been revealed. For this reason, you can <br>provide whatever information may be useful when the <br>Scene opens. After the initial description, ask the Hunters <br>questions to dispel doubts and better specify all the required <br>details.<br>Manage NPCs Agenda<br>Agendas are essential for keeping track of the opponent’s <br>possible actions in the Scenario. Checking the Agenda of <br>everyone involved in the Scene, and what those encountered <br>in previous Scenes might do, is a good way to clarify NPC <br>motivations and have them act consistently.<br>Ask questions and build on the answers<br>Questions are a great resource. Through a question, the <br>Storyteller can better understand the intention of a Hunter <br>or detail a Scene and a place. Whenever they deem it useful, <br>it is good for the Storyteller to ask questions and build on <br>the answers given by the Hunters.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":3800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241713,"modifiedTime":1783973241713,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"qUnN3BMmCgvLz9nV","name":"Pagina 39","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 39</h2><p>38<br>Give every Hunter the spotlight<br>The protagonists of the stories are the Hunters. Everything <br>starts with them and from them come the decisions that <br>will bring the Scenario to its conclusion. From a Hunter’s <br>sheet, you can glean many elements useful in building an <br>interesting Session. Gifts also reveal a lot about a Hunter’s <br>abilities. Presenting situations where the Gifts can stand out <br>is a good way to give a Player a chance to take action.<br>Interpret the rules and manage Position <br>Checks<br>The Storyteller has the last word on the interpretation of a <br>rule. This does not mean handing judgments from on high <br>as a superior and unfailing authority. The dialogue between <br>Players is essential, but it makes sense to save discussions of <br>rules for after the Session when it won’t stop the game. The <br>most “critical” mechanic to manage is understanding when <br>to call for a Check. This is because, as already mentioned, <br>the same action can be divided into more or fewer Position <br>and Defense Checks to better highlight the drama. This <br>decision is up to the Storyteller, as Players will instinctively <br>try to perform as few Checks as possible. After all, making <br>a Check means risking Failure or losing precious Soma <br>points. A good way to handle the breakdown of a situation <br>is to ask often: What are you doing now? This simple <br>question stops your description of the action and shifts the <br>responsibility to the Players: the narrative has entered a <br>new phase.<br>Manage the results of the Hunters’ actions<br>The result of the Hunters’ actions is a vital element of the <br>game. The Storyteller describes the results of a Position <br>Check, but with the goal of staying true to what the Hunter <br>expects to achieve. It is simple and easy to work from the <br>intent of the Players. Isn’t that what motivated a certain <br>action? From this point of view, the Increments must <br>confirm the Hunter’s success and the Costs must temper <br>the success of an action that has, in any case, achieved the <br>desired result. <br>The real reason the Storyteller manages Costs and <br>Increments is to make the game run smoother. Otherwise, <br>the narrative would stop with each Check to allow the <br>Hunter to choose an effect from a list. There is no good <br>reason not to give a Hunter what they want if they already <br>have a clear idea of how their success can become even <br>cooler.<br>Stay anchored to the story as it’s played <br>and not to whatever you have prepared in <br>advance<br>Even if you have an understanding of Scenario development <br>and detailed descriptions of NPCs and situations, the game <br>will suffer if you focus on what you expected of the Hunters <br>and not what they actually do. Scenarios are designed with <br>an open structure and the Agenda of the NPCs is intended <br>to make it easy to quickly come up with a consistent <br>reaction based on the Hunters’ moves. By default, the plot <br>is not decided by the Scenario but created directly at the <br>table. If a game group prefers a more classic structure, each <br>Scenario provides a Scene Tree to follow that will help you <br>set up a game more focused on story discovery and less tied <br>to improvisation.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":3900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241713,"modifiedTime":1783973241713,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"B3scoBfPE7XvPLX1","name":"Pagina 40","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 40</h2><p>39<br>If necessary, pause the game and ask other <br>Players for assistance<br>The Storyteller does not have to fear stalemate situations. <br>Sooner or later, it will happen that the Hunters make a <br>decision so unusual as to undermine all expectations about <br>what could happen. In these moments, pause the game and <br>make it clear that you need a moment to rearrange your <br>ideas. The Storyteller is not an entertainer and doesn’t owe <br>the Players any more than the opportunity to have fun. <br>While the Storyteller thinks, Players can take a break or <br>organize themselves to play a Memory Scene. For example, <br>two Hunters can play through a flashback in which they <br>confront each other in an argument, or in which NPCs are <br>present, perhaps interpreted by the other Players. Players <br>will kill time and have the chance to bring the Downside <br>into play and accumulate some precious XP , while the <br>Storyteller prepares for a return in style.<br>Do not call Position Checks ahead of time<br>While Position and Defense Checks look similar, they are <br>actually very different. A Position Check transports the <br>Hunter into a new narrative phase where the Hunter’s Player <br>gains the authority to decide whether to do something  and <br>why, taking a calculated amount of risk. Defense Checks, <br>on the other hand, are born as a side effect of the Hunter’s <br>action, and therefore are the ace up the Storyteller’s sleeve <br>to respond to actions and place the Hunters in danger.<br>Don’t make the Hunters look incompetent<br>Make the Hunters’ failures interesting moments, rather <br>than humorous sketches where a Hunter fails miserably. <br>Even the Descriptors’ Downsides are <br>excellent narrative hooks that can <br>put the Hunters on the spot. Use <br>them to create an exciting game <br>where Hunters are the heroes.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":4000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241713,"modifiedTime":1783973241713,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"pEIb7fA34AHgMmb6","name":"Pagina 41","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 41</h2><p>40<br>Don’t pressure yourself<br>Whenever possible, boil things down to two factions, <br>review Agendas between one Scene and the next to evaluate <br>how to move the NPCs, and take enough time to set the <br>stage for upcoming events. The Storyteller shouldn’t be in a <br>hurry to throw everything in the face of the Hunters right <br>away. It’s best to focus on a single Scene and a few NPCs to <br>better keep track of the situation. The more elements in the <br>spotlight, the more the Hunters will have distractions and <br>things to reflect upon, significantly slowing down the pace <br>of the game.<br>Make fights dynamic<br>Even if the rules feature the Exchange system, the narrative <br>of Broken Tales must always remain in the foreground and <br>account for the Hunters’ tactical choices. <br>A fight is always part of the story and will be more <br>interesting if the actions of different participants in the <br>Scene are handled with more flexibility, compared to the <br>classic procedure of attacking someone only when it’s your <br>turn. It is vital to remember that every NPC has an Agenda <br>that clearly determines what they want to achieve. Rarely <br>will that goal be fighting to the death against the Hunters. <br>Suddenly running away, overturning a wardrobe to block <br>someone, or setting fire to some part of the setting to make <br>it more dangerous, are all legitimate actions to be processed <br>first in the narrative, and only then by the rules. <br>Similarly, a fight does not end when all of the enemy’s <br>Wounds are depleted, but when the narrative makes it <br>clear that one of the two sides has won. The simplest rule <br>for handling a fight is to ask “what would this NPC do with <br>their action now, to fulfill their Agenda?”, and then narrate, <br>consequently, what happens in the fiction. The application <br>of the rules with Check, Gifts, and other mechanics, will <br>simply be a result of the choices made in the narrative.<br>Join the dots<br>A Scenario features a set of NPCs, Places, and possible <br>situations to create a connected macro-plot, but one <br>that will inevitably be tested by the actions and powers <br>of the Hunters. This is a good thing. They are the heroes <br>of the story and they are the ones who possess Gifts and <br>abilities that can make a difference. The Storyteller’s job <br>is to rearrange the Scenario after every Scene, having fun <br>working out the NPCs’ moves in relation to those of the <br>Hunters. Pursuing the Agenda of the NPCs, the Storyteller <br>must play like the others to see how it ends, not pigeonhole <br>the story in a pre-written path. Each Scenario in this book <br>can have an infinite number of very different endings – it <br>makes no sense to limit this creative potential. Perhaps <br>the most important task of the Storyteller is to use their <br>resources jointly with the Hunters, without ever worrying <br>that the story will take an unexpected turn.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":4100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241713,"modifiedTime":1783973241713,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"DtAmthUxKAIan61Q","name":"Pagina 42","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 42</h2><p>41<br>The creation process for Dark Presences follows the <br>same pattern as that for Hunters. It requires you to push a <br>fairytale character to their Breaking Point, then give it new <br>life in the world of Broken Tales. Dark Presences are for all <br>intent and purposes NPCs with a background connected <br>to the original fairytale, but aren’t specific to a Scenario. <br>Within the world of Broken Europe, a Dark Presence can <br>take on a life of its own. This makes them versatile figures, <br>which the Storyteller can drop in any Scenario or Campaign <br>to assist or oppose the Hunters.<br>Every Dark Presence must be born <br>from a fairytale<br>The starting point is deciding which fairytale character to <br>“break” in order to create their new version in the world of <br>Broken Tales. <br> ◆ Any source for the fairytale will do, whether it’s a book <br>or just a website.<br> ◆ Based on the original story, you have to decide what <br>kind of Dark Presence you want to create.<br>An Opponent is a Dark Presence meant to be an enemy. <br>Their Gifts will mainly be skills that put the Hunters <br>in trouble. NPCs with a mercenary or hired assassin <br>background would make excellent Opponents, as would <br>anyone unburdened by scruples.<br>An Ally is a Dark Presence aiding the Hunters. Their Gifts <br>will primarily serve a support function. Hunters will be <br>able to invoke or activate them in time of need. Allies are <br>often Order-bound NPCs – that’s why they are ready to <br>serve the Hunters.<br>Finally, a Neutral Dark Presence is a type of NPC with a <br>personal goal unrelated to the Order or what the Hunters <br>do. These NPCs can be both Allies or Opponents of the <br>Hunters, depending on their Agenda.<br>By following the following steps, it will be easy <br>to decide the inclination of a Dark Presence.<br>Dark Presences</p>","markdown":""},"sort":4200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241713,"modifiedTime":1783973241713,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ntYnEnjByBO54t7T","name":"Pagina 43","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 43</h2><p>42<br>Step 1 Bring the character <br>to their Breaking Point <br>Underline and take notes on all the interesting words or <br>phrases in the original fairytale. These will become the <br>Keywords. Keywords are narrative flags useful in detailing <br>all aspects of a Dark Presence. For some words or phrases, <br>the meaning of a Keyword should be flipped. This step is <br>necessary to reach the Breaking Point and transform the <br>classic character into its distorted version. <br>It’s now time to detail a story and give a background to the <br>Dark Presence. For historical notes and context, use the <br>Europe of 1780 as a reference. However, there is no need to <br>limit yourself to historical truth. <br>Step 2 Assign the <br>characteristics <br>We start by defining the Dark Presence’s Descriptor. A <br>Descriptor consists of a couple of sentences that must <br>summarize what the Dark Presence does and what <br>capabilities they have. As with a Hunter’s Descriptor, <br>the Dark Presence Descriptor can have a downside. The <br>Descriptor must make it clear who the Dark Presence is in <br>a few sentences.<br>We then establish how many Wounds the Dark Presence <br>can suffer, starting from 1 to a maximum of 6. Keep in <br>mind that the number of Wounds is not an indication of <br>the NPC’s power, only of their narrative “stamina” . An NPC <br>can be easy to knock out (1 Wound), but very capable and <br>powerful (Opposition Level 7 Hard). Generally speaking, <br>the average Dark Presence has 3 Wounds. <br>Finally, you have to decide on an Opposition Level (Easy <br>3, Medium 5, Hard  7). This is a general indicator of the <br>NPC’s strength. Medium 5 is the “standard” level for the <br>Dark Presence, Easy 3 is for less capable NPCs, while Hard <br>7 is only for the most powerful and dangerous subjects.<br>Step 3 Create the Gifts<br>Each Dark Presence must have at least two Gifts that <br>represent abilities, powers, or something special they can <br>do. Keywords will be of great help in staying consistent. <br>The basic rule is to describe what  happens during the <br>narration when the Dark Presence uses their Gift. Using <br>the description can clarify what the mechanical effect of the <br>Gift should be.<br> ◆ Gifts for Opponents must be aimed at fighting or <br>disrupting the Hunters. <br> ◆ Gifts for Allies must be formulated so that Hunters can <br>activate them in order to obtain a supporting effect. <br>It is also often useful to assign an Archetypal Cost (as <br>explained on page 81) to balance the Gift’s potential <br>benefit to the Hunters.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":4300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"dhyN2HwNaU0dL7c9","name":"Pagina 44","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 44</h2><p>43<br>A Gift Example for an Ally Dark Presence: Sinbad<br>Gift - Traveler of a Thousand Places: Sinbad has seen the whole world and much <br>of what the Broken Tales hide. In the course of a Scene, a Hunter can invoke his help <br>to obtain information or create an additional Descriptor that represents a specific <br>area of Sinbad’s knowledge. But the old sailor is an eccentric type, and to provide his <br>help he first must be entertained. The Storyteller will evaluate the current situation <br>and Sinbad’s level of boredom. A Hunter can capture Sinbad’s interest with creative <br>actions, as long as they’re appropriate to the current Scene.<br>Step 4 Agenda<br>The last step is to establish an Agenda for the Dark Presence, which <br>is a short sentence that determines a motivation for their actions. <br>The Agenda must be contextualized with the character’s story <br>or the Scenario in which the Dark Presence will be used. If <br>the Dark Presence comes from a fairytale from which one <br>of the Hunters was drawn, it’s possible to detail a Special <br>Agenda representing some connection between the <br>two.<br>Note: Some of the Special Agendas in the following <br>pages refer to Hunters featured in The Broken Ones <br>expansion book.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":4400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"RLkEfrx4fZE4mJel","name":"Pagina 45","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 45</h2><p>44<br>Ambrose the Sorcerer <br>known as Old Merlin<br>Inspired by Merlin from the Arthurian Myth (Neutral)<br>Deep mysteries still surround wielders of magic and their secret, <br>centuries-old struggle for control of the arcane world. Some legends tell <br>of the two most outstanding practitioners of arcane arts: Baba Yaga, the <br>witch forced into the body of a child, and Ambrose, constrained into <br>the body of a tired old man. Under the false name of Merlin, Ambrose <br>has been pulling the strings of humanity’s destiny for centuries. He <br>pretends to be of service to those who need him most, while in truth his <br>actions only strengthen his position. Many seek the old hermit Merlin for <br>advice or help, unaware that the only support he dispenses is that which <br>supports himself. With each new petitioner, the ancient sorcerer grows <br>ever closer to absolute power.<br>Descriptor: I am an ancient sorcerer, my body is weak, but my magical <br>power is unmatched.<br>1 Wound <br>Opposition Level: Hard 7 <br>Agenda: Pretending to be a wise old man who is always ready to <br>help others with the proper advice / Gaining personal advantage by <br>manipulating others. <br>Special Agenda (Baba Yaga):  I both respect and hate Yaga. <br>Hers is the only power that can stand against mine. While the laws of <br>magic prevent me from killing her directly, nothing prevents me from <br>maneuvering her into danger. And if she perishes due to her own <br>foolishness, all the better.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":4500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"zFcqWdMwY9jyHBMb","name":"Pagina 46","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 46</h2><p>45<br>Special Agenda (Morgana of the Lake):  I fear the <br>power of the greatest sorceress of all time. Thanks to an <br>agreement with Baba Yaga, we have sealed the memory of <br>young Morgana. I will do whatever it takes to keep her from <br>awakening.<br>Note: Morgana of the Lake is one of the Hunters featured <br>in The Broken Ones expansion book.<br>Special Agenda (Marina the Sea Explorer): I respect <br>Marina as a skilled witch and I seek her aid against Baba <br>Yaga. Obviously, once my great enemy is defeated, I will have <br>to make sure that Marina does not take her place.<br>Gift – Ancient Sorcerer:  Merlin’s power is incredible, <br>achieving practically anything he can think of through the <br>use of magic. Those who rely on his advice will be able, once <br>per Session, to activate the magic power that the wizard has <br>infused within them. The magical effects must be decided <br>at the time that Merlin blesses the character by defining an <br>appropriate Descriptor such as: Taking flight like a bird  or <br>Having skin as hard as a stone. Whoever carries Merlin’s <br>magic can activate its power once, obtaining the Descriptor <br>for the entire Scene. Once the Scene resolves the magic is <br>drained from the player and cannot be activated again.<br>Gift – Wise Advice:  Merlin will never intervene <br>personally but can appear in a dream or vision to his <br>protégés. Once per Scenario, a Hunter can spend 1 Soma <br>to summon Merlin’s help. The sorcerer will appear with <br>helpful information or to bless the character with one of <br>his spells.<br>Frog Face<br>Inspired by The Frog Prince (Neutral)<br>Once upon a time, the heir of a noble family was born <br>deformed. His face was broad and covered with pustules, his <br>eyes huge and yellow, and his skin a frog-like green. Destroyed <br>by grief, the young man’s mother wished to keep him hidden <br>from the world until he came of age. However, his father’s <br>untimely death made him the new head of the family. Locked <br>in a world of fairytales and lies by his mother, the young scion <br>was convinced that he was the victim of a curse that only a <br>kiss from someone truly in love could break. For years, Frog <br>Face tried to find love and break the spell, receiving in return <br>only rejection and contempt. On the verge of madness, Frog <br>Face decided that if he couldn’t have true love, he would take <br>someone else’s. Since that day, Frog Face travels accompanied <br>by his trusty servant Heinrich. The two spy on people and <br>when they find a couple in love, they kidnap one of the two <br>lovers to snatch a kiss. This perpetuates a vicious circle of hope <br>and disappointment that always culminates in the killing of <br>those who, in the eyes of Frog Face, do not nurture a love pure <br>enough to break the curse.<br>Descriptor: I am a wealthy, deformed noble, using my <br>resources to achieve my purposes.<br>3 Wounds <br>Opposition Level: Easy 3<br>Agenda: Find someone truly in love and force them to kiss <br>me to regain a normal appearance.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":4600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"aTiZAnhjFbbmFTlt","name":"Pagina 47","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 47</h2><p>46<br>Gift - By Any Means: Frog Face’s only desire is to break <br>the “curse” that afflicts him. When he is trying to obtain <br>something that obviously brings him closer to his goal, his <br>Opposition Level becomes Hard 7.<br>Gift - True Love’s Kiss:  After years of experimental <br>medicine, Frog Face’s saliva has acquired strange attributes. <br>Whoever is kissed or licked by Frog Face will go into a daze <br>for the rest of the Scene, lowering their Opposition Level <br>by 2 (in the case of an NPC) or receiving 2 Penalties at <br>each Check (in the case of a Hunter). A Hunter can make a <br>Defense Check to resist the effects of True Love’s Kiss.<br>Heinrich the Trustworthy<br>Descriptor: I am the old family coachman, the only one <br>who knows the truth about my master. Over time, the grief <br>for his fate has driven me mad.<br>3 Wounds <br>Opposition Level: Medium 5<br>Agenda: To help my lord realize his crazy dream, preserving <br>him from a truth he would not accept.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":4700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"RZf8k6HdhWwBzMAD","name":"Pagina 48","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 48</h2><p>47<br>Once upon a time, there was a young <br>girl who lived in the Far East. When <br>they drafted her old father for war, <br>the young woman pretended to be a <br>boy to take his place, as women were <br>not allowed to be soldiers at the time. <br>Under the false name of Hua Mulan, <br>the young warrior won every battle <br>and brought glory to her army, but <br>when her true identity was discovered, <br>envious generals took advantage of it to <br>accuse her of deception and betrayal. <br>Branded and exiled, the warrior fled <br>her home, eventually reaching Europe <br>after a long and wandering journey. <br>Tired and embittered at finding the <br>same sort of injustice wherever she <br>went, Hua Mulan decided she would <br>run no more. She made a disguise of her <br>ancestral armor, hiding her face behind <br>the features of a snarling demon. Under <br>the name of the Sword Demon, the <br>warrior now wanders around Europe, <br>wielding her blade against everything <br>that represents the status quo, such as <br>the Order itself.<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled warrior <br>and have won a thousand battles. I hate <br>injustice and I know that the way of the <br>sword is the only answer.<br>3 Wounds <br>Opposition Level: Hard 7<br>Agenda: Punishing injustice and <br>righting wrongs using the only tongue <br>the vile can understand – the language <br>of the blade / Deep in my heart I hope <br>to find someone who can show me what <br>true justice is.<br>Gift - Legendary Warrior:  The <br>Sword Demon’s prowess is unmatched. <br>During the course of a Scene, an <br>enemy will not be able to use the same <br>Gift twice against the Sword Demon. <br>Having seen them in action once, <br>the Demon will always find a way to <br>anticipate the enemy and counter <br>their strategy.<br>Gift - The Demon Blade:  Any <br>edged weapon wielded by the Sword <br>Demon becomes lethal. With her <br>weapon, the Demon can cut through <br>solid objects, stop arrows, and even <br>dispel magic. Thanks to her iron will, <br>the Sword Demon can defend herself <br>against any type of attack, canceling <br>the narrative advantage given by any <br>associated Descriptors.<br>Hua Mulan the <br>Sword Demon     <br>Inspired by the legend of Hua Mulan <br>(Opponent)</p>","markdown":""},"sort":4800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"gfH2fpgbL84MQIdv","name":"Pagina 49","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 49</h2><p>48<br>The Periwinkle Peer<br>Inspired by Prince Charming (Opponent)<br>Once upon a time, there was a handsome nobleman born <br>the heir to a wealthy family. The Young Lord was famous <br>for his prized, periwinkle blue cloak, which would catch <br>every eye whenever he entered a room. But despite everyone’s <br>admiration and every young woman claiming him as a lover, <br>the lordling was obsessed with only one thing: perfection. The <br>Young Lord’s parents were the only ones who knew of their <br>son’s bedeviling compulsion, which in the past had <br>driven him to kill his brother, executed for the <br>crime of being a better horseman. Blinded by love, <br>the Young Lord’s parents pushed him into a <br>military career. The Young Lord rose through <br>the ranks quickly, driven as he ever was to <br>excel. Then, he learned of sordid intrigues <br>that could be used to garner preferment <br>and promotion. His madness <br>resurfaced, eventually driving him to <br>murder once more. A wanted man <br>and a deserter, today the Young <br>Lord wanders endlessly, always <br>looking for challenges to prove <br>his superiority, putting himself <br>at the service of anyone who <br>praises his perfection.<br>Descriptor: I am the best <br>at everything I do and I must <br>win every challenge. I do not <br>excel in science and academic <br>knowledge, but no one must <br>discover this weakness of mine. I prefer to show off my <br>physical prowess and skill.<br>3 Wounds <br>Opposition Level: Medium 5 <br>Agenda: I must prove my perfection, even if it means <br>drowning doubters in blood.<br>Gift - Obsession for Perfection:  The Periwinkle Peer <br>draws strength from the drive to win every challenge. When <br>an enemy succeeds in a Defense Check against his action, <br>the Peer gets +1 to his Opposition Level for the rest of the <br>Scene. This bonus is cumulative. Once per Scene, when the <br>Peer receives his final Wound, he will mock his enemy <br>in a fit of rage and grit his teeth to keep from being <br>knocked out, immediately recovering 1 Wound.<br>Gift - Divine Charm:  The Periwinkle Peer <br>possesses good looks and charm out of <br>the ordinary. With his mere presence, <br>he is able to beguile anyone. During <br>a Scene in which he is present, the <br>Storyteller can create an Agenda <br>for a Minor NPC that describes <br>their infatuation with the Peer. <br>This Agenda is more important <br>than all of the NPC’s past ties, and <br>also any pacts they might have <br>struck with the Hunters. The Peer <br>can also influence Major NPCs (at <br>the Storyteller’s discretion) or a <br>Hunter. In this case, the Player will <br>create a Descriptor that represents</p>","markdown":""},"sort":4900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"AKPHHCbtCLUBhxBS","name":"Pagina 50","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 50</h2><p>49<br>how The Periwinkle Peer impressed the Hunter. This <br>new Descriptor lasts until the next Interlude and can be <br>marked as usual to get XP .<br>The Ancient Enemy<br>Inspired by the Dragon (Neutral)<br>Once upon a time, there lived an ancient and mighty <br>creature who had been a witness to the world’s unfolding <br>since time immemorial. Frightened mortals called it Draco, <br>fearing its proud bearing and immeasurable power. But <br>despite his fearsome appearance, Draco wasn’t evil, just <br>curious. In hopes of creating another of his kind, as he <br>had watched countless mortals do, Draco laid an egg once <br>every century. Each time, evil and unscrupulous men took <br>possession of it before it could be hatched, leaving him <br>alone. After a thousand years, despair stole Draco’s ability <br>to lay more eggs. The bitter truth was, to lay an egg was to <br>condemn it to an evil fate. Even today, it is said that Draco <br>keeps waiting for a person with a pure soul, able to show <br>kindness and compassion enough to warm his heart, thereby <br>giving him hope for the future. Meanwhile, the lying legends <br>of a great dragon, an ancient Enemy of mortals, have <br>spread, reinforced by self-serving tales grown into myths <br>and superstitions. More and more fools seek glory by setting <br>out in search of the Ancient Enemy, invoking the grace of <br>God’s protection, to slay the legend once and for all.<br>Descriptor: I am an ancient and powerful creature. <br>My body was formed in the fires of creation and common <br>weapons can do nothing against me.<br>6 Wounds <br>Opposition Level: Hard 7 <br>Agenda: To live in solitude and avoid contact with <br>humans, even if deep in my heart I still want to believe that <br>there is a mortal worthy of my respect.<br>Special Agenda (St. George the Dragon Slayer):  I <br>hate St. George because he is a symbol of those who judge <br>others blindly, overawed by faith. I want to humiliate him <br>and make those who believe in him see St. George as the <br>lowest of the low.<br>Gift - Colossal Body:  Draco possesses a colossal body <br>and is capable of flying at great speed. During a Scene <br>or Exchange, he can act 3 times instead of once: with his <br>powerful bite, with his front legs, and with his long tail. <br>Draco’s strength is so great that each of his actions inflicts <br>1 additional Wound. Finally, Draco can spit flames from <br>his mouth once per Scene, making an area attack in front <br>of him, engulfing everything in flames.<br>Gift – The Power of the Myth:  Draco is one of the <br>most powerful beings of any myth and, in the course <br>of a Scene, he can use the following powers at will: 1. <br>Shapeshifter: Take on the appearance of an ordinary <br>human or an animal.  2. Magicbreaker:  Immediately <br>cancel the effect of a spell or arcane object that has been <br>used in his presence (the user can attempt a Defense <br>Check to avoid the effect of this power). 3. Gift of the  <br>Dragon: Shed a piece of his body, such as a scale or a tooth, <br>which can be used to forge objects with extraordinary <br>powers.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":5000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"RMn2SymnK50xUHWA","name":"Pagina 51","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 51</h2><p>50<br>The Wild Swans Gang<br>Inspired by the Wild Swans (Opponent)<br>Once upon a time, there were eleven bold brothers, sons of an amiable <br>nobleman. All were deeply attached to their younger sister Elisa and treated <br>her like a queen. When the father remarried, the new wife, jealous of all the <br>attention that the family reserved for Elisa, made a pact with Morgana, the <br>famous witch, to cast a powerful curse. The brothers were turned into swans <br>and Elisa was blamed for it. Accused of being a sorcerer and cast out by <br>her father, Elisa wandered for months looking for a new home. Finally, she <br>reached another region, where she was welcomed by a local noble who soon <br>fell in love with her beauty. Elisa began living happily, regularly meeting her <br>brothers, who in the meantime had been looking for a way to break the curse <br>cast upon them. Elisa started to study magic to help them, but this attracted <br>the attention of the prelate of the country who, fearing the worst, requested <br>the Order’s intervention. Upon reaching Elisa’s presence, the Hunters noted <br>her propensity for magic and took her away, turning her over to the papal <br>inquisitors. When the eleven brothers found out, they cried bitter tears for <br>their sister’s fate and swore revenge against the Order, waging war in the hope <br>of finding Elisa alive.<br>Descriptor: We are a band of brothers and we specialize in fighting the <br>Order’s emissaries. Thanks to the curse that has been inflicted on us, we can <br>transform into swans.<br>1 Wound (for each of the 11 gang members)<br>Opposition Level: Medium 5</p>","markdown":""},"sort":5100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Q0Bc1xGeGmPGvemi","name":"Pagina 52","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 52</h2><p>51<br>Agenda: Defeat the Hunters of the Order and find Elisa / <br>Save Elisa from the clutches of the Order, even if it means <br>destroying it.<br>Special Agenda (Morgana of the Lake):  We learned <br>that everything that happened to us is the fault of Morgana <br>the Witch, so we want to kidnap and force her to save Elisa <br>with her magic.<br>Note: Morgana of the Lake is one of the Hunters featured <br>in The Broken Ones expansion book.<br>Gift – Change into a Swan:  A member of the Wild <br>Swans Gang can transform into a swan at will. The <br>transformation is immediate. When it happens, it gives him <br>the new Descriptor: I am a wild swan – I can fly well, but <br>I maintain my human consciousness. The gang member’s <br>clothing, items, and other possessions are never lost during <br>the transformation.<br>Gift – The Swans Gang:  When a member of the gang <br>acts and has at least one partner to support him, he <br>increases his Opposition Level by 1. If at least 3 members <br>focus on supporting the same action, whoever performs it <br>increases the Opposition Level by 3 points.<br>The Silent<br>Inspired by The Little Mermaid (Opponent)<br>Once upon a time, there was a young Mermaid who was <br>captured by a fisherman. Sensing her worth, the greedy <br>fisherman gave the Mermaid as a tribute to the local <br>nobleman. He displayed her as an exotic animal, fascinating <br>everyone, but particularly the nobleman’s son. Over time, the <br>young man began to look at the Mermaid with different eyes, <br>and his curiosity turned into passion. The two consummated <br>a forbidden desire, which led the young Mermaid to feel <br>sincere love for her prince. The feeling was, unfortunately, not <br>reciprocated. As soon as the opportunity arose, the nobleman’s <br>son left the family home to get married. The Mermaid was <br>sold to a circus, destined to end her days as a sideshow <br>monster frightening fools with her misery. The meeting with <br>a mysterious witch named Marina changed her destiny. In <br>exchange for her voice, she obtained a shapeshifting potion. <br>“Be careful, ” said the witch. “Do you really wish to give up <br>what you are to pursue a fleeting love?” The Mermaid didn’t <br>think twice about it and drank the potion to become fully <br>human. She returned to her prince only to find that he barely <br>remembered her and their time together. The Mermaid’s <br>heart darkened. On a full moon night, she drank the blood of <br>her lost love, and with it that of his entire new family.<br>Descriptor: I am an unscrupulous killer, I hate humanity <br>and the body to which I am condemned. My voice is reduced <br>to a faint whisper, which weakened my Siren powers but did <br>not take them away.<br>3 Wounds <br>Opposition Level: Medium 5</p>","markdown":""},"sort":5200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"WVzhGl3zK7keYBuR","name":"Pagina 53","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 53</h2><p>52<br>Agenda: I work for anyone who can afford to pay with <br>magic and arcane items, which I intend to use to become a <br>Mermaid again.<br>Special Agenda (Marina the Sea Explorer):  I hate <br>Marina for what she did to me. Even though she warned me <br>about what would happen, her power can ruin people’s lives. <br>I want her to make me a Mermaid again before I kill her.<br>Gift - The Siren’s Whisper: The Silent has given away <br>her voice, but she can still whisper. Any opponent acting <br>against the Silent must pass a Defense Check before taking <br>their action, or be dazed and miss the opportunity to act. <br>A target cannot be affected by this Gift more than once per <br>Scene.<br>Gift - The Siren’s Charm:  The Silent possesses an <br>otherworldly beauty that can awaken the lustful desire <br>of those around her. Once per Scene, if the Silent wants, <br>every subject in her presence will receive the Descriptor: <br>I desire the Silent with all my heart and would do anything <br>to have her. A Hunter can make a Defense Check to resist. <br>Particularly powerful NPCs, at the discretion of the <br>Storyteller, may not succumb to the Siren’s Charm.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":5300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"8UlWr6RLjKaEPRW7","name":"Pagina 54","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 54</h2><p>53<br>The Wise Fox<br>Inspired by The Golden Bird (Ally)<br>Since time immemorial some have set aside the wise words <br>that advised hard work and responsibility, preferring fast <br>and easy rewards. When the lessons of the wise are <br>ignored, pain is the teacher of last resort, bringing <br>with it the awareness that every mistake has a price. <br>A benevolent and kind Spirit knew this well and <br>for centuries had tried to teach mortals in order <br>to spare them the pain of a harsher lesson, only <br>to see them inevitably choose the less sensible <br>path. Eventually, the Spirit decided to help those <br>in need, but only if they could meet his price. <br>In this way, he thought, his help would be <br>more appreciated by humans, who value <br>something more the more it costs them.<br>Descriptor: I am an immortal spirit <br>incarnated in the body of a talking fox <br>and I have always watched over human <br>affairs.<br>6 Wounds <br>Opposition Level: Hard 7<br>Agenda: To help the humans I deem <br>deserving while asking a fair price in <br>exchange.<br>Gift - A Good Advice:  Once per <br>Scene, the Wise Fox can appear to <br>someone who has done a good deed, to <br>bring advice, an object, or information that will be decisive <br>for the current Scene. Before dispensing his help, however, <br>the Fox will ask for a price to be paid. Select between: 1. <br>Spilled Blood: Whoever benefits from the advice must <br>self-inflict 1 Wound by shedding blood as a symbol of <br>commitment. 2. Good Action: Whoever wants to receive <br>the Fox’s help will first have to perform the requested <br>action. This action, although apparently absurd, can <br>be contextualized by the Storyteller in a future <br>Scenario faced by the Hunters. The effort <br>required must include difficult or dangerous <br>situations to overcome. 3. Demonstrate <br>Commitment: To receive the benefit of the <br>advice, a Hunter has to go through an entire <br>Scene without using Gifts.<br>Gift - Offer Help:  Once per Scene, the <br>Wise Fox can appear and help one <br>who previously paid the cost he <br>required. A Hunter may spend 1 <br>Soma to get advice from the Wise <br>Fox, thus receiving 2 Additional <br>Successes on a Position Check.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":5400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"qAwV9ezNYIN28doV","name":"Pagina 55","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 55</h2><p>54<br>Fire Eater the Puppeteer<br>Inspired by Pinocchio (Neutral)<br>Once upon a time, there was a skilled puppeteer obsessed with <br>the idea of creating the perfect puppet. “If only my puppets <br>looked like real humans, ” he said. “Then my puppet shows could <br>really reach people’s hearts. ” After years of study, Fire Eater <br>found an ancient alchemy book containing a bloody ritual <br>capable of binding a person’s soul to an artificial body. From <br>that day on, the puppets in Fire Eater’s traveling coach were <br>never the same... Each puppet became the receptacle of a lost <br>soul, added to the puppeteer’s grim collection.<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled alchemist and puppet master. <br>Hidden within my clothes are all kinds of tools and weapons, <br>each useful for disassembling and reassembling bodies, whether <br>of flesh or wood.<br>3 Wounds <br>Opposition Level: Medium 5<br>Agenda: Listening intently to the personal stories of those I <br>meet and judging who deserves to join my puppet collection <br>/ Treating everyone equally, innocents and murderers alike, <br>because life as a puppet is a blessing.<br>Special Agenda (Carlo the Living Puppet):  I’m always <br>looking for the perfect puppet. Once I find it, I will make it <br>mine, no matter the cost.<br>Note: Carlo the Living Puppet is one of the Hunters featured <br>in The Broken Ones expansion book.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":5500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"irDhLH0QPipPuDBk","name":"Pagina 56","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 56</h2><p>55<br>Gift - The Puppets’ Rite:  Fire Eater can animate a <br>Puppet by harnessing the soul of a dying person within <br>it. From that moment on, the Puppet will be linked to <br>its creator until he decides to free it. A Puppet has the <br>following profile:<br>Descriptor: I’m an animated puppet and I do <br>everything my creator says... [see the Puppet Gift below]<br>1 Wound <br>Opposition Level: Easy 3<br>Gift - Puppet:  At zero Wounds a Puppet will shatter, <br>but if repaired it will immediately recover its Wound and <br>return to action. The Descriptor of each Puppet must <br>be completed with a feature related to what they were in <br>life. Acting on that part of the Descriptor can awaken the <br>dormant consciousness of the harnessed soul, allowing the <br>Puppet to act independently of its master.<br>Gift - Master of Puppets:  Fire Eater is always <br>surrounded by at least 6 Puppets. In his presence, increase <br>each Puppet’s Opposition Level by 1. When he would suffer <br>1 Wound, Fire Eater can sacrifice a Puppet instead.<br>The Masked<br>Swashbuckler<br>Inspired by the Puss in Boots (Opponent)<br>Once upon a time, there was a cunning Cat who made his <br>young master’s fortune. But alas, as often happens, instead <br>of thanking him the now rich scion was quick to abandon his <br>faithful companion. Disappointed, the Cat put himself at the <br>service of three other masters, but once success and wealth <br>were achieved, they all got rid of him. Thus it was that the <br>Cat swore to work only for himself. In the adventures that <br>followed, the Cat released an ancient spirit from which he <br>obtained a wish. Having heard of this miracle, the original <br>ungrateful master showed up, pitiful now after developing <br>a rare disease. He begged for forgiveness, repenting of his <br>arrogance, and asked the Cat to wish for a cure. In return, he <br>promised eternal gratitude. The Cat accepted and made the <br>wish. But, as soon as the miracle was performed the Cat’s old <br>master killed him, fearful of his incredible abilities. <br>But even a fool knows that cats have nine lives, though his <br>master might have forgotten. The next day the Cat returned <br>from the dead. Enraged by the betrayal, the Cat swore <br>revenge. He put on a mask capable of making him appear <br>human, allowing him to masquerade as a noble duelist. He <br>began to travel to courts and drawing rooms, taking revenge <br>on his ungrateful masters. After killing them one by one, the <br>Cat developed a taste for blood and decided that from that <br>day on, his only master would be money.<br>Descriptor: I am a cunning cat who can pretend to be <br>human thanks to a magical mask. I put myself at the service <br>of the highest bidder without qualms and I use my countless <br>lives to get the better of every problem.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":5600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"aRWeQaJ2HfilKVsd","name":"Pagina 57","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 57</h2><p>56<br>3 Wounds <br>Opposition Level: Medium 5<br>Agenda: To serve my customer without asking questions / <br>Mocking those who trust others too much.<br>Gift - Nine Lives Like a Cat: The Masked Swashbuckler <br>still has eight lives left, so he can return to action once <br>he is taken out. When he is eliminated, the Storyteller <br>can make him disappear from the current Scene in <br>a blatant way or by revealing his death, even if the <br>Hunters just wanted him disabled. In the following <br>Scene, The Masked Swashbuckler will rejoin the action <br>with the following perks: 1. Once per Scene, he can <br>prevent an enemy from using a Gift he has already <br>seen in action previously. This effect interrupts the <br>target and their action is wasted. 2. His Opposition <br>Level is increased by 1 when defending against an <br>enemy he has already faced in a duel. 3. Once per <br>Scene, he can take advantage of a magical item that <br>he has previously procured to defeat his enemy. <br>The item is disposable and the Storyteller must <br>create a Descriptor to accompany it, such as The <br>Invisibility Potion or The Stone of Blinding Light.<br>Gift - Cat Mask:  Thanks to his magical <br>mask, the Masked Swashbuckler can freely <br>transform between human and cat, taking <br>advantage of this to approach his enemy. <br>The transformation is instantaneous, but it <br>cannot be done in front of witnesses.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":5700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"i7Ri9VWU0UkGsbHw","name":"Pagina 58","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 58</h2><p>57<br>Orcus the Guardian<br>Inspired by the Evil Orc (Ally)<br>Once upon a time, there was a gigantic and deformed man <br>no one wanted to befriend. Orcus was mocked and excluded <br>from society, until one day he met a gentle nobleman who <br>knew how to look beyond his repugnant aspect. The nobleman <br>made Orcus his personal bodyguard. One day, during a trip <br>to the nearby capital, the nobleman’s carriage was attacked <br>by assassins. Orcus defended the nobleman and his family <br>with all his might. Lost in the heat of battle, he seized the <br>carriage itself to use as a weapon. He used it to crush his <br>enemies and, unwittingly, killed all the passengers too. Orcus <br>was destroyed by grief, and the Judge who oversaw the trial <br>that followed showed him mercy. He would serve <br>his sentence as a guard for the Judge. <br>But the tragedy only repeated <br>itself. During a hunt, <br>the unwary Judge <br>slipped off  <br>a cliff and was saved by the providential intervention of <br>Orcus who, with his immense strength, threw the man and <br>his horse back onto the road. The impact, however, was fatal. <br>The Judge ended up smashed like a ripe apple. From job to <br>job, Orcus was always welcomed by someone attracted by his <br>abilities, who ultimately ended up dying in some absurd way. <br>A wealthy merchant was pushed away to avoid being hit by <br>a cart but ended up mangled in the machinery of a nearby <br>factory... A skilled medic who fell into a river was rescued <br>by Orcus, but when the hapless giant attempted to apply the <br>resuscitation technique his master had taught him, the poor <br>man’s rib cage cracked before exploding to pieces under the <br>pressure. After going from master to master, Orcus eventually <br>found a home in the Order, perhaps the only place where his <br>Herculean strength could safely be put to good use.<br>Descriptor: I am a giant of incredible strength and repulsive <br>appearance. I serve the Order as the Hunters’ Guardian and <br>execute every order to the best of my ability.<br>3 Wounds<br>Opposition Level: Medium 5<br>Agenda: Do my best to serve the Hunt-<br>ers, but avoid killing anyone with my <br>strength.<br>Gift - Strength of the Ogre:  <br>Once per Scene, a Hunter can in-<br>voke Orcus’s help and use one of <br>the following effects: 1. Orcus can <br>lift, move, or break either an <br>object or part of the environ-<br>ment, with a force equal to <br>that of five men. 2. If Orcus</p>","markdown":""},"sort":5800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241714,"modifiedTime":1783973241714,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"CxaxTdPUBSpCA4C5","name":"Pagina 59","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 59</h2><p>58<br>can use his strength to support another Hunter’s action, the <br>Hunter he aids will receive 2 Additional Successes. When <br>this Gift is used, roll a die: with a 5 or 6, Orcus uninten-<br>tionally causes irreparable damage to an object, the envi-<br>ronment, or a person while using the Gift.<br>Gift - Guardian of the Hunters:  Once per Scene, a <br>Hunter can invoke the protection of Orcus, who will take <br>1 Wound in his place. When you use this Gift, roll a die: <br>on a 6, Orcus takes the Wound but inflicts 1 Wound on <br>the    Hunter by accidentally overwhelming them with his <br>incredible strength.<br>•<br>Goldilocks and her  <br>War Bears<br>Inspired by Goldilock and the Three Bears <br>(Opponent)<br>Once upon a time, there was a young orphan who, to escape <br>the clutches of a gang of thieves, took refuge in a forest. After <br>wandering for days, the young woman found a bear’s den <br>and, seized by desperation and hunger, ate the honey she <br>found there. Exhausted and cold, she recklessly fell asleep in <br>the den. When the bear came home it pounced on her, but the <br>girl managed to defend herself with an old knife found stuck <br>in the bones of a careless hunter. The young woman got the <br>better of the feral animal and slit its throat. Before dying the <br>bear inflicted dozens of deep wounds that spoiled her good <br>looks forever. Desperate but determined to survive, Goldilocks <br>heard a moan coming from the bottom of the den. She found <br>three newborn bears, orphans of the mother she just killed. <br>She took the cubs with her and, from that day, promised that <br>no one would ever toy with her life again. Years later, a rumor <br>was heard often across the battlefields, of Goldilocks and her <br>war bears who were revered and feared as the most dangerous <br>of all mercenaries.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":5900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"9h3C0jMPce2Qmc3H","name":"Pagina 60","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 60</h2><p>59<br>Descriptor: I am a young mercenary who combines fighting <br>skills with uncontrolled fury. My loyal war bears are my family <br>and no one can lay a finger on me.<br>3 Wounds <br>Opposition Level: Medium 5 <br>Agenda: Live without anyone telling me what I should or can <br>do / Take care of my beautiful blonde hair, the only part of my <br>body that hasn’t been spoiled.<br>Gift - War Bears:  Goldilocks is always accompanied by <br>her three trusty War Bears. The Bears only obey her and it <br>is not possible to influence their behavior or scare them, not <br>even with magic. When Goldilocks acts, she can expend one <br>of her Bears’ actions to obtain a single special effect: 1. Inflict <br>1 additional Wound with a successful attack. 2. Cancel 1 <br>Wound suffered, which a Bear will take instead. 3. Increase <br>the Opposition Level of an action by 1.<br>The Three Bears<br>Descriptor: We are Goldilocks’ children and fight alongside <br>her with unstoppable fury.<br>Fang - 3 Wounds Opposition Level: Easy 3 <br>Black - 1 Wound Opposition Level: Hard 7<br>Claw - 2 Wound Opposition Level: Medium 5<br>Agenda: Defending our mother at any cost.<br>Sinbad the Traveler of <br>a Thousand Seas<br>Inspired by Sinbad from One Thousand and One <br>Nights (Ally)<br>Once upon a time, there was a skilled sailor who traveled every <br>sea and witnessed every land. Dissatisfied and bored, Sinbad <br>turned to the strangest and darkest legends to find something <br>that could arouse his interest. Learning of The Broken Tales <br>was for him the discovery of a new world. From that moment <br>on, Sinbad became a seeker of forbidden treasures, hungry for <br>dark knowledge and secrets concealed from the eyes of mere <br>mortals. It was only a matter of time before he caught the at-<br>tention of the Order. Sinbad willingly put himself at the service <br>of the Hunters, offering his great experience in exchange for <br>the rare opportunity to feel the thrill of discovery once again.<br>Descriptor: I am an experienced traveler and have seen <br>every known land. I get bored easily if I’m not interested in <br>what I’m doing.<br>1 Wound <br>Opposition Level: Medium 5 <br>Agenda: I am willing to do anything to experience the thrill <br>of discovery once again. .<br>Special Agenda (Sherazade, the Weaver of Tales):  <br>I’m boost of knowing every story and legend, and I love to <br>mock those who pride themselves on limited knowledge. I <br>want to ridicule the stories Sherazade tells, highlighting the <br>truths that only I know.<br>Note: Sherazade the Weaver of Tales  is one of the Hunters <br>featured in The Broken Ones expansion book.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":6000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"SReLMfjbdB1ry8b7","name":"Pagina 61","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 61</h2><p>60<br>Gift - Traveler of a Thousand Places: Sinbad has seen <br>the whole world and much of what the Broken Tales hide. <br>In the course of a Scene, a Hunter can invoke his help to <br>obtain information or create an additional Descriptor that <br>represents a specific area of Sinbad’s knowledge. But the <br>old sailor is an eccentric type, and to provide his help he <br>first must be entertained. The Storyteller will evaluate the <br>current situation and Sinbad’s level of boredom. A Hunter <br>can capture Sinbad’s interest with creative actions, as long <br>as they’re appropriate to the current Scene.<br>Gift - I Know How To Do It:  Once per Scene, a Hunter <br>can get 1 Additional Success in his Check, asking Sinbad <br>for helpful advice. As with Traveler of a Thousand Places, <br>Sinbad needs to be intrigued before helping.<br>•<br>Alfred Leaves the Talking <br>Ghost<br>Inspired by Pinocchio’s Jiminy Cricket<br>Dark Presence by the Storymancer Collective <br>(Neutral)<br>Once upon a time, there was a rich and powerful criminal <br>named Alfred Leaves. Secrets were his weapons and his <br>business, and there was no one in London who did not have <br>unfinished business with him. Or, more simply, had some <br>unspeakably shameful secret uncovered by Leaves. He became <br>more and more obsessed with secrets, his thirst for knowledge <br>extending far beyond the affairs of miserable mortals. Who <br>had created the world? What was there after death? In a <br>frenzied madness, Alfred Leaves took his life by striking <br>himself on the temple with a heavy hammer. Returning as a <br>ghost, Leaves encountered the One Who Plots in the Shadow. <br>Finally, everything was clear to him. After a few days, Leaves <br>woke up, alive once more and ready to restart his business of <br>secrets on behalf of a new and dark master.<br>Descriptor: I am a usurer of secrets, and will sell them at <br>a high price. If I die, I become a ghost until I am reborn in <br>flesh and blood.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":6100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"3zsjFhuAJ58lZ3KU","name":"Pagina 62","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 62</h2><p>61<br>1 Wound<br>Opposition Level: Easy 3<br>Agenda: When I am alive, I want to discover all the secrets I <br>can,  in order to report them to the One Who Plots in the Shadow <br>/ When I am dead, I walk around like a ghost and feel the need to <br>share the secrets I know. <br>Special Agenda (Carlo the Living Puppet):  I hate lying, <br>because it does nothing but devalue a secret. That little animated <br>puppet is the ultimate representation of the power of lying and I <br>want to stop him from speaking.<br>Note: Carlo the Living Puppet (inspired by Pinocchio) is one of <br>the Hunters featured in The Broken Ones expansion book.<br>Gift - The Returning Ghost:  When Alfred is killed he <br>becomes a ghost and, after one or more Scenes (at the Storyteller’s <br>discretion), he will come back to life. When this happens, his <br>Opposition Level goes up one rank (at first Medium 5 and then <br>Hard 7) and he gains 1 Wound. After being killed the third time, <br>Alfred will revert to his normal profile, forgetting who killed <br>him. In ghost form, Alfred has no memories of when he was <br>alive and wanders like a restless soul in the city cemetery. The <br>Opposition Level remains Easy 3 and the Agenda changes.<br> <br>Gift - Trader of Secrets:  When the talking Ghost engages <br>in a conversation with someone, he will compel them to share <br>a secret or sin they have committed. A Hunter can oppose the <br>effect of this Gift with a Defense Check. The Talking Ghost <br>always knows a secret related to one or more of the NPCs linked <br>to the Scenario in which he appears.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":6200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Q1FklapgDcMhnxjt","name":"Pagina 63","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 63</h2><p>62<br>Oakheart<br>the Lady of the Woods<br>Inspired by Blodeuwedd (Ally)<br>Dark Presence by Chris <br>van der Linden and Chris <br>“Mono” Mahon<br>Those who venture into darkened woods <br>and lonely forests whisper of a twisted <br>woman with skin made of bark, legs <br>made of coiling roots, and a face hidden <br>by a crude wooden mask. Offered as the <br>mortal bride to a forest god centuries <br>ago, the woman was transformed into a <br>hideous being to please her new groom <br>but soon watched her husband wither and <br>die as the forest was cut down. Now bereft <br>of her home and her love, she wanders <br>the woods in search of companionship. <br>Dubbed “Oakheart, ” it’s rumored that <br>any mortal who glimpses her true face <br>is instantly driven mad by her terrifying <br>countenance, but some wanderers claim <br>to have been aided or even rescued by the <br>creature, who seems attracted to young <br>and beautiful travelers.<br>Descriptor: I am a twisted, lonely being <br>who wanders the forests and rewards <br>companionship and kindness with <br>boons.<br>1 Wound<br>Opposition Level: Medium 5<br>Agenda: Find companions willing to <br>look beyond my appearance and treat me <br>with kindness. I am attracted to those who <br>are particularly beautiful, as I secretly <br>desire a lover.<br> <br>Gift - Rotten Face: Oakheart removes <br>her mask, revealing her terrifying <br>face. Any creature who glimpses it is <br>driven temporarily mad. The madness <br>can take the form of single-minded <br>terror or gibbering catatonia. Create <br>a Descriptor to represent the insanity <br>induced by the vision of Oakheart’s face, <br>and inflict 1 Wound on anyone who sees <br>it. Alternatively, Oakheart can bestow <br>its hideous face on a Hunter, who will <br>receive the ability to use this Gift once <br>during the Scenario.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":6300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"gsdnA846yyQeHTtP","name":"Pagina 64","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 64</h2><p>63<br>Gift - Blossom Boon:  After experiencing love or true <br>friendship with a person, Oakheart’s withered branches <br>burst into bloom, raining petals on her and her new bond. <br>This generates 3 Petal Tokens. Each can be used to heal 1 <br>Wound. Alternatively, you can use 1 Petal to calm a subject <br>in the grip of negative feelings, so that they can ignore <br>Descriptors and Agendas related to the altered state for the <br>rest of the Scene.<br>The Feral Musicians <br>of Bremen<br>Inspired by The Bremen Town Musicians <br>(Neutral)<br>Dark Presence by Claudio Serena<br>Near Bremen in the deep north of Germany, there is a small <br>Inn that more experienced travelers recommend avoiding, <br>called “The Musicians”. The Inn was home for many refugees <br>and slaves who were abused by their masters or fleeing their <br>past. It was a safe place where the long arm of the law could <br>not find them. Over time, the Inn has also attracted bandits <br>and criminals of the worst kind, eventually becoming a <br>haunted place that travelers avoid and mothers use to scare <br>children who do not want to sleep. From the main hall, you <br>can hear a cacophony of horrible noises that no human being <br>could produce. Due to the violence that has taken place there, <br>the Inn has acquired a life of its own by making the pain <br>and fear of all those who have sought refuge there its own. <br>Whoever stays, by mistake or desperation, will encounter one <br>of the four aspects that the Inn is able to manifest, namely the <br>Musicians: the Witch, always followed by her black cat; the <br>Hunter, armed with a knife and accompanied by his hound; <br>the Judge, whose cock’s feather writes the faults of those who <br>meet his gaze; and the Monster, a shapeless creature whose <br>braying can lead to madness.<br>Descriptor: I am a place full of violence and suffering, <br>able to awaken the deepest fears in the souls of those who <br>approach.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":6400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ihOv8UJVF1D8YrW6","name":"Pagina 65","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 65</h2><p>64<br>4 Wounds (1 per Musician)<br>Opposition Level: Medium 5<br>Agenda: Feed the fears of the patrons, corrupting their <br>minds so they will revel in the violence that follows.<br>Gift - Cacophony: Whether it be the words of the Judge, <br>the spells of the Witch, the barking of the Hunter’s hound, <br>or the braying of the Monster, the cacophony of horrible <br>noises emitted by the entities inhabiting the Inn is more <br>than enough to make even the sturdiest soul waver. Any <br>action performed inside the Inn during the manifestation <br>of one of its aspects receives a 1 Penalty.<br>Gift - A Past of Suffering:  When one of the Musicians <br>is hit, the suffering of the Inn’s victims overwhelms the <br>attacker, causing cuts and bruises, then forcing them to <br>relive a moment in which they lost something important. <br>Inflicting 1 Wound to one of the Musicians requires a <br>Defense Check in order not to suffer 1 Wound in turn. Once <br>a total of 4 Wounds is inflicted on the Musicians, they quiet <br>down for the rest of the Scene, to regenerate completely in <br>the following one. The only way to truly destroy them is to <br>raze the Inn itself.<br>•<br>The Returning Wolf<br>Inspired by the Bad Wolf (Opponent)<br>Dark Presence by Peter Chiykowski <br>In the days when his heart still beat and his lungs still <br>drew breath, this wicked animal used to prowl the woods, <br>avoiding the huntsman who had long hunted him for his pelt, <br>and stalking for a tasty bite amongst unsuspecting human <br>travelers. Imbued with the powers of human speech and <br>cunning, the wolf tricked his victims into betraying their loved <br>ones into his clutches as well. He fed well until the fateful day <br>he ate up the little girl in the red hood and her grandmother. <br>That was the day the huntsman caught and slew the Wolf. <br>As the story of his death spread and changed from telling to <br>telling, he was tortured and executed in a dozen gruesome <br>ways: drowned in a trough, boiled in a pot, smashed into the <br>ground, cut down, cut open and his belly filled with heavy</p>","markdown":""},"sort":6500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"0SaxPTKCRyYGFUWL","name":"Pagina 66","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 66</h2><p>65<br>stones. The many tellings bled together and the Wolf, mangled <br>by countless hands and condemned by countless tongues, has <br>returned to claim revenge for every death he was subjected <br>to. He is everything that has been said about him. Big. Bad <br>And out for blood.<br>Descriptor: I am the Returning Wolf: I am bad, hungry, <br>and now I am the hunter.<br>3 Wounds<br>Opposition Level: Medium 5<br>Agenda: I am hell-bent on revenge on the human world. I <br>am a revenant animated by undying acrimony for the soft-<br>skinned creatures that invaded my woods and yet had the <br>audacity to condemn me to death. My only goal now is to <br>glut my endless hunger for human flesh and fear. I have a <br>particular hatred for children, the elderly, and Hunters, <br>whom I see as responsible for my many deaths.<br>Special Agenda (Iskra the Young Wolf):  I harbor <br>a deep hatred for this little pest. She is somewhat linked to <br>my pain. I want to swallow her and let her slowly die in my <br>stomach.<br>Note: Iskra the Y oung Wolf is one of the Hunters featured <br>in The Broken Ones expansion book.<br>Special Agenda (Garou the Old Wolf): I want to warn <br>the poor fool so that he understands what he will face if he <br>keeps by the side of these blasted humans. <br>Gift - Frightening Revenant: The Wolf reveals horrific <br>mutilations, each revealing something about his deaths. His <br>empty eyes are as cold and bottomless as the well he was <br>drowned in. His pelt is a patchwork of burns and skinned <br>flesh. His belly is full of slashes and stitches. His growl is <br>a terrifying sound, grinding painfully from a chest full of <br>heavy stones and broken bones. No NPCs will approach <br>or fight the Wolf, being paralyzed by terror. Particularly <br>powerful NPCs, at the Storyteller’s discretion, can ignore <br>this effect. When a Hunter acts against the Returning Wolf, <br>they suffer 1 Penalty for each action taken.<br>Gift - The Better to Eat You With:  The Wolf can <br>swallow his enemies whole, trapping them inside his belly <br>and crushing them to death with the heavy stones the <br>grandmother sewed inside it. When the Returning Wolf <br>inflicts 1 Wound, it can swallow the victim whole as an <br>additional effect. In the next action, the victim can only <br>try to free themselves. If they fail the Position Check, or if <br>they decide to stay in the belly of the Returning Wolf, they <br>receive 1 additional Wound.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":6600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"HCB1BJnEMAwCHsGQ","name":"Pagina 67","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 67</h2><p>66<br>The King’s Unlikely Tailor<br>Inspired by The Emperor’s New Clothes (Neutral)<br>Dark Presence by Guido Campanini<br>Once upon a time, there was a young provincial tailor with the gift of knowing <br>how to see into people’s souls in order to dress them in the best possible manner. <br>One day his best friend convinced him to sew a suit for a wealthy merchant. To <br>cover the wolfish soul of the greedy merchant, the poor tailor had to use his own <br>soul, one of a lamb, mixing his own blood in the dyes. It was a resounding success <br>and the rumor spread all over Paris. The more his wealthy clientele grew thanks <br>to the rumors spread by his friend, the more blood the poor tailor had to shed. <br>His success led him to the King’s court, where the young tailor began to kidnap <br>innocents from all over Paris to bleed them in his workshops. It was a necessary <br>step to manufacture dyes capable of disguising those with souls so corrupt. When <br>the King asked for a suit, the young tailor immediately realized that simple blood <br>would not be enough to conceal all the man had done to make his people suffer.<br>Descriptor: I am an anemic young man with a body covered in scars, escorted <br>and aided by my rich friend who considers me his most precious possession.<br>1 Wound<br>Opposition Level: Easy 3<br>Agenda: Finding the purest-hearted person in the nation to make a suit for <br>the King / I fell madly in love with the one person who never asked me for a <br>dress, the King’s youngest daughter. I wouldn’t spill a drop for her dress, she is <br>too pure. But I know that if I can’t find anyone for her father’s suit, I’ll have to <br>use her.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":6700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"DXGpffsOM09lPPT7","name":"Pagina 68","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 68</h2><p>67<br>Gift - Soul Tailor:  A suit sewn by the tailor masks the <br>soul so well that whoever wears it looks like another <br>person. They are seen as admirable and good, even while <br>committing atrocious acts. Only children and the innocents <br>can see beyond the illusion. A Hunter can perform a <br>Defense Check against an Opposition Level Hard 7 to see <br>beyond the deception of Soul Tailor.<br>The Cheating Friend<br>Descriptor: I am the young tailor’s “best” friend and, to <br>keep my life comfortable, I am willing to do anything. When <br>I act for my own benefit, no one can stop me.<br>1 Wound<br>Opposition Level: Hard 7<br>Agenda: Keep the tailor alive, become richer and richer, <br>and to use his favor to ask for the hand of the King’s daughter.<br>The Mothers of Fate<br>Inspired by the Fairy Godmothers of many <br>fairytales (Ally)<br>Dark Presence by Francesco Panitti<br>Cloris, Panis, and Galis, called the Mothers of Fate. Since the <br>dawn of time, there have been figures who control people’s <br>destiny, plot in the shadows, and hide in plain sight. They are <br>the ones we go to for advice and whom we trust blindly.<br>They use their proximity to manipulate people, enjoying their <br>intrigues and rejoicing when everything goes according to <br>their plans.<br>These figures are always represented as three sisters who, since <br>ancient times, have been weaving and cutting the threads of <br>everyone’s destiny. Their true identity is unknown as they <br>have always hidden behind the name of Fairy Godmothers.<br>When the three sisters insinuate themselves into the stories <br>they wove, they always did so by changing their appearance <br>and name, all to get closer to the protagonists and manipulate <br>them according to their will. Some rumors say that it is <br>possible to make deals with them, but always at a very high <br>price.<br>Descriptor: We are three sisters, we never show our real <br>identity, but we twist fate to our pleasure thanks to our <br>powerful magic.<br>3 Wounds [1 for each Mother]<br>Opposition Level: Medium 5</p>","markdown":""},"sort":6800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"1LLFsMvQ3G5mPMgY","name":"Pagina 69","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 69</h2><p>68<br>Agenda: Pretending to be friendly and kind, while <br>manipulating others’ choices according to our will / Appearing <br>out of nowhere in time of need, thanks to our magic.<br>Gift - The Way Forward:  The knowledge of the three <br>sisters is absolute and unlimited; they know the past, <br>present, and future. By asking the Mothers of Fate for <br>advice or information, you will be able to obtain guidance <br>to follow to achieve your goals or information that few <br>know. This all comes at a high price. Once per Session you <br>can ask the Storyteller a direct question about a person, a <br>place, or a secret, to which they will answer in detail and <br>with specifics. In exchange, the Hunter must perform a task <br>for the Mothers, but which the Hunter will not remember. <br>The Hunter receives 1 Pact Token, which the Storyteller can <br>spend during a Scene to introduce the effects of the action <br>the Hunter performed for the Mothers. The action can <br>be anything, even in open contrast to the Hunter’s moral <br>stances. They will be aware of what they have done only <br>when the truth is revealed.<br>Gift - As if by Magic:  The power of the Mothers of <br>Fate is such that it can change reality for a short period <br>of time. By unconditionally accepting a request from the <br>Mothers of Fate and spending 1 Soma, once per Session, <br>the Hunter can ask the Mothers to modify the surrounding <br>environment, adding or removing any object, creating an <br>advantage for themselves or whoever they wish.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":6900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"beW8oKuS8KWHgJ5Q","name":"Pagina 70","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 70</h2><p>69<br>The Hunter’s <br>Creation<br>Step 1 – Collect sources of <br>inspiration<br>Each Broken Tales’ Hunter is derived from a fairytale villain. <br>The first step will therefore be to decide which villain to <br>“break” and which source to draw inspiration from. It is <br>important to choose a fairytale, an essay, or another source <br>that speaks of the villain in its most classic incarnation, <br>trying to avoid modern takes. This is because fairytales and <br>classic stories feature characterizations very much in line <br>with the Broken Tales mood, without the adjustments for <br>modern sensibilities that are quite common with the more <br>recent versions. This step is a good opportunity to do some <br>research and maybe discover the dark sides of a fairytale <br>you thought you knew!<br>An important note: in the text, the term “fairytale” also <br>includes many classic stories such as The Wonderful Wizard <br>of OZ or Peter and Wendy, which are not technically real <br>fairytales. They are, however, stories that have entered the <br>collective imagination in much the same way. In truth, <br>Broken Tales draws from every source including fairytales, <br>folklore, and classic stories, encompassing them all in the <br>term “fairytale” for practicality.<br>Creating your own Hunter takes some time, but <br>it’s also very satisfying. Broken Tales provides a large <br>cast of ready-made Hunters which can be used to get <br>started right away. However, if the Players’ intention is <br>to tackle a Campaign, creating Hunters from scratch <br>can be a good option. Of course, nothing prevents you <br>from mixing things up! Maybe some people in your <br>group will create brand new Hunters, while the others <br>use one of those we provide with the game.<br>The Hunters’ creation does not simply consist of <br>describing the protagonists on paper. Use the steps in <br>this chapter as a guide, both for breaking the story of <br>an iconic villain, and creating the mechanics to describe <br>their powers. This process is called Bringing a Villain <br>to their Breaking Point: that’s how they’ll be reborn as <br>a Hunter in the world of Broken Tales.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":7000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Jcjw8Tl7h8VfuQA3","name":"Pagina 71","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 71</h2><p>BREAKING POINT<br>70<br>Analyzing an entire text can provide a lot of material, but it <br>is a rather long process. For this reason, a valid alternative <br>is to do some simple online research. The web is full of sites <br>that summarize and analyze classic stories, and Wikipedia <br>itself can be a good starting point.<br>Reading the story, we’ll underline or jot down interesting <br>words, phrases, or entire passages. These elements will <br>become Keywords. As explained in the rules section, <br>Keywords will serve as a guide and inspiration in working <br>out everything related to a Hunter.<br>Example: The Hunter we’re going to create is inspired by <br>Captain Hook from the novel Peter and Wendy. This choice <br>will allow us to illustrate the complete creation process and <br>at the same time show how easy it is to create an alternative <br>Hunter to the “canonical one” included in the ready-made <br>Hunters’ sheets (James the Swordsman, in this specific case).<br>To streamline the process, we’ll use Wikipedia as inspiration.<br>After a careful reading of the page, these are the Keywords <br>that we marked:<br>Infamous / Bad gentleman / Loves music and poetry / <br>Challenges Peter Pan to a    final  duel. When beaten, Peter <br>Pan, goaded by Hook himself, kicks the Captain off the ship <br>and right into the crocodile’s gaping mouth / Hook is not <br>his real name / Ruthless pirate captain, sometimes seems <br>compassionate / It saddens him to know that the Lost Boys <br>hate him, even though he has earned their hatred / Hook <br>is described as “cadaverous, ” with blue eyes and long, dark <br>curls of hair that look like “black candles” when viewed from <br>a distance / Barrie later wrote of him: “In a word, the most <br>handsome man I have ever seen, although, at the same time, <br>slightly disgusting. ”<br>Step 2 – Tell the Hunter’s <br>backstory and bring them to their <br>Breaking Point<br>In this section, we need to describe how our villain is reborn <br>in the world of Broken Tales, taking on a role and finding <br>their purpose within the Order. We will write a short story, <br>trying to integrate all relevant Keywords. Y ou don’t have <br>to use them verbatim: synonyms or phrases derived from <br>Keywords will also work. <br>In this short backstory, we’ll focus on detailing these points:<br> ◆ Who is the Hunter and what do they do in the Order?<br> ◆ What role do they play and how do they live in Broken <br>Europe?<br> ◆ What is the bond they maintain with their fairytale <br>counterpart?<br> ◆ What is their Breaking Point , or flipped details, <br>from the classic fairytale that makes this Hunter <br>original?<br>To accomplish all that, we’ll flip one or more parts of the <br>original story to separate the Hunter from their classic <br>identity as a villain. This inversion will serve to distinguish <br>them from the original in their objectives or actions. <br>The best way to do this is to think about one of the most <br>distinctive characteristics of the villain and make it a flaw (if <br>it isn’t one already) or change its connotation completely...<br>Some examples:<br> ◆ Garou the Old Wolf joined the Order so as to escape the <br>many humans chasing him. The strong and overbearing <br>wolf of many fairytales undergoes the treatment he has <br>always reserved for others.<br> ◆ Baba Yaga is a child witch and no longer the classic old</p>","markdown":""},"sort":7100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"4PPu4H99b4WmDhzT","name":"Pagina 72","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 72</h2><p>BREAKING POINT<br>71<br>hag that everyone fears. Trapped in the body of a little <br>girl, no one really takes her seriously. She’s relegated to a <br>secondary role when all she would like to be is respected <br>and feared. At least, until she shows off her power.<br> ◆ James the Swordsman is a gentleman who fights with <br>honor and respect . He let his guard down against a <br>mysterious boy and lost a hand for it . He suffered the <br>archetypical low blow that the original Captain Hook <br>inflicted on his enemies. As a man of honor, James would <br>never dare to do such a thing.<br> ◆ The Astonishing Pied Piper Without A Name lives only <br>for music and has committed various crimes in its name. <br>Money and punishing others are things that don’t interest <br>him.<br>Example: Let’s tell the story and take Captain Hook to his <br>Breaking Point.<br>I am a fearsome smuggler  and the sea has always been my <br>home. With my trusty crew, I have traveled along the English <br>coasts transporting all kinds of merchandise. We were <br>outlaws in the eyes of fools frightened of the word pirate. <br>During one of my raids, I rescued a strange boy from the sea. <br>Despite my instincts telling me otherwise, I decided to bring <br>him on board. Never was a choice regretted more. A curse <br>hung over the young man: the sky darkened and a terrible sea <br>monster struck my ship. I fought until the end when its giant <br>jaws closed over me. I survived, or at least my body survived. <br>My heart stopped beating and with it, my body began the <br>slow process of decay. <br>Immortal but doomed to ruin, I entered the Order in the <br>hope of finding a remedy for the spell that afflicts me and <br>which the mysterious boy passed on to me.<br>For this story we used these keywords:<br> ◆ Fearsome Smuggler (Infamous). <br> ◆ A Strange Boy / Terrible Sea Monster / I Fought until <br>the end (He challenges Peter Pan to a final duel. When <br>beaten, Peter Pan, goaded by Hook himself, kicks the <br>Captain off the ship and right into the crocodile’s gaping <br>mouth.)<br> ◆ Trustworthy crew / Pirate / On my ship (Ruthless pirate <br>captain, sometimes seems compassionate).<br> ◆ My body has started a slow process of decay (Hook is <br>described as “cadaverous, ” with blue eyes and long, dark <br>curls of hair that look like “black candles” when viewed <br>from a distance).<br>Hook’s Breaking Point is that he has lost his great challenge <br>and with it his obsession with defeating Peter Pan. Now <br>he is a walking corpse, but he would like to continue to be <br>considered the infamous gentleman he always was.<br>Step 3 – Detail the Hunter <br>Descriptors<br>In this step, we will define the three Hunter’s Descriptors. <br>Descriptors must cover:<br> ◆ Who is the Hunter and what do they do in Broken <br>Europe or at the service of the Order?<br> ◆ What is the Hunter’s most distinctive asset/feature?<br> ◆ What is the bond they maintained with their fairytale <br>counterpart?<br>The simplest way to create a valid Descriptor is to start from <br>one of the Keywords and use it as a guide for answering the <br>questions given for each category, so as to set up an excellent <br>starting point to inspire you. A Hunter’s Descriptor must <br>have both a positive part (useful/signals a resource) and</p>","markdown":""},"sort":7200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"gY5E2SDO39b0AIKl","name":"Pagina 73","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 73</h2><p>72<br>a negative part (the Downside ) that will provide XP if <br>brought into play. In this first step, however, it is good to <br>focus only on the first part of the Descriptor. Once you have <br>defined all three Descriptors, it will be easier to analyze <br>them and find good Downsides.<br>A Descriptor must be written in the first person, <br>in the Hunter’s own words.<br>To keep the Descriptors consistent, start with one of the <br>following active phrases: I know/I have something, I use <br>something, I get something, I own something, I am something, <br>I want/I will be something.<br>Descriptors have several functions in the game:<br> ◆ They outline the background, behavior, and <br>appearance of a Hunter, helping the Player to focus <br>their interpretation. <br> ◆ They can be invoked while narrating a Position or <br>Defense Check to get 3 Base Successes instead of just 1.<br> ◆ At the end of each Scene, if a Descriptor has caused <br>the Hunter troubles, it can be checked off and then <br>converted into 1 XP during the next Interlude. <br> ◆ They help the Storyteller and the Players understand <br>the Hunter’s skills and what they are capable of <br>doing. Descriptors are the basis from which to <br>determine if a Position Check is necessary, what results <br>can be obtained, and what information the Hunter has <br>about a menace they are facing.<br>In a Campaign, during an Interlude at the end of each <br>Scenario, it will be possible to change or evolve a Hunter’s <br>Descriptor according to what happened at the table. The <br>creation of the Descriptors is a very important step, but <br>don’t stress about it. As a Player, focus on what you like and <br>consider consistent with the story of your Hunter, without <br>thinking too much about the practical applications in-<br>game. The adventures faced by your Hunter will lead them, <br>over time, to change and make their Descriptors more <br>relevant to the path they have taken.<br>Example: Descriptors of the revived Captain Hook.<br>The first Descriptor describes who the Hunter is, what role <br>they play in the Order, and, in general, what do they do in <br>the world of Broken Tales.<br> ◆ I am a fearsome and merciless ship captain and with <br>my crew of criminals and smugglers I have carried out a <br>thousand raids. I’m always afraid of a mutiny and that’s <br>why I don’t trust others.<br>This Descriptor highlights that Hook is a skilled ship <br>captain and that his crew is a useful and active resource. <br>Unfortunately, Hook does not trust anyone and his paranoia <br>will surely lead him to hesitate at a critical moment.<br>The second Descriptor details one or more resources, <br>characteristics, or special abilities that define what the <br>Hunter can do.<br> ◆ Leadership requires decisiveness and charisma, traits I <br>possess in spades, which is also why I win every duel. <br>But I am a gentleman and I often spare my opponent to <br>prove my superiority.<br>This Descriptor represents Hook’s abilities as a duelist <br>and commander, especially when it comes to a challenge. <br>However, our captain will let his guard down if a challenge <br>is going his way...</p>","markdown":""},"sort":7300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241715,"modifiedTime":1783973241715,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"KiGc4Y54b9uSmwto","name":"Pagina 74","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 74</h2><p>73<br>The third Descriptor will be linked to the Hunter’s Dark <br>Ego, detailing the most powerful Gift.<br> ◆ I have an immortal, albeit repulsive , body. My corpse-<br>like appearance inspires fear in my opponents. Despite <br>it, I love elegant clothes and comfortable, refined places.<br>This Descriptor portrays Hook as undead, able to continue <br>even after suffering the worst injuries. His corpse-like <br>appearance scares mortals, making him even more <br>fearsome. Unfortunately, Hook can no more escape <br>his former life than he could surrender its pleasures. <br>We can’t wait to see him in action at some party, as he <br>awkwardly tries to pass for a distinguished nobleman! <br>Creating <br>Gifts<br>Gifts are unique abilities that make the Hunter special <br>compared to ordinary humans. On a mechanical level, <br>Gifts are the Player’s way of defining the Hunter’s powers <br>and abilities, which can significantly impact the narrative. <br>Gifts are divided into two categories:<br>Normal Gifts: The first two Gifts of each Hunter. They <br>are generally composed of 2 Archetypal Effects and 1 <br>Archetypal Cost.<br>Dark Ego Gift:  The third and most powerful Gift of any <br>Hunter. It can contain any number of Archetypal Effects, <br>but always requires the Archetypal Cost Activator, a <br>Descriptor that describes what the Hunter must do or what <br>has to happen for the Gift’s power to trigger. Alternatively, <br>the Dark Ego Gift can be activated when taking a Wound, <br>even a self-inflicted one, to represent the effort necessary to <br>unleash its power.<br>Describing what the Gift does in the story<br>The first step in creating a Gift is to describe what happens <br>in the Scene when the Hunter uses it. Based on the linked <br>Descriptor, the Keywords and what we would like the <br>Hunter to do, we need to explain what the Gift does in <br>order to have a foundation from which to process all <br>mechanical effects.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":7400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241716,"modifiedTime":1783973241716,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"BvaA1etmDMsoK1In","name":"Pagina 75","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 75</h2><p>ARCHETYPAL EFFECTS<br>74<br>These are the options at our disposal to find a base Gift to <br>build upon:<br> ◆ Find a relevant Gift from a Hunter sheet. All <br>ready-made Hunters are built to bring a specific <br>characterization into play. For this reason, they are <br>often the best starting point for a custom Gift.<br> ◆ Find a relevant Gift from one of the Order’s <br>Treasures (read more abouth them in The Broken <br>Ones expansion). Like those of the Hunters, they are <br>designed to represent iconic powers and abilities.<br> ◆ Add 2 Archetypal Effects and 1 Archetypal Cost <br>together (presented later in the chapter). Each Effect <br>grants a special rule that can be readjusted to the <br>Hunter’s backstory.<br>The number of Archetypal Effects is not limited in the case <br>of the Dark Ego Gift, and the Activator is extrapolated as a <br>Descriptor from the Gift’s effects. <br>It is essential to describe what the Gift does in the story <br>before settling on what it will do at the rules level. By <br>visualizing what happens when a Hunter uses their Gift, it <br>will be very easy to sift through similar Gifts from other <br>Hunters, Archetypal Effects, and Costs to make the right <br>choices.<br>Example: All ready-made Hunters’ Gifts are created on this <br>principle.<br>The Descriptor says: I am a sorceress and my magical powers <br>allow me to do whatever I want. I need the right amount of <br>time to cast my spells. Hence, we decide that Baba Yaga can <br>literally get what she wants with magic, but each spell must <br>have its own magic formula and a physical object to use as a <br>focus. The Archetypal Effect is Manipulating Reality and as <br>we have formulated it, Baba Yaga can literally do anything <br>she wants. From the description, it is clear that the use of an <br>object can be associated with the Archetypal Cost Sacrifice , <br>to which we add Soma Expenditure to limit the power of the <br>Witch.<br>The Gift becomes, therefore: When you want to achieve <br>something, you may use witchcraft. Choose what you want <br>with a sentence like: I want to fly on that old broom or I <br>want to look like a demon in the eyes of those fools. Your <br>spell must be focused on an object in your possession, such as <br>a broom to fly or a mask you can wear to look like a demon. <br>Pay a cost from 0 to 2 Soma, decided by the Storyteller, to <br>activate your spell for the duration of a Scene. Remember <br>that you can’t ask for someone’s sudden death, but you can <br>inflict Wounds with your actions through magic.<br>     <br>In the case of Babai the Judge, we imagined the Hunter with <br>a large, dark body that blends into the surrounding shadows. <br>Babai can scare anyone and only the bravest can hold his <br>searching gaze. His Gift has become: You are like a sinuous <br>shadow that can reach anywhere. During a Scene, you can <br>arrive at a location by covering any distance and overcoming <br>any obstacle if one of your allies or an NPC calls your name. <br>When you manifest your true nature, everyone who witnesses <br>it will be frightened and will not act against you unless you <br>threaten them first. The Storyteller may ask you for a Position <br>Check to frighten particularly powerful characters. Receive 1</p>","markdown":""},"sort":7500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241716,"modifiedTime":1783973241716,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"rjgO8CoRCqOXG5It","name":"Pagina 76","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 76</h2><p>ARCHETYPAL EFFECTS<br>75<br>Additional Success on all Defense Checks you make against the <br>actions of someone who is now fearful.<br>Because this is Babai’s Dark Ego Gift, we can use as many <br>Archetypal Effects as we want. In his case, they are: Freedom of <br>Movement to move in the shadows, Manipulate NPCs for the <br>fear Effect, and 1 Additional Success to strengthen the potency <br>of the Gift, as we have specifically said that only the bravest <br>dare to threaten Babai.<br>Keep in mind the fundamental rule for creating <br>a Gift: the narrative coherence of the Gift’s effect is more <br>important than how strong the Gift is. Don’t concern yourself <br>with Gifts that are too strong or too weak, but rather focus <br>on Gifts that are consistent with the narrative characteristics <br>of the Hunter, making sure that they add something to their <br>story.<br>After playing for a while, it’s always possible to modify the <br>Gift, or adjust the total Soma pool available to a Hunter, to <br>calibrate the availability of a Gift that either is too strong or <br>rarely used. It might take a few Sessions of experimentation, <br>but each Player must be aware that arriving at the ideal <br>version of the Gift may take time and the Storyteller may have <br>to evaluate what happens in the game. If a Gift makes sense <br>with 3 Archetypal Effects instead of 2, no problem: just add 1 <br>Archetypal Cost or subtract 1 from the Hunter’s Soma value. <br>If the choice of the Archetypal Effect is based on narrative <br>coherence and not on the quest for powerful combinations, <br>your games will improve.<br>All the Gifts of ready-made Hunters are created on these <br>principles and are great study material for understanding the <br>creation process, as well as reasons for making exceptions <br>and minor deviations from the standard rules.<br>Archetypal Effects<br>Archetypal Effects are mechanical bonuses representing what <br>happens when the Gift is brought into the game.<br>In some Gifts, two or more Archetypal Effects are added <br>together to achieve the intended narrative outcome. The <br>most iconic example is magic, with which a Hunter can <br>Manipulate Reality, Inflict Wounds, and Create Descriptors. <br>As already mentioned, the priority is always to create a Gift  <br>related to the Hunter’s backstory, limiting any potential <br>power by adding Archetypal Costs to either the same Gift or <br>to the Hunter’s other Gifts. Baba Y aga, the Child Witch is a <br>great example of how to tie together three Gifts to make her <br>Magic Gift very powerful.<br>1 Additional Success<br>Effect: +1 Additional Success to the Hunter Checks in a <br>particular situation.<br>Keywords: expert / advantage / focused skill / above average.<br>Tips: This is the standard Effect to complete a Gift in <br>the absence of other ideas, or to emphasize a particular <br>specialization of the Hunter. It is very easy to connect <br>1 Additional Success to a potential action generated by <br>the other Archetypal Effect of the Gift, and this is a great <br>reinforcement to characterize what the Gift does.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":7600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241716,"modifiedTime":1783973241716,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"f0YXOp01PLHNB4IK","name":"Pagina 77","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 77</h2><p>76<br>2 Additional Successes<br>Effect: +2 Additional Successes to the Hunter Checks in a <br>particular situation.<br>Keywords: master / best / lifelong experience / Unparalleled.<br>Tips: This Effect is great for highlighting an area where the <br>Hunter excels more than anyone else. The advantage of 2 <br>Additional Successes is palpable. For this reason, it is best <br>to tie this Gift to Costs that limit its use to very specific <br>narrative situations. Another recommended Cost is Check <br>Limit, binding the Gift to Position Checks or Defense <br>Checks.<br>3 Additional Successes<br>Effect: Grants +3 Additional Successes to a single Hunter’s <br>Check.<br>Keywords: master stroke / unleashing power / superiority <br>/ targeted action.<br>Tips: This Effect is great for a one-time power burst and <br>sets up an action that the Hunter will rarely fail. This Effect <br>is indicated for Gifts that generate fiction in which the <br>Hunter is confident when displaying their skill. <br>Additional Action<br>Effect: The Hunter has the possibility to act 2 times <br>consecutively in an Exchange, to act 1 extra time during an <br>Exchange, or to perform secondary actions.<br>Keywords: rush / quick / support / hit and run.<br>Tips: This Effect is used to create moments where the <br>Hunter moves to a better position after acting or is able to <br>perform multiple actions at the same time. If the description <br>of the Gift involves multiple actions such as hitting and <br>running, this Effect is best suited to add an extra maneuver. <br>Having additional actions is an Effect that ties in with Costs <br>requiring the investment of something: Soma, Wounds, or <br>Increments are great ways to represent the effort required.<br>Advantage Token<br>Effect: The use of the Gift grants the Hunter 1 or more <br>named Tokens linked to the Gift itself. The Hunter can then <br>spend these Tokens to create another bonus Archetypal <br>Effect.<br>Keywords: strategy / power charge / accumulation / <br>combination.<br>Tips: This Effect represents a mix of various powers that <br>need to be themed on the Hunter’s abilities. It is a great <br>Effect for creating combinations, where the Hunter does <br>something in the fiction to accumulate Tokens that will be <br>useful in the future.<br>Allies<br>Effect: One or more NPCs are in the Hunter’s service. Each <br>has a distinctive Descriptor and will do their best to help <br>the Hunter. The Hunter can also sacrifice or use an ally to <br>obtain additional effects.<br>Keywords: animal companion / followers / minions / gang.<br>Tips: This Effect encompasses all of the Hunter’s possible <br>connections to other NPCs traveling alongside them. <br>Followers, trusted animals, or silent guardians are all <br>grouped under this Effect. When creating a Gift with this <br>Effect it is good to think about what the Hunter can do if <br>their Allies are eliminated or put out of action so that the</p>","markdown":""},"sort":7700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241716,"modifiedTime":1783973241716,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"n6UHGgvCpHaRSgU0","name":"Pagina 78","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 78</h2><p>77<br>Gift doesn’t become useless during a Scenario. A great <br>additional Effect can be the ability to suffer a Wound in <br>place of the Hunter.<br>Automatic Successful Outcome<br>Effect: A single Check performed by the Hunter is <br>automatically a Successful Outcome, with the player <br>selecting one of the three types. Alternatively, a Failed <br>Check can turn into a Successful Outcome.<br>Keywords: determination / flipping the situation / <br>infallible / aiming at the goal.<br>Tips: This Effect can be very powerful and must therefore <br>be linked to one or more Costs limiting its use, such as a <br>time limit or a very specific Narrative Limit. In general, <br>it is not very exciting if the Hunter always succeeds at <br>the right time through the use of the Gift. It’s more fun <br>if a specific situation such as anger or pride leads them to <br>excel at any cost, thus affecting their behavior in the story.<br>Create a Descriptor<br>Effect: The Hunter can create a Descriptor that allows <br>them to power up or extend their abilities. The Descriptor <br>affects the Hunter, modifying their abilities.<br>Keywords: impose / manipulate / manage / create.<br>Tips: This Effect is one of the most versatile and can be <br>used in any Gift where the Hunter creates something to <br>use to their advantage. Magic is the most obvious example, <br>but the ability to adapt to the situation or have many <br>resources at your disposal are also excellent examples. <br>Create a Descriptor can be too versatile of an Effect, so it’s <br>recommended to tie it strongly to a theme that highlights <br>the background and characteristics of the Hunter.<br>Dampen<br>Effect: For one action, the Hunter is able to prevent an <br>enemy from using a Gift, or lower their Opposition Level <br>by 1 or more.<br>Keywords: exterminator / specialized against a threat / <br>hatred / revenge.<br>Tips: This Effect allows the Hunter to make enemies less <br>powerful and must be linked to some knowledge or to an <br>emotion that, in the fiction, makes them fundamentally <br>opposed to that specific threat. <br>Disguise<br>Effect: During the course of a Scene the Hunter can <br>appear different from what they really are, or make sure <br>that they are not noticed by others when entering or <br>exiting the Scene. No one can prevent them from doing so. <br>Keywords: underestimating / shadow / masquerading / <br>disguising.<br>Tips: This Effect is useful if the Hunter needs a free hand <br>without attracting attention. At the same time, it can also <br>represent individuals who enjoy behavioral freedom on a <br>social level. A good Cost related to this Effect is Reaction <br>to an Event, as it allows you to set a condition (such as a <br>certain behavior or the activation of other Gifts) to reveal <br>the Hunter’s deception.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":7800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241716,"modifiedTime":1783973241716,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"5pTSq9gLPImOBW78","name":"Pagina 79","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 79</h2><p>ARCHETYPAL EFFECTS<br>78<br>Freedom of Movement<br>Effect: Allows the Hunter to move freely, ignoring <br>environmental and enemy restrictions, such as a Defense <br>Check to avoid interference. <br>Keywords: escape routes / disappear / appear / hunt.<br>Tips: This Effect can allow the Hunter to move or follow a <br>target without performing Defense Checks. It is optimal for <br>elusive characters or as an additional Effect of an Outcome <br>with an Increment.<br>Get XP<br>Effect: The Hunter receives 1 or 2 XP for achieving a <br>particular type of action related to their story and personal <br>goals. In general terms, performing this action gives inner <br>strength to the Hunter.<br>Keywords: reward / goal / improve / willpower.<br>Tips: This Effect is perfect as a complement to some Gifts <br>as it does not provide a direct bonus that can throw the <br>story out of balance, instead offering a long-term benefit <br>for the Hunter. However, it is good to keep the story of the <br>Hunter in mind and consider the motives that drive them <br>to improve or to learn from mistakes.<br>Inflicting a Wound<br>Effect: This allows you to inflict 1 additional Wound on a <br>target or inflict 1 Wound by simply activating the Gift.<br>Keywords: mighty / anger / targeted / specialized. <br>Tips: This Effect is great for giving the Hunter offensive <br>power and making them feel more dangerous. Given the <br>small pool and their importance, it is good to limit the <br>possibility of inflicting additional Wounds with a dedicated <br>Cost, such as requiring an Outcome with Increment or, <br>even better, imposing a Narrative Limit. The Gift’s Effect <br>can also indicate a power that the Hunter manifests and <br>that inflicts 1 Wound on potential targets, independently <br>from the Hunter’s action.<br>Interruption<br>Effect: This allows you to interrupt an opponent’s action to <br>activate a special effect or act before them.<br>Keywords: lightning-fast / feint / foreshadowing / <br>bodyguard.<br>Tips: This Effect allows the Hunter to act outside of his <br>turn in an Exchange and to interrupt what is happening in <br>the story. It is a good way to highlight a Hunter’s predictive <br>and threat-management skills, allowing them to stand <br>between the danger and another subject or to activate an <br>Effect that is triggered in relation to a specific event. <br>Manipulate NPCs<br>Effect: The Hunter can impose conditions and behaviors <br>on the NPCs they interact with. By default, the Effect is <br>automatic on Minor NPCs and may require a Position <br>Check for Major NPCs and Dark Presences.<br>Keywords: charm / fear / charisma / trust.<br>Tips: This Effect represents a Hunter’s innate charm or <br>social skills. As it can be very useful in social contexts, it is <br>good to limit the Effect with Costs that mark its use as Once <br>per Scene or take into account that the Hunter will activate <br>it whenever they can.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":7900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241716,"modifiedTime":1783973241716,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"QtvM7PYNRxNggf67","name":"Pagina 80","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 80</h2><p>ARCHETYPAL EFFECTS<br>79<br>Manipulating Reality<br>Effect: The Hunter can decide on an Effect and make it <br>real. The Effect can vary based on context and encompass <br>several other Archetypal Effects, such as Reshaping the <br>Environment or Inflicting a Wound. It is usually good to <br>specify what can be done and what falls within the limits <br>of the Gift, such as affecting or not affecting living beings.<br>Keywords: magic / arcane power / supernatural item / <br>supernatural. <br>Tips: Like Create a Descriptor, this Effect allows the <br>Hunter to apply the Gift directly to the narrative without <br>going through a Position Check. It is advisable to tie this <br>Effect to Costs that require the investment of resources, <br>such as Soma or Wounds.<br>Multiple Benefits <br>Effect: A list of minor advantages (from 2 to 4 Effects) that <br>the Hunter can use independently or all at once. Advantages <br>can be inspired by all the other Archetypal Effects. The use <br>of each must be tied to a specific action.<br>Keywords: resources / versatile / variety / multifunction.<br>Tips: This Effect is especially good for Gifts that do many <br>different things. In this way, it is possible to wrap different <br>abilities within the same Gift. It is important that all of the <br>Gift’s options are consistent with its description. <br>Multiple Targets<br>Effect: Using the Gift allows the Hunter to hit more <br>than one target. However, a different Position Check for <br>each target is required. Alternatively, the Hunter can <br>automatically eliminate an NPC with a single Wound <br>without going through a Check.<br>Keywords: bloodlust / impetuousness / alone against all / <br>aimed shot.<br>Tips: This Effect makes the Hunter more fearsome against <br>multiple opponents. The most suitable Cost is Increment <br>Expenditure, so that using the Effect is not tied down by <br>more dire Costs, but is still linked to the success of a Check. <br>Against minor enemies with a single Wound, consider <br>using this Effect as a secondary bonus to another action. <br>Obtaining Information<br>Effect: Provides useful information to the Hunter on <br>one or more specific topics. The Hunter gets information <br>useful in the continuing Scenario or suggestions from the <br>Storyteller on a possible choice to make.<br>Keywords: wisdom / intuition / clairvoyance / travel.<br>Tips: This Effect is a great complement to a Gift and grants a <br>subtle advantage that can be used to mechanically represent <br>a Hunter’s skills or expertise. An easy way to add to the <br>fiction is to link the type of information obtained to talents <br>and knowledge indicated by the Hunter’s Descriptors.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":8000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241716,"modifiedTime":1783973241716,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"NQTr79uM1Inqq4SH","name":"Pagina 81","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 81</h2><p>80<br>Recover Soma<br>Effect: The Hunter can recover 1 Soma by achieving <br>a particular goal, such as demonstrating something or <br>making progress towards a personal quest. In general terms, <br>performing this action gives the Hunter inner strength.<br>Keywords: determination / milestone / inner strength / <br>goal.<br>Tips: Thanks to this effect, the Hunter can replenish their <br>Soma reserve as a result of certain actions. To prevent <br>abuse of this Effect, the specific actions required should be <br>somehow intimately linked to the Hunter’s background. Be <br>careful not to create a loop with Soma Expenditure, which <br>is an unpleasant situation where a Hunter spends 1 Soma <br>and then immediately recovers it. <br>Recover Wounds<br>Effect: The Hunter can recover, or help someone recover, <br>1 or more Wounds over the course of the Scene. This effect <br>can also represent a regeneration power or immortality.<br>Keywords: healing / regeneration / taking a breath / <br>endurance.<br>Tips: Thanks to this Effect, the Hunter can heal themselves <br>or others. It is good to limit the use of this Effect so as not <br>to make Wounds management during a Scene superfluous. <br>On the other hand, if the idea is to reproduce a regeneration <br>power, the recovery can be faster and free of additional <br>costs. <br>Replication<br>Effect: The Hunter can copy a Gift or Descriptor they have <br>seen in action. Alternatively, they can have access to several <br>Gifts for a limited time.<br>Keywords: adaptation / ace up your sleeve / replicate / <br>imitate.<br>Tips: This Effect is highly versatile. For this reason, it <br>must be limited in its use with relevant costs, such as Soma <br>Expenditure or Once per Scene. It can be a good idea to <br>limit the Gifts a Hunter can replicate to those which are <br>consistent with their Descriptors.<br>Reshaping the Environment<br>Effect: The Hunter can impose conditions and changes <br>to their environment, creating a dedicated Descriptor. <br>Normally the Effect lasts a Scene, but it can also be <br>permanent. It isn’t possible to directly harm someone <br>by Reshaping the Environment. The Storyteller can rule <br>that someone is at risk of injury if it makes sense in the <br>circumstances. However, in that case the Storyteller may <br>request a Position Check from the Hunter using this Gift.<br>Keywords: nature / light / dark / passage.<br>Tips: The significant difference from the Create a <br>Descriptor Effect is that this Gift does not act on the Hunter <br>but on the surrounding environment. It can still be a good <br>idea to link related Descriptors to the narrative theme of <br>the Gift, such as manipulating nature, a specific element, or <br>other themes suggested by your Hunter’s concept.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":8100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241716,"modifiedTime":1783973241716,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ruth3sZ98TxG26Zd","name":"Pagina 82","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 82</h2><p>81<br>Resources<br>Effect: The Hunter has or can easily procure whatever <br>resources are needed. This includes special items that can <br>grant 1 Additional Success.<br>Keywords: wealth / travel bag / contacts / organized.<br>Tips: As with the Allies Effect, you may want to consider <br>where the Hunter draws their resources from and what they <br>can do to recover access to them if the narrative separates <br>them from the main source.<br>Support<br>Effect: Using this Gift allows the Hunter to grant 1 or more <br>Additional Successes to an ally. If this is applied to an NPC, <br>the Gift allows them to increase their Opposition Level. <br>It is also possible to bestow other benefits such as Soma, <br>Wounds, or temporary Descriptors. The Effect is active for <br>the duration of a Check in the case of Additional Successes, <br>or for a Scene in the case of Descriptors. The Storyteller can <br>evaluate other cases. <br>Keywords: team play / advice / leader / strategist.<br>Tips: This Effect is a good way to empower Hunters related <br>to teamwork or leadership. The Once per Scene limitation <br>is a good Cost here, so as not to make support for other <br>Hunters a constant.<br>Archetypal Costs<br>Archetypal Costs represent a series of limits to prevent a Gift <br>from being used excessively during the game. Thanks to the <br>Archetypal Cost, the use of a Gift will be more focused and <br>distinctive, and its use more consistent with the Hunter’s <br>backstory. The Dark Ego Gift must always have Activator <br>as Archetypal Cost. This Cost compensates for the fact <br>that the Gift can contain more than two Archetypal Effects <br>without having to worry too much about balancing Costs.<br>Activator (Dark Ego Gift only)<br>Effect: The activation of the Gift is dependent on the <br>Descriptor, which acts as a trigger and represents the <br>link between the Hunter now and what they were in their <br>fairytale of origin. Alternatively, the Hunter can suffer or <br>self-inflict 1 Wound to activate the Gift.<br>Keywords: Dark Ego / the original fairytale / true self / <br>revealing what one really is.<br>Tips: The Activator must always be an action that connects <br>a Hunter to their villainous forebears in their original <br>fairytale. To outline it, think about what the Hunter has to <br>do in the narrative to highlight their connection with the <br>fairytale character they were. When the Hunter activates <br>their Dark Ego, what they used to be must unambiguously <br>re-emerge in the fiction.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":8200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241716,"modifiedTime":1783973241716,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"YDBVV3JHlUVKHSei","name":"Pagina 83","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 83</h2><p>ARCHETYPAL COSTS<br>82<br>Check Limit<br>Effect: The Gift can only be activated during a certain type <br>of Check: either Position or Defense. <br>Keywords: specialty / perfect defense / perfect action / <br>unrivaled.<br>Tips: This is a great way to limit Effects that grant <br>Additional Successes or that, in general, can be used too <br>frequently. Linking a Gift to a type of Check is also a good <br>way to make it more distinctive, with a Position Check <br>implying a more active role and Defense Check suggesting <br>a more passive one.<br>Checks Penalties<br>Effect: After the activation of the Gift, the Hunter receives <br>1 or more Penalties for Position or Defense Checks, either <br>for an action or the whole Scene.<br>Keywords: guard down / distraction / obsession / <br>confusion.<br>Tips: This Cost, when applied to the whole Scene, is a <br>serious problem and can be a good way to balance a Gift  <br>that is otherwise too strong. Conversely, a Penalty applied <br>to the following action allows you to balance a Gift with a <br>small disadvantage. It is easy to justify the Penalty in the <br>fiction by tying it to the Hunter’s emotional state, such as <br>being in a frenzy or confused by what happens after using <br>the Gift.<br>Drawback Descriptor<br>Effect: Activating the Gift allows the Storyteller to create a <br>related Descriptor that highlights a flaw or loss of control. <br>The Descriptor remains active throughout the Scene.<br>Keywords: loss of control / unexpected problem / attracting <br>attention / flaw.<br>Tips: This Cost is perfect for providing narrative hooks <br>that the Storyteller can exploit to take the story in new <br>directions. The Hunter avoids immediate, direct costs in <br>exchange for risking potential long-term complications.<br>Drawback Token<br>Effect: The use of the Gift grants the Storyteller 1 or more <br>named Token linked to the Gift itself. The Storyteller spends <br>the Tokens, later on, to represent a long-term cost to the <br>Hunter, creating a negative Descriptor, assigning 1 Penalty, <br>or other effects. As a minor Effect, this Cost allows you to <br>get rid of accumulated Drawback Tokens with a specific <br>action during an Interlude. The action must be linked to <br>the Hunter’s backstory.<br>Keywords: ignore the consequences / insanity / <br>unpredictable / promise.<br>Tips: This Cost represents a mix between spending <br>resources and creating long-term consequences in the <br>Scenario. The Hunter gets an immediate advantage, with <br>the Storyteller promising to make them pay for it at a <br>later time. It’s an excellent Cost when representing special <br>powers that aren’t fully under the Hunter’s control.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":8300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241716,"modifiedTime":1783973241716,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"U9LxEFCPj9dhhChW","name":"Pagina 84","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 84</h2><p>ARCHETYPAL COSTS<br>83<br>Increment Expenditure<br>Effect: The Gift can be activated as an Increment. <br>Keywords: mastery / superiority / show / combination.<br>Tips: This Cost is particularly suitable for Gifts related to <br>combat or fast actions. The frequency of use depends on <br>the number of Checks made by the Hunter. <br>Narrative Limit<br>Effect: The Gift can only be activated when a specific <br>condition manifests in the narrative, such as during a one-<br>on-one challenge or in the presence of a specific object. <br>Alternatively, the Gift has the obligation to introduce a <br>specific Descriptor representing the limit of what the Gift  <br>can do.<br>Keywords: basic rules / tools / situation / routine.<br>Tips: This is one of the most versatile and characteristic <br>Costs because it allows you to limit the use of a Gift by tying <br>it to its narrative component. Narrative Limit is a great way <br>to push the narrative directly towards what you expect <br>your Hunter to do in play. In general, a good place to start <br>is to analyze how the power of a Gift is activated. Often, <br>you’ll notice that the Narrative Limit is already in the Gift’s <br>description.<br>Once per Scenario<br>Effect: The Gift can be used once per Scenario.<br>Keywords: twist / changing the cards / great power / <br>absolute protagonist of the moment.<br>Tips: This Cost should be reserved only for Gifts with a <br>great impact on the narrative or which allow the Hunter to <br>perform incredible actions. If the idea of the Gift is out of <br>the box, like resurrecting or forever changing the mind of <br>a minor NPC, the limit of Once per Scenario is optimal to <br>give the right emphasis to the Gift and make it a real twist. <br>This Cost strongly limits the use of the Gift, so consider <br>applying it only to one of the Archetypal Effects. In this way, <br>a very powerful Effect can be contained without completely <br>impeding the Gift’s usage.<br>Once per Scene<br>Effect: The Gift can be used once per Scene.<br>Keywords: distinctive action / moment under the spotlight <br>/ marked / regular cost.<br>Tips: This is by far the most versatile Cost. During each <br>Scene it creates a moment in the spotlight for the Hunter’s <br>Gift, preventing abuse. <br>Once until the Next Interlude<br>Effect: After being used, the Gift recharges after an <br>Interlude. <br>Keywords: recharge / rest / preparation / limited.<br>Suggestions: This Cost strongly limits the use of the <br>Gift and it may be best to apply this Cost to only one of <br>the Archetypal Effects associated with a Gift. In this way, <br>a very powerful Effect can be limited without completely <br>impeding the Gift’s usage.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":8400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241716,"modifiedTime":1783973241716,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"LaoCxYI1NlNCEF2V","name":"Pagina 85","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 85</h2><p>84<br>Random Effect<br>Effect: The activation of the Gift is linked to a die roll. <br>When the chosen numbers are rolled the Gift may not <br>work at all, or does work but with a serious drawback, or <br>something totally unexpected may happen. Alternatively, <br>you can create a list of six random minor Effects that <br>accompany the Gift’s use.<br>Keywords: random / malfunction / try your luck / bet.<br>Tips: This Cost can be a good substitute for set Costs such <br>as Soma or Wounds, but should be used sparingly. Take into <br>account that with Random Effect a Gift could, with certain <br>rolls, always be activated for free or always have a Cost. In <br>the long run, that might prove frustrating for the Hunter. <br>Reaction to an Event<br>Effect: The Gift automatically activates or stops when a <br>specific event occurs.<br>Keywords: defense / reaction / contrast / preparation.<br>Tips: This Cost is great for encouraging the Hunter to <br>avoid certain actions with consequences that effectively put <br>an end to the Gift’s use. This is a Narrative Limit variant <br>relying on external circumstances rather than the Player’s <br>choice.<br>Sacrifice<br>Effect: Activating the Gift requires a special focus or the <br>sacrifice of an expensive resource. Each time or just once, <br>at the discretion of the Storyteller.<br>Keywords: essential components / ritual / pledge / specific <br>equipment.<br>Tips: This Cost is perfect for Gifts related to magic or that <br>require a focus to manifest. The sacrifice may not always be <br>easily within the Hunter’s grasp, or the Hunter may have to <br>come up with imaginative ways to satisfy the requirement <br>for a focus.<br>Soma Expenditure<br>Effect: Using the Gift requires the investment of 1 or more <br>Soma points.<br>Keywords: energy expense / limited resources / commitment <br>/ manifesting power.<br>Tips: This is the best Cost to limit Gifts that can be used <br>multiple times over the course of a Scene. It leaves the <br>Hunter free to decide when to use the Gift while imposing <br>a hard limit.<br>Wound Expenditure<br>Effect: Activating the Gift inflicts 1 or more Wounds to <br>the Hunter.<br>Keywords: effort / exposed / adrenaline / punishment.<br>Tips: Paying 1 Wound is a very heavy Cost. For this reason, <br>it is suitable for Gifts that are extremely versatile or have a <br>significant impact on the narrative.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":8500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241716,"modifiedTime":1783973241716,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"z9kCWu2TKl5NhF06","name":"Pagina 86","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 86</h2><p>85<br>Give a distinctive name to <br>the Gift<br>Even if it seems trivial, the name of a Gift reveals a lot about <br>the Hunter who uses it. I Will have my Satisfaction, James <br>the Swordsman’s Gift, immediately clarifies the feeling of <br>revenge that moves him. If Y ou Don’t Stop, I’ll Call the <br>Bogeyman! immediately makes us understand the true <br>nature of Babai the Judge. Choosing a good name for a Gift <br>must not be underestimated.<br>Example: Hook’s Gifts<br>The first Gift highlights the fact that Hook isn’t the only <br>survivor of the sea monster: his crew has returned from the <br>dead with him to serve him. Hook can then call his men <br>back to service at any time, resurrecting them from <br>the ground itself.<br>First of all, to build the Gift it’s a good idea to check <br>for a similar one among the Hunters’ ready-made <br>ones. We find a suitable one on Regina the Thief of <br>Hearts’ sheet.<br>The Queen: During a Scene you always have a <br>couple of trusted servants with you, ready to execute <br>your every order. Create a Descriptor for each, <br>which represents the skill for which you hold them <br>in your service. Your servants will do their best to <br>satisfy your every wish. Decide how you pay them. <br>The Storyteller, when and if they deem it necessary, <br>will ask you to honor their services so as not to lose <br>the use of this Gift for the rest of the Scene. You can <br>check this Descriptor multiple times to get XP .<br>Hook will have the crew around him and they will <br>be undead too. The first part of the Gift is therefore already <br>perfect for our purpose. On the other hand, it isn’t consistent <br>with Hook’s backstory that he has to “pay” for the services in <br>some way. After all, they are gallows’ material! We replace the <br>Archetypal Cost (Sacrifice, in the case of Regina) with Soma <br>Expenditure. We’re also expanding the Archetypal Effect of <br>Allies, adding the ability for Hook to shield himself with his <br>men. Since the Gift seems stronger than Regina’s, we add an <br>additional Archetypal Cost in the form of a Narrative Limit. <br>Hook’s followers are always undead, limited in their actions <br>by being corpses.<br>Summarizing, Hook’s Gift will be:<br>The Captain: During the course of a Scene you can spend <br>1 Soma to summon a couple of trusted sailors, who will <br>emerge from the ground to help you. Create a Descriptor for <br>each, representing the skill for which you hold <br>them in your service. Remember to use the <br>word walking dead and that, as versatile as <br>you wish them to be, they are still pirates. <br>Your subordinates will carry out your every <br>order, even the most dangerous ones. They’re <br>already dead, so things can’t get much worse. <br>Once per Scene, when you suffer a Wound <br>you can sacrifice one of your subordinates <br>to suffer it in your place, leaving them in a <br>thousand pieces.  <br>The base for the second Gift will consist of the <br>Keywords skillful, duel, and win. Hook is a <br>formidable opponent and his sword skills are <br>unmatched. To make him properly heroic, <br>he’ll be one of the best swordsmen in the <br>world.<br>The basis will be the Archetypal Effect <br>1 Additional Success , renamed Win</p>","markdown":""},"sort":8600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241716,"modifiedTime":1783973241716,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ftvhfsUWpCUnEdkH","name":"Pagina 87","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 87</h2><p>86<br>Every Challenge. As Archetypal Cost, we apply Narrative <br>Limitation. As a second Effect we pick Additional Action, <br>but another relevant Effect is 3 Additional Successes. Being <br>3 Archetypal Effects, a good way to have them all is to balance <br>them with 2 Costs represented by 2 extra Narrative Limits.<br>The second Gift of Hook becomes:<br>Winning Every Challenge: When you fight, few opponents <br>can stand up to you. Get 1 Additional Success when you <br>perform a Check to attack or disable an opponent. Once per <br>Scene, when you eliminate a Minor NPC with 1 Wound, you <br>can immediately take another action. Once per Scene your <br>bonus increases to 3 Additional Successes, but you cannot <br>use this Gift against an enemy who has already suffered a <br>Wound.<br>The third Gift is the Dark Ego one and, in this case, it is <br>possible to combine multiple Archetypal Effects without <br>limits. The important keywords are: immortal and awe-<br>inspiring.<br>Again, a Gift we already worked out for a Hunter serves as <br>a great foundation: Babai the Judge already has a fear-based <br>Gift.<br>Dark Ego - If Y ou Don’t Stop I’ll Call the Bogeyman!<br>You are like a sinuous shadow that can reach anywhere. <br>During a Scene, you can arrive at a location by covering <br>any distance and overcoming any obstacle if one of your <br>allies or an NPC calls your name. When you manifest your <br>true nature, everyone who witnesses it will be frightened <br>and will not act against you unless you threaten them first. <br>The Storyteller may ask you for a Position Check to frighten <br>particularly powerful characters. Receive 1 Additional <br>Success on all Defense Checks you make against the actions <br>of someone who is now fearful.<br>Activator: Enter or exit a shadow by manifesting your true <br>nature and scaring someone.<br>The first part of the Gift (related to moving in the shadows) <br>is not a good fit for Hook, while the part where he frightens <br>everyone is exactly in theme with the Keyword awe-<br>inspiring. It will therefore suffice to simply use the Archetypal <br>Effect Recover Wounds, linking it to the Keyword immortal.<br>The Dark Ego Gift will be:<br>Dark Ego - I’m the Fearsome Captain Hook!<br>Your body is immortal and therefore you cannot be destroyed <br>by conventional means. Once per Scene, you can spend 1 <br>Soma to immediately regenerate a Wound you have suffered. <br>You can move the severed parts of your body for a short <br>period of time. When you manifest your true nature all the <br>witnesses will be frightened and will not act against you <br>unless you threaten them first. The Storyteller may ask you for <br>a Position Check to scare off particularly powerful characters. <br>Receive 1 Additional Success on all Position Checks you make <br>to interrogate or intimidate someone.<br>Activator: Flaunt your cadaverous body and show everyone <br>that you have conquered even death.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":8700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"GzxbzSQkJiuydtnP","name":"Pagina 88","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 88</h2><p>87<br>Determine the reserve of Soma<br>A Hunter’s Soma reserve starts at 6 points and can be <br>reduced or increased in relation to the power of their Gifts.<br> ◆ If a Gift has many Archetypal Effects, it has a strong <br>influence on a Scene when it is activated, or can be used <br>with a very high frequency, you may want to consider <br>reducing the Hunter’s Soma reserve by 1.<br> ◆ If a Gift is very situational, confers a very specific <br>advantage, or is rarely used consider raising the <br>Hunter’s reserve by 1.<br>During the course of the game, don’t hesitate to adjust the <br>Soma supply if you find that a Gift is too strong and versatile <br>or not strong enough. As mentioned earlier, you don’t have <br>to categorically limit power, just make small corrections to <br>make a Hunter as balanced as possible. Y ou will realize that, <br>depending on your table’s style, the same Gift can have very <br>different applications in play!<br>A combat-based Gift will be enormously useful if your <br>playstyle points to very action-packed storytelling. On <br>the other hand, if you love investigations and social <br>confrontation, it could appear in the Scene with much less <br>frequency.<br>Example: Hook’s Soma reserve.<br>Hook has three Gifts that, from a first evaluation, are within <br>the average. Winning Every Challenge has 3 Archetypal <br>Effects but also 3 Archetypal Costs, and that should even <br>out the score. As a result, it is optimal for Hook to start <br>with a reserve of 6 Soma points. For comparison, James the <br>Swordsman has the Gift Tick Tock, Here Comes the Beast, <br>which is not fully under his control and can only be used in <br>open spaces. Because of these limitations, we have estimated <br>that its use is much more situational and therefore James’ <br>Soma reserve is 7.<br>Detail the equipment<br>All that remains to do is to detail the equipment and any <br>other possessions based on the Descriptors.<br>The story told so far and the Descriptors are the basis for <br>defining the equipment of the Hunter.<br>Even if the rules don’t focus on equipment as a game bonus, <br>this doesn’t mean that it’s not important to outline a Hunter’s <br>possessions, especially in order to describe something about <br>them. Each Player must outline the Hunter’s possessions, <br>with the help of the following questions.<br> ◆ What did the Hunter do before joining the Order? Do <br>they have a home and allies to return to?<br> ◆ Does the Hunter bring with them a present from a <br>loved one? Is it something they would never part with?<br> ◆ How does the Hunter deal with danger and combat? <br>With what weapons and means?<br> ◆ What items and possessions are essential for the Hunter <br>to do what their Descriptors suggest?<br> ◆ Does the Hunter have something rare and unique or <br>of great value with them? What advantages does this <br>possession confer?<br> ◆ Does the Hunter have an object, a coat of arms, or a <br>symbol with them that gives them social importance?<br>Finally, try to give the Hunter at least one item that is a <br>reference to their original fairytale.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":8800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Hi3VLJgCmQJMMCzK","name":"Pagina 89","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 89</h2><p>88<br>Example: Hook’s equipment.<br>The old ship Jolly Roger /A crew ready to serve me / My <br>trusted dueling blade / A tooth of the monster that devoured <br>me / Fine clothes for every occasion / A bag full of treasures <br>and riches of my raids /A book of poems.<br>The Hunters’ creation: <br>wrapping it up<br>At this point, it is good to stop for a moment and describe <br>what has been created. Each Player must portray the <br>character that has emerged from the Hunter’s Descriptors. <br>The Storyteller, meanwhile, can compile information <br>relating to the Order and the world of Broken Europe, <br>based on the same Descriptors. <br>For each Descriptor created, the Storyteller can ask one of <br>the following questions:<br> ◆ Where in the world is it characteristic to have this <br>Descriptor? <br> ◆ Who created the equipment, technique, or ability <br>outlined in the Descriptor? <br> ◆ Are the abilities of the Descriptor unique or do other <br>subjects possess them as well? <br> ◆ Why is it that the Descriptor is so important to the <br>Order? <br> ◆ Is the Order aware of the Descriptor? <br> ◆ How does the Hunter keep the Descriptor hidden from <br>the eyes of ordinary people? <br> ◆ Who allowed or taught the Hunter the power of the <br>Descriptor? <br> ◆ Why is the Descriptor so important to them?<br>Each takes turns describing the Hunter quickly and <br>answering any doubts and questions. Having done this, the <br>Player expresses an idea linked to their Hunter’s role in the <br>Order and how they ended up in the service of the Papacy. <br>This step is useful for creating Hunter-related situations <br>and NPCs.<br>As in the creation of the Descriptors, in this phase, the <br>Storyteller’s task is to connect to the players’ ideas and, <br>above all, to ask questions to obtain useful elements for <br>the first Scenario and suitable material to outline Broken <br>Europe.<br>The Players decide if the Hunters have already had the <br>opportunity to carry out missions together, or if the first <br>Scenario is the first time they meet. In Broken Tales, the <br>Order glues the Hunters together and the quick setup of the <br>game purposely avoids creating overly detailed backstories. <br>During Interludes, there will be the chance to ask more <br>questions about the other characters. This will allow Players <br>to add details of the evolving stories of the Hunters’ time <br>together. However, if the Players find it interesting, nothing <br>prevents them from deepening their Hunter’s backstory at <br>this juncture as well.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":8900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"RoFjLShMJxefub8r","name":"Pagina 90","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 90</h2><p>SCENARIOS<br>89<br>ScenariosEach Scenario of Broken Tales is inspired by a <br>classic fairytale, “breaking” it into a new story of mystery <br>and horror set in Broken Europe. Scenarios can be played <br>as single episodes, choosing a group of Hunters from the <br>pre-generated selection, or can be included in a long-term <br>Campaign as explained on page 243.<br>When the Storyteller selects a Scenario, they must read <br>it from top to bottom in order to have a clear idea of the <br>connections between the Main NPCs, their Agenda, and <br>the Events that are presented. Broken Tales’ emerging <br>play style will make each story feel different, thanks to the <br>possible combinations of Scenarios and Hunters. When <br>deciding which Scenario to suggest, the Storyteller must <br>keep in mind the following considerations.<br>Safety Keywords<br>Each Scenario presents a series of Keywords related to <br>sensitive topics that the plots will focus on. Depending on <br>how well they know their fellow players, the Storyteller will <br>thus be able to evaluate whether to list the Keywords to <br>the Players before starting to play, or possibly just mention <br>the themes that could come up. Knowing the Keywords <br>can suggest to the players what can happen during the <br>story and create a “spoiler” that may not be appreciated. <br>However, it is advisable to share them with groups of players <br>you don’t know or when in doubt, as not doing so could <br>make someone uncomfortable. The gaming table must be <br>a safe and fun place for everyone to enjoy the experience. <br>Some Scenarios are more adventurous and fantastic than <br>others and choosing them can be a good way to avoid <br>potentially awkward situations. However, it is always good <br>to highlight to all participants that Broken Tales is a game <br>that uses (even extreme) horror as one of its foundational <br>characteristics, and this aspect must be understood and <br>accepted by everyone sitting at the table.<br>Scene Tree<br>In each Scenario, the information provided is limited <br>to what the Storyteller really needs to manage the game <br>without setting up a plot in which the choices of the Hunters <br>would have little weight. The Scene Tree, on the other <br>hand, offers a plot “to follow” and is an excellent system <br>for a group of newbies or to run a single Session. Even if <br>the Storyteller is not planning on using the Scene Tree, the <br>information provided there makes for useful additions and <br>can help bring focus to various parts of the story such as <br>places and characters. The Scene Tree can therefore also be</p>","markdown":""},"sort":9000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"hppNF1NVh8HdqDu4","name":"Pagina 91","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 91</h2><p>90<br>used as inspiration to support what the Storyteller will have <br>to establish on the fly during the Session in response to the <br>choices of the Hunters.<br>Choosing the Hunters<br>After reading the Scenario, the Storyteller could opt to <br>exclude some Hunters from the roster if their Gifts would <br>cause problems in a Scenario, even if Players are otherwise <br>free to choose. To give an example, Bluebeard’s Gift, The <br>Key to Every Door, allows you to read the memories of a <br>corpse. This can make the Storyteller’s life difficult if the <br>Scenario opens at the scene of the crime, with the dead <br>person being immediately “interrogated” by Bluebeard <br>thanks to his Gift.<br>Even if Broken Tales is based on the absolute choice of the <br>Hunters, who hold the reins of the story, the game must also <br>be fun and interesting for the Storyteller to run. Excluding <br>a Hunter who would create difficulties because their Gifts <br>would too easily overcome the challenges in the Scenario is <br>absolutely an acceptable choice.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":9100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"XoNQ9R345mz2Iflv","name":"Pagina 92","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 92</h2><p>91<br>Scenario Creation<br>A Broken Tales Scenario is, at its core, a set of <br>information that the Storyteller prepares before the Game <br>Session, including events, characters, and other details. <br>A good Scenario introduces an interesting mystery for the <br>Hunters to investigate, leaving a lot of room for the Players <br>to “maneuver” between one Scene and the next. Although <br>it is possible to improvise everything on the spot, we don’t <br>recommend it: you risk losing the plot thread and may end <br>up with an incoherent and confusing Session. By nature, <br>Broken Tales references classic fairytales. Improvising a <br>Scenario that draws from a fairytale while twisting it into <br>a Broken Tale is a tall order. Instead, the Storyteller should <br>do some prep work before the game.<br>This book presents many ready-made Scenarios, inspired <br>by as many classic fairytales, which the Storyteller can use <br>to dramatically cut the preparation time. <br>Y ou might want, however, to break a fairytale not featured <br>in this book or break one that we’ve covered, but put your <br>own spin on it. This section is designed to explain in detail <br>the procedure to do so.<br>Step 1 – Choose a fairytale to break<br>Each Broken Tales Scenario is an investigation involving a <br>group of Hunters. Although the inciting incident can vary <br>(the Hunters arrive at someone’s request, or they happen <br>upon a mystery by chance or, again, they follow a lead from <br>a previous Scenario), the events will always be linked to a <br>story that unfolds through locations and NPCs inspired by <br>the fairytale we’ve chosen to break. <br>To begin, the Storyteller will have to choose the underlying <br>fairytale. As for the creation of the Hunters, in addition <br>to books, the web is full of sites and sources about classic <br>fairytales. The basic assumption is that starting from a <br>story, its broken version will be much darker, most likely <br>featuring elements of horror, and its protagonists will be <br>transfigured into something new. <br>The Scenario itself doesn’t have to be the inverted version <br>of the original story. What matters is that its core elements <br>are present and used in original ways. A good idea for an <br>interesting story to play is more important than consistently <br>following the fairytale’s story. If you creatively use Keywords <br>for inspiration, you’ll see situations and characters emerge <br>organically, already linked to their counterparts in the <br>original story.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":9200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"84MfRyvcSyeo12Oi","name":"Pagina 93","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 93</h2><p>92<br>We will use Red-Hood Iskra (inspired by Little Red Riding <br>Hood) as an example Scenario. You’ll find the full version in <br>this book, on page 118.<br>Step 2 – Jot down the Keywords<br>Once the fairytale has been chosen, it’s time to read it again <br>with an eye for the elements that interest you. Keywords can <br>be created by jotting down key phrases or concepts at the <br>core of the fairytale. As mentioned, Keywords will inspire <br>the creation of elements that are effortlessly consistent with <br>the original story.<br>Example: The Keywords of Little Red Riding Hood.<br>Little house near the wood / Little girl / Mother / Sick <br>Grandmother / Forest / The mother advises being careful <br>during the journey / Wolf in the woods / Deception / The Wolf <br>presents himself deceitfully / Disguise / The Hunter notices <br>what has happened / Opening the Wolf ’s belly and filling it <br>with stones / The Wolf decides to take a walk in the woods / <br>The Wolf is breathless and dies.<br>Step 3 – Define the Opponents, the <br>other Main NPCs, and their Agenda<br>Before writing a Scenario, it is good to define the “main <br>actors” on the stage. First of all, choosing the main <br>antagonist of the Scenario is crucial, since many of the <br>challenges the Hunters will face center on their opponent.<br>In Broken Tales, parts are switched. <br>The “bad guys” are now Hunters, while the “good ones” <br>become the Broken Tales at the center of the Scenarios. <br>However, casting the original protagonist as the one who <br>pulls the strings can become boring fast. It will often be <br>more interesting to assign this role to a secondary character <br>from the original fairytale. Many players approach the <br>game taking for granted the classic twist of good people <br>turning bad and will surely be surprised if the real enemy is <br>not who they expect.<br>Every single character in the fairytale can be a good <br>antagonist, provided they have the right motivations. <br>Considering that the “original villains” of a fairytale often <br>become Hunters, it is not necessary to include them in the <br>Scenario if an interesting role doesn’t naturally emerge in <br>the story. It is much more important to add depth to all the <br>other characters.<br>If inspiration doesn’t strike, roll several times on the <br>following table, once for each column. The results will give <br>you some hints regarding how to pick the right villain.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":9300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"54wLw6NV33IPFsro","name":"Pagina 94","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 94</h2><p>93<br>Roll Who What do they <br>want Why By what means<br>1 An ally of the protagonist. Redemption. To live a better life. Deception.<br>2<br>Someone the protagonist encounters during the <br>story. Power. To stop suffering. Magic.<br>3 The protagonist of the story. Wealth. To receive recognition. Servants.<br>4 Someone connected to the story's protagonist. Expertise. To bask in success. Resources.<br>5<br>Someone the protagonist helps throughout the <br>story. Revenge. To teach a lesson. Determination.<br>6 A neutral character who appears in the story. Control. To preserve themselves. Skill.<br>In the following paragraphs, we will show the step-by-step <br>process of creating the Scenario of Red-Hood Iskra as an <br>example. Spoilers ahead: read only if you intend to play <br>the role of the Storyteller.<br>Example: Iskra’s main opponent.<br>We immediately decided that the little protagonist of <br>Little Red Riding Hood would not be the real “villain” of <br>the Scenario. The following options remained among the <br>Keywords: Mother, Sick Grandmother, and Hunter. <br>By opting for Mother (a very marginal character in the <br>original fairytale and therefore great for taking the Players off <br>guard), we rolled on the table to determine her motivations, <br>obtaining: 3 for What does she want, 1 for Why , and 3 for <br>By what means. As a result, Little Red Riding Hood’s Mother <br>tried to get rid of her daughter in order to regain a comfortable <br>life (Wealth and To live a better life) as the wife of a naive <br>noble. She also manipulates those around her with the help of <br>her trusted Servants. These followers are Vincent the Chief of <br>the Guards (inspired by the Hunter in the original fairytale) <br>and little Anne.<br>Each NPC in the Scenario must have an <br>ambiguous role.<br>While we are discussing villains and switching roles, note <br>that it would be a mistake to think that all NPCs have to <br>be evil. Frequently, an opponent with logical motivations <br>is more interesting and charismatic than those who are <br>evil just for the fun of it. Make sure that different NPCs <br>types are represented in the Scenario, ranging from those <br>with noble purposes to those who are driven only by their <br>own base instincts. The protagonist of the original fairytale <br>should have a prominent role in the plot, even if they’re <br>not the main villain. They could be, for example, someone</p>","markdown":""},"sort":9400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"MFcynwaGJx2A00wT","name":"Pagina 95","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 95</h2><p>94<br>the real villain uses against the Hunters. In general, a good <br>Scenario should contain at least three types of NPCs:<br> ◆ NPC with an Agenda that is opposed to the Hunters’ <br>purpose: if not a direct follower of the main villain, <br>they could be someone who takes advantage of the <br>current situation or who generally does not appreciate <br>the Hunters’ presence.<br> ◆ NPC with an Agenda that supports the Hunters’ <br>purpose, or that simply has a good reason to be angry <br>with the main opponent.<br> ◆ NPC with a non-aligned Agenda: they can be both an <br>enemy or an ally, based on the choices that the Hunters <br>will make during the Scenario.<br>Example: Red-Hood Iskra’s other NPCs.<br>In Red Hooded Iskra we have Vincent, Former Huntsman <br>and Chief of Guards (inspired by the Hunter in Little Red <br>Riding Hood) as an NPC opposed to the Hunters, Anastazia <br>the Sorrowful Spirit (inspired by Little Red Riding Hood’s <br>Grandmother) as an NPC ally, and Greskar the Big Black <br>Wolf (inspired by the Big Bad Wolf) as a neutral NPC. Iskra <br>herself is an NPC with a neutral Agenda, since even if she <br>acts with the right motivations, she does it violently and <br>uncontrollably, which will ultimately lead to a confrontation <br>with the Hunters.<br>For inspiration regarding an NPC’s Agenda, you can roll <br>multiple times on the following table.<br>Roll Acts like this because... Opposed Agenda Favorable Agenda Non-aligned Agenda<br>1<br>Unaware of what they are <br>doing.<br>Hates the Order and the <br>Hunters.<br>Would give their life for the <br>one they love. Is looking for something.<br>2<br>Feels deep, ingrained <br>hatred.<br>Is the trusted right hand of <br>an opponent. Wants truth to triumph. Wants to get rich.<br>3<br>Is driven by greed and a <br>thirst for power.<br>Takes advantage of the <br>situation.<br>Wants to ingratiate <br>themselves with the Order.<br>Wants to replace the <br>antagonist.<br>4<br>Is seeking acceptance and <br>understanding. Shares a dark secret. Owes someone. Defends a place or a person.<br>5 Is forced. Enjoys manipulating others. Seeks redemption. Wants to subvert a <br>situation.<br>6<br>Is related to someone with a <br>strong influence. Is deeply evil. Is pure of heart. Seeks revenge.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":9500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"LRmA4lzA31buZKtr","name":"Pagina 96","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 96</h2><p>95<br>Step 4 – Give the Scenario a <br>backdrop<br>All the stories and events of Broken Tales are set in the late <br>1700s of an alternative Europe. More precisely, the year <br>1780 is used as a reference for events and places. This date <br>is not binding and events may span a few decades forward <br>or backward to include a place or a historical event useful <br>to contextualize the Scenario. Doing a little research can <br>provide useful inspiration. The eighteenth-century is a <br>period full of events and changes that complement the <br>rural and dark context of the Broken Tales.<br>Example: The setting of Red-Hood Iskra and the legend <br>of Gévaudan.<br>For the Scenario of Red-Hood Iskra, the historical connection <br>is with the legend of the Gévaudan Beast, which in 1764 <br>terrorized many small villages in that wooded area of France. <br>This choice immediately provides a useful backdrop from <br>which to draw references for locations and NPC names. As <br>in the original legend, Iskra and her pack harass the village <br>of Durfort, where Elizaveta (Iskra’s mother) took refuge after <br>abandoning her daughter in the woods at the mercy of wolves.<br>Step 5 – The story so far<br>Now that we have a starting point, some Main NPCs, and <br>a location where the Scenario is set, it’s time to write what <br>happened before the Hunters arrived. In this process, some <br>Keywords will have to be flipped, to create the Breaking <br>Point of the Scenario.<br>In the following example, you will find the Keywords that <br>we consider useful for the next Steps highlighted.<br>Example: Red-Hood Iskra’s background story.<br>Elizaveta of Volhynia (the main antagonist, inspired <br>by Little Red Riding Hood’s mother) has always been an <br>attractive woman, accustomed to the rich salons of the gentry, <br>and the pomp of nobles and courtiers. Becoming pregnant <br>with Iskra, her eldest daughter, was a curse for her. <br>Abandoned by her wealthy lover, Elizaveta was impoverished <br>for years, with few skills, little work, and only the help of her <br>old mother Anastazia (inspired by the sick Grandmother <br>of Little Red Riding Hood). A chance encounter with <br>Gerard Dubois (Minor NPC), who is ignorant of her past, <br>has rekindled Elizaveta’s ambition for a life of comfort and <br>decadence as the future wife of a nobleman. <br>Elizaveta, determined not to miss such an opportunity, <br>sent her daughter Iskra alone to visit her grandmother. <br>Elizaveta knew that she was exposing her to the dangers <br>of the dense forest of Białowieża, a place full of beasts and <br>bandits, and deadly to the unwary. Ten-year-old Iskra trusted <br>her mother and disappeared forever into the darkness of the <br>forest. Anastazia had always treated Iskra with love and <br>kindness and, overwhelmed by the grief of her granddaughter’s <br>sad end, died soon after. Free and unattached , Elizaveta <br>fled to Gévaudan  with her new husband, unaware of her</p>","markdown":""},"sort":9600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"bdjnCh7yBqoQKevQ","name":"Pagina 97","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 97</h2><p>96<br>daughter’s real fate. In fact, Iskra did not die, but joined <br>Greskar’s wolf pack (inspired by Little Red Riding Hood’s <br>Wolf), becoming a wolf herself...<br>Step 6 – The story when the <br>Hunters arrive<br>The background details of the story will lead to the <br>intervention of the Hunters. The next step is to briefly <br>describe the situation that will unfold from the first actual <br>game Scene. This is important to clarify the Storyteller’s <br>ideas and to detail the Main NPCs’ Agenda. The NPCs’ <br>Agendas are key to the Scenario, because they guide the <br>Storyteller’s decisions, particularly when deciding how <br>NPCs react to the Hunters’ actions. <br>As we compile the NPC statistics, this paragraph will help <br>us define the Agenda of each one of them. In the example <br>below, we have highlighted the Keywords that will come in <br>handy.<br>Example: The story when the Hunters arrive in Red-<br>Hood Iskra.<br>Iskra didn’t die in the forest of Białowieża. Instead, she faced <br>every trial with a fierce tenacity and eventually prevailed, <br>defeating Greskar. A huge, ferocious werewolf, Greskar <br>infected Iskra with the wolf ’s curse. Becoming a member <br>of the pack and the favorite of the alpha Greskar, Iskra set <br>off for the Gévaudan, following the scent of her mother, <br>determined to get her revenge. Thanks to the fury of the wolf <br>pack, Iskra has thrown the city of Durfort into disarray. Now, <br>she waits in the shadows for the right opportunity to enter <br>the palace and devour her unworthy mother. Elizaveta has <br>realized what is happening, for Iskra left a pendant she had <br>once made for her on the windowsill, a memento of a rare <br>moment of happiness. Elizaveta, a cunning manipulator , <br>got rid of the token and did not panic or lose her temper. After <br>convincing Gerard to turn to the Order, she will seek to move <br>the pieces on the chessboard, using them to rid herself of <br>her unwanted offspring once and for all...<br>Step 7 – Define all the Scenario <br>Parts<br>Now that we have good foundations for the story and its <br>main actors, it’s time to define the “stage” for the Hunter’s <br>investigation. This process is open-ended and does not <br>follow a strict list of instructions. In brief, this phase consists <br>of creating Places, Minor NPCs, and finally Events, which <br>are particularly useful in managing the Session. Y ou’ll often <br>go back and forth between all the various elements. This is <br>perfectly normal. Indeed, it is much easier to create hooks <br>and connected situations as you add details to other things, <br>rather than planning everything in advance.<br>When creating a Scenario, always keep in mind how much <br>you want to plan and how much of the story you want to <br>emerge from the Players’ choices. There are two main ways <br>to play Broken Tales.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":9700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"zyK1GKCLIXZoM2XP","name":"Pagina 98","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 98</h2><p>97<br>Emerging story<br>In this mode, Broken Tales’ Scenarios don’t have a <br>pre-built plotline, nor Scenes or situations that are <br>mandatory steps for the Hunters (with the exception <br>of the First Scene). Writing the background, the <br>story when the Hunters arrive, detailing the NPCs’ <br>Agenda, and eventually adding Information to <br>Places, will create a network of intentions and <br>situations that will put obstacles in the Hunters’ <br>way. A sandbox plot is key for a good game of <br>Broken Tales. The Hunters are individuals out of <br>the ordinary and their Gifts can easily break Scenes <br>that are overplanned. The Scenario must therefore <br>provide the Storyteller with all the Events and <br>Agendas necessary to allow the world to respond to <br>the Hunters’ actions.<br>Scene Tree<br>If you and your table enjoy a more guided game, the <br>last part of this chapter will cover how to create a <br>Scene Tree that gives you a more defined plotline <br>to follow. If the storyline of the Scenario is heavily <br>focused on investigation, a good option is to detail <br>all obtainable Information found in a Place and be <br>very explicit about it while playing. The Storyteller <br>will then have a series of narrative hooks useful to <br>connect the situations emerging at the table.<br>Defining Places<br>Each Scenario should have at least five or six Places to set <br>a “stage” for the different Scenes. The best way to select <br>Places to prepare is to think about the context in which the <br>Main NPCs move. It is essential to always have a village <br>or a city context to refer to. The Hunters may move their <br>investigation into the wilderness, but having a place to <br>return to is always useful in the course of a Scenario. One of <br>the key themes of the game is how the Broken Tales move <br>at the edges of society. An urban environment is useful <br>in creating social connections and providing “ordinary <br>people” who can experience the horror of the revealed <br>Broken Tales.<br>Keywords for an urban area:  A small village on the <br>edge of the forest / A remote mountain community / A small <br>seaport / A village along a major road / A remote military <br>outpost.<br>Y ou can get more granular for other types of Places, in <br>order to have more control over the range of action that <br>NPCs and Hunters will have in the Scenario.<br>Keywords for locations:  The mansion of a wealthy <br>family / An old abandoned tower / A natural cave complex / <br>A mine / A clearing in the woods with a strange magical aura <br>/ A cemetery / A large stable / A farmhouse on the edge of the <br>village / A secret tunnel / A small workshop / A deconsecrated <br>church / A hunting lodge / A craftsman’s shop / A warm and <br>welcoming tavern / The heart of a large forest / A small house <br>in the woods / A treehouse.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":9800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"UcYwPuuia9T9CaCm","name":"Pagina 99","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 99</h2><p>98<br>Each Place must have a Descriptor that outlines its <br>characteristics. The Place may also feature one or more  <br>Threats and a List of Related Situations.<br>We have seen how to define Descriptors and Gifts. Now, <br>let’s spend some words on the List of Related Situations, <br>which are a good method to give variety and depth to <br>the Places of a Scenario. This list features elements that <br>can enter the Scene randomly, giving the Storyteller new <br>ideas to reinvigorate the plot when Players are stuck or <br>undecided. Make a List of 3 or 6 items, then freely assign <br>each to the results of a d6.<br>Using the List is never mandatory, but can often be a <br>valuable aid. The same result cannot be used more than <br>once in the course of a Scenario to avoid repetitions. Lists <br>of Related Situations mainly serve two purposes:<br> ◆ Manage encounters: if a Place is occupied, or an area <br>NPCs are likely to pass through, each option would <br>determine who will be present when the Hunters <br>arrive.<br> ◆ Bringing clues into play: if the location contains <br>Information or areas to explore, a roll can determine <br>what the Hunters discover when they arrive.<br>Y ou can then consider +1 or -1 modifiers to make some <br>results more likely or link them to external elements, such <br>as arrival during night or day.<br>Example: The Oaks Glade.<br>In Red-Hood Iskra, the Oaks Glade is an area Iskra’s pack <br>may pass through. The List of Related Situations is:<br>1-3: The glade is empty, but there are traces of wolves and <br>the bones of devoured prey. After ten minutes, 8 Black <br>Wolves arrive and ambush the Hunters. <br>4-5: A pack is at the glade: Greskar + 8 Black Wolves. <br>6: Iskra is at the glade, alone if it is daytime or with the pack <br>(4-5 result, but without Greskar) if it is nighttime.<br>As a modifier: if it is night, add 2 to the roll.<br>Minor NPCs<br>While Major NPCs emerged in the initial planning <br>phase, when detailing Places and Situations it is good to <br>draw up some Minor NPCs connected in some way to <br>the plot. Minor NPCs will often be ordinary humans, but <br>nothing prevents you from using secondary characters <br>from the original fairytale that have not found space yet. <br>Each Minor NPC must be linked to a Main NPC or a <br>specific storyline situation. They should be considered <br>as a narrative hook that will be useful to give depth to <br>what happens in the Scene. If you reach a dead end during <br>the Session, introducing a Minor NPC will open up new <br>avenues for the Hunters.<br>Example: Red-Hood Iskra Minor NPCs.<br>There are seven Minor NPCs in the Scenario. Anne, the <br>Little Chatterer (linked to Elizaveta) who acts as an eye on <br>the village for her mistress. Nicholas, the Hunter  (related <br>to the wolves in the forest) who can lead the Hunters, as he <br>knows the forest. Geneviève, the Chemist  (connected to <br>Iskra’s Grandmother) who can communicate with spirits and <br>contact Anastazia. Corinne, the Housekeeper (connected <br>to the village) who can provide information and rumors of <br>various kinds. Marcel, the Time-Waster (connected to Iskra) <br>who can make the Hunters aware of Iskra’s presence. Didier, <br>the Grumpy Old Man (linked to Elizaveta) who can provide <br>information about Gerard’s new wife and her dubious past.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":9900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"wcXaOU1MfF7lZWiT","name":"Pagina 100","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 100</h2><p>99<br>Finally, we have Gerard Dubois (linked to Elizaveta), the <br>noble who requested the Hunter’s intervention and makes <br>decisions for the village, but who is easily manipulated.<br>Review the Agenda of the <br>Main NPCs<br>Each Main NPC must have an Agenda which, in general, is <br>defined at the beginning of the Scenario’s creation process. <br>Now that the Scenario is almost complete, review all the <br>Agendas of the Main NPCs to ensure they fit with all the <br>other elements. Minor NPCs may (but don’t have to) have <br>an Agenda. Often, defining everyone’s relationship with a <br>Main NPC is enough to get started.<br>Events of the Scenario<br>At this point, it is a good idea to come up with a list of <br>Events that “could happen” when a specific situation occurs. <br>Because Events are an extension of the NPCs’ Agendas, <br>managing the plot’s progress will be much easier if you <br>have a practical method of tracking when triggers occur, as <br>well as their associated Events. As with Minor NPCs, each <br>Event must be linked to one of the Main NPC’s Agenda, <br>to represent the effects of the NPC’s will on the Scenario. <br>Some Events may also be an inevitable occurrence (for <br>example, the eruption of a volcano).<br>To create an Event, you need to write a short sentence <br>containing an Activation Keyword, a trigger that will <br>communicate when the Event will occur. As soon as <br>this happens, the Storyteller can decide to bring the new <br>situation into play, possibly taking everyone by surprise. In <br>any case, it is good to leave clues along the course of the <br>Scenes to make the Hunters understand what could happen <br>or, alternatively, to give them time to prepare for an Event <br>that they have intuited and for which they started investing <br>time and resources. <br>Example: The Events of Red-Hood Iskra.<br>There are six Events in the Scenario. Here are a couple of <br>examples highlighting the Activation Keyword, with the <br>linked Agenda in brackets.<br>If a Hunter finds Iskra’s pendant in the well, Anastazia <br>will contact them, showing them a vision of Iskra as <br>a child drinking at the Oaks Glade. The spirit of Iskra’s <br>grandmother, while unable to communicate directly, will try <br>to make the Hunters understand that Iskra is not a monster. <br>(Agenda of Anastazia, Iskra’s Grandmother)<br>If Elizaveta goes out of town for any reason, Iskra will <br>immediately smell her scent and rush to eliminate her <br>regardless of any risk. Confronted with her mother, the <br>little girl will lose all restraint and refuse to listen to reason. <br>(Agenda of Iskra)</p>","markdown":""},"sort":10000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241717,"modifiedTime":1783973241717,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ETVYduDk7oLhGtsF","name":"Pagina 101","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 101</h2><p>100<br>Step 8 –  The First Scene<br>Now that all the elements of the Scenario are defined, <br>all that remains to do is to detail the First Scene, which <br>will introduce the situation to the Hunters and start the <br>investigation. As described in previous chapters, each <br>Scene consists of 4 elements: a Place , a Time, an Initial <br>Situation, and Information. Make sure to draw up a list of <br>Information, which will be the basis for the Hunters’ choices <br>in the following Scenes. Opening an investigation without <br>useful elements to start from would make little sense. <br>Example: The First Scene of Red-Hood Iskra.<br>The Scenario begins with the Hunters being invited for dinner <br>by a tense Gerard Dubois, who can’t wait to put an end to the <br>beasts that plague the Gévaudan.<br>Place: The ceremonial hall of the Dubois family’s grand <br>palace. A richly furnished room with an enormous painting <br>of Patrick Dubois, Gerard’s late father. Stern and sullen-<br>looking, Patrick seems to judge his son’s incompetence from <br>beyond the grave with ill-concealed contempt.<br>  <br>Time: The sun set more than two hours ago and after a long <br>journey, it is now dinnertime.<br>Initial Situation: Gerard is anxious for the Hunters to get <br>to work. Elizaveta studies the situation in silence, trying <br>to figure out how she can turn the Hunters’ arrival to her <br>advantage, using them as tools for her own purposes. Choose <br>one of the villagers to be her dinner guest, or create one of <br>your own. Vincent, her trusted head of the guards, will also <br>be present, of course.<br>Information: The following information/clues can be <br>obtained from the interview with Gerard.<br> ◆ The monsters that scourge the Gévaudan are ferocious <br>beasts, as can be seen from the state of the victims’ bodies.<br> ◆ The first two victims were Guy and Ivette, two young <br>lovers who used to meet secretly in the old cemetery just <br>outside the city. It is there that what remains of their <br>bodies are buried.<br> ◆ It is strictly forbidden to leave the city after sunset. The <br>fall of night now brings with it the mournful song of <br>howling wolves.<br>Step 9 – Scene Tree<br>The rules presented so far are optimal for the management <br>of a game with an emerging narrative. If you intend to <br>create a 100% complete Scenario, even if only to make it <br>available to the Broken Tales’ community, it’s good to also <br>detail a Scene Tree. This mode of play is not designed to <br>cover every possible choice the Hunters might make, but <br>provide Storytellers and novice players with a familiar way <br>to play. The use of Information at the beginning and end <br>of each Scene will therefore be more explicit, so that the <br>Storyteller can present the choices available to the Hunters, <br>and will keep them on the “line” drawn by the Scene Tree. <br>It’s inevitable that the Hunters’ actions will stray from what <br>the Scene Tree has foreseen. However, for the most part, <br>this mode will make it easier for the Storyteller to keep <br>hold of the reins of the story. Playing in this way requires a <br>conscious agreement between Storyteller and Players that <br>the goal is experiencing a good story together, following the <br>flow of clues presented in each Scene.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":10100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"E3De8wf9Ff1BhiJZ","name":"Pagina 102","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 102</h2><p>101<br>A Scene Tree consists of a series of Scenes linked <br>according to this basic structure:<br>The First Scene leads to the Second Scene, then there is a <br>choice between two options for the Third Scene, Option <br>A and Option B. The Fourth Scene leads to a Fifth Scene <br>and then there will be either a new fork or the Epilogue, <br>depending on the Scenario’s duration. Five Scenes with <br>a fork in the middle are optimal for playing a one-shot <br>Session of about three hours. Additional forks and Scenes <br>will increase playtime by approximately thirty minutes per <br>addition.<br>The First Scene must be structured exactly as we’ve already <br>described, but with the addition of a new item: End of <br>Scene, which roughly describes which new Scene the <br>action will switch to.<br>The new Scene structure is therefore:<br> ◆ A Place where the Scene takes place.<br> ◆ A Time, to know when it takes place with respect to <br>the previous Scene.<br> ◆ An Initial Situation  that defines what happens and <br>what to describe to the Hunters before starting the <br>Scene.<br> ◆ Information, which can be obtained from the Scene. <br>Information will act as a “guide” to the Hunters’ choices, <br>so it must be explicit. Don’t be afraid to railroad the <br>game too much, that’s exactly what we’re looking for!<br> ◆ End of Scene , which is a brief description of the <br>consequences of the current Scene. The Storyteller will <br>use it to direct NPC actions and bring other elements <br>to the attention of the Hunters.<br>Example: The Second Scene of Red-Hood Iskra.<br>Place: The old cemetery of Durfort in the middle of the large <br>Gévaudan forest. It is reached by a narrow dirt path that <br>winds its way through the woods from the main road.<br>Time: It is early morning, the sun is high on a clear winter sky.<br>Information: In the cemetery, there are many wolf tracks. <br>In the middle of them are the prints of two small bare feet, <br>almost certainly a little girl. At the bottom of the old well <br>can be found the pendant that Elizaveta tried to make <br>disappear. The wolves’ tracks lead deep into the forest, to <br>their den. Anastazia will contact the Hunter who recovered <br>the pendant, sending them a vision of Elizaveta trying in vain <br>to wash her bloodstained hands.<br>End of Scene: Hunters can decide whether to return to the <br>town to report (THIRD SCENE OPTION A), or follow <br>the trail to the wolves’ lair (THIRD SCENE OPTION B).   <br>Step 10 – Scenario Gifts<br>As a final touch to the Scenario, you can create a list of <br>Scenario Gifts. This step is not mandatory.<br>Exclusive Gifts can be of two types:<br>Scenario Gifts: Can be acquired during an Interlude, if <br>the Hunter has fulfilled certain storyline conditions. These <br>Gifts represent knowledge and skills that persist only for <br>the duration of the Scenario itself and are an addition to <br>the three Gifts the Hunter already possesses. The Gift must <br>be built with the rules presented in the Hunter’s Creation <br>chapter and the narrative requirement for having it can be <br>considered as an Archetypal Costs. It is not possible to have <br>more than one Scenario Gift at a time.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":10200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"nAU9kexgKmkUQDTS","name":"Pagina 103","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 103</h2><p>102<br>During a game Campaign, a Hunter can use a <br>previously acquired Scenario Gift in another <br>Scenario if this fits the context and events. <br>If this occurs, the Player must bring this <br>possibility to the attention of the Storyteller, <br>who will decide (evaluating the impact on the <br>current Scenario) whether to allow the Hunter <br>to use what they have learned in their previous <br>adventures. Even in this case, however, the <br>limitation remains 1 Scenario Gift per Hunter.<br>Example: A Scenario Gift from Red-Hood Iskra.<br>Wolf-killer<br>Requirement: Having faced the wolves in a fight at least once.<br>You know how to deal with the fiercest of wolves and are careful <br>not to be surrounded. When you obtain at least a Standard <br>Outcome on a Position or Defense Check against a pack of <br>beasts, you can immediately eliminate 1 Minor animal NPC <br>with 1 Wound.<br>Special Gift: This is a Gift reserved only for the Hunter who <br>is the villain of the original fairytale that inspired the Scenario <br>being played if present among the Hunters. As soon as the <br>requirement is met, the Hunter will automatically gain the <br>Gift for the duration of the Scenario, in addition to the ones <br>already owned and without having to spend XP . Whether they <br>like it or not! The Gift must be built with the rules presented <br>in the Hunter’s Creation chapter. Bear in mind that the Gift  <br>needs to represent a connection between the Hunter and the <br>Scenario and not necessarily a mere advantage! When creating <br>this Gift, don’t worry as much about balancing the Archetypal <br>Effects and Costs. Y ou can even have more Costs than usual.<br>Example: A Special Gift from Red-Hood Iskra<br>Where are you going all alone, sweetie?<br>Hunter: Garou the Old Wolf.<br>Requirement: To meet Iskra alone in the forest.<br>You are attracted to the little girl who pretends to be a wolf and <br>you dream of devouring her. Once per Scene, you can spend 1 <br>Soma to know exactly where she is. If you anticipate her and <br>arrive somewhere before her, you get 1 Additional Success on <br>every Check you make to hurt or devour that little morsel. <br>You can’t wait to swallow that tidbit and it makes you let your <br>guard down. As long as she is present on the Scene, you receive <br>1 Penalty in all Defense Checks.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":10300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"hnsFHsTJITVPvBL2","name":"Pagina 104","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 104</h2><p>103<br>Broken Europe<br>Once upon a time…<br>Year 1780. There are strange, half-sensed presences moving <br>at the edge of our reality. Beings once relegated to the realms <br>of make-believe have assumed nightmare forms, no less real <br>for being fantastic. Alarmed by the constant calls for help in <br>dealing with supernatural evil, Pope Clement approves the <br>creation of the Order: a secret group consisting of the Hunters, <br>led by the mysterious Guardians. The Hunters accept into <br>their ranks anyone who has demonstrated qualities outside <br>the norm, revealing a connection to the world beyond the <br>threshold of reality. The Hunters’ task is to seek out and defeat <br>any supernatural threat. But aren’t the Hunters themselves <br>children of the twilight at the edge of reality?<br>The world of Broken Tales<br>Broken Tales is set in a fictional 18th century Europe, a <br>continent made up of a patchwork of small, rural locales. <br>The exploits of the Order, to which the Hunters belong, <br>happen in the shadows of everyday life. They investigate <br>rumors and mysteries unimaginable to the common minds <br>of the time. While art and culture are discussed in drawing <br>rooms, the dark shadows of the Broken Tales lurk in small <br>villages, waiting to snatch unsuspecting victims. The world <br>of Broken Tales is but a darker and more fairytale version of <br>1780’s Europe, a theater made up of small villages and large <br>cities, where superstition and shadows move on the edges <br>of what the common man defines as “normality. ”<br>In this chapter, we will further illuminate facts and <br>characteristics that are helpful for managing the environment <br>around the Hunters during their investigations. The world <br>of Broken Tales is entirely an invention and this game makes <br>no claim to historical accuracy. In fact, the fundamental <br>idea is to add as many fantastic elements as possible, while <br>keeping them hidden in the shadows, at the edge of what <br>humans can perceive. The Europe of Broken Tales is not <br>even a cohesive and “linear” world. Each Scenario is set in a <br>different place, with unique rules and situations. What this <br>chapter tries to provide is a series of useful details for the <br>Storyteller to add color to the journeys and adventures of <br>the Hunters. <br>If you look at the Broken Europe Map, you’ll see many <br>places and cities. Anything that has a name on the Map <br>has a Scenario connected to it (either in this book or in <br>The Broken Ones expansion) or is a starting point for new <br>stories and situations. These elements are detailed in the <br>chapter Playing a Broken Tales Campaign on page 243.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":10400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"8dDEau0wNhK3CRex","name":"Pagina 105","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 105</h2><p>BROKEN EUROPE<br>104<br>Overall mood<br>To better get into the mood of the Broken Tales setting, <br>keep these simple points in mind:<br> ◆ Rural life is the backdrop for the Hunters and the <br>Broken Tales they investigate. Hunters have to deal with <br>small villages and simple-minded people. Superstition <br>and fear of the supernatural surround the Hunters. <br> ◆ When the horror of the Broken Tales is revealed, most <br>people cannot help but be terrified. <br> ◆ Common people are poor, living on what little they <br>earn with back-breaking labor. The nobility lives safe, <br>opulent lives in big cities. Social differences are clear.<br> ◆ Children see what the adults refuse to understand. <br>The elderly have the wisdom of a lifetime and the <br>experience that darkness really exists. Adults are <br>crushed by a world that rejects what is considered <br>strange and unusual.<br> ◆ Large ancient forests, shadowed labyrinths, lonely <br>cottages in the woods, and all the abandoned places <br>of the world. The Broken Tales live freely in places <br>humanity has forsaken. In the midst of society, they <br>have to hide their true nature.<br>Keywords<br>This section is entirely based on the use of Keywords, a <br>series of terms that reveal information related to Broken <br>Europe. For example, if the Hunters set out to reach the <br>next destination, the Storyteller, scrolling through this <br>section, could stop at the keyword TRAVEL to get useful <br>information about it. That way, you can expand on an <br>aspect of the setting only when it is really necessary.<br>Armors &amp; Weapons<br>While bulky, full suits of armor are but relics of a bygone era, <br>steel breastplates are still in use among the cavalry corps of <br>the Ottoman army and knights in the service of the Papacy. <br>For ordinary people, wearing armor is a very strange thing. <br>But despite this, many Paladins remain within the Order <br>who still wear their sacred armor.<br>For those who follow the sword as a profession, padding <br>prevents dangerous, deep wounds during training, but in <br>everyday life, armor remains very impractical to use.<br>As far as sidearms are concerned, swords are still the overall <br>favorite. The most common examples have straight and <br>thin blades. More practical and concealable blades such <br>as stilettos and daggers are common as well. Large two-<br>handed blades are a thing of the past, and only in remote <br>areas such as Scotland is the claymore still used, which is a <br>kind of hand-and-a-half sword. Eastern influences in the <br>Balkan area favor the spread of curved and light blades <br>like sabers. Usually, only the rich, the nobility, or military <br>officers possess proper swords or sidearms (and the nobles <br>often have them custom-made at very great expense). On <br>the other hand, a good handcrafted dagger is extremely <br>simple to make and available to anyone.<br>Additionally, any pointed or heavy work tool carried by <br>a farmer can in fact be a weapon. Imagine a pitchfork, a <br>scythe, or a blacksmith’s hammer being used with violent <br>intent.<br>Putting aside cannons, which are used only on the battlefield, <br>the most popular firearms are pistols and flintlock rifles. <br>Wheel locks and matchlocks have been out of use for about <br>seventy years. Despite being the most advanced technology</p>","markdown":""},"sort":10500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"TrqRVSkDiXTl7xXj","name":"Pagina 106","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 106</h2><p>BROKEN EUROPE<br>105<br>of its time, various elements such as humidity, jamming, <br>and flint breakage mean that firearms aren’t particularly <br>reliable. Although powerful, firearms are inaccurate due <br>to the smooth bore inside the firing barrel. Beyond three <br>hundred feet, it’s challenging to shoot accurately. The <br>exceptions are dueling pistols and well-made shotguns <br>which, thanks to a rifled barrel, are incredibly accurate, but <br>also infinitely more expensive.<br>Magical weapons related to the Broken Tales are highly <br>sought after among senior army officers. They represent <br>trophies to show off and brag about in war councils. The <br>Order actively monitors new discoveries, replacing the real <br>weapon with a copy at an opportune time and taking the <br>original for safekeeping in the underground chambers of <br>Valea Viilor.<br>Cities, towns and villages<br>Big cities are a safe place for the whole range of social <br>classes. Nobles and wealthy people live in beautiful houses <br>and large palaces, artisans, and merchants of the petty <br>bourgeoisie can afford a modest home in the suburbs, <br>perhaps on the second floor of a terraced house. The further <br>you go towards the slums, the harsher life is, down to the <br>poorest and most desperate, forced to sleep on the street. <br>The law of the state is paramount everywhere, both in the <br>countryside and in the main cities. The primary difference <br>is that, in a large city, the representatives of the law and of <br>the state are physically present, often in good numbers. <br>Meanwhile, small villages rely on the ruling of the elders <br>and religious authority. The most prominent and serious <br>crimes are usually tried in city courts. The cities can’t <br>afford to spread their men-at-arms thinly across both rich <br>and poor neighborhoods, and the rulers don’t intervene <br>to prevent unrest because soldiers are much more useful <br>on battlefields. For the simplest tasks, local or city militias <br>are used, called up to help only when requested by the <br>authorities. If a serious crime occurs in a small village, it is <br>often necessary to contact the authority of the nearest city, <br>hoping that someone there has the time and willingness to <br>intervene...<br>The Broken Tales fear cities, but often the dark feelings <br>that animate them are strong enough to push them into <br>unreasonable risks.<br>Countryside<br>In almost all of Europe, the majority of people live off  <br>agriculture, following the cycle of the seasons. In spring <br>and summer, the land is worked to care for the fields and <br>the crops. Winter months are dedicated to repairing homes, <br>stables, granaries, and tools. Some peasants own the land <br>they work, but most are just laborers. In many regions, <br>agriculture as an industry has become highly developed, <br>made up of wide pastures and all the buildings associated <br>with animal husbandry (such as stables, granaries, ovens, <br>mills, fields). Laborers can also live by forming small <br>communities. <br>For the Broken Tales, the countryside is the best place to live <br>and thrive, safe from the crowds of big cities. Small houses <br>in the woods, natural caves, and old abandoned mills are <br>great places to live without completely losing contact with <br>mankind.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":10600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"PIaq4cxo4AhA0P0j","name":"Pagina 107","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 107</h2><p>106<br>Education<br>Public education doesn’t exist, only private lessons and schools <br>are available. Basic education is provided by the family and, in <br>fact, almost everyone outside the city is illiterate. For practical <br>reasons, almost everyone learns some basic mathematics. <br>Nobility and bourgeoisie may both vary widely in terms <br>of culture and education. Some may barely know how to <br>read and write, while others possess significant academic <br>knowledge including history, philosophy, politics, classical <br>Latin and Greek culture, linguistics, and music. In many <br>countries, knowledge of the Holy Scriptures and the Bible is <br>considered essential.<br>Fire<br>In every home there is a fireplace, kept constantly lit in winter. <br>It is a vital source of heating and in simpler homes serves as <br>a place for cooking food. In large residential homes, on the <br>other hand, fireplaces are present in all rooms or in the most <br>important rooms, including the bedrooms. In these buildings <br>the kitchens are in a dedicated space, often on the ground <br>floor where the servants’ areas are located. There, the cooking <br>fires are almost always lit. The embers are kept warm to make <br>it easy to start a fire. <br>Candles are the most common lightsource. The rich use <br>wax, while tallow is sufficient for the poor (the latter being</p>","markdown":""},"sort":10700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ITknjD8mh1WlcEJj","name":"Pagina 108","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 108</h2><p>107<br>much more smoky). Sparking devices using flintlocks have <br>become popular for lighting fires – they are so useful that <br>some have begun carrying them on their person.<br>Food<br>By 1780, naval voyages connected every continent and <br>the most powerful nations had vast colonial empires. <br>As a result, it’s possible to find goods from all over the <br>world in Europe. Obviously, some are much more <br>exotic than others, such as the pineapples that can <br>be found only at the tables of English nobles, <br>but nowhere else in Europe. American <br>products (potatoes, tomatoes, corn) are now <br>available in markets and cultivated in crops. <br>Tobacco and cocoa (only imported and not <br>cultivated), however, remain reserved for <br>the higher classes. Cocoa is consumed as a <br>drink, while tea from India has long since <br>become a tradition for the English nobility. <br>The most popular products are grains and <br>bread forms the basis of every meal, from <br>the richest to the poorest. Wine and oil are <br>very common products, as is beer (or cider in <br>some regions). Butter or lard are used both for <br>cooking and as condiments.<br>Government<br>Absolute monarchy, in its “enlightened” variant, is the <br>most widespread form of government. The most powerful <br>nations in the world such as France, England, the Austrian <br>Empire, Prussia, Spain, and Russia, are all ruled by <br>monarchs endowed with absolute power. Many allow <br>parliamentary assemblies or Councils of State <br>but keep them mostly powerless, except for <br>occasionally being consulted. Each monarch <br>is convinced that it is essential for a sovereign <br>to hold the ultimate authority, in order to <br>secure their people’s welfare, despite often <br>disastrous results.<br>The one exception to royal authority is the <br>Church. It remains independent and held <br>in the utmost esteem thanks to the work of <br>the Order.<br>Usually, only the nobility are allowed to <br>participate in politics, representing solely <br>the ruling class, including also members <br>of the high clergy, such as the bishops. <br>Immediately below them, however, <br>intellectuals or wealthy citizens (merchants, <br>artisans, notaries, bureaucrats, students and <br>writers) are often actively involved in politics <br>as well. Peasants have no say in who rules them, <br>being mostly  poor, humble, and illiterate.<br>Information<br>Some newspapers are published regularly, but they are <br>usually just a few sheets and are not released daily. In the <br>most important public squares there are always posting <br>poles or boards, where the government shares decrees or</p>","markdown":""},"sort":10800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"EjQV2bBx1Ak4zjJH","name":"Pagina 109","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 109</h2><p>108<br>information of great importance with the citizens. In many <br>cities the doors of prominent churches are used for posting <br>notices. Even “town criers” (people who shout the most <br>important news out in the street) are still widely used. <br>The Order controls information to the best of its ability, <br>casting news of monsters and magic as simple superstition. <br>It is a difficult and painstaking job, which requires them <br>to downplay the threat so as not to frighten the common <br>people. However, the Order does not stifle the stories <br>completely, so that rumors still travel from one mouth to <br>next, until they reach the ears of the Hunters.<br>Night<br>Only cities have walls and, consequently, gates that are <br>closed at night and controlled by the patrols of the city <br>militia. In small villages, you fort up at night, locking doors <br>and windows while anxiously waiting for the daylight... For <br>commoners, the night is a time of rest, to recover strength <br>in anticipation of a new day of work. For the nobles, <br>however, the night is dedicated to parties and lust. For the <br>Broken Tales, night is the best time to act, safe from most <br>prying eyes.<br>Nobility<br>One is noble by birth, by investiture thanks to merit earned <br>by a particular family, or by pretending to be one. Since the <br>use of documentation is not widespread, with enough spine <br>and a lot of charisma it is possible to simply talk your way <br>into the nobility.<br>Being noble grants many benefits including an active role <br>in politics, and the possibility of aspiring to the highest <br>military and judicial posts. Often, as in France, the most <br>important noble families are entitled to an income paid <br>directly from the state coffers. Even the most prestigious <br>religious offices (cardinals, bishops of the largest cities, <br>and abbots of the richest monasteries) are still largely <br>the prerogative of aristocratic families. Even if treaties, <br>deals, and contracts are written and signed, the word of a <br>“gentleman” can often be a sufficient guarantee in itself.<br>The life of a noble is made up of large palaces, servants, <br>sumptuous clothes, balls and masquerades. Lazing around <br>at any time of the day is normal, because physical work <br>is considered common and degrading. Extravagance is <br>everywhere, depending on the actual wealth of the family. <br>It is easy for wizards and witches to dupe a noble and thus <br>obtain wealth and privileges. In the lounges and courtyards, <br>however, gossip makes the rounds quickly, with a risk that <br>the Order hears of it.<br>Order (The)<br>The Order represents the most powerful and extensive secret <br>society of Broken Europe. Every member of the Church, <br>from the humblest country priest to the richest bishop of <br>Rome, is aware of the war that the Church has always fought <br>with the Broken Tales. Although the Order is an established <br>truth to all of them, far fewer know of the Hunters and their <br>incredible abilities. The Order acts directly under the Pope’s <br>authority, but in reality, it is the different groups of Hunters <br>that make the difference. Depending on their choices and <br>the results of their investigations, the Broken Tales are <br>eliminated or absorbed into the Order, expanding the ranks <br>of the Hunters themselves or the hoard contained in the <br>fortress of Valea Viilor.<br>The Order has no ultimate purpose, other than to counter <br>the Broken Tales that constantly come into being over <br>time because of the One Who Plots in the Shadows. This <br>mysterious figure seems to be deeply connected to the <br>Broken Tales, but little is known about him except for</p>","markdown":""},"sort":10900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"rmjUhBsUpNTHv8KI","name":"Pagina 110","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 110</h2><p>109<br>vague rumors and the few clues collected by the Hunters, <br>despite years of research. <br>The Order is not protected from palace intrigues and power <br>games. Many bishops and others in the Church’s hierarchy <br>yearn for its control or, simply put, to get their hands on <br>the many magical treasures it protects. For this reason, the <br>management of the Order changes constantly, with the <br>Pope himself as the only true constant. Hunters therefore <br>enjoy great freedom of action and, each having their own <br>personal goals, they can take advantage of the protection of <br>the Order to progress in their own quests.<br>The Order is a reality that many are aware of, but nobody <br>really wants to talk about. It represents the dark side of <br>the Church, which must be trusted to settle what normal <br>people cannot deal with.<br>Ordinary people’s belongings<br>A pocket knife is always useful for many tasks, as is a pipe <br>if you can afford to buy tobacco from time to time. A small <br>necklace with a cross made of humble materials such as <br>wood and iron is commonly kept for moments of prayer, <br>especially among women. Clothes and accessories are <br>simple and suitable for work, such as aprons so as not to get <br>too dirty and handkerchiefs to clean your hands. In most <br>houses, there are candlesticks for light, which are made of <br>iron or wood, though the rich can afford silver. Families <br>also need tools for everyday life, such as looms for weaving <br>and kitchen utensils.<br>Personalities<br>The Eighteenth century is the century of the Enlightenment, <br>which gave birth to a plethora of important historical <br>personalities. Below is a brief, and obviously not exhaustive, <br>roundup of historical personalities whom the Hunters <br>could come across.<br>Artists<br>Gotthold Ephraim Lessing (1729 - 1781) was the great <br>father of the German literary Enlightenment. Johann <br>Christoph Friedrick von Schiller (1759 - 1805), scholar, <br>poet, philosopher. Donatien-Alphonse-François de Sade <br>(1740 - 1814), French writer, philosopher, poet, playwright, <br>essayist, aristocrat and revolutionary politician, known <br>for his numerous libertine and gothic-themed literary <br>works, centered on a mixture of violence and sexuality. <br>Carlo Goldoni (1707 - 1793), the great father of modern <br>comedy. Giuseppe Parini (1729 - 1799), one of the leading <br>exponents of the Italian Enlightenment and Neoclassicism. <br>Johann Wolfgang von Goethe (1749 - 1832), a man of all-<br>around culture (philosopher, politician, writer, poet, art <br>critic, music critic, etc.), the original inventor of the concept <br>of Weltliteratur (world literature), due to his admiration <br>and great knowledge of the national literatures of distant or <br>foreign countries (English, French, Italian, Greek, Persian <br>and Arabic). Christoph Willibald Gluck (1714 - 1787), <br>composer and opera player, one of the major initiators <br>of the Classicism movement. Franz Joseph Haydn <br>(1732 - 1809), one of the greatest exponents of Viennese <br>Classicism, is still considered the “father” of the symphony <br>and the string quartet. Antonio Salieri (1750 - 1825), a <br>great composer, who tutored many musicians who later <br>became famous including Beethoven, Schubert, and Liszt. <br>Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart (1756 - 1791), a true genius of</p>","markdown":""},"sort":11000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"g22Vk4qUsDL1X2Xh","name":"Pagina 111","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 111</h2><p>110<br>classical music. Francisco Goya (1746 - 1828), the greatest <br>Spanish painter of the 1700s. Sir Joshua Reynolds (1723 <br>- 1792), founder of the Royal Academy of Arts. Antonio <br>Canova (1757 - 1822), the greatest European sculptor and <br>the greatest exponent of Neoclassicism.<br>Scholars and scientists<br>Henry Cavendish (1731 - 1810), scientist. Jean Baptiste <br>Le Rond D’ Alembert (1717 - 1783), mathematician <br>and physicist (writer of the Encyclopédie with Diderot). <br>Leonard Euler  (1707 - 1783), mathematician and <br>astronomer. Daniel Bernoulli (1700 - 1782), physicist. <br>Alessandro Volta (1745 - 1827), physicist. Luigi Galvani <br>(1737 - 1798), physicist and anatomist. The Montgolfier <br>brothers (1740 - 1810/1745 - 1799), inventors of the air <br>balloon. Antoine-Laurent de Lavoisier (1743 - 1794), <br>chemist. Georges-Louis Leclerc de Buffon (1707 - 1788), <br>naturalist. Denis Diderot (1713 - 1784), author of the <br>Encyclopédie together with D’ Alembert. Adam Smith <br>(1723 - 1790), economist. Carl Linnaeus, also known as <br>Linnaeus (1707 - 1778), physician, botanist and, above <br>all else, naturalist. Carl Scheele (1742 - 1786), chemist, <br>discoverer of oxygen. Jan Ingenhousz (1730 - 1799), <br>botanist and chemist. Frederick William Herschel (1738 <br>- 1822), astronomer, physicist, and composer. James Watt <br>(1736 - 1819), physicist, engineer and inventor of the steam <br>engine.<br>Politicians<br>Cesare Beccaria (1738 - 1794), jurist, author of the essay <br>“On Crimes and Punishments. ” Leopold II of Habsburg-<br>Lorraine (1747 - 1792), Grand Duke of Tuscany, a true <br>enlightened ruler: the first monarch in the world to abolish <br>the death penalty. Frederick II of Prussia, known as the <br>Great (1712 - 1786), enlightened ruler par excellence, was a <br>philosopher (he was a friend of Voltaire, with whom it was <br>rumored he actually had a relationship), composer, jurist <br>and great political innovator. Maria Theresa of Austria <br>(1717 - 1780), the female Austrian equivalent of Frederick <br>II, and Edmund Burke (1729 - 1797), English politician <br>and statesman.<br>Religion<br>Broken Europe hosts various religions. Catholicism is <br>present in Spain, France, Italy, Austria, Poland, Ireland <br>and in some Germanic areas. Protestantism is widespread <br>in the Netherlands, in many areas of the Holy Roman <br>Empire (Prussia, Palatinate, Saxony), Denmark, Sweden <br>and Norway. Anglicanism is in England, Calvinism in <br>Switzerland, Orthodox Christianity in the whole Balkan <br>area and especially in Russia. Islamism can be found in <br>many parts of the Balkans, in Asia Minor, in the Middle <br>East, and throughout Mediterranean Africa. Many <br>religious minorities, such as Judaism, are widespread, but <br>have always kept a low profile out of fear of retaliation <br>from the powers-that-be due to the great solidarity of their <br>communities.<br>Churchmen play a very important role in society, both the <br>high clergy (representing a branch of the aristocracy) and <br>those who take care of the many villages.<br>Although the Enlightenment has begun to undermine the <br>dominance of religious beliefs, few dare to call themselves <br>atheists. Almost everyone else, in any European or <br>Mediterranean area, are fervent supporters of their faith. <br>It is customary to regularly attend religious services and <br>receive the sacraments, and this applies to the nobles, the <br>rich, the poor, and the peasants, without distinction.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":11100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"lBjXBEknhZfoUaZX","name":"Pagina 112","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 112</h2><p>111<br>Rich people’s belongings<br>The best way to show off wealth is to wear it, including <br>elegant clothes, made by professional tailors, but also shoes <br>and boots. Even weapons can be a subject to fashion, such <br>as dueling pistols or very elaborate and engraved shotguns. <br>Of course, jewels like rings (also used by men) and <br>necklaces (especially for women) can range from tasteful <br>to opulent. Ladies desire expensive perfumes and highly <br>coveted dressing tables. In wealthy homes works of art, fine <br>furniture, tapestries, and fine silverware are common.<br>Sickness<br>Seasonal ailments such as flu and cold are omnipresent, <br>to the point of being deadly for those who cannot afford <br>treatment.<br>Smallpox epidemics break out continuously and syphilis, <br>tuberculosis, and cholera are more or less widespread. <br>Among the nobility, due to a diet featuring a great deal of <br>meat, gout is widespread, while scurvy is rampant among <br>sailors. Although not really a disease, septicaemia and <br>gangrene are a constant presence among the wounded on <br>the battlefield, often with lethal consequences. Tetanus is <br>also a common infection. <br>In most cases, the ill are treated with home remedies and <br>according to popular wisdom. Only the affluent can afford <br>the expensive care of a doctor. If a sick person can continue <br>to work, they will be grateful to avoid ending up in a <br>hospital or, worse, abandoned on the street... <br>Superstition<br>The Enlightenment is undermining many popular beliefs <br>and superstitions, but only among the upper social classes, <br>meaning those who can afford adequate education and are <br>genuinely literate. Among the common people, however, <br>popular belief in legends and the existence of supernatural <br>forces are well rooted, and often “Christianized” as being in <br>service to the Devil.<br>Every region, if not every single village, has its own folk <br>remedies. There are literally hundreds of different ways to <br>interpret a situation through superstition. The great witch <br>hunts have been over for years now, but in the countryside, <br>it is still easy to believe in dark forces and question any <br>person who deviates even slightly from what is considered <br>“normal” . Regarding the Church, the Order secretly deals <br>with every supernatural phenomenon, leaving the village <br>priests with the task of maintaining a fear of the unknown. <br>For the common people, it is natural to wait for the <br>intervention of the Church to resolve a mystery. For the <br>nobles and rulers of the cities, the Order is an established <br>truth not to be named in public, but on which one must <br>blindly rely in case of need against the forces of darkness.<br>Traveling<br>Traveling is not easy. For farmers, survival is anchored to <br>the land they cultivate. It is difficult to move around except <br>for a few rare exceptions, such as fairs and markets. Those <br>who travel often are nobles, scholars, merchants, and of <br>course ambassadors and political officials. <br>The horse is the most popular way to travel. The nobility <br>have their own horses, but scholars, notaries, or those who</p>","markdown":""},"sort":11200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Ye6OlfmtjHvzAGRU","name":"Pagina 113","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 113</h2><p>112<br>live in the city must necessarily pay for a ride in a horse-drawn <br>carriage or coach. Traveling by ship is a good way to move along <br>the coasts, though there are no passenger ships, but only merchant <br>ships which offer passage for a few coins. <br>The borders between the various states of Broken Europe are not <br>well defined and border controls are focused almost exclusively <br>on the main roads. It is also true that safe roads are few and very <br>busy, and moving a heavy cart through inaccessible streets is not <br>the easiest of operations. <br>For Hunters, traveling is what connects one investigation to the <br>next and accounts for a good portion of the time they spend on a <br>mission each week. The Order enjoys respect and esteem almost <br>everywhere, and it is common practice to accommodate Hunters <br>within the limits of one’s ability. Even the humblest of peasants will <br>open their home to them.<br>Work<br>The industrial revolution is upsetting Broken Europe. Talking about <br>industries means talking about extreme manpower requirements, <br>where the power of rivers and coal play an important role. Except for <br>the nobles, who do not work (because it is considered humiliating <br>to perform hard work), all other social classes start working during <br>childhood. Especially in the countryside, children regularly help <br>their parents with every task. Even in the cities, artisans and <br>merchants are helped by their children at least in the simplest jobs, <br>even if only to pass on the family profession. <br>Work is often a means of redemption for Broken Tales that yearn <br>for a normal life. Although, as you can imagine, a lifetime of <br>restraint can be ruined by a single moment in which they manifest <br>their special abilities.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":11300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"IcU9vrTfkFq2yJBg","name":"Pagina 114","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 114</h2><p>113<br>Spoiler<br>! Warning !<br>Go no further if you don’t want to lose your way... <br>This part of the book presents the complete rules for playing a Broken Tales Campaign, all the <br>Scenarios and the truth behind the tale of the Child Savior.<br>If you want to experience Broken Tales as a player, stop here. After all... would you peek at the <br>last page of a novel you are reading?</p>","markdown":""},"sort":11400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241718,"modifiedTime":1783973241718,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"XNaEASAUZhZt6ZK6","name":"Pagina 115","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 115</h2><p>114<br>The Fairytale Of <br>The Child Savior  <br>Once upon a time... the world of fairytales was on the verge of ending, forsaken by children who grew up too fast and forgot <br>the value of old stories. Within the void left by failing stories, darkness and oblivion blossomed. All the inhabitants of fairytales <br>wept with fear at the long-dreaded end. “ All it would take is one last reader. One single young heart willing to believe in us still, ” <br>sighed the weary Fairytale King.<br>Once upon a time... A writer labored in obscurity, desperately trying to create new <br>fairytales that could find a place in the hearts of children. But every time his stories were <br>rejected. Too dark. Too dangerous. Drawn from old tales no one remembered anymore. <br>“People don’t want to hear about fairytales, ” people teased him.<br>Reprise</p>","markdown":""},"sort":11500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"pbEjhfXfbAzxu5mX","name":"Pagina 116","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 116</h2><p>115<br>The Writer drove himself harder and harder, giving birth to even darker and more painful <br>stories, resigned to the fact that nobody would appreciate them. Perhaps the fairytales were to <br>blame, stubborn things unwilling to change? After having devoted his entire life to writing, the <br>fairytales were refusing to help him, stubbornly unchanging for hundreds of years. <br>Weren’t the fairytales the first to bask in undeserved immortality?<br>The Fairytale King noticed the little <br>dreamer, for if even a single reader was <br>ready to believe in fairytales, the whole <br>world would continue to do so. Thus the <br>Child became the Savior. From his dreams, <br>fairytales drew new life. As a reward, the <br>Fairytale King granted the Child Savior a <br>wish. “Thanks to you we are remembered. I <br>trust you will find in your heart the proper <br>reward to ask for. ”<br>In the darkest moment of his life, the Writer no one believed in was <br>lost in the memories of a forgotten <br>childhood, when the magic of fairytales <br>ignited the passion in his heart. <br>Then he remembered everything: <br>he remembered a distant wish, he <br>remembered what he saved, and saw <br>how ungrateful the fairytales were.<br>But there was a Child who still believed in fairytales. Alone and abandoned by everyone, the Child found shelter in those old stories. <br>Within was protection from the world outside, too real and too cruel. Lost among myths and tales, he forgot the pain of a family <br>unable to give him the childhood he deserved. “I love all fairytales full of heroes and villains to defeat, ” said the Child. “Why doesn’t <br>anyone write new fairytales? If only I knew how, I would do it, ” the little dreamer kept repeating.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":11600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"YOKLvRVOk9C13RDb","name":"Pagina 117","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 117</h2><p>116<br>So it was that the villains <br>became good, the heroes <br>became evil. <br>And all fairytales <br>shattered.<br>For a long time, the Child searched his heart for the most beautiful wish he could think of. However, hidden in <br>his heart’s innermost corner, he found his own shadow. The One Who <br>Plots in the Shadows emerged from the future, driven by rejection, whispering in the Child Savior’s mind a malicious intention. <br>The Child Savior truly believed that it was a good idea. <br>Innocent, he said, “I would give new life to the rogues, a chance at redemption for every character who has been relegated to the <br>role of villain for centuries. ”<br>But every light needs its shadow.<br>Hunched over in his studio, into the darkness of his soul, The <br>Writer no one believed in died, to rise again as <br> The One Who Plots in the Shadows.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":11700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"99cLTMaoeQpZuxW4","name":"Pagina 118","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 118</h2><p>117<br>Scenarios</p>","markdown":""},"sort":11800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"9XfCb52U5OerN5dP","name":"Pagina 119","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 119</h2><p>118<br>Red-hood <br>Iskra Once upon a time…<br>The prosperous village of Durfort in <br>Gévaudan, France is being terrorized by <br>ferocious beasts. Gerard Dubois, the local <br>lord of the manor, is recently married to the <br>beautiful Elizaveta of Volhynia but finds <br>he cannot enjoy his honeymoon when his <br>desperate subjects are constantly pestering <br>him for help. Finding that the cause of <br>their fears are beyond his meager ability to <br>manage, Gerard has written a letter to the <br>Papacy, quietly begging for help. The letter, <br>written in Lord Gerard’s trembling hand, <br>reads, “The beasts that menace the Gévaudan <br>are unnatural, fashioned by something other <br>than God. ”<br>A group of the Order’s Hunters is sent to the <br>village of Durfort to find out what is really <br>going on...<br>A Scenario inspired by <br>Little Red Riding Hood <br>(Charles Perrault)<br>Safety Keywords:<br>  <br>Child neglect / Revenge</p>","markdown":""},"sort":11900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"woVu7wdBX9twQ7Q9","name":"Pagina 120","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 120</h2><p>Play the official Red-Hood Iskra <br>soundtrack during your game <br>session!<br>119<br>The story that led us here…<br>Elizaveta of Volhynia has always been an attractive <br>woman, accustomed to the rich salons of the gentry, and <br>the pomp of nobles and courtiers. Becoming pregnant with <br>Iskra, her eldest daughter, was a curse for her.<br>Abandoned by her wealthy lover, Elizaveta was  <br>impoverished for years, with few skills, little work, and only <br>the help of her old mother Anastazia. A chance encounter <br>with Gerard, who is ignorant of her past, rekindled <br>Elizaveta’s ambition for a life of comfort and decadence as <br>the future wife of a nobleman. Elizaveta, determined not to <br>miss such an opportunity, sent her daughter Iskra alone to <br>visit her grandmother. Elizaveta knew that she was exposing <br>her to the dangers of the dense forest of Białowieża, a place <br>full of beasts and bandits, and deadly to the unwary. Ten-<br>year-old Iskra trusted her mother and disappeared forever <br>into the darkness of the forest. Anastazia had always treated <br>Iskra with love and kindness and, overwhelmed by the <br>grief of her granddaughter’s sad end, died soon after. Free <br>and unattached, Elizaveta fled to Gévaudan with her new <br>husband, unaware of her daughter’s real fate. In fact, Iskra <br>did not die, but joined Greskar’s wolf pack, becoming a wolf <br>herself...<br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunters…<br>Iskra didn’t die in the forest of Białowieża. Instead, she <br>faced every trial with fierce tenacity and eventually <br>prevailed, defeating Greskar. A huge, ferocious werewolf, <br>Greskar infected Iskra with the wolf ’s curse. Becoming a <br>member of the pack and the favorite of the alpha Greskar, <br>Iskra set off for the Gévaudan, following the scent of her <br>mother, determined to get her revenge. Thanks to the fury <br>of the wolf pack, Iskra has thrown the village of Durfort <br>into disarray. Now, she waits in the shadows for the right <br>opportunity to enter the palace and devour her unworthy <br>mother. <br>Elizaveta has realized what is happening, for Iskra left  <br>a pendant she had once made for her on the windowsill, <br>a memento of a rare moment of happiness. Elizaveta, a <br>cunning manipulator, got rid of the token and did not panic <br>or lose her temper. After convincing Gerard to turn to the <br>Order, she will seek to move the pieces on the chessboard, <br>using them to rid herself of her unwanted offspring once <br>and for all...</p>","markdown":""},"sort":12000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"0aTerQGjNLmK6cFw","name":"Pagina 121","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 121</h2><p>1<br>120<br>First Scene<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  Our story opens as you are <br>being interviewed by a nervous Gerard Dubois, who, anxious <br>to get rid of the monsters infesting his lands, has organized a <br>dinner for his long-anticipated guests. A room has been booked <br>for you at the town’s finest inn, but even though it’s been a long <br>day’s journey, the urgency of the matter at hand demands that <br>no time be wasted. Next to the fireplace, a beautiful woman <br>is pouring wine from a goblet and smiling at you. She is Lady <br>Elizaveta, Gerard’s wife.  <br>Place: The ceremonial hall of the Dubois family’s grand <br>palace. A richly furnished room with an enormous painting of <br>Patrick Dubois, Gerard’s late father. Stern and sullen-looking, <br>Patrick seems to judge his son’s incompetence from beyond <br>the grave with ill-concealed contempt.<br>Time: The sun set more than two hours ago and after a long <br>journey, it is now dinnertime.<br>Initial situation: Gerard is anxious for the Hunters to get to <br>work. Elizaveta studies the situation in silence, trying to figure <br>out how she can turn the Hunters’ arrival to her advantage, <br>using them as tools for her own purposes. Choose one of the <br>villagers to be her dinner guest, or create one of your own. <br>Vincent, her trusted head of the guards, will also be present, <br>of course.<br>Information: The following information/clues can be <br>obtained from the interview with Gerard.<br> ◆ The monsters that scourge the Gévaudan are ferocious <br>beasts, as can be seen from the state of the victims’ bodies.<br> ◆ The first two victims were Guy and Ivette, two young <br>lovers who used to meet secretly in the old cemetery <br>just outside the city. It is there that what remains of their <br>bodies are buried.<br> ◆ It is strictly forbidden to leave the city after sunset. The fall <br>of night now brings with it the mournful song of howling <br>wolves.<br>The Dubois Palace<br>Descriptor: A great palace with more than a hundred rooms, <br>rich and opulent.<br>When the Hunters visit the palace, roll 1 die to determine a <br>special feature.<br>1-2: The palace cellars are filled with excellent wine and fine <br>game meat.<br>3-4: A secret passageway connects the large dining room to <br>the inner courtyard.<br>5-6: Every room in the palace is filled with flattering paintings <br>of Patrick Dubois, Gerard’s father.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":12100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"cLEH2UJK0F0olPtL","name":"Pagina 122","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 122</h2><p>121<br>Gerard Dubois the Incapable Noble<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am the noble baron of Durfort and my <br>word is law. I live in the shadow of my late father’s glory.<br>Agenda: Put an end to the menacing werewolves and <br>cover up any possible mischief.<br>Elizaveta – The cruel bride<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am skillful and charming. I’ll do whatever <br>is needed to get what I want.<br>Agenda: To maintain the comforts and luxuries I have <br>earned. That means ridding myself of my annoying daughter <br>Iskra.<br>Vincent Arn – Former Huntsman and Chief of <br>the Guards<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled hunter. I have no qualms <br>about doing whatever is needed. I want to enjoy a good life <br>without working so hard.<br>Agenda: I understand how the world works and who <br>really runs the Dubois household. Pleasing Elizaveta is the <br>best way to maintain my status.<br>Gift - Veteran:  Vincent is skilled in taking advantage <br>of any situation. When he has the support of at least two <br>of his men, every action against him receives 1 Penalty <br>and Vincent can inflict 1 additional Wound.<br>The Guards of Gerard Dubois<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are duty-bound    -    as long as we get <br>paid.<br>Agenda: Vincent is the boss. We’ll follow his lead.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":12200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"zeWLG7tid5f8jqBg","name":"Pagina 123","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 123</h2><p>122<br>Durfort Village<br>Descriptor: A rich and prosperous place thanks largely to the <br>previous baron, Patrick Dubois.<br>When the Hunters roam Durfort, roll 1 die in each Scene to see <br>who they will meet:<br>1 Anne the Little Chatterer<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: Lady Elizaveta has instructed me to keep her <br>informed about what is being said in town. I do my job as a spy <br>because I don’t want her to stop giving me gifts.<br>2 Nicholas the Huntsman<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I know the ferocity of wolves and I can’t wait to <br>show off in front of Baron Gerard.<br>3 Genevieve the Chemist<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I escaped from a past full of witchcraft and deceit. <br>I know how to summon spirits and talk with them.<br>4 Marcel the Time-Waster<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I frequently wander the town and may be found <br>anywhere. Once, I saw a young girl at the Oak Glade, but no <br>one believed my story because I am too young.<br>5 Corinne the Housekeeper<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I know all rumors in the village, partly because <br>I start most of them myself. I’m easily offended and I love <br>receiving gifts.<br>6 Didier the Grumpy Old Man <br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I hate all foreigners and I miss the old baron. He <br>knew how to stand up for himself. Not like that lax Gerard who <br>even married a foreigner!</p>","markdown":""},"sort":12300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"LAtnHCKrVozRQnQF","name":"Pagina 124","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 124</h2><p>123<br>The Great Gévaudan Forest<br>Descriptor: A huge expanse of trees and natural ravines. Home to animals and fairy creatures.<br>The Old Cemetery<br>Descriptor: A small cemetery with rusty gates and stone tombs. A <br>small, abandoned church lends a gloomy aura to the place.<br>When Hunters wander through the cemetery, roll a die:<br>1-2: A small hidden path leads to an abandoned well, where <br>Elizaveta has thrown an old earthenware pendant that Iskra once <br>made for her as a gift.<br>3-4: Armand, an old, rich wine and spice merchant, arrives in a <br>hurry at the cemetery. The wolves are following him. Roll a die: <br>1-3: 8 Black wolves.<br>4-5: 8 Black wolves + Greskar. <br>6: 8 Black wolves + Iskra.<br>5-6: A group of bandits is traveling through Gévaudan, carrying <br>illegal game. Jozef, their leader, is a former lover of Elizaveta and <br>knows the woman’s past. The bandits want to stop in town to rest, <br>but without attracting attention from the authorities.<br>Descriptor: A small green area just over an hour from <br>Durfort. The glade is a place of arcane power in the middle <br>of the great Gévaudan forest.<br>Gift - Fairyland: Any action that has to do with magic <br>receives 1 extra Success within the small glade. This place <br>absorbs energy from living things. For every hour you stay <br>there you must spend 1 Soma or receive 1 fatigue Wound.<br>When the Hunters arrive at the glade, roll a die to see who <br>they will meet:<br>1-3: The glade is empty, but there are traces of wolves and <br>the bones of devoured prey. After ten minutes, 8 Black <br>Wolves arrive and ambush the Hunters.<br>4-5: A pack is at the glade: Greskar + 8 Black Wolves.<br>6: Iskra is at the glade, alone if it is daytime or with the <br>pack (4-5 result, but without Greskar) if it is nighttime.<br>As a modifier: if it is night, add 2 to the roll.<br>The Oaks Glade</p>","markdown":""},"sort":12400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"oEFdfAHRX84DCaLH","name":"Pagina 125","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 125</h2><p>IskraIskra<br>124<br>The Wolves’ Lair<br>Descriptor: A large, natural cave full of tunnels and <br>small chambers, less than three hours from Durfort. <br>During the day the den is full of resting wolves, but at <br>night it is almost always empty.<br>Gift - Defense Lair:  Moving into the lair without <br>masking your scent will cause the beasts to quickly <br>become alert. At the start of each Scene spent in this <br>place, you must pass a Medium OL Defense roll. If you <br>fail, 1d6 (2d6 if it is daytime) black wolves arrive.<br>As the Hunters explore the lair, roll a die at each Scene <br>to see what they will encounter, or present the rooms in <br>ascending order:<br>1-2: Iskra’s personal den. It is clear that this space is <br>occupied by a little girl. Drawings on the walls depict <br>a mother and daughter holding hands. They are drawn <br>in blood.<br>3-4: A prisoner that is too badly injured to move. <br>Depending on what has happened thus far, he may be <br>one of the inhabitants of Durfort (see the Village table) <br>or one of the encounters at the Old Cemetery that hasn’t <br>already been triggered.<br>5: A large cave full of bones and human corpses.<br>6: A long underground tunnel leading from the Den to <br>the old well in Dufort’s main square.<br>Anastazia the <br>Sorrowful Spirit<br>OL Hard 7 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a restless spirit, bound to the memory of <br>my granddaughter. My condition as a spirit does not allow <br>me to communicate with the living except through dreams, <br>whispers, and visions.<br>Agenda: Preventing further harm to Iskra and find a way to <br>save my granddaughter’s soul.<br>Gift - Spirit: Anastazia is a spirit and can only be damaged <br>by magic. She may appear in a dream to a target, who may <br>resist with a Defense Check or accept contact voluntarily. <br>The target suffers 1 Wound from stress but will receive from <br>Anastazia a vision of a present or past event with a barely <br>whispered phrase.<br>Gift - Loving Grandmother:  Anastazia always follows <br>Iskra and protects her from danger. Thanks to her strong <br>will, she can interact with the material world by moving <br>objects and manipulating the environment, even inflicting <br>a Wound on a target. If a subject is likely to help save her <br>granddaughter, Anastazia will simply fill their mind with <br>memories of her.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":12500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"xxixFXWDsgb8I9pq","name":"Pagina 126","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 126</h2><p>IskraIskra<br>125<br>Greskar the <br>Big Black <br>Wolf<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC  <br>(4 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a huge, mighty <br>werewolf. I have to constantly prove my <br>strength to stay the alpha of the pack.<br>Agenda: Protect Iskra and devour as <br>many humans as possible.<br>Gift - Big Wolf: Greskar is an enormous <br>black wolf, as big as a horse. When he <br>grabs someone with his jaws, in addition <br>to inflicting a Wound, he can drag or <br>hurl them away as if they were a rag doll. <br>Once per Scene, Geskar’s bite can inflict <br>1 additional Wound.<br>Gift - The Wolf’s Smell:  Greskar’s <br>sense of smell is infallible. The big wolf <br>will always be able to identify someone if <br>he knows their scent, ignoring all kinds <br>of disguises and even magic.<br>Red-Hood Iskra<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (4 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I possess the strength and agility of a wolf. I <br>hide my face with a rudimentary wooden mask that I made <br>with my own hands. I wear a threadbare red cape, the <br>last gift from my mother.<br>Agenda: To unleash her animalistic fury <br>on Elizaveta and anyone who defends <br>her. Taking revenge on my mother has <br>become an obsession for me.<br>Gift - Wolf’s Blood:  Iskra is <br>moved by an animalistic fury <br>that allows her to act twice in <br>the course of an Exchange.<br>Gift - The Senses of a <br>Wolf: Iskra’s sense of smell <br>has become infallible. The <br>little girl will always be able to <br>identify someone if she knows <br>their scent, ignoring all kinds <br>of disguises and even magic.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":12600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"PF4sEnzYN00ntBWj","name":"Pagina 127","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 127</h2><p>126<br>Black Wolves of <br>Greskar’s Pack<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are fierce black wolves, we hate <br>humans and obey only our pack leader.<br>Agenda: Follow without hesitation every order <br>from the pack’s alpha.<br>Gift - The Power of the Pack:  Any action <br>taken while being engaged by two or more Wolves <br>receives 1 Penalty.<br>Story Events<br>In this Scenario, there are six main Events. As Storyteller, feel <br>free to create new ones in response to the actions of the Hunters.<br>If the raids of the wolves are not stopped in one day:  <br>many of Gerard’s soldiers will be eliminated, victims of a much <br>more intense attack than those that have occurred so far, taking <br>place at the gates of the palace. After the furious assault, the <br>city’s defenses will be reduced to a minimum and it will be very <br>easy for Iskra to break into the Dubois palace under the cover of <br>darkness.<br>If a Hunter finds Iskra’s pendant in the well:  Anastazia <br>will contact them, showing them a vision of Iskra as a child <br>drinking at the Oaks Glade. The spirit of Iskra’s grandmother, <br>while unable to communicate directly, will try to make the <br>Hunters understand that Iskra is not a monster.<br>If Elizaveta goes out of town for any reason:  Iskra will <br>immediately smell her scent and rush to eliminate her regardless <br>of any risk. Confronted with her mother, the little girl will lose all <br>restraint and refuse to listen to reason.<br>If Iskra is captured: the wolf pack led by a furious Greskar <br>will launch a tremendous attack on Durfort. Elizaveta will try to <br>eliminate her daughter with a powerful poison.<br>If Iskra is killed: Anastazia’s spirit will turn on her murderer, <br>sending visions of Elizaveta trying to wash the blood of a dead <br>child from her hands.<br>If someone accuses Elizaveta: Gerard will deny everything <br>out of fear and shame, invoking concrete and irrefutable <br>evidence. Elizaveta, for her part, will play the role of the victim, <br>always trying to highlight the danger posed by the wolves.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":12700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"bxENa7VSAM8NUYFv","name":"Pagina 128","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 128</h2><p>1<br>2<br>127<br>Scenario Gifts<br>These Gifts represent special abilities related to the <br>Red-Hood Iskra Scenario and can be acquired once the <br>conditions are met. A Hunter can only acquire one Scenario <br>Gift. If they buy a new one during an Interlude, they will <br>have to forgo the previous one.<br>Voice of the Spirits<br>Requirement:    You have come into contact with the Gift  <br>Spirit.<br>By calming your mind and concentrating, you can open <br>your mind to the spiritual world and communicate with <br>restless souls. Spend 1 Soma to contact a creature with the <br>Spirit Gift you’ve previously encountered. Y ou do not suffer <br>the Wound caused by the stress of spiritual connection.<br>Wolf-killer<br>Requirement: Having faced the wolves in a fight at least <br>once.<br>Y ou know how to deal with the fiercest of wolves and are <br>careful not to be surrounded. When you obtain at least a <br>Standard Outcome on a Position or Defense Check against <br>a pack of beasts, you can immediately eliminate 1 Minor <br>animal NPC with 1 Wound.<br>Where are you going all alone, <br>sweetie? (Special Gift for Garou the <br>Old Wolf)<br>Requirement: To meet Iskra alone in the forest.<br>Y ou are attracted to the little girl who pretends to be a wolf <br>and you dream of devouring her. Once per Scene, you can <br>spend 1 Soma to know exactly where she is. If you anticipate <br>her and arrive somewhere before her, you get 1 Additional <br>Success on every Check you make to hurt or devour that <br>little morsel. Y ou can’t wait to swallow that tidbit and it <br>makes you let your guard down. As long as she is present <br>in the Scene, you receive 1 Penalty in all Defense Checks.<br>The Scenario Red-Hood <br>Iskra in Scenes<br>FIRST SCENE – Dinner with <br>Gerard Dubois<br>It’s the same one you find on page 120.<br>End of Scene: Gerard asks the Hunters to look for traces <br>of the Wolves by sending them to the Old Cemetery, <br>where the first massacre took place. Continue to SECOND <br>SCENE - The old cemetery.<br>SECOND SCENE – The old <br>cemetery<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: The old cemetery of Durfort <br>lies just over ten minutes’ walk from the town. With the <br>constant threat of wolves, it is now totally abandoned. Beyond <br>the old rusty gate, you can see many weathered gravestones, <br>a small church, and an old well whose wooden planks have <br>recently been dismantled.<br>Place: The old cemetery of Durfort in the middle of the <br>large Gévaudan forest. It is reached by a narrow, dirt path</p>","markdown":""},"sort":12800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241719,"modifiedTime":1783973241719,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"cygvhbvqn5avkH0g","name":"Pagina 129","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 129</h2><p>3a<br>3b<br>128<br>that winds its way through the woods from the main road.<br>Time: It is early morning, the sun is high on a clear winter <br>sky.<br>Information: In the cemetery, there are many wolf <br>tracks. In the middle of them are the prints of two small <br>bare feet, almost certainly a little girl. At the bottom of <br>the old well can be found the pendant that Elizaveta tried <br>to make disappear. The wolves’ tracks lead deep into the <br>forest, to their den. Anastazia will contact the Hunter who <br>recovered the pendant, sending them a vision of Elizaveta <br>trying in vain to wash her bloodstained hands.<br>End of Scene:  Hunters can decide whether to return <br>to the town to report (THIRD SCENE OPTION A - <br>Reporting) or follow the trail to the wolves’ den (THIRD <br>SCENE OPTION B - On the Wolves’ Trail).<br>THIRD SCENE OPTION A – <br>Reporting<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: Now that you see Durfort in <br>broad daylight you realize how large the village is and how it <br>is slowly expanding, so much so that it could almost be called <br>a city. Trade flourished in Dufort under the old baron’s rule, <br>but now all that is threatened by the savage beasts lurking in <br>the nearby forest. <br>Place: Along the streets of the village, men and women go <br>about their daily business. Their somber glances betray the <br>fear that runs through the population.<br>Time: It is late morning, just over an hour until noon, and <br>the whole village will stop to have a frugal lunch.<br>Information: Along the streets of the village, two of the <br>inhabitants (see Durfort Village table) will approach the <br>Hunters to interact. At the palace, Vincent will greet the <br>characters by asking them how it went at the cemetery, <br>gathering information for a report to Elizaveta. Gerard, <br>once he hears the Hunters’ report, will hesitantly ask about <br>their next move. Elizaveta will try to learn what the Hunters <br>have discovered, showing excessive interest if the pendant <br>is shown.<br>End of Scene:  Hunters can either look for the wolves’ <br>lair (THIRD SCENE OPTION B - On the Wolves’ Trail) <br>or ambush Iskra while remaining in the city (FOURTH <br>SCENE - Surprise Attack).<br>THIRD SCENE OPTION B – <br>On the Wolves’ Trail<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  Following the tracks <br>in the forest is not easy and several times you risk getting <br>lost. Eventually, the tracks lead to a large natural cave that <br>disappears into the darkness underground.<br>Place: The lair of the Black Wolves. Traces of the pack are <br>clearly visible outside.<br>Time: Crossing the forest takes more than half a day.<br>Information: Depending on whether it is day or night, <br>consult The Wolves’ Lair to see who the Hunters will meet. <br>In the lair, it will be possible to discover traces of Iskra and <br>information about her. If freed, the village prisoner will tell <br>the Hunters, in great detail, of a little girl, masked and in <br>a threadbare red cloak, that is the leader of the wolf pack.<br>End of Scene:  While the Hunters are in the lair, Iskra, <br>Greskar, and the remaining wolves of the pack launch an</p>","markdown":""},"sort":12900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241720,"modifiedTime":1783973241720,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"b0p8HQOi7CG4WWvT","name":"Pagina 130","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 130</h2><p>4 5<br>129<br>attack on Durfort, decimating Vincent’s men. The Hunters <br>may arrive in the middle of the battle or when the fight <br>is almost over. Continue to FOURTH SCENE - Surprise <br>Attack.<br>FOURTH SCENE – Surprise <br>Attack<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: The cries of the townspeople <br>mingle with the howls of the wolves, while large feral figures <br>dart through the alleyways in the moonlight. Using a secret <br>passageway, the pack launched a furious attack on the <br>Dubois mansion. <br>Place: The village of Durfort, doors barred and terrified <br>villagers fleeing through the streets.<br>Time: It is night, but a full moon high in the sky illuminates <br>the village with a gloomy white light.<br>Information: There’s no mercy in the wolves’ fury and <br>many villagers will be devoured alive if the Hunters don’t <br>save them. At the head of his men, Vincent tries to repel <br>Greskar and his wolves, but he will not fight to the death. <br>Iskra, meanwhile, has snuck into the palace in search of her <br>mother.<br>End of Scene: However the battle goes, the Hunters arrive <br>at the palace to find a terrified Gerard fleeing the scene. <br>The nobleman tells them that a small, furious creature <br>has broken into the palace and is now hunting down his <br>beloved bride. It’s time for a showdown. Go to FIFTH <br>SCENE - Which Side Are You On?<br>FIFTH SCENE – Which Side <br>Are You On?<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  The Dubois palace is a <br>veritable slaughterhouse. It seems that a whole pack of wolves <br>has run rampant, destroying as they went. When you hear <br>Elizaveta’s cry, you rush into the great hall where you had <br>dinner when you first arrived. In front of you, a terrified <br>Elizaveta is confronting a little girl covered in mud and <br>blood. The little girl bares her teeth like a wolf, but she has the <br>crystal blue eyes of her mother.<br>Place: The ceremonial hall of the Dubois family’s grand <br>palace.<br>Time: Time for a showdown.<br>End of Scene:  Elizaveta will ask the Hunters for help. <br>Iskra, on the other hand, after a moment of surprise at the <br>newcomers, is ready to die in order to have her revenge. If <br>he is still alive, Greskar’s howling will hint that the big wolf <br>will arrive any moment. If someone has made a connection <br>with her, Anastazia will intervene with a vision to help the <br>Hunters realize who in the room is truly the monster.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":13000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241720,"modifiedTime":1783973241720,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"QmmeWrwGAnOOi1g7","name":"Pagina 131","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 131</h2><p>130<br>Once upon a <br>time…<br>The Hunters arrive in Sinalunga, a small <br>town in the Grand Duchy of Tuscany where <br>a gruesome discovery has been made. Not <br>far from the town, the mutilated corpses of <br>ten people were found in an old well,  solving <br>almost all of the many disappearances in <br>recent months that have made the area <br>the epicenter of macabre rumors and tales. <br>Of Flesh <br>and Wood<br>A Scenario inspired by <br>Pinocchio (Carlo Collodi)<br>Safety Keywords:  <br>Blood sacrifices / Mutilation / Body Horror<br>The Papacy, determined to clarify what <br>happened, fears that there is an ancient <br>esoteric practice behind the killings, one <br>that involves the sacrifice of innocent <br>souls. Once before Sinalunga had been <br>the setting of a terrible story: the noble <br>Azzurra De Baciocchi was accused of <br>witchcraft for sacrificing young women <br>in search of eternal youth, and burned at <br>the stake in 1513. The task of the Hunters <br>will therefore be to understand what lies <br>behind the many disappearances now <br>afflicting Sinalunga.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":13100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241720,"modifiedTime":1783973241720,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"TOkDpVOJi4Pd1TjN","name":"Pagina 132","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 132</h2><p>131<br>The story that led us here…<br>Two old alchemists, Antonio and Geppetto, have <br>worked on a magic oak tree, hoping to obtain the fantastic <br>ingredients required to uncover the secret of eternal life. <br>They were led to the supernatural discovery by an ancient <br>text in their possession, which revealed the alchemical <br>formula for unending life, the key component being a body <br>made of enchanted wood. <br>The mystical material would bestow immortality, but to live <br>among men without frightening them it must be covered in <br>flesh. In the course of their experiments, the two alchemists <br>were astonished to discover that the magical oak had a life <br>of its own. Animated by the power of fairy magic, whose <br>only purpose is to bedevil humans, this piece of wood <br>could bring lies to life.<br> <br>To prove it, the enchanted oak turned into a living, wooden <br>puppet named Carlo, who by his nature could not help but <br>deceive Geppetto and Antonio about the veracity of their <br>theories. Carlo, unable to speak even a single word of truth <br>to the two alchemists, convinced them that the rite they <br>searched for required harnessing a person’s soul inside a <br>wooden body. Antonio and Geppetto then began to kidnap <br>the poor and desperate around Sinalunga, torturing and <br>flaying them alive according to Carlo’s instructions. After a <br>few weeks, horrified by the situation he unwillingly created, <br>Carlo escaped to the city. <br>After the discovery of the well, Antonio and Geppetto fled <br>the old carpenter’s workshop they used as a laboratory and <br>took refuge in Villa Cilesterino, an old abandoned manor <br>house not far from Sinalunga. Here the two alchemists met <br>the spirit of Azzurra, the ancient owner of the villa, who <br>wanders in this world longing for past glories. The gullible <br>pair did not hesitate to tell her the whole story. Azzurra <br>deceived them in turn, animating the mannequins with her <br>powers and convincing Geppetto and Antonio that their <br>research was heading in the right direction. Azzura’s spirit <br>now needs to find Carlo and take advantage of the fairy <br>magic that animates him, using it to bring herself back to <br>life.<br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunters…<br>Carlo escaped from the old carpenter’s shop and is now in <br>Sinalunga. Every morning, thanks to the power of his lies, <br>he disguises himself as a real child. Carlo has even begun <br>attending school, where he met Lucino, a loyal and studious <br>child who took a liking to the living puppet. At Villa <br>Cilesterino, Antonio continues his experiments, animating <br>more and more mannequins that he wraps in human flesh <br>to make them look like ordinary people. Azzurra’s magic <br>completes the “miracle” by combining flesh and wood, <br>thereby creating servants to do her will. Geppetto, tricked <br>by Azzurra, has instead returned to Sinalunga, where for <br>days he has been desperately trying to track down Carlo <br>and take him back to his mistress.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":13200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"6nkC1qZQS8uEqxBM","name":"Pagina 133","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 133</h2><p>1<br>132<br>First Scene<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  You have recently arrived <br>in Sinalunga. The small town is bustling with activity and <br>no one seems to have noticed your presence. However, in <br>the eyes of the city’s inhabitants you clearly see a darkness, <br>reflecting the horror that has recently been discovered... <br>You notice a man in military uniform, intent on talking to <br>a couple of peasants who are dragging a large pig with an <br>injured leg. The two townspeople look puzzled at the officer, <br>and from their disinterested expressions, you understand that <br>they can’t wait to get back on the road and leave the insistent <br>investigator behind. The Order is in close contact with the <br>Grand Duchy of Tuscany, so the officer should be aware that <br>a group of Hunters is arriving in town. Could he be an ally in <br>your investigation?<br>Place: The road that crosses the whole town of Sinalunga. <br>The townspeople are hard at work, trying to finish all their <br>chores before dinner.<br>Time: It is less than an hour before sunset and the low, <br>intensely red sun illuminates the surrounding hills, full of <br>vineyards.<br>Initial situation:  The Hunters have arrived in the <br>town of Sinalunga. They already have various pieces of <br>information regarding the incident and they know where <br>the old well, and makeshift morgue, is located. In front of <br>them, Vincenzo Carabiniere, the military officer, is also at <br>work to unravel the murder mystery.<br>Information: What the Hunters already know.<br> ◆ The well is a ten-minute walk from the town and was <br>part of an old manor estate called Villa Cilesterino.<br> ◆ The bodies found had their skin flayed off. It seems that <br>the killer wanted only the skin and muscles of their <br>victims, but not the organs and entrails.<br>Speaking with Vincenzo, the Hunters will discover that the <br>two farmers he was questioning are Lapo and Cino, the <br>ones who found the well. The two were reluctant to talk <br>because at the time of their discovery they were hiding at <br>the well to eat some bread they had stolen from the bakery. <br>The two know very little and Vincenzo will make it clear <br>that they are not the sharpest knives in the drawer.<br>Vincenzo Carabiniere<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a loyal soldier and I always try to do my <br>best to help others. Given my integrity, my superiors keep me <br>away from battlefields.<br>Agenda: Find out what lies behind the disappearances in <br>Sinalunga.<br>Sinalunga<br>Descriptor: A small town in the Tuscan hills. Thanks to its <br>famously delicious wine, many in the town manage to have a <br>good standard of living.<br>By wandering around town and talking to the inhabitants, <br>the Hunters can get some information. The fear that <br>an intervention by the Grand Duchy could upset life in <br>Sinalunga means the inhabitants are reluctant to speak to <br>anyone other than the authorities. Only Lapo and Cino, <br>who are not particularly bright, won’t hesitate to talk with <br>the Hunters, though only with the promise of a reward.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":13300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"PuWPfermWZCyTPT0","name":"Pagina 134","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 134</h2><p>133<br>Threat - Distrustful Inhabitants<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: We don’t want to attract too much attention <br>to Sinalunga, so we’re reluctant to talk to foreigners. Nobody <br>here wants to lose what they have gained through years of <br>hard work.<br>Information from the townspeople: <br>Roll a die or pick from the list.<br> ◆ 1-2: 10 people have been found, but 11 went missing. <br>Nino’s body is still missing. He is Mastro Antonio’s <br>apprentice carpenter. Antonio is known as Mastro <br>“Cherry” Ciliegia because of his squat and red nose. <br> ◆ 3-4: Villa Cilesterino is haunted by the ghost of the <br>old owner, Azzurra. She was burned at the stake for <br>witchcraft.<br> ◆ 5-6: The high standard of living in Sinalunga led to the <br>opening of Villa Balocchi, a tavern on the edge of town <br>where one can find company as well as a comfortable <br>bed. The tavern is managed by Amabile Burromo and <br>is in open competition with the historic town inn, the <br>Gambero Rosso (meaning “the Red Prawn”).<br>The Old Well<br>Descriptor: An old abandoned well in the middle of a <br>dilapidated vineyard. A nauseating smell from the bottom of <br>the well reminds anyone who approaches of the horror that <br>it hides.<br>Information: <br> ◆ The bodies have already been removed and burned to <br>avoid infection and disease. <br> ◆ When going down into the well, however, there are still <br>some remains and traces of blood. <br> ◆ On the bottom, it is possible to find a carpenter’s chisel <br>that Geppetto lost while moving the corpses. <br>The Gambero Rosso Inn<br>Descriptor: A small and cozy tavern, full of bottles of good <br>wine.<br>Information: <br> ◆ Speaking with the innkeeper, a big fat man named <br>Duccio, the Hunters will learn that Villa Balocchi is a <br>place steeped in sin, where men and women gamble <br>and entertain themselves in shady encounters. <br>During the evening, Geppetto is at the Gambero Rosso and <br>will not hesitate to play out his little rehearsed spectacle of <br>the worried father for whoever shows up. Geppetto will <br>describe Carlo as an annoying child with a pair of old, <br>elegant shoes that Geppetto gave him for his first day of <br>school.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":13400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"KpksPB5satLpptUi","name":"Pagina 135","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 135</h2><p>134<br>Geppetto Gullible Alchemist <br>Apprentice<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a poor man who has always been looking <br>for a way to make a living. I learned the basics of alchemy <br>from master Antonio.<br>Agenda: Pretend to be Carlo’s father and find him / Obtain <br>the secret of eternal life, thanks to alchemy.<br>Gift - Improvised Alchemist:  Geppetto can rely on <br>a series of alchemical compounds contained in vials that <br>he hides under a tacky yellow wig. When he throws a vial, <br>roll a die: 1-2 Explosive: The liquid explodes on contact <br>with the air, causing 1 Wound to everyone within thirty <br>feet. Thick black smoke will engulf the whole area; 3-4 <br>Stench: A nauseating odor fills the air giving 1 Penalty to <br>all actions within the area for the rest of the Scene; 5-6 Air <br>Bomb: All subjects in an area of thirty feet are knocked <br>back and fall to the ground. If they hit an obstacle they can <br>suffer 1 Wound. Geppetto is immune to the effects of his <br>alchemical concoctions.<br>The Old Carpenter’s Shop<br>Descriptor: Once the alchemical laboratory of Mastro <br>Antonio, the carpenter’s shop was abandoned after the <br>discovery of the corpses. <br>Information: <br> ◆ The place is a normal carpenter’s shop, abandoned for <br>some time. The only element that catches the Hunters’ <br>attention is a series of chisels on the wall, with one</p>","markdown":""},"sort":13500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"iTTMB90fAY3fF22S","name":"Pagina 136","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 136</h2><p>135<br>missing from the set. If the Hunters have recovered the <br>chisel in the well they will see that it is the missing tool. <br> ◆ Among other things of interest, the Hunters can find <br>an old leather bag with some books for the local school.<br>At the back of the carpenter’s shop are the remains of a <br>hastily packed alchemical laboratory. On the wall, there <br>are two human-sized wooden mannequins, skillfully <br>made but stained with blood and decomposing skin. These <br>are Marionettes, the first two produced by Antonio and <br>Geppetto’s experiments, later animated by Azzurra’s magic. <br>The Marionettes will spring on the Hunters as soon as they <br>get close.<br>Marionette <br>OL Easy 3 - Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: We are souls cursed by Azzurra in the wooden <br>bodies of marionettes. We hate all living beings and want to <br>be destroyed to be free again.<br>Agenda: Attacking every human we meet.<br>Gift - Boundless Rage:  Azzurra’s power animates and <br>forces the Marionettes to do evil acts. When a Marionette <br>suffers the last Wound it will immediately spring on the <br>enemy with incredible momentum as Azzurra’s power <br>compels them one last time. The Marionette can take a <br>final action with OL Hard 7. This action must be aimed at <br>harming a living being.<br>The School<br>Descriptor: A small school for the studious children of <br>Sinalunga. Jolly voices and shouts cover the lamentation of <br>a dispirited teacher.<br>Information: <br> ◆ The school is open in the morning and brings together <br>all the town’s children who want to learn something. <br>The situation is clearly out of control and the teacher, <br>a young academic from Florence, does not know what <br>to do. <br> ◆ The school is attended by Carlo who, however, appears <br>as an ordinary child. In fact, he does not correspond <br>to the description that Geppetto may have given. The <br>old shoes on his feet are the only clue that the Hunters <br>may notice.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":13600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"0iC7fCjr31dufnGs","name":"Pagina 137","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 137</h2><p>136<br>Carlo The Living <br>Puppet<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a puppet animated by fairy magic. The <br>lies I tell become reality for a short time.<br>Agenda: Living a carefree life without responsibility / I don’t <br>want to abandon Sinalunga and my new friend Lucino, but <br>I’m always afraid that Geppetto and Antonio will catch me. <br>Gift - Lies: Carlo can bring the lies he tells to life <br>by creating a Descriptor that allows him to <br>perform incredible feats. All lies must be <br>centered on him. For example: I can walk <br>through walls or I am invisible to the human <br>eye. The effects of the lies’ power are literal. <br>For this reason, Carlo would not be able to <br>go through a closed door and he would be <br>seen by animals. The effect of Lies lasts for 1 <br>Scene or until a new lie is told.<br>Lucino - The Good Friend<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC  <br>(1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a dutiful and studious child <br>who can’t wait to learn a trade to help my family.<br>Agenda: Help Carlo become a responsible <br>child / Work to help adults who behave well <br>and follow the law.<br>Villa Balocchi<br>Descriptor: A beautiful and sumptuous inn, recently <br>refurbished.<br>Information: <br> ◆ Amabile hosts little Carlo, making him sleep in a small <br>back room. <br> ◆ The Puppet pays the greedy innkeeper with stones <br>which he temporarily turns into gold coins with his <br>powers. Throwing the coins into a safe in his room, the <br>innkeeper hasn’t yet noticed the Puppet’s trick. <br> ◆ During the afternoon and evening, Carlo is at Villa <br>Balocchi and can be found playing with Lucino or <br>pretending to study.<br>Amabile Burromo<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC  <br>(1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled business owner <br>and I manage my inn without delegating <br>anything to anyone. I trust myself only.<br>Agenda: To make profitable deals, <br>without worrying about scruples.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":13700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"nhA5NhLS5jK0nSHy","name":"Pagina 138","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 138</h2><p>137<br>Villa <br>Cilesterino<br>Descriptor: An old abandoned manor house. Weeds and <br>plants have covered everything, while the large garden is <br>abandoned to the passing of time.<br>Information: <br> ◆ Villa Cilesterino is divided into 3 environments: the <br>Garden, the Villa, and the Secret Laboratory. <br> ◆ Azzurra is connected to the whole place and will always <br>be aware of anyone who ventures onto her property.<br>The Garden<br>Descriptor: A large abandoned garden where flowers and <br>plants of all kinds grow. <br>Information: <br> ◆ The Garden is guarded by 4 Marionettes and by <br>old Medoro, a sick bear that Azzurra enslaved with <br>her powers. Wandering around the Garden will <br>immediately alert the guardians.<br>Medoro The Old Bear<br>OL Medium 5 - Minor NPC (4 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a deformed old bear that has lost all its <br>fur. Azzurra treats me like her faithful dog and I am happy to <br>serve her. I have retained most of my bestial strength, despite <br>my age.<br>The Villa<br>Descriptor: A large manor house, once flamboyant, but <br>now covered in dust and mold. <br>Information: <br> ◆ Azzurra is wandering around the Villa and will not <br>hesitate to appear and confront intruders.<br> ◆ In the dining room, there is a huge painting on the <br>north wall depicting a whale swallowing an entire <br>ship. By looking behind the painting, the Hunters can <br>activate the mechanism which opens the secret door to <br>access the Secret Laboratory.<br> ◆ The remaining 4 Marionettes covered in human skin <br>roam around the Villa, but they only act on Azzurra’s <br>orders.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":13800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"nFUnKwLS8z8qsWYU","name":"Pagina 139","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 139</h2><p>138<br>Azzurra The Spirit of the Witch who <br>Spurns Death<br>OL Hard 7 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am the spirit of an old and powerful witch. My powers allow <br>me to summon the souls of the dead and bind them to my will. <br>Agenda: To come back to life thanks to Carlo’s power.<br>Gift - Ancient Spirit:  Azzurra’s body is immaterial and can only be <br>damaged by magic. Azzurra can interact with the world by evoking the souls <br>of the dead, choosing between various effects. 1. Poltergeist: Throw up to <br>3 objects at once. The force with which the objects are thrown is such that <br>they can cause a Wound. 2. Cacophony of the Dead: Frighten everyone <br>with the agonized voices of the damned. Anyone who hears the cacophony <br>must pass a Defense Check or lose 2 Soma points. 3. Possession: Take <br>possession of a target’s body and cause them to perform a single action, <br>albeit not a self-destructive one. Azzurra must change the spirits’ effect with <br>each action and must use all three before she can use an effect again.<br>The Secret Laboratory<br>Descriptor: The cellar of Villa Cilesterino, converted into an alchemical <br>laboratory by Antonio. The smell of wine and mold is unbearable.<br>Information: <br> ◆ Antonio continues his research under Azzurra’s guidance. This led him <br>to create a magical brazier in which Carlo is to be burned.<br> ◆ Nino, the carpenter’s apprentice, is tied to a table, alive but with his legs <br>now ruined by Antonio’s slow flaying. Azzurra wants him kept alive, as <br>she needs innocent blood for the rite.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":13900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"8yZMYV9D44YU7NVm","name":"Pagina 140","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 140</h2><p>139<br>Antonio Ciliegia <br>Gullible Alchemist<br>OL Medium 5 - Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an old alchemist who has never discovered <br>anything concrete. Despite my skills and my experience, luck <br>is never on my side.<br>Agenda: Obtaining the secret of eternal life thanks to <br>alchemy. <br>Gift - Unlucky Alchemist: Antonio can rely on a series <br>of alchemical compounds contained in vials that he hides <br>in his tunic. When using a vial he rolls 1 die. On a 5 or <br>6 something goes wrong and Antonio suffers 1 Wound <br>due to his proverbial bad luck. 1. Fire: The target and the <br>surrounding area catch fire. All targets involved suffer 1 <br>Wound. If the fire is not extinguished, burning targets <br>suffer 1 Wound per action. 2. Thunder:  The target <br>is knocked over thirty feet away and ends up on the <br>ground. If they hit something they will suffer 1 <br>Wound. 3. Glue: an adhesive compound that <br>quickly solidifies in the air. The target will be <br>paralyzed until the compound is removed. <br>The Glue can take 2 Wounds.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":14000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"wrCKUZKLNApHbzAu","name":"Pagina 141","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 141</h2><p>140<br>Events of the Scenario<br>In this Scenario, there are six Events. As a Storyteller, feel <br>free to create new ones in response to the actions of the <br>Hunters.<br>If the Hunters put pressure on Carlo:  Lucino will <br>intervene to help his friend by giving him time to escape.<br>If the Hunters reveal their identity to Vincenzo:   <br>the officer will be at their disposal, trying to help them <br>whenever possible. <br>If the Hunters meet Geppetto: the man will attempt to <br>play on their sympathies with the made-up story of the lost <br>son. Geppetto is not a genius, but neither is he stupid. If <br>he understands who the Hunters really are, he will try to <br>follow them to see if they find Carlo.<br>If the Hunters gain Carlo’s trust:  the Puppet will <br>reveal the truth. Geppetto and Antonio are to blame for <br>everything. The Puppet ignores that it is now Azzurra who <br>runs things.<br>If Geppetto is captured by the Hunters:  he will lead <br>them to Villa Cilesterino, where his companion is. Geppetto <br>will pretend to know nothing, aware that once they arrive, <br>Azzurra will get rid of the Hunters.<br>When Azzurra meets the Hunters:  she will try to <br>deceive them by pretending to be a good spirit who tries <br>to watch over the inhabitants of Sinalunga. Azzurra will <br>ask the Hunters to help her recover a magical Puppet, <br>animated by a dark force that is devouring the souls of the <br>poor townsfolk.<br>Exclusive Scenario Gifts<br>These Gifts represent special abilities related to the Flesh and <br>Wood Scenario and can be acquired once the conditions <br>are met. A Hunter can only acquire one Scenario Gift. If <br>they buy a new one during an Interlude, they will have to <br>forgo the previous one.<br>Marionettes’ Destroyer<br>Requirement: Defeat any Marionette or understand that <br>they are souls imprisoned against their will.<br>Y ou know how to calm restless spirits by giving them <br>a proper greeting when their soul is freed. Y ou are not <br>affected by the Boundless Rage Gift. Receive 1 Additional <br>Success when defending against beings that are animated <br>or controlled by spirits or magic.<br>A True Friend <br>Requirement: Gain Carlo’s trust despite all his lies.<br>Carlo understands that he can trust you and will run to <br>your aid if you need it. Y ou can spend 1 Soma to have Carlo <br>appear in the Scene as your NPC ally. Carlo will use the <br>power of his lies to help you to the best of his ability.<br>The Field of Miracles (Special Gift for The Fox <br>and the Cat)<br>Requirement: Arrive in Sinalunga.<br>Y ou know Sinalunga well because it is where one of your <br>secret shelters is located. Once per Scene you can spend 1 <br>Soma so you or another subject can leave the Scene and <br>hide in the Field of Miracles. No one can find the exact <br>location of the shelter. When you are at the Field, once per <br>Session you can recover 1 Wound you have suffered.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":14100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"3qQSX2yNiS4BRNhd","name":"Pagina 142","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 142</h2><p>2<br>1<br>3a<br>141<br>The Scenario of <br>Flesh and Wood in <br>Scenes <br>FIRST SCENE - Arrival In <br>Sinalunga <br>It’s the same one you find on page 132.<br>Information: <br> ◆ Speaking with Vincenzo or the citizens, the Hunters <br>will discover that Villa Cilesterino is a place considered <br>cursed. <br> ◆ They’ll also discover that the well where the corpses <br>were found is located on the edge of the same estate as <br>the villa.<br>End of Scene:  The Hunters leave in the direction of the <br>old well to better understand what happened. If they want, <br>Vincenzo will accompany them. Go to SECOND SCENE - <br>The Old Well.<br>SECOND SCENE - The Old <br>Well<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  You find the old well after a <br>ten-minute walk from the town. On the nearby hill, the old, <br>shabby silhouette of Villa Cilesterino looms over you like a <br>dark shadow. The boards that closed the well are uprooted and <br>are now just laying across the top. The stench of death still <br>lingers in the air, still strong enough that it cannot be ignored.<br>Location: The old well on the edge of the Cilesterino estate. <br>Time: The sun is now setting and it won’t be light for much <br>longer.<br>Information: <br> ◆ By descending into the well, the Hunters will find <br>Geppetto’s chisel. <br> ◆ Around the well there are traces of people which then <br>lead towards the abandoned villa.<br>End of Scene:  The Hunters can decide to investigate the <br>Old Carpenter’s Shop from which the chisel surely comes <br>(THIRD SCENE OPTION A - At The Old Carpenter’s Shop) <br>or follow the tracks to Villa Cilesterino (THIRD SCENE <br>OPTION B - Villa Cilesterino).<br>THIRD SCENE OPTION A - <br>At The Old Carpenter’s Shop<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  From the outside, the <br>workshop seems abandoned. A large sign outside sways, blown <br>by the wind. It reads “Mastro Antonio Ciliegia, Carpenter. ” <br>Apparently what they told you in the town is true. It seems <br>that Antonio has left and closed up his business. <br>Place: Mastro Antonio’s carpenter’s shop, a well-kept place <br>that, on the inside, does not seem abandoned at all.<br>Time: It is night now and no inhabitants of Sinalunga <br>wander the streets. The shutters in the windows flutter as <br>prying eyes stare at the Hunters.<br>Information: <br> ◆ Upon entering the Old Carpenter’s Shop, the Hunters <br>will come across the Marionettes on guard. Once the</p>","markdown":""},"sort":14200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"x4obz7IertstPCdL","name":"Pagina 143","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 143</h2><p>43b<br>142<br>clash is resolved, the Hunters will be able to verify that <br>the chisel found in the well is just what is missing from <br>the wall rack. <br> ◆ A school bag full of old books attracts their attention. <br>Among other things, they find an unsent letter <br>requesting enrollment for a boy named Carlo.<br>End of Scene:  Hunters can go to Villa Cilesterino <br>(THIRD SCENE OPTION B - Villa Cilesterino) or wait for <br>the morning to go to FOURTH SCENE - The School.<br>THIRD SCENE OPTION B - <br>Villa Cilesterino<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: As soon as you step into the <br>large garden of the abandoned villa you realize that what was <br>once a magnificent garden is now nothing more than a thick <br>mass of scrub and weathered stone statues. Your attention, <br>however, is attracted by a bestial verse, which materializes in <br>the grotesque figure of a bear, but one without fur, the hairless <br>skin pocked by who knows what disease. The creature sniffs <br>the air. After spotting you, it starts charging. <br>Time: It is night and a cloud-veiled moon illuminates the <br>old marble statues in the garden with a gloomy glow.<br>Information: <br> ◆ Medoro lashes out at the Hunters. Azzurra will <br>intervene at the end of the battle to ask the Hunters to <br>spare the unfortunate creature she uses as a guardian. <br>Then, she will show them the Marionettes in the <br>garden, saying that in the town someone is carrying out <br>atrocious experiments on the townsfolk. Azzurra will <br>tell the Hunters that everything started with a small <br>puppet animated by dark magic. Azzurra will ask for <br>the Hunters’ help. They should bring back the puppet <br>who hides among the townspeople pretending to be a <br>real child named Carlo. Once captured and brought <br>before her, Azzurra will use her power to banish the <br>evil spirit that animates him.<br> ◆ Azzurra’s intention is to deceive the Hunters, in the <br>hope that they will bring her little Carlo.<br>End of Scene: Hunters can also go to the Old Carpenter’s <br>Shop in search of clues (THIRD SCENE OPTION A - At <br>The Old Carpenter’s Shop) or wait for the morning to go to <br>FOURTH SCENE - The School if they have already obtained <br>the clues from the carpentry. <br>FOURTH SCENE - The School<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  The small school of <br>Sinalunga welcomes no more than thirty students. A young <br>teacher with the typical Florentine accent yells and gestures <br>in a vain attempt to get the unruly young scholars to settle <br>down. But children run everywhere like ferrets, ignoring the <br>disconsolate man’s calls. <br>Information: <br> ◆ Watching the children play, the Hunters will notice <br>that one of them has no school bag or books with him. <br>If asked about it, the teacher will say that the pupil is <br>called Carlo and that he is an orphan who comes to <br>school but has never been officially enrolled. The man <br>is not sure where he lives and what he does outside of <br>school.<br> ◆ If a Hunter knows magic, they will sense that there is <br>something strange about the child.<br> ◆ Carlo, sure of his disguise, plays with his friend Lucino, <br>but as soon as the Hunters corner him he will try to <br>escape using the power of his lies.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":14300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"OzPoR0gR8AJara9n","name":"Pagina 144","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 144</h2><p>5<br>143<br> ◆ Once captured, Carlo will reveal the whole truth to <br>the Hunters. The Puppet doesn’t know about Azzurra <br>but will speak of Geppetto and Antonio as two <br>unscrupulous killers.<br>End of Scene:  The Hunters have managed to capture <br>Carlo. Whether they decide to believe him or not, it is clear <br>that Villa Cilesterino is hiding a secret. Go to the FIFTH <br>SCENE - Return to the Villa.<br>FIFTH SCENE - Return to the <br>Villa<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  When you arrive at the <br>Villa you perceive a strange tension in the air. The weeds that <br>had swallowed the garden are uprooted as if displaced by a <br>supernatural force that has created a path for you. The door <br>of the mansion is wide open, while from the broken windows, <br>the dim light of the candelabra suggests that some kind of <br>welcome is awaiting you.<br>Location: Villa Cilesterino and the Secret Laboratory in <br>the basement, where Antonio and Geppetto carry out their <br>grim experiments.<br>Time: It is just past noon, but the sky is full of clouds, <br>giving a gloomy atmosphere to the abandoned villa.<br>Information: At this point, the story can go in two <br>distinct directions.<br> ◆ If the Hunters trust Azzurra, the spirit will hand over <br>Carlo to Antonio and Geppetto. The two will take <br>refuge in the basement dragging the weeping puppet <br>with them. At this point, Azzurra will order the <br>Hunters to leave. If not listened to, she will try to get rid <br>of them with the help of the Marionettes and Medoro, <br>if it’s still alive.<br> ◆ If the Hunters believe Carlo, Azzurra will try to kill <br>them in order to capture the puppet but will not <br>hesitate to flee if the situation turns for the worse. <br>Antonio and Geppetto, abandoned by their mistress, <br>will take refuge in the Secret Laboratory, trying to put <br>up a last resistance to the Hunters.<br>End of Scene:  However it goes, the Hunters will have <br>Carlo’s fate in their hands and somehow, they will shed light <br>on the disappearances that took place in Sinalunga.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":14400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"sjLX0UlEfv4vPEUy","name":"Pagina 145","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 145</h2><p>144<br>The Smile in <br>the Darkness<br>Once upon a <br>time…<br>The Hunters are sent to Paris, where someone <br>has been setting fires in the city’s slums for <br>weeks. At first, some assumed the radicals and <br>agitators opposing the monarchy were to blame. <br>However, many of the fires’ victims have been <br>the poor and desperate living beneath the city <br>in the catacombs, suggesting a different cause <br>and drawing the interest of the Order. Father <br>Adrien, a humble servant of the Church in the <br>city, has reported rumors that speak of the eerie <br>laughter of children and glimpses of strange, <br>dark presences. Hidden in the shadows, these <br>entities grab all those who have a soul to lose...<br>A Scenario inspired by The Little Match Girl (Hans Christian Andersen)<br>Safety Keywords: Murder / Revenge / Corpses / Religion / Burning Flesh</p>","markdown":""},"sort":14500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"KnMmFaeeL3NVNE9x","name":"Pagina 146","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 146</h2><p>145<br>The story that led us here…<br>Yvonne was a ragged, little orphan who sold <br>candles as a way of surviving on the streets. The girl was <br>scorned by all, even by the poor of the city who had always <br>considered her only to be a burden. Little Yvonne found <br>compassion only in Father Adrien, a young priest who <br>had always offered her a helping hand and a warm shelter <br>from the cold Parisian winter. Unfortunately, one evening <br>Yvonne discovered the laboratory where Adrien distills <br>absinthe. The man, his sin discovered, strangled the girl <br>into unconsciousness. To hide his deed, Adrien set the little <br>girl on fire and threw her remains in the catacombs. What <br>was found the following day was a small, charred body with <br>only one part left intact: the teeth, shining white and locked <br>in a deathly grin. Many poor people in the city who depend <br>on Adrien for a few pennies worth of work witnessed the <br>scene, but they kept quiet so as not to lose the priest’s favor. <br>Thrown into a mass grave without ceremony, Yvonne was <br>reborn the following night as a spirit. Her vengeful ghost <br>now wanders in the darkness of The Catacombs of Paris, <br>where she torments those who were silent at her murder <br>with maddening laughter and vicious whispers. When <br>her quarry sparks a light to discover who is hiding in the <br>darkness, the spirit feeds the flame to set the victim afire. <br>Yvonne is slowly burning alive all those who know her <br>murderer and yet say nothing, one by one, saving Adrien <br>for her grand finale.<br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunters…<br>Yvonne is carrying out her revenge with methodical <br>determination, killing one person every night. Only a <br>young man named Olivier has escaped her attention and <br>then she can pour out all her hatred on Adrien. If left  <br>unchecked, Yvonne plans to burn all of Paris, igniting the <br>Cemetery of the Innocents, full of rotting flesh and slime <br>from the corpses crammed inside. With the wisdom of the <br>dead, Yvonne knows she will only be able to satisfy her need <br>for revenge during the passage of a comet called Morituris. <br>With the comet’s passage, the souls of the unquiet dead <br>will fill with mystical energy, which Yvonne will be able to <br>channel into an inferno. The passage of the long-tailed star <br>is scheduled for December 31, coincidentally the day the <br>Hunters arrive in Paris. Adrien understands that something <br>fearsome and dark is pursuing his flock of followers, which <br>is why he wrote to the Order. The priest is sure that it all <br>has to do with Yvonne’s death, as every night he dreams <br>and relives the moment he set the child on fire, before the <br>vision widens to reveal the whole of Paris burning. Olivier, <br>a barely eighteen-year-old boy in Adrien’s service, saw his <br>companion Thierry be burnt alive after Yvonne’s spirit <br>began to seek revenge. The young man confided in Adrien <br>but quickly realized that the priest would do nothing for <br>him. He is now desperately trying to leave the city in a <br>hurry. Olivier doesn’t know that he is the next one on <br>Yvonne’s list…<br>A historical note: The Catacombs of Paris were born as <br>gypsum and clay quarries and only began to be used as a <br>sepulcher starting in 1788. In our story, the government of <br>Paris has already begun to work out future plans for the <br>catacombs and this name has already spread among the <br>citizens of Paris. It is worth noting also that, in reality, the <br>Cemetery of the Innocents was closed in 1780 and emptied <br>in 1786.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":14600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241721,"modifiedTime":1783973241721,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"g9ZST8zDAKKcQSGN","name":"Pagina 147","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 147</h2><p>1<br>146<br>First Scene<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: Our story begins in the small <br>church of Saint Pierre, where Father Adrien welcomes you <br>tiredly. The young priest has been in the service of the city <br>of Paris for just over a year, but already wrinkles caused by <br>worry and stress are starting to show. Adrien has the swollen <br>eyes of someone who hasn’t slept for days and his fatigue is <br>obvious as he guides you into the small sacristy. “You have <br>finally arrived, Hunters. A hidden presence lurks beneath the <br>whole city and I fear there is no hope of salvation without the <br>intervention of the Order... ”<br>Place: The small church of Saint Pierre, one of the oldest <br>in the city.<br>Time: It is late afternoon and the Hunters have arrived <br>after a long journey.<br>Initial Situation:  Adrien will tell the Hunters that he <br>fears an evil spirit is haunting the catacombs. Many beggars <br>have been found burned alive. And, while in the wealthier <br>parts of the city not a finger is raised for the lowest of society, <br>Adrien has always welcomed and cared for them, and he <br>cannot allow this to go on. From interviewing the young <br>priest, the Hunters will learn the following information:<br> ◆ The denizens of the catacombs insist a spirit wanders <br>beneath the city, where many of the poor and desperate <br>sleep in the absence of a roof over their heads. The <br>presence manifests itself only at night, first with a <br>childish laugh and then by whispering in the shadows.<br> ◆ A certain Lorenzo Scannapecore settled in the city <br>cemetery. Lorenzo is an Italian doctor very famous for <br>his unorthodox practices on corpses and who is said <br>to be able to speak with the dead. Lorenzo was hired <br>by the cemetery manager to investigate strange noises <br>coming from the mass graves.<br> ◆ Adrien will be careful not to mention little Yvonne and <br>the fact that she was the first victim to be found.<br>The Church <br>Descriptor: One of the oldest churches in Paris. An old <br>passage directly connects the cellars where Adrien has his <br>workshop to the catacombs.<br>Information: The church is not well maintained, but <br>welcoming. In the basement, there is a large cellar that <br>Adrien has adapted into his laboratory. The smell of <br>absinthe is clearly recognizable to anyone who has the <br>slightest knowledge of distillation as soon as they set foot <br>in the laboratory. A heavy trap door connects the cellars to <br>the catacombs and from there Adrien passes his loads of <br>absinthe to his henchmen.<br>Father Adrien<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds) <br>Descriptor: I am a young priest who chose to take holy <br>vows to avoid a life of struggle. I am a scholar of alchemy and <br>distillation, but I do not shy away from the pleasures of life. <br>Agenda: Accumulate wealth through absinthe smuggling <br>and then flee across the ocean to rebuild my life in the new <br>world.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":14700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241722,"modifiedTime":1783973241722,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"giy8wq9ykvsoVetM","name":"Pagina 148","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 148</h2><p>147<br>The Catacombs<br>Descriptor: A series of tunnels and galleries that extends <br>under most of Paris. Over time, they have become a refuge <br>for the poor and homeless.<br>Gift - A Tunnel for Everywhere:  Using the <br>catacombs, it is possible to reach many places in <br>the city through hidden openings or old buildings. <br>A Hunter who has a minimum of familiarity with <br>the place (that is, who has visited at least 1 of the <br>6 places presented below) can make a Position <br>Check against an OL Medium 5 to arrive at a <br>specific place in the city.<br>The catacombs are divided into environ-<br>ments that the Hunters can explore. Y ou <br>can roll a die to see where they arrive or <br>simply decide the place when needed.<br>1 - The Dormitories:  A <br>series of tunnels and galleries that make <br>up an old gypsum and clay quarry. <br>Connected to one of the city’s squares, <br>poor and homeless people take refuge <br>here to have a roof over their heads. By <br>exploring the dormitories it is possible <br>to gather some information:<br> ◆ In the catacombs, there are <br>many scoundrels who engage in <br>smuggling and illicit commerce. It <br>is quite easy, especially at night, to <br>come across one of these groups.<br> ◆ Spirits roam the catacombs, though <br>by the grace of God and with a <br>little luck, they rarely trouble good <br>folks. Recently, several burned bodies have been found <br>in the catacombs and for this reason, those who feel <br>they are being followed by a strange presence prefer to <br>douse torches and other flames.<br>The poor people of Paris<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are the poor and desperate who have <br>no other home but the catacombs.<br>When the Hunters interact with the poor, you can <br>decide or roll a die to learn their history and what <br>information they can give.<br>1. Marie lost all her children and her husband to <br>the war. She had grown fond of little Yvonne and <br>weeps for the end she met.<br>2. Claude is a soldier who lost a leg in the war. <br>He wanted to go into business with the Ravens <br>who live in the east side of the catacombs, but <br>they are all young and arrogant and have <br>turned down his offer.<br>3. Brigitte is a little girl who lost her parents <br>during the most recent plague. She knew <br>Yvonne and occasionally went to sell candles <br>with her. She knows that Adrien had taken <br>Yvonne into his service to do small jobs in the <br>sacristy.<br>4. Jerome is an old man who has almost <br>completely lost his sight. In the past, he was <br>a skilled goldsmith, until his blindness left <br>him without a job. He will say that he heard</p>","markdown":""},"sort":14800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241722,"modifiedTime":1783973241722,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"NLguF9dsOyu0nJe1","name":"Pagina 149","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 149</h2><p>148<br>the Ravens boast about the profits they made thanks <br>to an important customer. Their mysterious employer <br>is someone who will never be suspected and who can <br>therefore provide goods in defiance of any authority.<br>5. Bernadette is a youth who witnessed a murder and <br>is now wanted. She fears that the killer wants to make <br>her disappear and shut her mouth for good. The young <br>woman will tell of having encountered a strange <br>presence in the catacombs. In terror, Bernadette threw <br>her torch to the ground and fled into the darkness.<br>6. Bruno is an arrogant street boy, but he knows the <br>catacombs like the back of his hand. He’ll boast that he <br>can get anywhere, but he wants to get paid for it.<br>2 - Yvonne’s Alcove: A small stone alcove with <br>a bed of straw and rags. An old vase of withered flowers <br>indicates that no one has been using it for some time. If the <br>Hunters ask around, a poor old woman will tell them that <br>a foundling named Yvonne slept there. The girl hasn’t been <br>back for more than a week.<br>3 - The Tunnels: It’s easy to get lost in <br>the maze of intricate tunnels.<br>Threat OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: A dense network of tunnels <br>that all look alike.<br>Getting lost in the Tunnels will force <br>the Hunters to waste several hours <br>before finding the exit.<br>4 - The Ravens’ Hideout:  This part of <br>the catacombs is only frequented by scoundrels who had <br>business with Adrien. A couple of broken bottles of absinthe <br>are scattered among some makeshift beds. To those with a <br>sensitive sense of smell, the scent of alcohol is still strong. <br>An old dagger and a wooden crucifix are the only other <br>noteworthy details.<br>Information: If the Hunters arrive here before sunset, they <br>will find Olivier preparing his escape. When night falls, they <br>will find his charred corpse.<br>Olivier the Raven on the run<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I’m a thug always looking to fill my pockets with <br>coin, no matter how dirty the job.<br>Agenda: Collect the money I have hidden in the catacombs <br>and flee far from Paris before the fire spirit finds me.<br>5 - The Burns: Scattered through various tunnels, <br>large patches of ash indicate where the bodies of the burned-<br>alive victims were found. Under the ashes of Yvonne’s, it is <br>possible to find a small candle, miraculously untouched by <br>the flames. During the day, Yvonne remains near the place <br>where she burned, sadly absorbed in the memory of her <br>death.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":14900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241722,"modifiedTime":1783973241722,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"VFfhGpTuCzgpwrnJ","name":"Pagina 150","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 150</h2><p>149<br>Yvonne the Spirit who Longs for <br>Revenge<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a restless spirit who can manipulate fire.<br>Agenda: Get revenge on Adrien and all those who ignored <br>my death / Set Paris ablaze with the fires of the dead.<br>Gift - Spirit:  Yvonne is in a spirit form and can only <br>truly be damaged by magic. The touch of a Spirit absorbs <br>life energy and inflicts 1 Wound. Physical protection <br>and barriers cannot help against this Gift. If the Spirit <br>is harmed by non-magical means, she still will suffer a <br>Wound. However, when Yvonne has no Wounds left, she <br>disappears and rematerializes immediately. In doing so, all <br>her Wounds are healed, except those inflicted by magical <br>means. Once per Scene, Yvonne can call 3 Restless Spirits <br>to her who will obey her will.<br>Gift - Soul of Fire:  Yvonne can manipulate fire at will. <br>This Gift only affects a fire that is already lit. Manipulating <br>fire, for Yvonne, is considered an additional action. The fire <br>inflicts 1 Wound and if the Defense Check is an Outcome <br>with a Cost, the target will continue to burn. During the <br>following Exchange, if not put out, the fire will inflict <br>1 additional Wound. Thanks to her power, Yvonne can <br>multiply the width and size of a flame by up to ten times.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":15000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241722,"modifiedTime":1783973241722,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Eeja0aCsxBjY3SRQ","name":"Pagina 151","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 151</h2><p>150<br>6 - The Halls of the Spirits: In the most <br>central part of the catacombs there is a great concentration <br>of restless souls, who will not hesitate to target the living.<br>Restless spirits<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are restless souls and yearn for the essence <br>of the living.<br>Agenda: We sense Yvonne’s wrath, driving us to prey on the <br>living.<br>Gift - Spirit: This NPC is in a spirit form and can only be <br>damaged by magic. The touch of a Spirit absorbs life energy <br>and inflicts 1 Wound. Physical protection and barriers <br>cannot help against this Gift. If the Spirit is harmed by <br>non-magical means, it still will suffer a Wound. However, <br>when the Spirit has no Wounds left, it disappears and <br>rematerializes immediately. In doing so, all its Wounds are <br>healed, except those inflicted by magical means. <br>Information: If a Hunter communicates with Spirits <br>through the Gift Voice of the Spirits, they will be able to <br>learn of Yvonne’s presence.<br>The Cemetery<br>Descriptor: The great cemetery of Paris, protected by <br>high walls and well-maintained thanks to the work of many <br>custodians. Strange noises and a strong smell of death come <br>from the mass graves.<br>Information: The cemetery is currently under the control <br>of Lorenzo Scannapecore, an Italian doctor hired by the city <br>of Paris to manage the excessive number of corpses inside <br>the mass graves. Lorenzo has sent the cemetery keepers <br>away with the excuse of requiring quiet for his studies. <br>However, that was only a ruse to secretly host Alizée, a nun <br>he has fallen in love with and whom he keeps safe from the <br>severe judgment of the Church. Lorenzo’s intent is to wait <br>until the new year to embark with his beloved towards the <br>New World.<br> ◆ Speaking with Lorenzo, the Hunters can learn about <br>the dire state of the mass graves of the cemetery, which <br>in fact is about to explode due to the excessive number <br>of decaying corpses. Lorenzo will appear strangely <br>nervous, looking wary. The man fears that the Hunters <br>may discover Alizée hidden among the tombstones.<br> ◆ Lorenzo is also a good astrologer and will be able to tell <br>the Hunters about the passage of Morituris and how, <br>according to the legend, this gives power to the spirits.<br> ◆ Alizée will observe the Hunters from behind some <br>tombstones, trying not to be discovered. However, she <br>will always remain nearby, ready to intervene to help <br>her beloved.<br> ◆ Alizée will try not to reveal her abilities. When cornered, <br>she may report that the spirits are very agitated, both <br>due to the presence of a very powerful and hateful <br>spirit among them, and due to the imminent passage <br>of the comet.<br> ◆ Strange smells and noises come from the mass graves. <br>Lorenzo will say that it is the dead bodies generating</p>","markdown":""},"sort":15100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241722,"modifiedTime":1783973241722,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"oTXBckrbLIwTdI6Y","name":"Pagina 152","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 152</h2><p>151<br>gas during decomposition. By opening one of the large <br>hatches, it is possible to access the underground pit.<br> ◆ Lorenzo has all the keys to open the hatches to access the <br>underground pit.<br>Lorenzo Scannapecore the <br>Plague Doctor<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled plague doctor. My attention to <br>detail is obsessive.<br>Agenda: Pretend to work in the cemetery to protect Alizée <br>from prying eyes.<br>Alizée the Fugitive<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a young nun who repudiated her vows out <br>of love. I have always been able to see spirits, though my ability <br>sometimes scares me.<br>Agenda: Escape with Lorenzo to a place where we don’t need <br>to fear the Church’s punishment.<br>Gift - Spiritualist:  Alizée can see and communicate with <br>spirits. If anyone has been in contact with spirits in the past <br>twenty-four hours, Alizée will sense the remaining spirit <br>energy. With each use of this Gift, the young woman can <br>obtain a single piece of information about the spirit aura she <br>has perceived. The Spiritualist Gift can also be used to remove <br>a Grudge Token from the Gift Mass of Restless Spirits.<br>The Underground Pit<br>Descriptor: A huge pit where the corpses of all those who <br>cannot afford a burial are thrown. Crowds of restless spirits <br>throng among the inert bodies, invisible to mundane eyes.<br>Gift - Mass of Restless Spirits:  The pit accumulates <br>spiritual energy thanks to the passage of the comet Morituris. <br>At the beginning of each Scene, there are 2 Grudge Tokens <br>in the pit. An NPC with the Gift Spirit, Alizée with the Gift  <br>Spiritualist, or a Hunter with a Descriptor associated with <br>magic or spirits, can use their action to add or remove 1 <br>Token from the mass. If at midnight on December 31st there <br>are 3 Tokens in the pit, all the accumulated energy will cause <br>a powerful explosion capable of wiping out half of Paris. <br>The passage of the comet will add 1 Token at the stroke of <br>midnight. There can never be more than 4 Grudge Tokens on <br>this Gift.<br>Threat - Grudge of the Dead<br>Descriptor: We are the spirits of those who are dead and <br>forgotten by all. We hate the living and their life energy, and we <br>attack anyone who dares to approach the underground pit.<br>OL Hard 7<br>Gift - Chorus of the Dead: A powerful spirit cacophony that <br>only those who perceive spirits or understand magic can hear. <br>For everyone else, the chorus is nothing more than a terrible, <br>overwhelming feeling that prompts you to walk away. Anyone <br>wishing to act in the area where the choir can be heard will <br>lose 1 Soma for each minute staying under its influence. If <br>they do not have Soma, a subject will suffer a Wound until <br>they faint. A Defense Check can shelter a subject for 1 minute <br>from the effect of this Gift.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":15200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241722,"modifiedTime":1783973241722,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"GdZO2YFmy2dmUOyO","name":"Pagina 153","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 153</h2><p>152<br>Scenario Gifts<br>These Gifts represent special abilities related to the Smile <br>in the Darkness Scenario and can be acquired once the <br>requirements are met. A Hunter can only have one Scenario <br>Gift and if they acquire a new one, they will have to forgo <br>the previous one.<br>Voice of the Spirits<br>Requirement: You have been in contact with either the <br>Spirit or Spiritualist Gifts.<br>With the right peace and focus, you can open your mind <br>to the spirit world and communicate with restless souls. <br>Spend 1 Soma to contact any creature with the Spirit Gift  <br>that you’ve previously encountered. Y ou can communicate <br>with the Spirit and understand what it says.<br>Exorcist<br>Requirement: Have a Church or Magic-related Descriptor. <br>Talk to Adrien or Alizée about practices used against Spirits.<br>Y ou have learned how to use your skills against the Spirits. <br>All your actions can affect a target who has the Spirit Gift  <br>and all Wounds you inflict cannot be ignored by the Spirit <br>Gift.<br>Scenario Events<br>In this Scenario, there are eight Events. As a Storyteller, feel <br>free to create new ones in response to the actions of the <br>Hunters.<br>If the Hunters encounter Olivier in the catacombs <br>before night falls:  Yvonne will arrive before the <br>scoundrel opens his mouth to try and silence him by taking <br>her revenge.<br>If the Hunters talk to more than two poor people <br>in the catacombs: Yvonne will notice their presence and <br>will come to spy on them, trying to stay hidden.<br>If Olivier is not found before sunset:  news of a new <br>charred body will spread in the catacombs shortly after 10 <br>pm.<br>If Olivier is saved by the Hunters:   he will tell of a <br>strange presence that has killed his companions. The <br>scoundrel won’t make mention of his connections with <br>Adrien and Yvonne unless put under pressure in some way.<br>If Adrien is confronted with his faults:   he will <br>collapse in tears and ask for forgiveness. At this point, <br>he will reveal the recurring dream in which he sees Paris <br>burning on New Y ear’s Eve.<br>If the Hunters attempt to mediate with Yvonne:  the <br>spirit will be willing to give up blowing up the graveyard, <br>but not her revenge on Adrien.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":15300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241722,"modifiedTime":1783973241722,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"UuLXc8ZDGHxNN4UB","name":"Pagina 154","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 154</h2><p>1<br>2 3<br>153<br>The Scenario <br>The Smile in the <br>Darkness in Scenes<br>FIRST SCENE – Father Adrien<br>It’s the same one you find on page 146.<br>End of Scene: Adrien will suggest to the Hunters to speak <br>to Lorenzo Scannapecore, as he is an expert on the dead <br>and ghosts. The doctor lives in the cemetery in Paris. Go to <br>SECOND SCENE - The Cemetery.<br>SECOND SCENE – The <br>Cemetery<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  The Cemetery of the <br>Innocents stretches as far as the eyes can see and is probably <br>one of the largest you have ever seen. As you wander through <br>tombstones and family mausoleums, a black-cloaked figure <br>is busy fumbling among the tombs. The typical beak mask <br>identifies him as a plague doctor. The figure had been <br>occupied exhuming a grave, but now he puts down his shovel <br>and approaches you.<br>Place: The great cemetery of Paris.<br>Time: It is late afternoon and the winter wind whistles <br>through the corridors of the cemetery.<br>Information: Lorenzo will prove helpful to the Hunters, <br>while Alizée will keep watch from behind a noble’s large <br>tomb. Lorenzo will be visibly nervous, however, often <br>looking over his shoulder at her. It’s simple to deduce that <br>someone is hiding nearby.<br> ◆ Having discovered Alizée, the Hunters will know <br>from her that the spirits are restless, due partly to the <br>passage of the comet, but above all from the presence <br>of a particularly angry spirit in the catacombs.<br> ◆ Lorenzo will confirm the passage of the comet <br>Morituris and how it charges the spiritual world with <br>energy.<br> ◆ Towards the end of the interview, Father Adrien will <br>arrive to warn the Hunters that another charred corpse <br>has been found in the catacombs.<br>End of Scene:  The Hunters rush to the <br>catacombs to find out what happened. Go to <br>THIRD SCENE - The Catacombs.<br>THIRD SCENE – The <br>Catacombs<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  You go <br>down in The Catacombs of Paris and what <br>you see is a maze of narrow tunnels that <br>open onto small chambers and dark alcoves. <br>The stale smell mixes with the stench of <br>unwashed, desperate people crowded into <br>the narrow spaces. Apparently, those who <br>do not have a roof over their head can find a <br>shadow of comfort under the city, effectively <br>disappearing from the sight and conscience of <br>“respectable” people.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":15400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241722,"modifiedTime":1783973241722,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Yy9GAtwhzOzxhHej","name":"Pagina 155","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 155</h2><p>4a<br>154<br>Place: The Catacombs of Paris.<br>Time: The sun has set and in the streets, the last workers <br>hurry to return to their homes. <br>Information: The Hunters explore the catacombs until <br>reaching the place where Olivier was found. The body is still <br>there, along with an intense burning smell. The expression <br>of sheer terror is still discernible on his charred features. If <br>the Hunters have Alizée with them, the woman will sense <br>Yvonne’s presence. Either way, the spirit will attack the <br>Hunters with the support of 3 Restless Spirits. Yvonne’s goal <br>is to drive the Hunters out of the catacombs.<br> ◆ Regardless of how the fight ends, the Hunters will be <br>approached by Marie, who witnessed the scene. The <br>woman will reveal that the spirit is little Yvonne, a <br>foundling who lived by selling candles Father Adrien <br>had given her. The little girl has been missing for more <br>than a week and Marie was convinced she had gone to <br>stay with Adrien, given the charming, almost paternal <br>relationship that was forged between the two. It will <br>be clear to the Hunters that Adrien has not told the <br>whole truth, but at the same moment, a roar from the <br>graveyard will cause the earth to shake.  <br>End of Scene:  The Hunters can go find Adrien at the <br>church (FOURTH SCENE OPTION A - Confession ) <br>or head to the cemetery to find the source of the roar <br>(FOURTH SCENE OPTION B - Return to the Cemetery).<br>Note: Given the obvious emergency of both situations, <br>advise the Hunters to split up to deal with both Scenes.<br> <br>FOURTH SCENE OPTION <br>A – The Confession<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: You arrive at the church <br>looking for answers when Adrien’s cry breaches the <br>stillness of the night. When you open the door, the priest is <br>kneeling in the center of the aisle, his face covered in tears <br>as he whispers, “Forgive me, please forgive me for what I <br>have done. ” In front of him, the spirit of the little girl you <br>faced in the catacombs floats ominously, while behind her, <br>the flames of the offering candles swell until they become <br>tongues of fire.<br>Place: Father Adrien’s church.<br>Time: It is almost midnight on December 31st and it is <br>possible to observe the passing comet, Morituris, in the <br>sky outside the church.<br>Information: Yvonne intends to kill Adrien. If <br>stopped by the Hunters, she will inform them that in <br>less than an hour the cemetery will explode thanks to <br>the anger of the spirits she has stirred up.<br> ◆ Cornered, Adrien will confess to what he did to <br>Yvonne and to his involvement in the absinthe <br>trade. The priest, however, will try to distract the <br>Hunters with the knowledge that now the little girl <br>is a spirit full of anger and, in fact, a hostile creature <br>of the sort that the Order would hunt down.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":15500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241722,"modifiedTime":1783973241722,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"xhplMAdOJtlPALPm","name":"Pagina 156","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 156</h2><p>4b<br>5<br>155<br> ◆ Adrien will try to escape through the secret passage <br>in the cellar if he has the opportunity. The man is <br>absolutely not sorry for what he did.<br> ◆ Yvonne will be willing to help the Hunters if they don’t <br>interfere with her revenge and allow her to deal with <br>Adrien.<br>End of Scene: The Hunters must run to the graveyard to <br>avert the explosion. Go to the FIFTH SCENE - The Fire of <br>Revenge.<br>FOURTH SCENE OPTION B <br>– Return to the Cemetery<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  You hurry back to the <br>cemetery and find Lorenzo passed out on the ground. When <br>he wakes, the doctor tells you that the reinforced trap doors of <br>the mass graves all exploded in unison, and now Alizée feels a <br>spirit force beyond comprehension. If something is not done, <br>the consequences for the city will be catastrophic.<br>Place: The Cemetery of the Innocents.<br>Time: It is almost midnight on December 31st and it is <br>possible to observe the passing comet Morituris in the sky.<br>Information: Hunters will have to approach the pit to <br>quell the Mass of Restless Spirits. After having retrieved <br>at least 1 Token (with Alizée’s help, if they have no other <br>resources), the Hunters will be aware that, until the comet’s <br>passage is complete, the graveyard is a potential bomb. <br>End of Scene:  When the Hunters reduce the Grudge <br>Tokens to zero, go to the FIFTH SCENE - The Fire of <br>Revenge.<br>FIFTH SCENE –  The Fire of <br>Revenge<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  A long and heart-breaking <br>lament rises from the mass graves, deep enough to make your <br>skin crawl. Apparently, the dead have no intention of resting <br>forever.<br>Place: The Cemetery of Paris.<br>Time: The stroke of midnight on December 31st. In the <br>sky, the comet Morituris is as bright as a small sun.<br>Information: This Scene has two possible developments.<br> ◆ If the Hunters haven’t faced the FOURTH SCENE <br>OPTION A - Confession , Yvonne will appear in the <br>center of the mass grave with Adrien. The spirit intends <br>to throw the priest to the spirits and thus activate <br>the explosion of the cemetery. Yvonne will face the <br>Hunters backed by 4 Restless Spirits. If during the fight <br>the Grudge Tokens reach 3, there will be an explosion. <br> ◆ If the Hunters have Yvonne’s support, the pit spirits will <br>rebel against their own mistress. 9 Restless Spirits will <br>appear in the graveyard to face off against the Hunters <br>and Yvonne. During each Exchange, 1 Spirit will use its <br>action to add 1 Grudge Token.<br>End of Scene:  It will be time for the Hunters to judge <br>Adrien (if still alive) and decide what to do with little <br>Yvonne, condemned to eternal unlife.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":15600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241722,"modifiedTime":1783973241722,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"t51guOpEMrwiydaN","name":"Pagina 157","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 157</h2><p>156<br>A Soldier’s Duty<br>Once upon a <br>time…<br>The Hunters arrive in Borgholm, on the <br>beautiful island of Oland. The Hunters’ <br>intervention is ordered by the Papacy after <br>a request from the Riksråd, the great council <br>of the kingdom of Sweden. A former soldier <br>and war hero named Nils, also called the <br>Poor Devil, has sent a letter to the council, <br>imploring them to help him and his former <br>comrades. Six valiant soldiers were all that <br>remained of their company after the bloody <br>war between Sweden and Russia. Now, they <br>are being killed one by one by a monster that <br>seems able to take a bullet without batting an <br>eye. Two of the comrades have already fallen <br>to the monster’s fury. Those that still live <br>have barricaded themselves in the mansion <br>of their one-time commander, Andersen, who <br>now leads them in defense of their own lives <br>and those of his family.<br>A Scenario inspired by The Steadfast Tin Soldier <br>(Hans Christian Andersen)<br>Safety Keywords:<br>  <br>Rape / Revenge / Murder</p>","markdown":""},"sort":15700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241722,"modifiedTime":1783973241722,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ptj6JiyoLlc7B2K9","name":"Pagina 158","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 158</h2><p>157<br>The story that led us here…<br>Six years earlier, a company of Carolean soldiers was <br>stationed in Vaasa, a small town on the Finnish coast. Here <br>Private Enar fell in love with Satu, a young and beautiful <br>dancer. Enar deserted to remain near his beloved but was <br>discovered by his comrades. They judged him a sinner <br>according to the strict religious discipline of the Caroleans.<br>Led by Captain Andersen, the soldiers punished Enar by <br>cutting off his leg and throwing him into the sea. But in <br>reality, the true reason for Andersen’s ferocity arose from <br>the fact that the officer too had fallen in love with Satu and, <br>mad with jealousy, had punished Enar far beyond what the <br>rules dictated. After Enar’s execution, unknown even to his <br>own men, the Captain tried to romance Satu, who rejected <br>him. Unable to accept that refusal, Andersen raped her and <br>as a result of that terrible act, the girl became pregnant. <br>Six years later, the company disbanded and Andersen, a <br>wealthy war hero, paid his underlings handsomely to keep <br>the secret of Enar’s death. Having retired to private life, over <br>time, Andersen grew to regret his deplorable behavior. He <br>sought out the dancer and, after regaining contact with her, <br>discovered with great shame the existence of his son, Erik. <br>Ravaged by guilt for what he had done, Andersen managed <br>to earn Satu’s grudging forgiveness after months of effort. <br>He freed her from a life of hardship as an assistant cook and <br>took her with him to his mansion, together with his son. <br>But Enar’s fate did not end beneath the sea waves. Love for <br>Satu soon turned into blind hatred for Andersen and his <br>former comrades. Below the waves, Enar remained alive for <br>a long time while the fish slowly devoured his flesh. Of the <br>soldier’s body, only the heart was spared and, as it fell into <br>the abyss, it attracted the attention of a Sea Fairy. The Fairy <br>took pity on him and, seeing that heart so wounded, infused <br>it with new life. Enar’s body slowly began to regenerate, but <br>the young soldier’s mind was now lost. All the accumulated <br>hatred and resentment had driven him insane. Worse, in <br>the process of his rebirth, the soldier’s body began to absorb <br>everything it found. Algae, shells, and timbers from an old <br>wreck fused to his limbs, making him an immortal monster <br>bound to the world only by an infinite grudge...<br>Six years have passed, and Andersen managed to get closer <br>to Satu, who is now at least accepting him. At the same <br>time, Enar’s heart has started beating again. Now that his <br>greatest enemy, Andersen, has found something he truly <br>loves and would not want to lose, Enar is ready to return to <br>take it away from him.<br>Appearing every day an hour after sunset, Enar began his <br>personal war by killing his fellow soldiers, one by one, in a <br>heinous fashion. Six survived the war, and two have already <br>been murdered, with one gutted and another burned alive <br>after being flayed. Andersen soon understood the nature of <br>the threat and brought Hans and Christian, his remaining <br>former companions, to his mansion. Only Nils was not <br>called, being unable to move due to his war wounds. The <br>Poor Devil has many friends, however, and has gathered <br>information from his home in Sundsvall.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":15800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241722,"modifiedTime":1783973241722,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"TJPl2gPrQKOMoSWX","name":"Pagina 159","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 159</h2><p>1<br>158<br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunters…<br>Enar is completely insane and fully intent on killing all his <br>former comrades, only to finally “merge” into one being <br>with his beloved Satu. Nils in his heart sensed that the <br>killer is Enar and, seized by a sense of guilt, he summoned <br>the Order to try and stop his former comrade in arms. <br>Andersen has found happiness with Satu and Erik, and <br>despite the shame he feels for what he has done in the past, <br>he is absolutely determined to destroy the revived Enar to <br>secure a future with his new family.<br>Satu has guessed who the monstrous being that appears <br>every night really is, but fear makes her hide from Enar’s <br>gaze. The woman now wants nothing more than the best <br>for her child, even to the detriment of her own happiness, <br>even if it means accepting a life alongside the one who took <br>away her true love six years earlier.<br>On this sad stage, all the actors have something to hide <br>while Enar represents the truth that, inescapably, will <br>destroy the wall of lies built with care by Andersen and his <br>men.<br>First Scene<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: It is late afternoon when you <br>finally see the mansion of Andersen Olsson, the war veteran <br>who, according to the letters they’ve received, is the victim of <br>an attack by a monstrous creature. You notice immediately <br>that the mansion has been fortified. A wrought iron fence <br>and main gate, reinforced and strengthened by barricades, <br>form an improvised wall around the grounds. A smaller gate <br>that allows access to the garden has been bent in a way that <br>suggests some very violent force has acted there, knocking it <br>down and warping its hinges. A rudimentary watchtower <br>has been built in a large oak that rises beyond the makeshift  <br>palisades and, from the top, a figure beckons to you with his <br>hand before descending to the ground and running to meet <br>you. He wears a soldier’s uniform, and with every step, a <br>saber clatters in the scabbard at his side. The man arrives <br>at the gate with a grim and serious expression, asking who <br>goes there.<br>Place: Andersen’s large mansion just outside the town of <br>Borgholm.<br>Time: It is late afternoon and the sun begins its slow <br>descent. The salty air that comes from the sea teases the <br>nostrils.<br>Initial Situation: The soldier who welcomes the Hunters <br>is Christian, who will not allow the Hunters to enter the <br>estate without first understanding who they are. As soon <br>as it becomes clear they belong to the Order, Christian will <br>call Andersen to let him handle the situation.<br>Information: During the Scene, Andersen will make <br>no secret of his disappointment at seeing the Hunters. By <br>talking to him you can learn the following information.<br> ◆ Andersen disapproves of the fact that Nils sent a letter <br>to the Order. The creature attacking his property yearns <br>to take revenge on his men. The identities of the first <br>two victims, his former comrades-in-arms Jacob and <br>Wilhelm, were enough to convince him of that.<br> ◆ Andersen has called the survivors to him to deal with <br>this new threat, which he is sure is connected to the <br>many deaths his company caused during the war. <br>Andersen will make no secret of the fact that he and <br>his men had their souls soaked in so much blood they <br>were stained crimson. The monster is able to travel</p>","markdown":""},"sort":15900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241722,"modifiedTime":1783973241722,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"hZhNt2ay5qvwDn1B","name":"Pagina 160","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 160</h2><p>159<br>great distances since the first two victims lived many <br>days’ travel from each other. That’s why Andersen has <br>gathered everyone on his estate to join forces.<br> ◆ Although Andersen despises Nils because he has <br>always been a coward, he has sent Hans to keep him <br>safe, as the Poor Devil has lost his legs in battle and is <br>unable to travel. Nils lives a day’s drive from the estate <br>in the village of Sundsvall and Hans left a few hours <br>before the Hunters arrived.<br> ◆ Andersen is a soldier and if the Hunters insist, he will <br>reluctantly welcome them into his home, respecting <br>the authority of the Order.<br>Note: This Scenario uses Events as timers for story <br>development. For this reason, the Storyteller must keep in <br>mind some factors.<br> ◆ There are only 3 places (the Andersen Estate, the town <br>of Sundsvall, and the cliff) that make up an equilateral <br>“triangle” . Moving from one place to another always <br>takes 1 day of travel on foot. <br> ◆ Some Events have an indicative day number in which <br>they occur: 1st day, 2nd day, and so on. In this way, <br>the Storyteller will always know where Enar will be and <br>who he will try to strike.<br> ◆ Since the action always occurs in two places at the same <br>time, the Storyteller must point out that all the former <br>soldiers are in danger, and that this mission requires <br>action on multiple fronts. For this reason, splitting <br>the Hunters into two groups is encouraged. However, <br>it is not an essential condition and the final decision <br>regarding what to do will always be up to the Players.<br> ◆ For better management of Events, given their <br>importance, they are shown below instead of at the end <br>of the Scenario as usual.<br>Scenario Events<br>In this Scenario, there are eight Events. As Storyteller feel <br>free to create new ones in response to the actions of the <br>Hunters.<br>Day 1:  Enar will attack Andersen’s estate shortly after <br>sunset. If the Hunters are not present, Christian will be <br>killed.<br>Day 1: Hans arrives in Sundsvall to interrogate Nils, who <br>will no longer be willing to keep quiet about Enar’s murder. <br>If the Hunters are not present, the soldier will kill the Poor <br>Devil.<br>Day 2: Enar will arrive after sunset in Sundsvall to punish <br>Nils. If the latter is already dead, then he will find Hans <br>ready to ambush him. If the Hunters are not present, <br>Hans will die. If Nils is alive, however, Enar will attempt to <br>eliminate him unless the Hunters do something to prevent <br>it.<br>Day 2: Erik will recognize the shells that have fallen from <br>Enar’s body as those present on the cliff. If the Hunters <br>are present, Andersen will invite them to investigate. <br>Otherwise he will send Christian, who will be eliminated <br>by the Sea Fairy. <br>Day 3: Enar will arrive at the estate after sunset to eliminate <br>Andersen and possibly Christian. Once this is done, he will <br>try to reach Satu.<br>If Erik is put in danger:  Both Andersen and Satu will <br>put their lives at risk for him. Both are willing to confess if <br>this can save the child from danger.<br>If Enar discovers that Erik is Andersen’s son: The <br>child will become his new target, as killing him is the best <br>way to make Andersen feel the pain he has inflicted.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":16000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"yOrO5ZaYNUJDPu1m","name":"Pagina 161","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 161</h2><p>160<br>If the Hunters convince the Sea Fairy of their good <br>intentions: The Fairy will lead one of them to the bottom <br>of the sea where Enar’s heart is.<br>Andersen’s Estate<br>Descriptor: A large, lush estate ten minutes from the city <br>center.<br>Wandering around the estate, the Hunters may encounter <br>one or more of these NPCs. Roll a die:<br>1-2 Satu: With a sad and depressed air, the woman will try <br>to avoid any interaction with the Hunters. Her shy demeanor <br>will make it clear that something is bothering her.<br>3-4 Erik: Intrigued by the Hunters, he will approach them <br>brimming with questions. He is a lively child, and it will soon <br>become clear to the Hunters that he is not fully aware of the <br>danger he is in.<br>5-6 Adam the Chatty Servant:  A young man in his 20s <br>who can’t escape to the city, as he works on the estate to <br>pay off a debt to Andersen. Adam will speak without much <br>hesitation about the fact that there is a complex relationship <br>between his master and Satu, and that the woman comes <br>from the past of the former commander. Adam will add that <br>Andersen is also very considerate of Erik and it becomes <br>clear that he regards the boy as a son.<br>Information: Over twenty servants work on the estate, <br>but few are capable of wielding a weapon. The whole defense <br>rests on the shoulders of Andersen and Christian. It will be <br>clear to the Hunters, however, that Andersen’s abilities as a <br>commander allow him to keep everything under control and <br>to bring out the best even from inexperienced servants.<br>After the first encounter with Enar, Erik will recognize the <br>shells he collected when he lived with his mother in a small <br>cliffside village. According to some old stories, under the cliff <br>there is a dense network of caves where a Sea Fairy is said to <br>reside.<br>Andersen<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a war veteran with strong leadership skills. <br>In addition to being a good leader, I am also a capable fighter.<br>Agenda: Defend my new family from the danger that Enar <br>represents / Redeem myself in the eyes of Satu and make her <br>understand that I am now a different man / Prevent anyone <br>from discovering what I have done.<br>Gift - Commander:  Andersen is skilled at giving orders <br>and managing a battle. Up to 3 times per Scene, Andersen <br>can issue an order to an ally who will receive 1 Additional <br>Success (+1 to OL in the case of an NPC) while executing it.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":16100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"FqsRGmzzz6MCiWfj","name":"Pagina 162","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 162</h2><p>161<br>Satu<br>OL Easy 3 – Main NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a former dancer who has lost everything. <br>I am but a shadow of my former self.<br>Agenda: Defend my son Erik, the only reason that I keep <br>going.<br>Erik<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a lively child who can never sit still. <br>Agenda: Understand who Andersen really is, and why he <br>took my mom and me out of the misery we lived in.<br>Christian<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a former soldier, called the Relentless <br>by all because of my cold determination. I act without any <br>qualms when it comes to executing an order.<br>Agenda: Help Andersen in memory of the old days and a <br>military life I can’t forget / Eliminate Enar to prove I am the <br>better man.<br>Gift - The Relentless: When he is carrying out an order, <br>Christian is immune to any effect that affects his behavior, <br>such as fear or charm. The soldier increases his Opposition <br>Level by 1 when he tries to eliminate an obstacle that stands <br>between him and the subject of an order he must carry out.<br>Enar<br>OL Hard 7 – Main NPC (4 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an immortal being, the result of all the <br>hatred I harbored in my exile into the abyss. I have the <br>strength of five men and my body feels no pain.<br>Agenda: Take revenge on Andersen, but not before I have <br>eliminated all my former companions / After eliminating <br>Andersen and his people, I want to meld with Satu so that <br>our bodies and souls are united for eternity.<br>Gift - The Eternal Soldier:  Enar’s body is the result of <br>powerful magic tainted by hatred. When Enar suffers his <br>final Wound, his body becomes seawater and soaks into <br>the ground. The following day, Enar completely regenerates <br>himself at the bottom of the sea, where his heart is, the very <br>focus of his existence. Only by recovering the heart and <br>destroying it can Enar be permanently eliminated. <br>Gift - Rage of the Sea:  Thanks to the magic granted by <br>the Sea Fairy, Enar has gained powers. When he acts, he <br>can always choose an additional effect. 1. Algae Whip: A <br>string of algae stretches from Enar’s body and can perform <br>a second independent action. 2. Wave:  Enar’s body <br>becomes seawater for a few moments, allowing him to slip <br>away and cover a distance of 30 feet before regrouping. <br>3. Shells: 3 large seashells are shot from Enar’s body in <br>different directions, which should be considered 3 attacks <br>with OL Medium 5. The shells must be aimed at 3 different <br>targets.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":16200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"RKizz2bEFZyTRPls","name":"Pagina 163","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 163</h2><p>162<br>The Cliff<br>Descriptor: A steep cliff overlooking <br>the sea, riddled with many inlets. In <br>the most inaccessible part, there are <br>entrances that lead to underground <br>caves.<br>Going down the cliff, it is possible to <br>arrive at the caves’ entrance. In the <br>center of the tunnel network, there is a <br>pool where the Sea Fairy lives. Getting <br>to the pool may require you to deal <br>with one or more of these Threats. <br>Roll a die:<br>1-2 Landslide:  As they descend <br>along the cliffs, part of the rock path <br>collapses under the Hunters’ feet. <br>Descriptor: A sudden landslide. OL <br>Hard 7. <br>In the landslide, a Hunter can suffer <br>1 Wound or lose some of their <br>equipment to the sea.<br>3-4 Submerged tunnel:  To get <br>to the central pool you need to swim <br>through a narrow tunnel. <br>Descriptor: A long, narrow <br>submerged tunnel. OL Medium 5. <br>Failing the Check means not being <br>able to make it through the tunnel <br>successfully and returning to the <br>entrance.<br>5-6 Hook’s Crew: A dozen pirates <br>died here after a shipwreck and now <br>their souls are demanding vengeance <br>on the living.<br>Dead Pirates<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC  <br>(1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a lost soul who only <br>wishes for revenge on those who are still <br>alive. My body is a heap of swollen and <br>rotten flesh that moves slowly.<br>Special agenda (James the <br>Swordsman): We recognize James <br>as the one who killed our captain in <br>a duel! It is his fault that our ship was <br>wrecked, and we will taste his flesh <br>first!<br>Gift - Walking Dead:  The body <br>of the Dead Pirate is rotten and <br>putrescent, but it does not stop even if <br>dismembered. After suffering his only <br>Wound, a Dead Pirate can still take his <br>action before being eliminated, if he <br>has not already done so in the course <br>of the Exchange. If a Dead Pirate acts <br>against an outnumbered enemy, his <br>Opposition Level is increased by 1.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":16300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"rraHO8v9XM8SxRSL","name":"Pagina 164","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 164</h2><p>163<br>Sea Fairy<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a fairy of the sea and my magic allows me to <br>perform true miracles. My entire existence is tied to the sea and <br>leaving it would destroy me.<br>Agenda: I am sad because Enar has forsaken the love that kept <br>him alive in favor of blind hatred. I would like to do something <br>for him, but I cannot go to the mainland to stop his fury or find <br>his beloved.<br>Special Agenda (Marina the Sea Explorer):  I have <br>heard of Marina and know her reputation. She uses her powers <br>only to enrich herself at the expense of others. I will never agree <br>to help her unless she first shows me that she is also capable of <br>good deeds.<br>Gift – Sea Magic:  The Sea Fairy can always use one of <br>the following effects.  1. Water of Life:  A target recovers 1 <br>Wound and, if they have been dead for no more than a day, <br>they can even come back to life.  2. The Fury of the Sea:  <br>The water of the sea engulfs everything, sweeping away all <br>threats. Those who are within 30 feet must pass a Defense <br>Check against OL Hard 7 to avoid being overwhelmed by <br>the waves and being washed away, suffering 1 Wound. The <br>Sea Fairy can deliberately avoid hitting anyone in the area of <br>effect.  3. The Waves of the Sea: The Sea Fairy can travel to <br>any point of the sea within 6 miles. This shift is instantaneous, <br>and if she wants, the Fairy can take up to 2 subjects with her.<br>Sundsvall<br>Descriptor: A small coastal town, where the tranquillity of the <br>sea provides peace and serenity.<br>Information: It’s easy to find old Nils just by wandering <br>around the town. The Poor Devil has invested himself in <br>the community by donating part of his wealth to the <br>neediest, and he is well regarded by all in town. In Nils’ <br>house rests a diary where the former soldier wrote <br>down everything that happened six years earlier. From <br>the Poor Devil’s memories, it is possible to reconstruct <br>Enar’s identity and his relationship with Satu, but not <br>that Erik is Andersen’s son. The abuse perpetrated by <br>the officer was never discovered by his comrades in <br>arms. However, it will be clear from the writings that <br>the punishment reserved for Enar was beyond reason.<br>Nils the Poor Devil<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an old soldier who lost his legs <br>in the war.<br>Agenda: The guilt for what we did to Enar <br>haunts me, I want to find a way to bring him <br>peace.<br>Hans<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC  <br>(4 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a former soldier, once one <br>of the company’s best marksmen. I never miss <br>my mark and always have a loaded weapon <br>hidden under my heavy overcoat.<br>Agenda: Convince Nils to keep our <br>secret or remove him.<br>Gift - Gunslinger:  Hans owns a <br>pair of prized experimental pistols, <br>which he bought from an inventor</p>","markdown":""},"sort":16400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"7zQUMFDpLGBINYpr","name":"Pagina 165","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 165</h2><p>164<br>for more than half of his war earnings. <br>Hans’s guns can fire multiple shots <br>at the same time and with one attack, <br>the soldier can aim at 3 targets that are <br>within an area of 30 feet square. While <br>firing one pistol, Hans can reload the <br>other as an additional action. When <br>he draws a pistol from under his coat, <br>Hans can make an attack with OL Hard <br>7.  <br>Gift - Smoke Bombs:  Hans has <br>some smoke bombs, which he uses <br>to surprise the enemy. While firing <br>a pistol, Hans can drop a bomb as an <br>additional action. The thick smoke <br>will cover an area of 30 feet square and <br>inside it, everyone receives 1 Penalty <br>for every action that requires the use of <br>sight, except for Hans, who is immune <br>to the effect. Additionally, he can always <br>get away from opponents who engage <br>him without anyone preventing him.<br>Scenario Gifts<br>These Gifts represent special abilities <br>related to the A Soldier’s Duty <br>Scenario and can be acquired once the <br>requirements are met. A Hunter can <br>only have one Scenario Gift and if they <br>acquire a new one, they will have to <br>forgo the previous one.<br>Blessing of the Sea<br>Requirement: Prove to the Sea Fairy <br>your intention to do something for poor <br>Enar.<br>Y ou are blessed by the mighty Sea <br>Fairy and therefore sea-related abilities <br>have no effect on you. Y ou receive 2 <br>Additional Successes on each Defense <br>Check you make to defend yourself <br>against a Gift, spell, or action made <br>using a Descriptor that includes the <br>word sea. <br>Art of Command<br>Requirement: Withstand an on -<br>slaught from Enar by fighting alongside <br>Andersen.<br>Y ou’ve observed a good leader and <br>figured out how to hone your strategies. <br>Once per Scene, you can give an <br>order to one of your allies and if they <br>try to carry it out, they will receive 2 <br>Additional Successes to any Check.<br>Coral of the Sea Fairy <br>(Special gift for Marina <br>the Sea Explorer)<br>Requirement: To kill the Sea Fairy.<br>Y ou dispatched that hateful fairy and <br>harnessed her soul in a lump of coral. <br>Now her power is yours. Y ou can use 1 <br>Treasure Token to unlock this Gift for <br>the duration of the Scenario. Spend <br>1 Soma to tap into the Coral’s power <br>and choose one of the following effects.   <br>1. Water of Life:  A target recovers <br>1 Wound.  2. The Fury of the Sea:  <br>The water of the sea engulfs everything, <br>sweeping away all threats. Those who <br>are within 30 feet must pass a Defense <br>Check against OL Hard 7 to avoid be-<br>ing overwhelmed by the waves and be-<br>ing thrown away, suffering 1 Wound.   <br>3. The Waves of the Sea:  Y ou can <br>travel to any point of the sea within 6 <br>miles. This shift is instantaneous and <br>you can take up to 2 subjects with you.<br>Sea creatures sense what you have done <br>and will attack you without hesitation <br>to try to free the soul of the Fairy.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":16500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"gbLaD8RisvUkwJmC","name":"Pagina 166","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 166</h2><p>1<br>2a<br>165<br>The Scenario <br>A Soldier’s <br>Duty in Scenes<br>FIRST SCENE – The Arrival at <br>the Estate<br>It’s the same one you find on page 158.<br>End of Scene:  After talking to Andersen, the Hunters <br>have a rough understanding of the situation. Given the <br>danger on several fronts, Andersen will ask half of the <br>Hunters to stay at the estate (SECOND SCENE OPTION <br>A - The Defense) and the other half to travel to Sundsvall to <br>help Hans protect Nils (SECOND SCENE OPTION B - The <br>Poor Devil).<br>SECOND SCENE OPTION A <br>– The Defense<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  The sun has just set, while <br>servants are nailing a last few planks across the windows <br>on the first floor. What should be a luxurious mansion <br>increasingly resembles a fortress under siege. Andersen and <br>Christian take the last few puffs on a pipe while setting up <br>their rifles, a ritual that probably formed during the days <br>they fought side-by-side on real battlefields. Then the pungent <br>smell of burnt tobacco fades, covered by that of salt and rotten <br>fish. A figure stands at the entrance to the garden, huge and <br>ungainly. It is a colossus of pale flesh, driftwood, rocks, shells, <br>and other debris from the sea. The being stares at the large <br>mansion for a moment, before roaring out its rage.<br>Place: Andersen’s fortified mansion.<br>Time: It is night, but a high moon and a cloudless sky <br>allow for good visibility.<br>Information: <br> ◆ Enar will attack without hesitation, ignoring any <br>mediation attempts by the Hunters. However, it will be <br>clear that Enar understands what he is told but simply <br>ignores it.<br> ◆ Andersen will give his best as a leader, using his <br>Commander Gift to lend a hand to the Hunters.<br> ◆ When Enar is left with 2 Wounds, little Erik will enter <br>the scene. Sneaking out of the mansion to get a better <br>look, he will find himself in the middle of the battle. <br>Satu will arrive soon after and the Hunters will be able <br>to observe the reactions of Enar and Andersen.<br> ◆ Enar will understand from their actions that Erik is the <br>couple’s son. When he does, he will roar in anger and <br>try to unleash his rage on the child.<br> ◆ When Enar is defeated, his body will fall apart, and <br>Erik will recognize some particular shells he has always <br>seen at the cliff.<br>End of Scene: Erik recognizes the cliff shells, which could <br>be a good clue to find out where Enar resides. Go to the <br>THIRD SCENE OPTION A - The Cliff.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":16600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"dzyUMKp10u6WpAog","name":"Pagina 167","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 167</h2><p>2b<br>3a<br>166<br>SECOND SCENE OPTION B – <br>The Poor Devil<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  Sundsvall is a charming <br>seaside town, with colorful houses and smiling people. Here, <br>it really seems that war and suffering have never happened. It <br>is easy to find Nils’ house. Apparently, the former soldier has <br>donated a lot of money to the poor of the city and these, given <br>his handicap, often give him a hand to thank him. When <br>you arrive at the small red brick house, you’re surprised to <br>find the front door open. Did Hans get there before you? The <br>sudden sound of a gunshot does not bode well.<br>Place: Nils the Poor Devil’s little house.<br>Time: It is late afternoon.<br>Information: When the Hunters arrive, Hans is trying <br>to execute Nils after the Poor Devil has expressed his <br>resolution to confess what happened six years ago. Hans <br>is ready to fight to the death against the Hunters while <br>keeping the elimination of Nils as his main goal.<br> ◆ If the Hunters kill Hans and Nils survives, the Poor <br>Devil will tell them everything he knows. From the <br>memories of the Poor Devil, it is possible to reconstruct <br>the identity of Enar and his relationship with Satu, <br>but not that Erik is the son of Andersen. The abuse <br>perpetrated by the officer was never discovered by his <br>comrades in arms. However, it will be clear that the <br>punishment reserved for Enar was beyond measure.<br> ◆ If Nils dies, it will be possible to find out the truth <br>regarding Enar’s punishment by reading his diary.<br> ◆ If Hans is captured, the soldier will not speak even <br>under torture and will try to give the Hunters a hard <br>time.<br>End of Scene:  It is now clear that Andersen is hiding a <br>secret linked to Enar’s revenge. The Hunters must return <br>to the estate, go to SCENE THREE OPTION B - Return to <br>the Estate.<br>THIRD SCENE OPTION A – <br>The Cliff<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  Following the directions <br>of little Erik, you finally reach the coast. The sea is stormy <br>and crashes against a long cliff that acts as a promontory. <br>It doesn’t take long to find what looks like a natural path <br>between the rocks, exactly as Erik described to you.<br>Place: The cliff on the stretch of sea from which Enar <br>emerges.<br>Time: The setting sun is covered with rain clouds.<br>Information: Descending along the cliff will put the <br>Hunters to the test. Select or present in order the Threats on <br>page 162. Once on the bottom, they will be able to meet <br>the Sea Fairy and convince her to stop Enar. The Fairy will <br>reveal that Enar’s heart is darkened by great pain for the <br>injustice he has suffered and that it is safely laying on the <br>bottom of the sea. The Fairy can bring it to the Hunters, but <br>only if they first do justice to the memory of Enar, bringing <br>her Satu so that she can say a last goodbye to Enar’s heart. <br>The woman is Enar’s lost love and it is right that the <br>unfortunate soldier should have a chance to rest in peace.<br>End of Scene:  The Hunters must return to the estate <br>to retrieve Satu and join their other companions. Go to <br>SCENE FOUR - Destinies.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":16700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"0icUXeZlCR8LS5Kn","name":"Pagina 168","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 168</h2><p>3b<br>4<br>167<br>THIRD SCENE OPTION B – <br>Return to the Estate<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: Tired from the long journey, <br>you arrive at Andersen’s estate as the sun goes down. You <br>are determined to untangle this story, but all your intentions <br>collide with a monster’s insane howl. Like every night, the <br>fearsome brute has come to carry out a massacre.<br>Place: Andersen’s Estate, marred by the previous night’s <br>clash.<br>Time: The sun is slowly setting, but the estate remains lit <br>thanks to lanterns expertly positioned by Andersen.<br>Information: As with the previous night, the clash with <br>Enar will be inevitable. With the monster down, the Hunters <br>will be able to ask Andersen why he tried to eliminate Nils. <br>The man will fall to his knees as he tells his entire story, <br>including his abuse of Satu. Wanting Erik to keep both a <br>father and mother, Andersen will ask the Hunters to end <br>Enar’s persecution.<br> ◆ As the Hunters sent to the cliff arrive, Erik will come <br>out of the barricaded mansion crying. Satu fled during <br>the fight, to head to the cliff. The woman reassured her <br>son that the monster will not harm her and that only <br>she can stop his fury.<br>End of Scene: It will be clear to the Hunters that Satu will <br>try to meet Enar at the cliff. Andersen will want to leave <br>immediately and nothing can stop him. Go to SCENE <br>FOUR - Destinies.<br>FOURTH SCENE –  Destinies<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  By the time you get to the <br>cliff, night has fallen. The storm has passed, and a clear and <br>gloomy moon illuminates two figures on the edge of the rocks. <br>One is the graceful silhouette of Satu, the other the huge, <br>grotesque mass of Enar. The two observe each other for a <br>few moments. Then tentacles of seaweed emerge from Enar’s <br>body, reaching out to seize his lost love.<br>Place: The Cliff.<br>Time: It is night, but a clear moonlight illuminates the <br>epilogue of this sad story.<br>Information: Stopping Enar is a priority or he will <br>assimilate Satu by merging with her within the course of <br>one Exchange. The Hunters know that the only way to <br>permanently kill him is to call the Sea Fairy to bring the <br>monster’s heart.<br>End of Scene:  Enar, Satu, and Andersen’s fate will be in <br>the hands of the Hunters</p>","markdown":""},"sort":16800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"g1QNc71sofugmC0j","name":"Pagina 169","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 169</h2><p>168<br>Wonderbedlam<br>Once upon a time…<br>No less than the Duke of Norfolk himself has approached <br>the Order with a request which must remain secret. Five <br>months ago, his daughter Alissa was taken to Wonder, <br>the bedlam of Y ork, the most renowned asylum in all of <br>England. Under the guidance of a mysterious Director, <br>the Duke hoped for the quick recovery of his daughter, <br>who possessed an attitude that was too rebellious and <br>unseemly for a young noblewoman. After the first <br>month, Alissa’s letters to her family became more and <br>more terrified and delusional, until they abruptly <br>ceased. According to Alissa’s words, Wonder is hell on <br>earth, where strange presences move in the dark rooms, <br>animated by an evil will. The Duke’s plea to the Hunters is <br>simple: save Alissa and shed a light on the dark dealings <br>happening in the asylum of Wonder.<br>A Scenario inspired by Alice’s Adventures in Wonderland (Lewis Carroll)<br>Safety Keywords: Mental illness / Imprisonment / Abuse / Cannibalism</p>","markdown":""},"sort":16900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"N4TryHDIeToGFYFf","name":"Pagina 170","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 170</h2><p>169<br>The story that led us here…<br>Alice Liddell, daughter of an English aristocrat <br>in great favor with the Crown, developed a complex <br>mental illness as a child. From an early age, she suffered <br>from visions and delusions about a fantasy world hidden <br>in her dreams.<br>“Treated” in great secrecy by the family with drugs and <br>experimental therapies, Alice has learned to control <br>her madness enough to appear to be as sane as the next <br>person. At the age of twenty-seven, she graduated with <br>a degree in medicine, dedicating herself body and soul <br>to the treatment of mental illness. The culmination of <br>this dazzling career is Wonder, a “hospital” meant to <br>welcome children of wealthy families who want to avoid <br>patronizing one of the infamous asylums of England. <br>Little do they suspect that inside Wonder, Alice has <br>created a world of sheer madness, where unquestioning <br>patients must follow her every perverse idea to the letter, <br>in a physical and mental ordeal that she believes will bring <br>them back to sanity. Alice’s lucid madness has wrung <br>more and more strength from the patients’ suffering, <br>allowing her to shape reality itself. Wonder has become <br>a building out of space and time, where a door might <br>lead you anywhere unless you know the right words. To <br>control Wonder and not fall victim to her own creation, <br>Alice has hired the most skilled inventor in all of England, <br>Hatta Carter, famous for his theories on automatons. The <br>man has thoroughly researched Wonder in an attempt to <br>make sense of the physics-defying nature of the asylum. <br>Thanks to Hatta’s hard work, the structure now responds <br>to Alice’s will, and it has become a place from which it is <br>impossible to escape without the consent of its Director. <br>Thanks to her power, Alice controls a large, trained lynx <br>named Cheshire. By moving through the narrow conduits <br>of the asylum, she acts as the eyes of her mistress.<br> <br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunters…<br>The young Alissa of Norfolk proved incredibly resistant to <br>Alice’s “cures, ” and for this reason the Director of Wonder <br>imprisoned the girl in the Hall of the Mind, disregarding <br>her normal procedure. Day after day, Alice invades <br>Alissa’s mind with nightmares in an attempt to quell her <br>rebellious spirit. Alice manages Wonder completely by <br>herself, taking advantage of her control over the building <br>and rooms, which can only be accessed with the right <br>passwords. Hatta Carter is the only other person able <br>to solve the Wonder puzzle. For this reason, Alice has <br>imprisoned the mad inventor in the bedlam’s Basement, <br>intending to keep him safe for use in future projects. <br>Meanwhile, Alicia, Alissa’s young lover, has infiltrated <br>Wonder in an attempt to free her imprisoned partner. <br>In addition to their romantic bond, Alicia is driven by <br>guilt, convinced that Alissa was sent to Wonder due to <br>the two girls’ relationship. Alissa had even refused several <br>promising marriage proposals to remain with Alicia, <br>indifferent to her duty as the Duke of Norfolk’s heir. <br>Despite her courage and tenacity, Alicia soon became a <br>prisoner of the deranged rooms of Wonder.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":17000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"QuwoP6FT8LLw2Rwk","name":"Pagina 171","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 171</h2><p>1<br>170<br>First Scene<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: You have finally arrived <br>at Wonder, the most famous and renowned bedlam in all <br>of England. What you see, however, is certainly not what <br>one might expect from a place where people are being cured <br>of mental illness. After crossing an immense garden full of <br>dead plants, you find yourself in the entrance hall before an <br>immense, mirrored wall that reflects your perplexed faces. <br>A large, tree-shaped fountain gushes water into a pool full <br>of colorful fish. Three doors on the east wall attract your <br>attention. The central one is of normal size, while the one <br>on the right is twice as large, and the one on the left is <br>barely half the normal size. On the west wall, a painted <br>inscription dominates in large letters: “In this place, <br>madness becomes reason, so that the sick can become <br>healthy again”. Finally, you notice a fourth door that <br>initially escaped your gaze, painted on the floor with <br>such skill as to seem real. While you are wondering <br>who will come to welcome you, a small white rabbit <br>peeps out from behind the large fountain. Around his <br>neck, he wears a small message holder, in which you <br>can see a rolled-up note.<br>Place: The Entrance Hall of Wonder. Hunters <br>will have the strange feeling of not being able to <br>estimate the exact size of the place. <br>Time: It is early in the morning and sunlight <br>filters through the large windows on the west <br>wall, the only ones in the room. Hunters <br>will feel like they can’t tell the exact time. <br>Initial Situation: Thirty minutes have passed since the <br>Hunters arrived and it is becoming clear that no one will <br>come to welcome them. <br>Information: Exploring the Entrance Hall and the <br>exterior of Wonder will yield the following information.<br> ◆ Catching the rabbit will be easy. The animal seems <br>accustomed to the presence of humans and for this <br>reason, it will get close. The message it brings with it is <br>clearly addressed to the Hunters: “You are not welcome <br>at Wonder, as you are not here seeking something <br>but someone. This place welcomes only those who <br>need healing of the mind.” The paper is signed, “The <br>Director” .<br> ◆ The exterior of the asylum looks quite bizarre. <br>From the outside, all the windows on the walls, the <br>doors except the entrance door, and in general every <br>possible entrance to the building, seem real but are <br>just painted. There are therefore no real access points <br>to the building, except the main door leading to the <br>Entrance Hall.<br> ◆ To a Hunter who understands magic through <br>their Descriptors, it will be clear that all of the bedlam <br>is under the influence of a powerful arcane force (see <br>the Place Wonderbedlam on page 171).<br> ◆ The three doors in the east wall open smoothly, <br>all three leading onto a long corridor that ends with <br>another identical door.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":17100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"TjTTCEM1AOC7XaIR","name":"Pagina 172","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 172</h2><p>171<br>The Entrance Hall of Wonder<br>Gift - Beyond the Mirror:  The large wall mirror hides <br>the passage leading to the Hall of the Mind. Only by saying <br>the formula, “Beyond madness, beyond the basement, <br>beyond the mirror, ” is it possible to see the passage. The <br>complete formula is known by Hatta Carter, detained in the <br>Basement.<br>Gift - The Door to The Below:  The door painted on <br>the floor hides the passage to get to the Basement. Just <br>by tapping a foot on the painting and saying the formula, <br>“Is anyone under the house?” or something in that vein <br>you can see the passage. The instructions to open it are <br>contained in the message holders of the White Rabbits all <br>across Wonder.<br>Gift - The Doors to Elsewhere:  The three wall doors <br>each lead to one of the Cure Rooms. When traversing the <br>connecting corridor, the senses are confused and clouded <br>by the magic of Wonder. When you finally open the door <br>at the end of the corridor, you realize you are in another <br>place. Attempting to take something out of the Cure Rooms <br>activates the Gift Place of Pure Madness (see this same <br>page).<br>Cheshire The Faithful Lynx<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a snappy and aggressive lynx. I roam the <br>halls of Wonder guided by the will of my mistress.<br>Gift - Elusive:  Thanks to the power infused in Wonder, <br>Cheshire can disappear and reappear a short distance away, <br>and move through doors and walls. Cheshire can always <br>move without anyone being able to stop her. All actions to <br>attack or capture Cheshire receive 1 Penalty because of the <br>constant appearance and disappearance of the lynx. This <br>Gift is not affected by the Place of Pure Madness Gift.<br>WonderBedlam<br>Descriptor: I am a building animated by sheer madness <br>and no one can attempt to alter me without Alice Liddell’s <br>permission.<br>Gift - Place of Pure Madness:  When a subject <br>attempts an action or uses a Gift to change Wonder’s insane <br>structure (such as breaking through walls or circumventing <br>passageways), the building’s inherent magic activates. <br>Before the action taken is resolved, roll a die to see where <br>the subject will end up being teleported.<br>1-2: The Rabbit Hole. <br>3-4: The Labyrinth of Doors. <br>5-6: The Caterpillars’ Greenhouse.<br>This magical shift causes a side effect that lasts throughout <br>the Scene; roll a die to determine what happens.<br>1-2 Shrunk: The subject receives the Descriptor I am half <br>the size I was, all my physical abilities are diminished as well.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":17200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"zohGdEbTNUk08Jdf","name":"Pagina 173","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 173</h2><p>172<br>3-4 Enlarged: The subject receives the Descriptor I am <br>twice as big as I was and I move awkwardly and slowly.<br>5-6 Confused:  The subject receives the Descriptor My <br>mind is confused, I can’t concentrate, and I misunderstand <br>words when spoken to.<br>The three Cure Rooms<br>Descriptor: Magical places, out of space and time, where <br>patients are thrown to face whatever is troubling their mind.<br>Information: The Rabbit Hole, the Labyrinth of Doors, <br>and the Greenhouse are three places connected by magical <br>corridors to the Entrance Hall of Wonder. Within the various <br>sections of the asylum, the pitiable patients are left to fend for <br>themselves. The main purpose of the rooms is to encourage <br>patients to see “beyond” their madness and understand, <br>through the clues of the White Rabbits, how to access the <br>Basement. Once there, Alice Liddell will pick them up to <br>take them to the Hall of the Mind. Every room will feature <br>the Threat The White Rabbit.<br>Alicia The Young Girl in Love<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a young rebel from the slums who knows <br>how to get by on her own. Thanks to my tenacity, I can <br>overcome every obstacle.<br>Agenda: I want to save Alissa from this cursed place and run <br>away with her to live out our love in peace.<br>Threat - The White Rabbit<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: I’m a little white rabbit wandering around the <br>Cure Rooms and I have a message holder tied around my neck. <br>I fear those I do not know.<br>Gift - Messenger:  By capturing a White Rabbit it is <br>possible to take the message it carries. Roll a die.<br>1-2: It’s not always convenient to knock on a door with your <br>hand. <br>3-4: Knocking on a door is the bare minimum to be <br>expected of a respectable person. <br>5-6: When you arrive at a door, it is polite to ask if anyone <br>is home.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":17300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241723,"modifiedTime":1783973241723,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"otYjc7IyyFrivV97","name":"Pagina 174","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 174</h2><p>173<br>The Patients of Wonder<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are mad and desperate, driven to Wonder <br>in the hope of curing our ailments. Madness guides our <br>actions and we no longer understand that there is a world <br>outside the bedlam.<br>Gift - Why I Am Here: Roll a die to see what problem led <br>them to Wonder.<br>1 Violence: The Patient struggles to contain their anger. <br>When they act violently increase their OL by 1. <br>2 Kleptomania: The Patient yearns for any object they <br>deem interesting and will do everything to have it. Once <br>per Scene, they can act 2 times consecutively, though the <br>additional Action must be used to attempt to escape and <br>hide with the stolen goods.<br>3 Abandoned:  The Patient was interned at Wonder to <br>be forgotten. Hardened by loneliness, they gain 1 extra <br>Wound.<br>4 Split personality: The Patient changes personality in <br>the face of a specific event, such as a threat. When the new <br>personality acts, its OL becomes Hard 7.<br>5 Dementia:  The Patient is not fully aware of what is <br>happening around them. They are immune to all attempts <br>at intimidation. Increase their OL by 1 when defending <br>against a violent action.<br>6 Illness: The Patient is ill or horribly disfigured. Each <br>action against them receives 1 Penalty.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":17400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241724,"modifiedTime":1783973241724,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Wk9yAj14CWxUCRUr","name":"Pagina 175","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 175</h2><p>174<br>Room 1 – The Rabbit Hole<br>Descriptor: A series of burrows and tunnels full of dirt <br>and vegetation. In the small rooms and crevices, naked and <br>emaciated patients move like animals, always looking for <br>something to eat.<br>When the Hunters roam the Rabbit Hole, roll a die.<br>1-2: A group of 1d6 + 3 Patients will approach the Hunters <br>in search of food. <br>3-4: Alicia is busy fending off a group of aggressive <br>Patients. <br>5-6: A White Rabbit passes a few meters from the Hunters.<br>Room 2 – The Labyrinth of <br>Doors<br>Descriptor: An infinite series of rooms, all with doors <br>leading into a long corridor. Each room is decorated in a <br>different and macabre way, recreating situations of torture <br>and stress.<br>When the Hunters roam the Labyrinth of Doors, roll a die. <br>1-2: A group of 1d6 + 3 Patients will approach the Hunters <br>to push them into a room shouting, “We must see what’s <br>beyond!”<br>3-4: Alicia is busy fending off a group of aggressive <br>Patients. <br>5-6: A White Rabbit passes a few meters from the Hunters.<br>Room 3 – The Caterpillars’ <br>Greenhouse<br>Descriptor: A huge greenhouse full of alien and unknown <br>plants. A strong smell of pollen saturates the air, making <br>it difficult to breathe. A dense yellow fog sharply reduces <br>visibility.<br>When the Hunters are roaming the Caterpillars’ <br>Greenhouse, roll a die.<br>1-2: Two Patients are escaping from a Caterpillar of the <br>Wonderful Lands.<br>3-4: Alicia is busy fending off 2 Caterpillars of the <br>Wonderful Lands.<br>5-6: A White Rabbit passes a few meters from the Hunters.<br>Caterpillar of the Wonderful <br>Lands<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a huge carnivorous caterpillar over two <br>meters long. I feed on fresh meat and then lay my eggs in the <br>carcasses of creatures I’ve devoured.<br>Gift - Hunter Caterpillar: When a Caterpillar moves, any <br>human-sized subject in its path risks being overwhelmed. <br>Whoever is in the Caterpillar’s way must perform a <br>Defense Check in order not to end up knocked down. The <br>Caterpillar inflicts 1 Additional Wound against people <br>prone on the ground.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":17500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241724,"modifiedTime":1783973241724,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"VmmY1zrfPcuhcGkv","name":"Pagina 176","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 176</h2><p>175<br>The Basement<br>Descriptor: A huge underground hall filled with food and <br>comfortable cushions to sit on. Unnatural darkness surrounds <br>the room, making it difficult to distinguish the walls.<br>Information: The Basement is the place where Patients <br>arrive when they have figured out how to open the door on <br>the floor of the Entrance Hall. In Alice’s crazy theory, those <br>who arrive underground have understood how to leave <br>behind their issues and psychoses, represented in the Cure <br>Rooms. In the Basement, a Patient can refresh themselves and <br>then be picked up in their sleep and taken to the Hall of the <br>Mind. Hatta Carter is a prisoner in the Basement, kept alive by <br>Alice to be used for future bedlam expansion projects. Hatta <br>has gone mad with loneliness and has built two Automata as <br>pretend tea companions.<br>Hatta Carter The <br>Mad Inventor<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled inventor, the most brilliant of my <br>time. My emotional fragility leads me to frequent mood swings <br>and aggressiveness.<br>Agenda: I want the company of witty people and not cold <br>automata. I long for the chats I had with Alice.<br>Gift - Time Clocks: Hatta can manipulate one of his clocks <br>to influence time.  1. Slow: Once per Scene, Hatta increases <br>his OL by 2 when defending against a threat.  2. Speed <br>Up: Once per Scene, Hatta and one of his Automata can <br>act, immediately stopping anyone’s action regardless of the <br>situation in the narrative. If an Automaton has already acted, <br>it can act again thanks to this Gift.<br>Rabbit Automaton<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC  <br>(2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an automaton in the service of Hatta <br>Carter. Thanks to my strong legs I can make incredible <br>jumps and crush everything when landing.<br>Gift - Leap:  When it acts, the Automaton can free <br>itself from any engagement with ease by jumping away. <br>If it lands on a victim, it increases its OL by 1 for the <br>attack and if it inflicts 1 Wound, the target will also be <br>knocked to the ground.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":17600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241724,"modifiedTime":1783973241724,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"1Z0APc99BN6i9Qfx","name":"Pagina 177","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 177</h2><p>176<br>Lizard Automaton<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an automaton in the service of Hatta <br>Carter. Thanks to my large tail I can perform several actions <br>at the same time.<br>Gift - Tail: The Automaton always acts twice, once with its <br>front legs and once with its long tail, but cannot focus both <br>its actions on the same target.<br>Hall of the Mind<br>Descriptor: A series of rooms painted entirely in white. The <br>doors themselves do not have handles and it takes a careful <br>look to distinguish them from the walls. A large central hall <br>gathers all the Patients, lying on rows of beds, asleep in a state <br>of trance. The distant ticking of a clock breaks an otherwise <br>unnatural silence, creating a hypnotic echo.<br>Information: In the Hall of the Mind, it is possible to <br>find several Patients in a catatonic state, including Alissa <br>of Norfolk. Alice Liddell will not seek a confrontation with <br>any intruders but will be friendly and willing to listen to the <br>unexpected guests. Alice will offer a good tea in which <br>a powerful sleep drug is mixed.<br>Threat - Alice’s special tea<br>OL Hard 7<br>Descriptor: A delicious tea mixed with a powerful <br>soporific.<br>Gift - Sleep: Those who drink the tea and fail their Defense <br>Check will fall into a deep sleep for over eight hours. Only <br>suffering severe pain (equivalent to receiving 1 Wound) or <br>the use of magic can awaken a sleeping subject.<br>Alice Liddell The <br>Director<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am the director of Wonder and, thanks to the <br>power of madness, I can enter people’s minds to heal them.<br>Agenda: Safeguard what I have built within Wonder and <br>all the incredible discoveries that the magic of madness can <br>give to mankind / Solve every problem by transforming it into <br>a Patient to be treated.<br>Gift - Alice from Other Worlds:  As an action, Alice <br>can attempt to possess the body of a person or animal by <br>looking into their eyes. Hunters can make a Defense Check <br>to prevent this. Alice can both act through the body she <br>controls and continue to use her Gifts and Descriptors. <br>The possession ends when Alice’s body suffers 1 Wound. <br>Alice cannot control more than 3 common subjects or a <br>single Hunter at the same time.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":17700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241724,"modifiedTime":1783973241724,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"MbjwtlMTRS2NU9lF","name":"Pagina 178","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 178</h2><p>177<br>Alissa of Norfolk <br>The Rebel<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I have been physically tested by my stay in <br>Wonder, but my mind is still strong. My love for Alicia kept <br>me in the real world.<br>Agenda: Escape from Wonder and my old life and make a <br>future with Alicia.<br>Scenario Events<br>In this Scenario, there are five Events. As a Storyteller, feel <br>free to create new ones in response to the actions of the <br>Hunters.<br>When the Hunters visit the third Cure Room <br>without first meeting Alicia:  they will encounter <br>Alicia, who is lost. The young woman will be reluctant to <br>reveal her true identity but will give her name and introduce <br>herself as a patient.<br>On a regular basis, if the Hunters waste time in the <br>Entrance Hall of Wonder:  one of the bedlam Patients <br>will walk out of one of the three doors into another. The <br>Patient will mumble disjointed words such as “see beyond” <br>or “go under” .<br>If the Hunters cause too much havoc in a Cure <br>Room: Alice will take control of Cheshire and order the <br>Hunters to leave, or try to surprise them by making it clear <br>that they are being watched.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":17800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241724,"modifiedTime":1783973241724,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"NGQxTxd64YT4jwAa","name":"Pagina 179","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 179</h2><p>178<br>If the Hunters try to leave the Basement: a desperate <br>Hatta Carter will attack them with the help of his Automata <br>to keep his new guests with him.<br>If the Hunters corner Alice Liddell:  the Director will <br>be ready to make deals, such as freeing Alissa or whatever <br>the Hunters ask. Alice’s real worry is that Wonder might be <br>destroyed.<br>Scenario Gifts<br>These Gifts represent special abilities related to the <br>Wonderbedlam Scenario and can be acquired once the <br>conditions are met. A Hunter can only acquire one Scenario <br>Gift. If they buy a new one during an Interlude, they will <br>have to forgo the previous one.<br>Friend of the Rabbits<br>Requirement: To have captured at least one White Rabbit.<br>Y ou are able to approach the little white rabbits without <br>frightening them. Receive 2 Additional Successes when you <br>face the Threat The White Rabbit. Once picked up, your <br>new little friends will be able to deliver a message for you to <br>any room in Wonder. This Gift allows you to send a White <br>Rabbit even through seemingly closed doors.<br>Lucid Madness<br>Requirement: Having suffered the Gift Place of Pure <br>Madness at least once.<br>Y ou are slowly figuring out how to make the weirdest ideas <br>real. Y ou can spend 1 Soma to try to activate the mad magic <br>of Wonder. State something crazy that you are capable of, <br>such as I want to walk on walls or I want my arm to stretch <br>out of proportion. The Storyteller will ask you for a Position <br>Check against an OL proportional to the madness of your <br>request. If you succeed, you get the Descriptor you declared <br>for the rest of the Scene; if you fail, you have spent your <br>Soma in vain. The effect of this Gift also ends when someone <br>makes clear that what you are doing is utter madness.<br>The Forgotten Queen (Special Gift for Regina <br>the Thief of Hearts)<br>Requirement: Visit a Cure Room.<br>Confusing flashbacks and painful emotions grip your <br>mind. Y ou’ve been here as a patient before, but maybe <br>you’ve forgotten why. Are you sure you want to remember? <br>Once per Scene, you can try to remember something of <br>your experience in Wonder. Choose a place or a subject <br>from the bedlam, and the Storyteller will give you useful <br>information about a Descriptor, a Gift, or their Agenda. <br>Remembering is painful. For the rest of the Scene, when <br>you use one of your Gifts, roll a die: on a 5 or <br>higher you lose 1 Soma and you <br>are no longer so sure that you are <br>the Queen.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":17900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241724,"modifiedTime":1783973241724,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"UI1FwHD8vMOSl5V1","name":"Pagina 180","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 180</h2><p>1<br>2 3<br>179<br>FIRST SCENE – Arrival in Wonder<br>It’s the same one you find on page 170.<br>End of Scene:  For the Hunters, it will be clear that the <br>only way forward is through one of the three doors to the <br>Cure Rooms.<br>SECOND SCENE – The First Room<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  You walk through a long <br>corridor that leads you in front of a door exactly the same <br>as the one you just went through. As in the Entrance Hall, <br>time seems to flow differently in this place. You have the <br>impression that the few steps necessary to cross between one <br>door and the other takes hours rather than moments. You <br>open the door and what is shown to you...<br>Note: As the Storyteller, continue the description based on <br>the room that was chosen by the Hunters.<br>Place: One of the Cure Rooms.<br>Time: It is impossible to establish the exact time and, <br>from one room to another, day changes to night in a totally <br>random way.<br>Information: The Hunters encounter the result 1-2 of <br>the relevant room. Once the encounter is resolved they will <br>notice a White Rabbit and, by capturing it, they will get the <br>first part of the hint to enter the Basement.<br>End of Scene: It will be clear that each Cure Room holds <br>a clue to progress through Wonder. The Hunters must <br>move to another room. Go to THIRD SCENE – The Second <br>Room, the Encounter with Alicia.<br>THIRD SCENE – The Second <br>Room, the Encounter with Alicia<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  You walk through a long <br>corridor that leads you in front of a door exactly the same <br>as the one you just went through. As in the Entrance Hall, <br>time seems to flow differently in this place and you have the <br>impression that the few steps necessary to cross between one <br>door and the other takes hours rather than moments. You <br>open the door and immediately you are alerted by the cry of <br>a girl.<br>Note: As the Storyteller, continue the description based on <br>the room that was chosen by the Hunters and highlight the <br>presence of Alicia engaged in an encounter, as a result of <br>3-4 of the relevant room.<br>Place: One of the Cure Rooms.<br>Time: It is impossible to establish the exact time and, <br>from one room to another, day changes to night in a totally <br>random way.<br>Information: The Hunters are aware that without their <br>intervention the young woman will succumb. <br> ◆ Once safe, Alicia will introduce herself, saying that <br>she is in Wonder to save a friend from this place of <br>madness. Alicia has two clues with her, one from the <br>The Scenario Wonderbedlam in Scenes</p>","markdown":""},"sort":18000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241724,"modifiedTime":1783973241724,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"jlzmGoZlcsGg0YJU","name":"Pagina 181","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 181</h2><p>4<br>180<br>White Rabbit in this room and one from the one the <br>Hunters have not yet visited. <br> ◆ During the discussion with Alicia, Alice will <br>attack the girl by surprise via Cheshire, and then <br>make the lynx flee through a wall.<br>End of Scene:  It should now be clear to the <br>Hunters how to access the Basement (Alicia can <br>help them if they haven’t quite figured out how to <br>do it yet). Go to FOURTH SCENE - The Basement.<br>FOURTH SCENE –  <br>The Basement<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  When the door <br>opens, you see a large flight of stairs that descend <br>underground. A few minutes later you find yourself in <br>a large room, richly furnished with colored cushions <br>and drapes. The Basement is hard to see across, so <br>much so that you can’t make out the walls. Suddenly, <br>a shrill voice calls for your attention. In front of you, <br>a gentleman with a strange top hat on his head <br>converses amiably with two Automata, one in the <br>form of a large rabbit, the other of a lizard. In a <br>grotesque imitation of teatime, the man with the <br>top hat conducts a one-way conversation, where his <br>words are left unanswered by the cold, unintelligent <br>gazes of the Automata.<br>Place: The Basement of Wonder, where those <br>who have passed the Cure Rooms can rest while <br>waiting to be picked up.<br>Time: It is not possible to distinguish between day <br>and night, but the atmosphere and the soft lighting <br>recall the time for evening tea.<br>Information: Hatta Carter will be delighted to have new <br>guests and will invite the Hunters to join him for tea. By <br>talking to him you can get the following information.<br> ◆ Those who pass through the cycle of therapies in the <br>Cure Rooms can access the Basement where they <br>can refresh themselves, dress again, and wait for the <br>transfer to the Hall of the Mind. The Director keeps <br>Hatta tucked away for future expansions.<br> ◆ Hatta is a prisoner of the Director. He built Wonder <br>and knows the formula for going beyond the mirror, <br>accessing the part of Wonder that is exclusive to the <br>Director. <br> ◆ If the Hunters point out to Hatta that if he knows every <br>secret, he can escape whenever he wishes, the man will <br>nod in amazement, revealing the formula for going <br>beyond the mirror to the Director’s sanctum. Once <br>this is done, however, he will return to his madness, <br>complaining once more about his imprisonment.<br> ◆ Hatta will say that he doesn’t know the Director’s real <br>name, but he knows that she is a renowned doctor and <br>that she is not really a bad person. As a scientist, he <br>understands well that indelicate acts must sometimes <br>be done in the name of scientific progress.<br> ◆ The tablecloth on the table is actually the blueprint of <br>Wonder drawn by Hatta during construction. It reveals <br>the formula for going beyond the mirror. The mad <br>inventor, however, will strongly object if the Hunters <br>try to take the map, as this would ruin the table’s setting <br>for tea.<br>When the Hunters attempt to leave the Basement, Hatta <br>will beg them to stay with him, insisting until he becomes <br>aggressive and unleashes the Automata against the Hunters.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":18100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241724,"modifiedTime":1783973241724,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"pQgpExqKyDRbQ7SE","name":"Pagina 182","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 182</h2><p>5<br>181<br>End of Scene:  After Hatta and his Automata are dealt <br>with, the Hunters know the formula to cross the mirror <br>and finally discover who is behind Wonder. Go to FIFTH <br>SCENE - The Director.<br>FIFTH SCENE –  <br>The Director<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: In front of the large mirror <br>on the north wall, you say the formula “Beyond the madness, <br>beyond the basement, beyond the mirror, ” and you see a <br>small door appear. Crossing through it, you find yourself in <br>a bare and aseptic environment with walls, furniture, and <br>doors, all in white. The doors themselves do not <br>have handles and only with a careful inspection is <br>it possible to distinguish them from the surrounding <br>walls. Finally, you arrive in a huge room, furnished <br>solely with an endless series of beds on which placid <br>patients are sleeping. The distant ticking of a clock <br>breaks an otherwise unnatural silence. Then, a door <br>opens and a distinguished-looking woman with <br>a cold gaze appears in front of you. “Welcome to <br>Wonder. I’m the Director.”<br>Place: The aseptic Hall of the Mind of Wonder.<br>Time: It is not possible to distinguish between day and <br>night, but the atmosphere and the white lights recall a visit <br>to a hospital.<br>Information: Alice will offer her guests a fine cup of tea, <br>trying to put them to sleep. Alternatively, she will try to take <br>control of Alicia and pass her off as Alissa. The Director will <br>claim that Alicia is a second personality Alissa has created <br>inside Wonder to escape from herself. Alice will try not to <br>give the real Alissa to the Hunters, but she won’t be willing <br>to lose Wonder to keep her.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":18200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241724,"modifiedTime":1783973241724,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"WkSGgrdHgVPJyCcI","name":"Pagina 183","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 183</h2><p>182<br>Tuvstarr’s <br>Reflection<br>A Scenario inspired by Tuvstarr <br>(Helge Kjellin) by Petter Nallo<br>Safety Keywords: Decay / Corruption of body and <br>mind / Folk Horror<br>Tuvstarr’s Reflection is a special Scenario built as a Scene Tree (see page 100) and <br>is great for introductory Sessions, one-shots, or to introduce Sherazade the Weaver <br>of Tales to a Campaign. <br>This Scenario takes place within a story told by Sherazade, an emissary of the One <br>who Plots in the Shadows (page 196). The Hunters will awaken in the world of <br>Princess Tuvstarr and must solve the mystery of her disappearance in order to <br>awaken.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":18300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241724,"modifiedTime":1783973241724,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"C1wS2bzSzqVmGd6G","name":"Pagina 184","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 184</h2><p>183<br>Once upon a <br>time…<br>Good evening my dear hosts, my name is <br>Sherazade and I am a weaver of tales. My <br>words will take you to incredible worlds <br>and follow the feats of brave Hunters… <br>however this story is not like the others <br>and these feats are not just imaginary. Will <br>our heroes succeed in their quest? Or will <br>they perish, disappearing forever from the <br>memory of time? <br>The story that led us here…<br>The original fairy tale was written by Helge Kjellin <br>in 1913 and tells how Princess Tuvstarr left her home to <br>follow Skutt the moose into the forest.<br>Tuvstarr does not listen to Skutt’s advice, and so the <br>Fairies steal her crown, the Hulder (a forest spirit) steals <br>her dress and, finally, she loses a golden heart-shaped <br>necklace in a black pond in the depths of the woods. The <br>Princess will stay there staring at the black pond until she <br>turns into a blade of grass: Tuvstarr (Carex Cespitosa).<br>But stories don’t always go as they were originally <br>written... Appalled by the wickedness of the world, <br>Princess Tuvstarr learns from rumors around the court <br>of the existence of a pond, deep in the woods, where <br>wishes can come true. Tuvstarr asks the trusty moose <br>Skutt to lead her through the woods. There, the Princess <br>trades her crown with the Fairies, to gain free access to <br>their lands. <br>Tuvstarr then gives the Hulder her dress to continue <br>her search, and finally arrives at the heart of the forest. <br>There, in the black Pond that no human being has ever <br>seen, she plunges her heart and soul. Tuvstarr desires a <br>perfect world, where everything is bright and good. And <br>that’s what she finds on the other side. A perfect dream <br>world. There she is happy, the fields are always green, and <br>idealized constructs that resemble her mother and father <br>smile at her. But the Dream World needs to balance itself <br>out. And so reality, its mirror, becomes dark and twisted. <br>The sun sets in eternal darkness, the forest is corrupted, <br>animals get sick, and the soil rots.<br>Tuvstarr’s father and mother, the King and Queen, send <br>their knights to bring her back. None of them returns. The <br>lands are becoming increasingly corrupt and the people <br>are desperate. Eventually, the rulers turn to anyone who <br>can help them. This is where our story begins.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":18400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241724,"modifiedTime":1783973241724,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"FlC8emhJkntu18ID","name":"Pagina 185","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 185</h2><p>1<br>184<br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunters…<br>The land is bewitched. The fields are sterile, the church <br>bells are silent, mothers forget to feed their children, and all <br>dreams are dark and full of pain. The sun now rests below <br>the horizon and the lands are covered by eternal twilight. <br>Tuvstarr the Child Princess is gone, wandering into the <br>forest and the curse is believed to have something to do <br>with her disappearance. The knights were sent to the forest, <br>the wetlands, and the wilderness to find her, but none <br>have returned. The King and Queen now seek out new <br>champions to retrieve their daughter from the wilds and <br>end this curse.<br>First Scene<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: Sherazade clears her throat, <br>then smiles at her guests before speaking. “Our story opens <br>with a rude awakening. You are in a strange inn which is <br>certainly not the place where you fell asleep last night. The <br>bedroom door is thrown open violently and a tall, thin man <br>in a soldier’s uniform asks you to follow him out of the room. <br>Apparently, the King and Queen of this strange place await <br>you to give you an audience.  In the midst of a field of withered <br>flowers and rotting crops stands a mighty castle. The walls are <br>covered with ivy and the roofs, once gilded, seem blackened <br>and burned by the rays of a dying, red and menacing sun. ”<br>Place: The royal castle, in the center of a large city. The air <br>is gloomy, and the faces of the people are sad and dejected. <br>A black sky illuminated by a faint crimson light hangs over <br>everything like an eternal night.<br>Time: It is early morning on a gloomy autumn day.<br>Initial Situation:  The Hunters are summoned by the <br>King and Queen for an important mission. They are aware <br>that they are in another world or, perhaps, within a dream.<br>Information:<br> ◆ The King and Queen sit on their thrones staring sternly <br>at the Hunters. They do not speak, but their butler, a <br>lean and hunched old man, will offer the Hunters gold <br>and honors to bring back Princess Tuvstarr. She has <br>fled into the great forest that lies beyond the castle. <br> ◆ Before departure, the old butler will join the Hunters <br>to talk out of the King and Queen’s earshot. He will say <br>that there is a curse upon the land. The Hunters must <br>prepare themselves for the necessity of an extreme act <br>to save the kingdom, perhaps even to kill the Princess <br>herself.<br> ◆ As the Hunters set out for the wild forest, people in <br>the villages will report that many have seen Princess <br>Tuvstarr ride a moose and disappear into the woods. <br>And from that moment, the world has changed.<br>End of Scene:  The Hunters head into the great wild <br>forest in search of Princess Tuvstarr’s trail. Go to SECOND <br>SCENE - The Wild Forest.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":18500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241724,"modifiedTime":1783973241724,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"dbnDv5ClN6Yn5LBX","name":"Pagina 186","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 186</h2><p>185<br>The moose and the moths<br>“He was once a majestic being, the King of the Woods and <br>Wildlands. The name Skutt was given to him by the rocks, <br>torrents, and small streams, as he had the ability to make <br>great leaps through any obstacle. One day, when the sun was <br>bright, he ventured into the fields and flowers near the castle <br>that humans built. There, he met Tuvstarr and was fascinated <br>by the little creature with her white dress, long golden hair <br>and sparkling crown. When Tuvstarr asked him to see the <br>rest of the world, he couldn’t refuse and put her on his back to <br>ride into the wilderness. <br>He told her about the pond in the middle of the woods where <br>all wishes can be fulfilled, but only if the wish is made by <br>an innocent child. And so she asked to go there. During the <br>journey the Princess traded both the crown and the dress for <br>safe passage, and at the pond she disappeared into the black <br>water, leaving only her reflection. Then there was a crack in <br>the sky, which froze the sun in place forever.<br>Not knowing what to do, Skutt wandered the lands in shame. <br>He came across one of the knights sent by the King and Queen. <br>The noble warrior charged the moose with his spear couched <br>under his arm. The moose faced him head-on and killed the <br>armored foe and his steed. But the spear had hit its mark and <br>Skutt fell, dying. However, the power of Tuvstarr’s affection <br>would not allow him to die. The Princess was so anxious that <br>she wished that Skutt could exist forever, even in death. <br>The moose is now rotting. Large worms crawl into his flesh, <br>and in the moonlight, they hatch into ghostly moths that <br>flutter around his horns. His stench is carried by the wind <br>and even carrion-eating birds avoid him. At the time of his <br>death, he forgot his name. But he can’t forget Tuvstarr and <br>the guilt he feels… ”<br>Skutt the Moose<br>OL Hard 7 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a majestic and magnificent moose, <br>ravaged by the decay of death and Tuvstarr’s magic which <br>keeps me alive.<br>Agenda:  I have to find someone to save Tuvstarr from the <br>black pond and the illusion she fell into, because I can’t get in <br>/ Protect Tuvstarr above all else, even if it means having the <br>world rot away.<br>Gift - Spectral Presence:  Skutt cannot truly be <br>eliminated as long as Tuvstarr’s wish keeps him alive. <br>The moose can move through fog, disappearing and <br>reappearing even many feet away. Within the fog, no one <br>can stop or impede Skutt’s movement. When he suffers <br>his third Wound, Skutt falls apart, only to revive in the <br>following Scene.<br>Information: Skutt is a Main NPC that Hunters can <br>encounter in any Scene. He will always appear accompanied <br>by a thick fog, stinking of rot, and surrounded by pale <br>moths. From his horns, like a ghostly veil, hangs the torn <br>fabric of a knightly cloak, and a spear is half driven into <br>his body.<br>If the Hunters fight:  Skutt is not interested in the fight <br>but is still a proud animal, so he will lash out at the enemy, <br>charging with his antlers. <br>If the Hunters talk to Skutt:  He can tell how he took <br>Tuvstarr to the sacred pond, deep in the woods. Whatever <br>Tuvstarr did by diving into the lake, it wreaked havoc on the</p>","markdown":""},"sort":18600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241724,"modifiedTime":1783973241724,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"4MzaltcJZmFa2Rww","name":"Pagina 187","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 187</h2><p>2<br>186<br>world. Skutt wants to save Tuvstarr, but without endangering <br>her. He cannot enter the pond himself, nor can any other <br>inhabitant of these woods.<br>The magic of the pond binds anyone seeking it to make the <br>same journey as the Princess, crossing the places where she <br>exchanged her treasures to continue forward. If the Hunters <br>bring those treasures to him, Skutt will lead them to the <br>pond where Tuvstarr has disappeared.<br>SECOND SCENE – The Wild <br>Forest<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: Sherazade remains silent for <br>a moment, the audience motionless in ecstatic admiration. <br>Then, the Weaver brings a glass of wine to her mouth, though <br>she barely wets her lips. “You travel past the meadow covered <br>with withered flowers, small villages, hills, and streams.  <br>The closer you get to the wilderness and the great forest, the <br>more the atmosphere changes. The woods before you are <br>shrouded in perpetual darkness. Only the faintest light of the <br>sun hanging just beyond the horizon reaches this place. But the <br>sun never really rises, leaving this land enclosed in a twilight <br>and ghostly hour. The creatures of the woods have gone mad. <br>Corrupted by the whispers in the grass, mesmerized by the <br>moon’s reflections, they drink poisonous sap and foam that <br>smells of sulphur. ”<br>Place: The wood that separates the kingdom from the <br>deepest forest is basked in the faintest twilight glow. <br>Time: Time has stopped and no longer has any meaning.<br>Information: When crossing the wood, the Hunters may <br>have some encounters. Roll a die or choose. <br>Note: During this Scene, the Hunters may encounter Skutt.<br>1: A fox is killing and eating its own pups while giving birth <br>to them. <br>2: Two ravens, Hugin and Munin, messengers of Father <br>Odin, approach the Hunters. Even the ancient gods want <br>to stop this disease. If a Hunter approaches the ravens, they <br>will realize they can mentally communicate with them. The <br>ravens want to follow the Hunters. Anyone who makes a <br>pact with them receives the Hugin and Munin Scenario Gift, <br>without the need to have an Interlude.<br>3: Black fumes fill the air, foamy and dense bubbles emerging <br>from a dark pond. A knight in rusty armor lies dead near one <br>of the springs. His eyes are white and puffy, like a sack of eggs <br>ready to burst. The corpse holds an ashwood spear with an <br>iron point. If a Hunter chooses to take the spear, he gains the <br>Lance of the Fallen Knight’ Scenario Gift without the need to <br>have an Interlude.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":18700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"k6uUOIQTmpPF9Uhh","name":"Pagina 188","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 188</h2><p>3a<br>187<br>4: The Troll Stallo sleeps sitting under a tree, and a bird has <br>built a nest in his hair. If he is awakened by too much noise <br>or for any other reason, he will try to eat the Hunters.<br>Stallo<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an old troll and my appetite is <br>matched only by my strength. A bird has made its nest on <br>my head and when it gets angry it starts to peck me in the <br>eye, which is incredibly annoying!<br>Gift – Troll:  Stallo possesses enormous strength and <br>each Position Check for a physical action attempted <br>against him receives 1 Penalty. At the end of each of his <br>actions, Stallo recovers 1 Wound he suffered. When he <br>reaches 0 Wounds, the troll will collapse to the ground, <br>only to regenerate within minutes. <br>5: A saddled warhorse, magnificent and white as fresh <br>snow, is grazing in the tall grass. This mount belonged to <br>one of the knights who met a dire fate in the search for <br>Tuvstarr. The steed will be reluctant to be approached, but <br>if the Hunters succeed (Threat OL Medium 5, Descriptor: <br>I am a fast, mighty, and frightened horse), it will take them <br>to the body of its old master, where the Hunters can retrieve <br>the knightly crest showing a fox with two tails. This crest <br>will be useful when meeting the Gallant Knight (page <br>191).<br>6: A ruined castle on a hill. The castle is the scene of a <br>massacre. The men and women who once lived within its <br>walls have apparently killed each other. Only a ten-year-old <br>girl remains alive, but she is angry and will try to attack the <br>Hunters with a hidden knife.<br>Angry Little Girl<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I survived the adults’ madness and now I <br>struggle like a ferocious animal not to succumb to this <br>cruel world.<br>Agenda: Find a safe place to stay or a group of people <br>ready to accept and protect me.<br>End of Scene:  after one or more encounters (at the <br>discretion of the Storyteller) the Hunters come across <br>the crown of the Fairies (THIRD SCENE OPTION A - <br>The Crown of the Fairies) or the Hulder (THIRD SCENE <br>OPTION B - The Hulder and the white dress).<br>THIRD SCENE OPTION A – <br>The Crown of the Fairies<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: Sherazade smiles at a young <br>nobleman among her audience who has risen from his chair <br>to get a better look at her. She winks at him and says: “Sit <br>down my little guest, now the best is coming. ” <br>“The swamps are shrouded in thin veils of a ghostly mist. All <br>is silent. The moon appears to crack and bleed into the sky, <br>and the faint stars die out one by one as you travel deeper <br>into this nocturnal realm. There is a light in the distance, a <br>glow that is reflected in the swamps and still water. This light <br>comes from a small golden crown, and all around, many <br>silhouettes dance as if enthralled by its light. Fairies look like <br>pale women with long hair. They glide, dance, and writhe in <br>the air as if adrift in an invisible current. They are dreamlike, <br>ethereal, but their bodies meet, touch and brush against each <br>other or, sometimes, through each other. Their eyes are shut</p>","markdown":""},"sort":18800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"TpybxG4dneNMVpGy","name":"Pagina 189","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 189</h2><p>188<br>and they seem to moan with pleasure as they bask in the light <br>that shines from the golden crown. Not far away, sitting in <br>the damp mud, are the bodies of all those who have drowned <br>here over the centuries. They have emerged from the earth, <br>awakened from the dead, to watch the Fairies dance. They <br>sit, motionless, observing the show with dull eyes and empty <br>eye sockets. ”<br>Place: The swamp where the fairies have <br>carried the crown of Tuvstarr.<br>Time: An eternal night, shrouded in fog and <br>under the light of a faded moon.<br>Information: The crown is sitting on a small <br>islet in an open swamp. It is possible to reach <br>it by jumping between the various stones that <br>emerge from the water.<br>Threat OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: A marshy swamp with a stone <br>track as its only path.<br>The water is black, cold, and deep enough to slow a <br>Hunter who falls into it.<br>Note: During this Scene, the Hunters may encounter <br>Skutt.<br> ◆ The Fairies are corrupted by the splendor of the crown <br>and will not allow anyone to touch it. It is possible to <br>communicate with them by interrupting their dance. <br>The Fairies will tell the story of a human princess who <br>gifted them with the crown, as bright as a small sun, <br>in order to cross the swamp. It is difficult to maintain <br>a conversation with dreamlike entities, and in a short <br>time they will slip back into their dreams and start <br>dancing again.<br> ◆ If the Hunters attempt to take the crown, the Fairies <br>will awaken from their trance. Screaming in pain, they <br>will attack the culprits without hesitation. Around the <br>crown there are always twelve fairies.<br> ◆ Somehow blocking the light emanating from the <br>crown will awaken the Fairies from the spell. They will <br>look at the cracked moon, screaming in agony as they <br>realize how much the lands around <br>them have been corrupted. Some will <br>suffer so much that they will become <br>dew in the grass or a pale reflection in <br>the pond. Others will ask the Hunters <br>to do something to save their lands.<br>Fairies<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC  <br>(1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are Fairies, spirits of nature <br>who move gracefully in a world of clumsy humans.<br>Agenda: Defend the crown that Tuvstarr has given us and <br>dance forever wrapped in its sweet light. <br>Gift – Madness: Made mad by the light of the crown, the <br>Fairies rage at anyone who tries to touch it. Two or more <br>Fairies can attack together to make a single action with a <br>bonus to the OL equal to the number of fairies involved. If <br>the action succeeds, in addition to inflicting 1 Wound, the <br>target will be thrown into the swamp to be drowned. Once <br>in the water, the target can attempt to break out of the flurry <br>of drowned, dead hands pulling from the bottom with a <br>Defense Check against OL Medium 5.<br>End of Scene: After recovering the crown of the Fairies, <br>the Hunters must also recover the dress from the Hulder <br>(THIRD SCENE OPTION B - The Hulder and the White</p>","markdown":""},"sort":18900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"KQIdyIMner0hL8HI","name":"Pagina 190","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 190</h2><p>3b<br>189<br>Dress) or, if they already have it, go through the forest to the <br>black pond (FOURTH SCENE - The Black pond).<br>THIRD SCENE OPTION B – <br>The Hulder and the White Dress<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: Sherazade takes out two paper <br>shapes from a bag, the first is the silhouette of a graceful Fairy, <br>the second that of a deformed creature. She places them in front <br>of the flame of a candle and on the wall, as if by magic, the <br>projected shadows swap places. “This area of the forest is even <br>darker than any you have been through so far. The woods are <br>deep, dark, and full of evil shadows. You come across giant <br>boulders entirely covered in dense moss and bearded lichens <br>hanging from tree branches, with the cold wind whipping <br>through the foliage. On the ground you see a streak of blood and <br>slime, as if forming a gloomy path that guides your steps. ”<br>Place: Among the trees of a dark forest, where not even the <br>light of the moon dares to show itself.<br>Time: It is night. Darkness envelops the forest, giving the <br>trees ghostly shapes.<br>Information: This is the Hulder’s realm. A spiritual forest <br>entity with feminine traits that once lived in symbiosis with <br>trees but is now corrupt and repulsive. Tuvstarr traded her <br>dress for passage through the woods. The Hulder took the thin <br>fabric in her hands, and it immediately made her feel unlike <br>anything she had felt before. With the dress, she felt strong <br>and beautiful, but also prey to a voracious hunger. Now the <br>dress is nothing more than a dirty piece of cloth that the spirit <br>has tied over her eyes like a blindfold. The Hulder obsessively <br>repeats how beautiful, graceful and lovely she is. This can be a <br>hint to help the Hunters realize that with the blindfold on the <br>monster is unaware of her true appearance.<br>Note: During this Scene, the Hunters may encounter Skutt.<br> ◆ It is easy to spot the tracks of the Hulder. A trail of blood <br>and slime is left on the ground where the creature crawls. <br>Her sense of smell is almost non-existent, but if the <br>Hunters make a noise entering her part of the forest, she <br>will charge furiously forward to devour them. <br> ◆ The Hulder is powerful and killing her in a fight will be <br>difficult. The best way to defeat her is to lure her into a trap <br>so as to tear the dirty piece of cloth – the dress Tuvstarr <br>gave her – from her eyes. If this happens near a reflective <br>surface (such as one of the many ponds that fill this area), <br>she will see her reflection and what she has become. She <br>will scream in agony and crawl away into the ashes of the <br>night. There, she will throw up everything she ate before <br>returning to her original form, filled with shame and guilt.<br>The Hulder<br>OL Hard 7 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an ancient forest spirit. I have eaten so many <br>living things that I have become fat and swollen, and the pieces <br>of the animals and people I have devoured are dripping from my <br>slobbering lips.<br>Agenda: Devour everything I meet.<br>Gift – Corrupted Spirit:  The Hulder has a feminine form, <br>but her skin is spongy and slimy. Her breath smells of rot. She <br>doesn’t realize what a grotesque monster she has become, as in <br>her mind she is still beautiful and seductive. When she suffers <br>1 Wound, the Hulder vomits a cloud of foul vapor that reeks <br>of rot. All the subjects hit by the cloud suffer 1 Wound in turn. <br>The effect of this Gift can be avoided with a Defense Check. <br>Gift – Swollen with Flesh and Blood: If killed, the Hulder <br>will emit a long, heart-breaking cry that will echo in the <br>woods, and all the dead she has eaten will scream in agony in a</p>","markdown":""},"sort":19000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"iZki4M7VIVAVPfQU","name":"Pagina 191","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 191</h2><p>4<br>190<br>cacophonous chorus. Anyone <br>who hears the cry loses 2 Soma <br>and receives 1 Penalty on any <br>action for the rest of the Scene.<br>End of Scene: After recovering <br>the dress, the Hunters must <br>also recover the crown from <br>the Fairies (THIRD SCENE <br>OPTION A - The Crown of the <br>Fairies) or, if they already have it, <br>cross the forest to the black pond <br>(FOURTH SCENE - The Black <br>Pond).<br>FOURTH SCENE <br>– The Black Pond<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  <br>“My dear guests, after a long journey <br>our heroes have finally reached <br>their destination... or have they?” <br>Sherazade winks at you and, for a <br>moment, you have the impression that <br>she has moved just a few steps away.  <br>“You arrive at the center of the forest. The <br>trees are tall and menacing, and they seem <br>clustered around a pool of freezing, black <br>water. Any light that penetrates here looks <br>thin and weak, as if it were an intruder in <br>this land consecrated to darkness. Everything <br>is still and silent. ”<br>Place: The center of the great forest, bathed <br>in an unnatural darkness.<br>Time: An indefinite hour, in a place out of the normal flow <br>of time.<br>Information: As Hunters approach the water, they can <br>discover two things.<br> ◆ While the princess is gone, Tuvstarr’s reflection can <br>still be seen in the black waters, showing an image of <br>a naked girl sitting on the shore and staring into the <br>abyss. Next to her is a knight’s plate armor. The shield <br>has a fox with two tails as a heraldic symbol. There are <br>footsteps on the muddy shore leading into the black <br>water.<br> ◆ To enter the mirror world, the Hunters will have to dive <br>and swim to the bottom of the Pond, through the cold <br>and fatal darkness. When they are at the bottom, in <br>the mud and slime, suddenly a light will appear from <br>above. Sunlight in a clear sky. By swimming to the <br>surface, the Hunters will enter the Dream World that <br>Tuvstarr has built for herself.<br>The Dream World<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  “What stretches out before <br>your eyes is the Dream World that Tuvstarr created with <br>her wish. It is a land of joy, happiness, and goodness. Here <br>the days are eternal, bees never sting, and nature provides <br>everything those who live there need. It is built on all that is <br>good, siphoned out of the real world and remodelled according <br>to the will of the Child Princess. The grass is emerald green, <br>the sky is blue with perfect white clouds. A thousand and <br>a thousand more flowers. Butterflies and pollen in the air. <br>Everything is lush and new. What was once a quagmire is <br>a field with rolling hills, what used to be a forbidding forest <br>is now a lush wood with flourishing trees and meadows <br>carpeted with flowers. In the distance, the high towers of the <br>castle reflect the sunlight. ”</p>","markdown":""},"sort":19100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"lRFhwbbq7WG2cF0E","name":"Pagina 192","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 192</h2><p>5<br>191<br>Place: The perfect dream world created by Tuvstarr.<br>Time: Early morning, on a beautiful summer day.<br>Information: When they arrive, the Hunters will feel like <br>they have been reborn. Their wounds will stop hurting (it is <br>considered a special rest that allows all Hunters to recover <br>1 Wound). Their garments and clothes will be mended, in <br>fact looking better than ever before. The water they drink <br>and the fruit they eat are the best meal they have ever eaten. <br>It is truly a paradise.<br> ◆ Encounter with the Gallant Knight: The Gallant Knight <br>sits under a tree, eating an apple. His sword is beside <br>him. He is an old man, but there is still strength in his <br>steps and voice. In fact, his hair isn’t as grey as it used <br>to be. His pains have lessened. An old wound that once <br>grieved him is now merely a white scar. The Knight has <br>abandoned his quest. He found his way to the black <br>pond, entered the deep waters, and arrived in the <br>Dream World. He met Tuvstarr, tried to bring her back, <br>but she offered to let him stay here. He agreed, vowing <br>to continue to protect her from any threat. However, he <br>can be convinced to pick up his quest once more if he is <br>told that his brothers all died in the search and if he is <br>shown the two-tailed fox crest (page 187). <br> ◆ If the Hunters possess the Lance of the Fallen Knight, <br>the Gallant Knight will ask them to return it to him <br>so that it can be brought back to the castle in the real <br>world. Whether defeated or convinced, the Knight will <br>reveal that Tuvstarr is in the Dream World.<br>The Gallant Knight<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a respected and experienced knight of the <br>kingdom. My skill is only matched by my honor.<br>Agenda: Respect my knightly duties and serve the young <br>Princess Tuvstarr / Save the kingdom from what’s happening.<br>Gift - Gallant Knight:  The Knight is incredibly skilled, <br>but he would never use his full abilities against anyone <br>he doesn’t consider truly evil. When defending against <br>an enemy attack, his mastery increases his OL by 1. The <br>Knight will never inflict the final Wound on a target if he <br>doesn’t feel it truly deserves death.<br>End of Scene:  After finding out where Tuvstarr is, the <br>Hunters can proceed to the FIFTH SCENE - The Castle of <br>Dreams.<br>FIFTH SCENE – The Castle of <br>Dreams<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  “ Ahead, you see a castle <br>bigger than any other building in the country. The roof shines <br>with gold while the tallest tower is like another sun, shining <br>ever so bright. Looking around you, however, you notice that <br>everything seems to be nothing more than a false reflection <br>of reality. Farmers at work, animals in the fields, the King <br>and Queen themselves you see at the gates of the castle, all do <br>nothing but smile and nod. They speak in a low voice and say <br>comforting things like: “Stay here, everything is fine, the lands <br>are fresh and full of life. ” You realize that they are nothing <br>more than simple, idealized creations of Tuvstarr’s memories, <br>but full of joy and warmth. ”</p>","markdown":""},"sort":19200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"mL8jMJlX4N4TUTBO","name":"Pagina 193","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 193</h2><p>192<br>Place: The perfect dream world created by Tuvstarr.<br>Time: Early morning, on a beautiful summer day.<br>Information: The Hunters may encounter Tuvstarr in the <br>village, the forest, or the castle. She is simply a child who <br>wanders, naked and full of life. Tuvstarr goes around creating <br>things in her dream world.<br> ◆ Tuvstarr will ask the Hunters to remain in her kingdom, <br>just like the Gallant Knight. If they agree, the Hunters will <br>spend their lives in a dream and will soon forget about the <br>world on the other side of the pond.<br> ◆ Fighting Tuvstarr is a very difficult challenge. But if the <br>Hunters manage to imprison her or push her near the <br>lake, they may throw her in to make her <br>emerge on the other side.<br> ◆ Getting her to leave <br>her dream is difficult as <br>she only has vague <br>memories of the real <br>world, as if that <br>were the dream <br>to her. She <br>does not <br>like the pond in the forest. There is something about it <br>that makes her uncomfortable or even scares her, but she <br>does not have the ability to “remove” it with her power, <br>as it is the gateway between worlds. Talking about Skutt’s <br>painful existence will confuse her and could be a lever to <br>convince her to follow the Hunters’ advice. The Gallant <br>Knight, if persuaded back to his mission, could also be of <br>help in convincing Tuvstarr to trust the Hunters.<br> ◆ The Crown and the Dress: The Hunters will be able to <br>show Tuvstarr the crown that enchanted the fairies and <br>the dress that she gave to Hulder in order to make her <br>recall memories of the real world. The Princess will have a <br>vague memory of owning and trading them. Taking them <br>in her hand, she will recognize them. She will remember <br>the weight of the crown on her head and the warmth of <br>the dress’s fabric against her fingers. Wearing her items, <br>she will realize the difference between what is dream <br>and what is reality, and will begin to cry. At this point, <br>however, she will be even more strongly opposed to the <br>idea of returning to the real world.<br>Princess <br>Tuvstarr<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a pure and innocent soul, who just <br>wants a world without suffering.<br>Agenda: I want to stay forever in my perfect world. I <br>have been here for so long that I have forgotten what my <br>life was like before.<br>Gift – Creative Will:  Tuvstarr has the power to create <br>anything she wants in the Dream World. She can make a</p>","markdown":""},"sort":19300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"GN3a0Xo1kXNtaIog","name":"Pagina 194","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 194</h2><p>193<br>bird appear out of nowhere or make an apple tree grow <br>from nothing to bearing fruit in a couple of seconds. She <br>can deflect a river, make sunlight warmer, shape clouds, <br>and make small fish glow around her when swimming in <br>a river. Each new creation draws life from the real world, <br>making it more corrupt and darker. Tuvstarr can use her <br>power to defend herself by literally manipulating the <br>whole world. If Tuvstarr is killed in this world, she will <br>transform into colorful butterflies to regenerate herself at <br>her castle. Although Tuvstarr has virtually infinite power, <br>her innocence means that even if threatened, she will never <br>try to kill a living being. Rather, the Princess will try to hurt <br>and scare any threats and, in the worst case, drive them <br>away.<br>Gift – Pure Innocence: Tuvstarr radiates innocence and <br>beauty. Whoever meets her will fall under her spell. She is <br>always friendly, and her voice is clear and beautiful, with <br>the sharpness of ice breaking on a winter pond. Those who <br>interact with Tuvstarr must make a Defense Check or be <br>fascinated by her. For the rest of the Scene, the bewitched <br>subject will not take any action that could harm Tuvstarr <br>and, furthermore, will defend her at the cost of their life <br>from any threats. Seeing how the world outside the pond <br>is rotting will make a bewitched subject instantly come to <br>their senses.<br>The other Skutt<br>Skutt is always near Tuvstarr and will appear as soon as <br>the Hunters encounter the Princess. For the Hunters it will <br>be clear that this is not the real Skutt, but another dream <br>created by Tuvstarr. Skutt follows the Princess and she rides <br>him through the kingdom. Since he is a dream, this Skutt <br>will have no recollection of the Hunters. In reality, a spark <br>of the original Skutt resides in his dream projection and <br>can be exploited by the Hunters to push him to remember <br>the real world.<br>Skutt the Moose<br>OL Hard 7 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a majestic and magnificent moose who <br>protects the sweet Princess Tuvstarr with all his might.<br>Agenda: Protect Tuvstarr from all threats and make her <br>happy / Listen to a small part of my soul that cries out that <br>this perfect world is just a wishful illusion.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":19400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"1kZldXXcntMtV8Av","name":"Pagina 195","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 195</h2><p>194<br>A sad ending<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: “You take Tuvstarr back across <br>the pond as her Dream World dissolves. The sun returns to the <br>lands. The madness that has infested the animals is forgotten as <br>a passing nightmare. Skutt can finally let go, sighing in relief as <br>it is time to lay down his big head and forgive Tuvstarr for her <br>transgressions. Tuvstarr, after mourning the death of her dear <br>friend, returns to her parents’ arms filled with sadness. <br>An uncertain future awaits her. Perhaps she will become a wise <br>queen or maybe they will find her little body floating in a river, <br>drowned as she tries to return to a Dream World that no longer <br>exists. ”<br>“We have come to the end of this story. My thanks to all those <br>who have had the patience to listen to the words of this humble <br>storyteller. But even the most enchanting places cannot delight <br>when you are there against your will, and at this point I think <br>it is time to say goodbye to our protagonists, knowing that the <br>tragic story of Princess Tuvstarr has also touched their hearts. <br>But let the sadness at our parting be tempered by anticipation, <br>for our heroes will be caught in another story before too long.<br>With gratitude, Sherazade the Weaver of Tales. ”</p>","markdown":""},"sort":19500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"TDOx8ZPsNtLrfPiV","name":"Pagina 196","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 196</h2><p>195<br>Scenario Gifts<br>These Gifts represent special abilities related to the <br>Tuvstarr’s Reflection Scenario and can be acquired once <br>the requirements are met. A Hunter can only have one <br>Scenario Gift and if they acquire a new one, they will have <br>to forgo the previous one. Unlike with the normal rules, in <br>this case an Interlude it is not necessary to acquire the Gifts.<br>Hugin and Munin<br>Requirement: To meet Hugin and Munin and make a <br>pact with them.<br>Once per Scene, you can ask for advice from Hugin and <br>Munin. Ask the Storyteller a question, choosing from <br>among: “Where should I go?” “How can I defeat that <br>enemy?” “What is missing in my search?” The Storyteller <br>will answer with a cryptic sentence, which always includes <br>a useful hint. Get 1 Additional Success on all Defense <br>Checks against an attack from a non-human creature, <br>thanks to the blessing of Odin himself. At the beginning <br>of each Scene, you must spend 1 Soma to feed the spirits of <br>Hugin and Munin, or lose the use of this Gift for the rest of <br>the Scenario.<br>Lance of the Fallen Knight<br>Requirement: Collect the lance of the knight who died in <br>the search for Tuvstarr.<br>When you wield this spear and obtain an Outcome with <br>Increment on an attack, you can inflict 1 Additional <br>Wound. The tip of the lance can ignite at will, casting a light <br>and allowing you to have a burning fire always near at hand.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":19600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"fXjkNXTR1lDNK5Z8","name":"Pagina 197","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 197</h2><p>196<br>One Thousand and <br>One Nightmares<br>A special Scenario inspired by One Thousand and One Nights<br>Safety Keywords: Mental manipulation / Malignant psychological manipulation</p>","markdown":""},"sort":19700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"KGLKQKsA9svgvszO","name":"Pagina 198","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 198</h2><p>197<br>Once upon a <br>time…<br>A beautiful storyteller from the mysterious <br>East seduces all the courts in which she <br>performs, telling dark stories about a group <br>of Hunters of the Order. But where the story <br>ends, a real nightmare begins, as some of the <br>characters from the stories are brought to <br>life as monstrous shadows ready to steal the <br>souls of simple mortals...<br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunters…<br>One Thousand and One Nightmares is a special <br>Scenario that can be used during the course of any <br>Campaign or for a short game. In fact, once Sherazade is <br>introduced as an opponent, this Dark Presence will have <br>several ways of putting a spoke in the wheel of the Hunters. <br>After each interference, the Hunters will be able to collect <br>a clue as to the whereabouts of Sherazade and set out in <br>search of her to finally put an end to her work.<br> <br>How to use Sherazade<br>Sherazade can interfere in many ways during the adventures <br>of the Hunters.<br>Summoning the Shadow of an <br>enemy from the past<br>The Shadow is a unique opponent, a Dark Presence that <br>reminds the Hunters of an opponent they’ve already faced. <br>The Shadow sent by Sherazade will act in all respects as an <br>Opponent Dark Presence (in addition to all the normal <br>content of the chosen Scenario).<br>Shadow of Sherazade <br>(Opponent Dark Presence)<br>OL Medium 5 – (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: That of the original NPC.<br>Agenda: Interfering with and impeding the path of the <br>Hunters of the Order, preventing them from achieving their <br>mission.<br>Gift - Variable:  The Shadow has all the Gifts of the <br>original NPC. <br>Gift - Shadow Body:  A Shadow is a darker, sadder <br>version of the original. They can speak and behave like <br>the character they are modelled after, but on a careful <br>inspection they will appear cold and mechanical. Once per <br>Scene, a Shadow can appear or disappear from the darkness <br>by moving through walls and other solid obstacles. When <br>it spawns, it increases its OL by 1 because of the element</p>","markdown":""},"sort":19800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"8n7ofpkm3gyfh4qy","name":"Pagina 199","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 199</h2><p>198<br>of surprise. When it suffers the Wound that would kill it, <br>the Shadow dissipates until its turn in the Exchange. At <br>that point, it will emerge from the darkness as if nothing <br>had happened. The Shadow will not reappear if the area <br>the Hunters are in is fully illuminated with light sources <br>or magic. The only way to truly destroy the Shadow is to <br>expose it to sunlight.<br>Telling a story starring the Hunters<br>Another way to involve the Hunters in the plots of <br>Sherazade is to have them awaken within a story she’s <br>telling. Tuvstarr’s Reflection on page 182 is a great example <br>of a Scenario involving Hunters in this way.<br>The Scenarios imposed by the stories of Sherazade must be <br>created in the classic way presented on page 91, but the <br>introduction must always be the following.<br>Once upon a <br>time…<br>Good evening my dear hosts, my name is Sherazade and I am <br>a weaver of tales. My words will take you to incredible worlds <br>and follow the feats of brave Hunters… however this story <br>is not like the others and these feats are not just imaginary. <br>Will our heroes succeed in their quest? Or will they perish, <br>disappearing forever from the memory of time?<br>The Scenarios brought into the game by Sherazade allow <br>you to create stories with more fantasy elements, and if you <br>wish, even stories disconnected from the context of Broken <br>Europe in which the Hunters normally move. In this way <br>it is possible to explore mythology or stories that are not <br>fairytale-related, focusing on the group of Hunters who, <br>experiencing Sherazade’s story as both audience-member <br>and Hunter, must solve the mystery to be able to awaken. <br>Through a Scenario told by Sherazade, it is also possible <br>to replay a Scenario already faced, adding a completely <br>different element and creating a “what-if ” version of what <br>the Hunters have already experienced. <br>Just think of a version of Red-Hood Iskra where Elizaveta <br>comes to Durfort to save her daughter Iskra, kidnapped by <br>the dangerous werewolf Gerard Dubois. Or an alternate <br>telling of The City of Pigs, where the three Browne brothers <br>have turned the whole city into a sect of The God Under the <br>Mine and are preparing the rite for his awakening, which <br>obviously consists of sacrificing old Bardolf Greed.<br>Defeating Sherazade<br>From the moment she comes into play, Sherazade should <br>become a constant presence in the adventures of the <br>Hunters, sending Shadows to get in their way or throwing <br>them in the middle of some absurd story. During the <br>Scenario, however, the Hunters must be able to deduce the <br>influence of Sherazade and find a clue to her location.<br>How Shadows release clues:<br> ◆ When it has an obvious advantage, the Shadow says <br>something like: “My Lady Sherazade will be proud of <br>m e .”<br> ◆ When defeated, the Shadow can exit the scene shouting, <br>“My Lady Sherazade will avenge me. ”<br> ◆ When defeated, alternatively, the Shadow can dissipate, <br>leaving behind a small object typical of the area where <br>Sherazade currently resides. This could be a coin, a <br>garment, or a poem. Collecting these items, it will be</p>","markdown":""},"sort":19900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"JeauMant79iMJRcj","name":"Pagina 200","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 200</h2><p>199<br>clear to the Hunters that they serve as focus to animate <br>the Shadows and that, in fact, they all come from the <br>same area.<br>How the stories told by Sherazade <br>reveal clues:<br>At the end of each story, when the Scenario is solved, <br>the Hunters will see a short scene of Sherazade with her <br>audience entranced by what has just been told. The first <br>time, the Hunters will be able to understand the region of <br>Europe in which the Weaver of Tales is located; the second <br>time, Sherazade herself will turn towards them smiling, as <br>if to underline the mutual awareness of the bond that her <br>story has created.<br>How to deal with Sherazade<br>At some point, it will become clear to the Hunters that <br>Sherazade is a problem that needs to be <br>addressed. The journey to find her can develop <br>in several ways:<br> ◆ The Storyteller creates a Scenario to face <br>Sherazade. In the Scenario, the Weaver of <br>Tales will be protected by at least one of the <br>Main NPCs, fascinated by her Gift Words like <br>Honey.<br> ◆ The Storyteller adds Sherazade to one of <br>the unplayed Scenarios. In this case, she <br>will act as an Opponent Dark Presence <br>that will arrive at the site of the <br>investigation at the same time as <br>the Hunters. Sherazade will work <br>to ensure the Hunters’ failure, <br>thus proving their powerlessness.<br> ◆ The Hunters may find a way (using magic, with a <br>Treasure of the Order, etc.) to drag Sherazade into one <br>of the stories in which she has imprisoned them. In this <br>case, the Weaver of Tales will be forced to collaborate <br>with them so as not to remain a prisoner of what she <br>has created. At the end of the story, the Hunters will <br>meet once more with Sherazade, no longer allies, for <br>the final confrontation.<br>Sherazade in a Broken Tales <br>Campaign<br>Due to the recursive nature of her stories, Sherazade is a <br>great addition to any Broken Tales Campaign. In the list <br>of clues on page 246 there are also prompts to link her <br>to the story of the Child Savior and The One who Plots in <br>the Shadows. As written in her Agenda, Sherazade is not <br>a purely evil character, but more of a wounded soul who <br>has lost everything she cared about and who could even <br>become an ally of the Hunters.<br>Note: Sherazade is featured as a Hunter of the <br>Order in The Broken Ones expansion.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":20000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"gqzVADbGSD9Nam6i","name":"Pagina 201","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 201</h2><p>200<br>Sherazade  <br>the Weaver of Tales  <br>(Opponent Dark Presence)<br>Sherazade is a young storyteller who, together with her sister <br>Dinarzad, was captured and taken to the court of a wealthy Sultan. <br>The Sultan was a man with a dark soul who enjoyed inflicting <br>fear and pain on other people, and who invented trivial excuses <br>to torment poor innocents. The debauched, rich man decided to <br>play a game with Sherazade. Every night she had to tell him a <br>story. If he liked it, Dinarzad’s execution would be postponed for <br>a day. After thirty days of tales, the two sisters would earn their <br>freedom. Sherazade created a new story every night, always with <br>the threat of displeasing the Sultan and thus condemning her <br>beloved sister. But every evening, the Sultan was amazed by the <br>beauty of Sherazade’s tales and granted her another day. Thus <br>the fateful thirty days passed and on the morning of the thirty-<br>first, Sherazade was summoned by the Sultan. The man threw <br>himself at her feet, weeping, having had Dinarzad executed <br>the first night, certain of Sherazade’s failure and eager to <br>see her despair even should she succeed. But now, after <br>over thirty nights of beautiful stories, the Sultan’s heart was <br>filled with love and admiration for Sherazade. He wanted <br>her by his side as his bride. The Sultan offered Sherazade all <br>his wealth, power, and everything she might desire to forget <br>Dinarzad and her death. But Sherazade had her sister’s <br>smile etched in her mind as the last happy moment she could <br>recall, something not even the Sultan’s great wealth could erase. <br>And so all the stories told took shape, black shadows emerging <br>from the walls to seize the Sultan and hold him in terrible darkness</p>","markdown":""},"sort":20100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241725,"modifiedTime":1783973241725,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"RDd7901PEdBjRRhs","name":"Pagina 202","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 202</h2><p>201<br>for eternity. Empty of any emotion, Sherazade wandered all <br>over the known world and finally met a tired and stooped <br>man, a writer who, like her, had seen every happy memory <br>destroyed by the selfishness of others. The two forged a bitter <br>alliance to bring new life into the stories now broken by the <br>wish of the Child Savior.<br>OL Medium 5 – (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a storyteller who can bring the characters <br>I invent to life. My charm is so beguiling that it cannot be <br>ignored.<br>Agenda: Punish all those who believe they can change the <br>world for the better / Find peace and smile once again.<br>Gift - Words like Honey:  Sherazade can tell one of <br>her stories to bring out a memory, an emotion, or a fear. <br>Highlight 1 Keyword from this brief story. If a Hunter or <br>NPC hears the story and is linked to the Keyword, the <br>related emotion will awaken, leading them to open up to <br>Sherazade and share something about themselves. <br>Gift - A Thousand and One Nights:  One of <br>the characters from a Scenario already faced <br>by the Hunters comes to life as a Shadow. <br>Create a Descriptor to represent it. The <br>Shadow thus created will be at the service <br>of Sherazade and will do whatever they <br>are ordered. Shadows cannot speak <br>nor act in places where there is more <br>light than shadow. During a Scene, <br>Sherazade can create a number of <br>Shadows equal to the Hunters she <br>is facing plus one. For each Hunter <br>who has been affected by Words like <br>Honey, Sherazade can summon an <br>additional Shadow.<br>The Shadows <br>The Shadows of Sherazade are but the dark reflection of <br>what they were in the story they come from.<br>See page 197.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":20200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"5DhNKGmcAREvRoqs","name":"Pagina 203","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 203</h2><p>202<br>The City of Pigs<br>Once upon a <br>time…<br>The busy town of Whitehaven is experiencing <br>a rebirth under the leadership of Bardolf <br>Greed. The rich industrialist has invested his <br>considerable fortune in the extraction of coal, <br>employing a large part of the population at the <br>large mine near the town. Soon, there came <br>inevitable accusations of exploitation and <br>starvation wages, giving rise to an anarchist <br>group called the Pig Heads, named for the <br>macabre masks with which they cover their faces. <br>With his success darkened by disappearances, <br>bloody sacrifices, and mysterious figures moving <br>in the night, Bardolf turned to the Order to shine <br>the light of hope to the streets of Whitehaven…<br>A Scenario inspired by The Three Little Pigs (Joseph Jacobs)<br>Safety Keywords: Body horror / Worker exploitation / Prostitution / Blasphemy</p>","markdown":""},"sort":20300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Ac9FllTFWQimsY2D","name":"Pagina 204","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 204</h2><p>203<br>The story that led us here…<br>Bardolf Greed is a wealthy industrialist who made <br>his fortune thanks to shrewd deals and trade. Reaching the <br>ripe old age of seventy without an heir, Bardolf has decided <br>to dedicate his life to the only true, great love of his life: <br>money. Too old to travel, Bardolf has moved to Whitehaven, <br>an unremarkable town whose only resource was the <br>rich mines beneath the city. Within a few years, Bardolf <br>transformed Whitehaven into an industrial city by trapping <br>all its inhabitants into employment with starvation wages. <br>But not all of Whitehaven’s citizens were willing to give <br>in to the wealthy magnate. The brothers Clarence, Frank <br>and Arthur Browne have always cared for the community. <br>Arthur, in particular, worked for years to make Whitehaven <br>a quiet town where every resident could have a home and <br>a job to get by. Bardolf, however, has bought the town’s <br>favor, seizing property and leveling houses to build both <br>factories and dormitories for the now homeless workers. <br>By falsifying some official papers, Bardolf managed to <br>throw the three brothers out on the street, forcing them <br>to accept a job as miners or starve. Clarence soon quit, <br>choosing the life of a slacker over labor in the mines. Frank <br>and Arthur’s time in the mines was ended by a major mine <br>collapse, during which Frank lost an arm and a leg, and <br>Arthur was trapped by falling rubble and left for dead. The <br>collapse was caused by the awakening of The God Under <br>the Mine, a huge pig-like creature embedded in the rock <br>below the city. Alive and trapped underground, Arthur <br>found the God’s head and after days of agony he fed on <br>divine flesh, discovering that it confers incredible powers. <br>Crazed with grief and a wild hope that Arthur wasn’t dead, <br>Frank dug a long vertical tunnel, eventually managing to <br>create a communication channel with Arthur. United in <br>vengeance and endowed with the power of divine flesh, <br>the three brothers then began their personal war against <br>Bardolf Greed.<br>The story at the arrival of the <br>Hunters…<br>Whitehaven is devastated by acts of violence and sabotage, <br>which have interfered with its industrial productivity <br>considerably. People are afraid to walk the streets because <br>a criminal gang, called the Pig Heads, goes around <br>kidnapping the most skilled and capable workers. From <br>under the Mine, Arthur leads the rebellion by passing <br>pieces of the quickly regenerating God’s flesh to Frank. <br>Frank has managed to get hired as a butcher at the big meat <br>factory in the city and secretly mixes the flesh of the God <br>with common meat, infecting the unsuspecting miners who <br>eat it. When the mutation begins to take effect, Clarence <br>approaches the targets, offering them the opportunity to <br>join the gang. Bardolf senses that the city is under threat <br>but does not imagine that his enemy is someone he already <br>hates: Arthur, left for dead after the accident. With over fifty <br>Pig Heads now working in the mines, Arthur counts the <br>days before he can launch his personal revolution.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":20400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"lo1M2LWQOHwKBS4Y","name":"Pagina 205","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 205</h2><p>204<br>First Scene<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  Our story starts with you <br>in conversation with the wealthy industrialist Bardolf Greed. <br>Mr. Greed is a man in his seventies, his face plump and <br>surrounded by thick, lupine sideburns, while a pair of shrewd <br>eyes peek out over small round glasses. Bardolf ’s mansion is a <br>perfect example of the changes that big industries are bringing <br>to Europe and the rich magnate has spared no expense, nor <br>has he spared the wretched workers whose sweat built it. <br>With a bottle of fine wine near at hand, Bardolf fumbles with <br>his box of tobacco. Behind him stands a dozen men from his <br>personal guard, making it clear that the wealthy industrialist <br>does not feel safe at all...<br>Place: The dining room of Greed’s palace. Paintings and <br>cutlery with gold lining highlight Bardolf ’s great wealth. <br>Greed’s personal guards stand with their backs to the wall, <br>staring at the guests like silent statues.<br>Time: It is early afternoon. Visible through the window is a <br>sky gray with rain and fumes from the factories, which are <br>constantly active.<br>Initial Situation: Bardolf calmly explains the situation to <br>the Hunters, while the trusty William records everything in <br>a large black leather book.<br>Information: The following information / clues can be <br>obtained from the interview with Bardolf.<br> ◆ A gang of criminals wanders through the backways of <br>the city. They kidnap or injure only the factory workers <br>to make them unable to work. Nobody recognizes <br>them, because they hide their faces under grotesque <br>pig masks.<br> ◆ The city had been given new life thanks to Bardolf ’s <br>investments. Only one family (the Brownes) strongly <br>opposed the birth of the Factories, but in the end, they <br>too became Greed’s employees.<br> ◆ The mine works at full capacity under the watchful <br>control of Edward Right, an honest and dutiful man. <br>The textile factories also operate constantly, as does the <br>large slaughterhouse run by Frank Browne.<br> ◆ For Greed, productivity is everything. If forced to <br>choose, Hunters should put the preservation of property <br>and machinery before the lives of the townspeople.<br>1</p>","markdown":""},"sort":20500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"FtVXbmkfTOlAgAWz","name":"Pagina 206","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 206</h2><p>205<br>Greed’s Mansion <br>Descriptor: A small castle in the center of Whitehaven. The <br>pomp of each room underlines Greed’s incredible wealth.<br>Bardolf Greed <br>the Wealthy Industrialist<br>OL Hard 7 – Main NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a wealthy and skilled businessman who <br>always knows how to find a good deal, the one that turns a <br>profit for me. My body is old, but my mind remains infallible.<br>Agenda: Own every business and aspect of trade in <br>Whitehaven, so that the whole city is under my total control.<br>Gift - Smell the deal:  Bardolf is a master of negotiation <br>and reading others. After talking to a subject, Bardolf <br>can obtain one of the following pieces of information:  <br>1. Discover a secret regarding the person he is speaking <br>with; 2. Obtain an object or piece of information valuable <br>to the other party in the negotiation, and which he can use <br>as leverage. A Hunter can make a Defense Check to prevent <br>Bardolf from using this Gift on them.<br>William the Man of Law<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a prominent lawyer and I know all of <br>Bardolf ’s secrets. I manage the accounts of both the Factories <br>and mine with zealous attention.<br>Bardolf’s personal <br>guard<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are long-time mercenaries, paid hand-<br>somely by Bardolf for our loyalty.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":20600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"GltWnUOB9wX5vnZN","name":"Pagina 207","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 207</h2><p>206<br>The Factories<br>Descriptor: A series of shoddy, stone buildings used as textile factories and <br>foundries. Access is forbidden to outsiders.<br>If the Hunters talk to some workers, they can get the following information. <br>Roll a die or pick from the list:<br>1-2: Everyone aspires to work at the slaughterhouse where the shifts are less <br>pressing, but the unpleasant Frank Browne selects the staff. Frank ignores even <br>the most piteous plea and no one understands how he chooses who can work <br>alongside him.<br>3-4: Just outside the city there is an apple orchard that once employed many <br>inhabitants of Whitehaven. Now it is just a place where slackers like Clarence <br>Browne, as well as those who are unable to work in the factories or in the mine, <br>take refuge.<br>5-6: Not long ago, there was a collapse in the mines that injured or killed many <br>miners. Arthur Browne, a prominent citizen who did much for the city before <br>Greed’s arrival, was one of the victims.<br>Whitehaven<br>Descriptor: An industrial city growing around a large coal mine. The noise and <br>fumes from the factories fill the air at every hour of the day, while groups of workers <br>go back and forth waiting for their shift.<br>When the Hunters roam the city, roll 1 die.<br>1-2: They meet Clarence, who will try to pump the Hunters for information by <br>pretending to be well connected.<br>3-4: They meet Emma, who offers her services and is curious to talk to foreigners.<br>5-6: A group of Pig Heads equal to double the number of Hunters set up an <br>ambush.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":20700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"XlrnYohPwUgZwDkc","name":"Pagina 208","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 208</h2><p>207<br>The Pig Heads<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are a band of revolutionaries in the service <br>of the three brothers. The God’s flesh gives us power and fills <br>us with the anger we need to wage our war.<br>Gift – Pigs’ Gang:  When they act, each member of the <br>gang changes to become stronger. Their head becomes <br>that of a pig and only another Pig Head will be able to <br>communicate with them. Their mutation grants a random <br>power, roll 1 die. 1. Strength, able to inflict 1 additional <br>Wound once per Scene; 2. Speed , once per Scene acts <br>2 times consecutively; 3. Resistance , +1 Wound;  <br>4. Abomination , +1 to Opposition Level; 5. Grunt , <br>once per Scene can emit a loud squeal, enemies who hear it <br>receive 1 Penalty on their next action; 6. Out of control , <br>the OL rises to Hard 7 but, at the end of their action, the <br>NPC explodes into a cloud of flesh and blood.<br>Martha Browne the Mother<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am the mother of three brothers, and I am <br>so old that I have almost completely lost my sight. My son <br>Frank takes care of me, but he doesn’t tell me anything. I <br>am convinced that Arthur is not dead, for my instinct as a <br>mother tells me so.<br>Emma the Childhood Friend<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a childhood friend of Clarence and have <br>a special relationship with him. He has always promised that <br>he will take me away from this place, but I know that he will <br>never abandon his brothers. I understand that he has a big <br>secret, but tries to protect me by keeping me in the dark.<br>The Orchard<br>Descriptor: A large apple orchard which, before the arrival <br>of the factories, was one of the main sources of work in the <br>city. Now, however, it is abandoned and represents a home for <br>all those who cannot get a job.<br>When the Hunters roam the orchard, roll 1 die, or present <br>the encounters in sequence.<br>1-2 The orchard: The trees have been neglected and on <br>the ground there are still abandoned tools and baskets for <br>harvesting apples. A sign next to a tool shed reads “Gift  <br>courtesy of the Browne family” .<br>3-4 Clarence’s shack: A rickety rundown house with a <br>thatched roof. Inside, it is possible to find a rusty key that <br>says “slaughterhouse” and a sketched map of the mines that <br>says “well” . Around the hut there are always 1d6 + 2 Pig <br>Heads.<br>5-6 Clarence:  The youngest of the Browne brothers is <br>lying on the ground, visibly drunk, under an apple tree. <br>Clarence always pretends to be drunk with strangers to take <br>them off guard.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":20800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"blsUxR9TsNteqI4F","name":"Pagina 209","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 209</h2><p>208<br>Clarence Browne the <br>Younger Brother<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am the youngest of the Pig Heads and, despite <br>believing in our fight, I am not going to waste much time on <br>it. From hanging around, I know Whitehaven like the back <br>of my hand.<br>Agenda: Having fun and lazing around all day, carrying on <br>the Pig Head’s cause in my spare time.<br>Gift - Slacker:  Clarence is a master of the art of <br>disappearing when things get tough. In the presence of <br>even a small crowd, Clarence can leave a Scene when it <br>is his turn to act, without anything or anyone being able <br>to stop him. When using this Gift, Clarence hides in the <br>orchard, passing the entire following Scene there. <br>Gift - Gang Leader:  Eating the flesh of The God Under <br>the Mine gives the Browne brothers the ability to transform <br>into monstrous beings. Once per Scene, the NPC can <br>mutate, gaining the following benefits: 1. Recover a Wound <br>once they reach 0. Though apparently dead, the NPC will <br>revive within minutes of falling; 2. Once per Scene, act a <br>second time during the Exchange, even consecutively;  <br>3. Once per Scene, increase the Opposition Level by 2 for <br>a single action where they can harness their superhuman <br>strength.<br>The <br>Slaughterhouse<br>Descriptor: A huge gray building inside which cattle from <br>coastal pastures are slaughtered. Entry is forbidden to non-<br>workers.<br>When the Hunters wander around the slaughterhouse, roll <br>1 die to see how far they go without attracting attention, or <br>present the environments in sequence.<br>1-2 The outdoor garden:  It is more an open-air barn <br>than a garden patch. Bloodstains and excrement suggest <br>that the slaughter starts here. Several signs reading “No <br>Trespassing” suggest that the area is very controlled.<br>3-4 The slaughterhouse: Composed of a series of large <br>spaces, several stairs lead to underground chambers where <br>the meat is preserved. Around ten workers are present day <br>and night, all members of the Pig Heads.<br>5-6 The salting room: A small room at the back of the <br>building, where Frank prepares the meat that will be served <br>in the cafeterias throughout the city. During the day Frank <br>is always present, intent on hiding the flesh of the God <br>within freshly butchered beef.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":20900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Q9IMNSmbzCipk4Zw","name":"Pagina 210","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 210</h2><p>209<br>Frank Browne the Middle <br>Brother<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (4 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am the middleman of the Pig Heads and act <br>as the strongarm of the gang. I have control over all cultists, <br>and the power of The God Under the Mine has given me <br>strength and endurance equal to that of five men.<br>Agenda: Take revenge on Bardolf for what he did to me and <br>find a remedy for the wounds that have marred me since the <br>day of the accident / Mix the flesh of The God Under the Mine <br>with beef from the slaughterhouse and feed it to the miners to <br>add to the ranks of the gang.<br>Gift - The Pincer:  Frank replaced his left arm with a <br>home-made mechanical arm with many functions. During <br>a Scene, Frank can use each of the following one time:  <br>1. Crush, a hit with the pincer inflicts 1 additional Wound; <br>2. Pulley, the pincer can launch from the arm and raise <br>or lower Frank about thirty feet. Frank can carry 2 other <br>subjects with him. <br>Gift - Gang Leader:  Eating the flesh of The God Under <br>the Mine gives the Browne brothers the ability to transform <br>into monstrous beings. Once per Scene, the NPC can <br>mutate, gaining the following benefits: 1. Recover a Wound <br>once they reach 0. Though apparently dead, the NPC will <br>revive within minutes of falling; 2. Once per Scene, act a <br>second time during the Exchange, even consecutively; 3. <br>Once per Scene, increase the Opposition Level by 2 for a <br>single action where they can harness their superhuman <br>strength.<br>The Mine<br>Descriptor: A gigantic coal mine where miners work day <br>and night. Many areas are abandoned in favor of more <br>profitable veins. <br>Gift - Maze of Galleries: Whitehaven’s Mine is gigantic <br>and without a guide it’s not easy to get to a specific location. <br>With each exploration roll, you can get 1 or more Map <br>Tokens which represent progress in learning the layout of <br>the mine. Upon reaching 3 Map Tokens, you can go directly <br>to the Special result.<br>When the Hunters explore the mine, roll 1 die or choose <br>directly based on the narrative.<br>1-2 Work zone A:  Threading through the tunnels, <br>deafened by the sound of steam engines and digging, the <br>Hunters encounter a group of miners (2d6 + 6 Minor <br>NPCs). If the Hunters do something weird, one of the <br>workers will alert Edward. Exploration will yield 1 Map <br>Token.<br>3-4 Work zone B:  Threading through the tunnels, <br>deafened by the sound of steam engines and digging, the <br>Hunters encounter a group of miners (2d6 + 6 Minor <br>NPCs). If the Hunters do something weird, 1d6 + 6 miners <br>will reveal themselves as Pig Heads and attack. Exploration <br>will yield 2 Map Tokens.<br>5-6 Abandoned lodging: In an area close to the collapse, <br>recent traces of passage can be found. The Hunters meet <br>Frank and 5 Pig Heads who are going to the well to meet up <br>with Arthur. Exploration will yield 2 Map Tokens.<br>Special (3 Map Tokens):  By moving a heavy stone, <br>the Hunters will find the mouth of the well that leads to <br>Arthur’s chamber. The shaft is narrow and thirty feet deep,</p>","markdown":""},"sort":21000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"nO4Cbq9rwzmwnRSF","name":"Pagina 211","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 211</h2><p>210<br>but with a little attention a person can descend it. Climbing <br>down the pit can alert Arthur (see the Cave of The God <br>Under the Mine location on page 210).<br>Edward the Miners’ Chief<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a long-time friend of Arthur and mourn <br>his death. Everyone in the mine does what I say, and I hate <br>foreigners who want to poke their nose into my work. I allow <br>Frank into the mine often to visit the place where Arthur died.<br>The Cave of the <br>God Under the <br>Mine<br>Descriptor: A large natural cave, which Arthur has made <br>into a home. You can enter only by descending from a narrow <br>well. In the north wall, the enormous pig head of the God <br>gasps and groans as it waits to wake up.<br>Gift - Arthur’s House: The mastermind behind the Pig <br>Heads worked hard to make the Cave an intruder-proof <br>haven. If someone drops from the well, Arthur will be <br>alerted (a Position Check can avoid this). At the bottom of <br>the well is a large tub that Arthur can fill with boiling water. <br>Whoever arrives through the well suffers 1 Wound if they <br>have no way of avoiding the hot water. Inside the room, <br>Arthur can turn the lights on and off thanks to a system <br>he has invented, throwing the chamber into either light or <br>darkness. While intruders wander blindly, Arthur can use <br>his knowledge of the place to move freely.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":21100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"q9aW6EtT6RlMgMeF","name":"Pagina 212","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 212</h2><p>211<br>Arthur Browne the Big <br>Brother<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am the eldest of the Pig Heads and act as <br>the mastermind of the gang. Living in my natural prison has <br>taught me how to see even in total darkness.<br>Agenda: Take revenge on Bardolf for corrupting everything <br>I built in Whitehaven and regain control of the city / <br>Transforming all the inhabitants of Whitehaven into Pig <br>Heads.<br>Gift - The Flesh of The God Under the Mine:  Arthur <br>can tear pieces of flesh from the God’s head to harness its <br>powers. When he spends an action, the piece becomes <br>a Spawn of the God and begins to grow disgustingly, <br>engaging all nearby enemies. Arthur can tear one piece of <br>meat off per action, up to a maximum of 3.<br>Gift - Gang Leader:  Eating the flesh of The God Under <br>the Mine gives the Browne brothers the ability to transform <br>into monstrous beings. Once per Scene, the NPC can <br>mutate, gaining the following benefits: 1. Recover a Wound <br>once they reach 0. Though apparently dead, the NPC will <br>revive within minutes of falling; 2. Once per Scene, act <br>a second time during the Exchange, even consecutively;  <br>3. Once per Scene, increase the Opposition Level by 2 for <br>a single action where they can harness their superhuman <br>strength.<br>The God Under <br>the Mine<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (6 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a creature as old as the world, trapped <br>beneath the bedrock. Millennia of inactivity have made me <br>catatonic and there is nothing that can really wake me up. <br>Only pain can stir me even slightly.<br>Gift - The Head of the God:  Only the enormous head of <br>the God emerges from the rock, and pieces of meat can be <br>obtained from it. When he suffers 1 Wound, the God emits <br>a loud grunt that sends everyone flying (a Defense Check <br>can avoid this). As an additional effect of the grunt, the <br>God’s fetid breath taints the air, granting 1 Penalty to the <br>next action of all affected subjects, excluding Arthur. When <br>reduced to 0 Wounds, the God falls into a deep sleep to <br>fully regenerate in the following Scene.<br>Spawn of The God Under the <br>Mine<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: An abomination of flesh and tentacles, obeying <br>Arthur’s will.<br>Gift – Flesh Abomination:  A Spawn can perform its <br>action with a flesh tentacle up to a range of 6 feet, and at the <br>end of each Exchange it will grow as indicated in the table. <br>If not engaged in a conflict, the Spawn will grow 1 step per</p>","markdown":""},"sort":21200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Nfm933a6ByDktlkF","name":"Pagina 213","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 213</h2><p>212<br>Scene. When the Spawn acts, roll 1 die: from 1 to 5 it will <br>rage against one of Arthur’s enemies chosen at random. On <br>a 6, it will act against an ally or Arthur himself. If the Spawn <br>has more actions, roll the die for each single action.<br>Step Wounds Actions OL Special<br>1 +1 / +1 Range of 12 feet.<br>2 / +1 +1 If a target fails a Defense Check, in addition to suffering 1 Wound it will <br>be dragged towards the Spawn or thrown away.<br>3 +1 / +1 Mass growth to a size of 18 cubic feet.<br>Scenario Events<br>In this Scenario, there are eight Events. As a Storyteller, feel <br>free to create new ones in response to the actions of the <br>Hunters.<br>If the supply of infected meat is not stopped:  after <br>two days from the arrival of the Hunters the Pig Heads will <br>number over one hundred and Arthur will give the order <br>to attack the city.<br>If the Hunters discover that Arthur is still alive:  <br>Bardolf will give full access to the mine and its maps. With <br>them, it will be possible to calculate the exact location of <br>The God Under the Mine.<br>If the Hunters make their way to the mine and <br>Clarence or Frank know about it:   Frank will set up <br>a defense with a dozen Pig Heads, and Arthur will help his <br>brother, passing him pieces of meat to create several Spawn <br>of the God.<br>After Arthur creates the third Spawn in the same <br>Scene: The God Under the Mine goes mad with pain <br>and tries to move, causing a new earthquake. The mine <br>collapses, overwhelming everyone inside, though the <br>Hunters may find a quick way to escape.<br>If the Hunters talk to Bardolf about the three <br>brothers and express any doubts about them:  the <br>shrewd moneymaker will ask for time, and after 1 Scene he <br>will bring to the Hunters either Emma, Edward, or Martha.<br>If the Hunters commit to more than one Scenes <br>outside the city:  Clarence will attempt to assassinate <br>Bardolf in his palace, but will fail and end up on the run, <br>chased by the guards after being injured. Bardolf will</p>","markdown":""},"sort":21300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"S3JJ6ngHIFjnIUZg","name":"Pagina 214","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 214</h2><p>1<br>213<br>call the Hunters in to report, describing a Pig Head who <br>was acting alone and who is now wounded and therefore <br>recognizable.<br>Scenario Gifts<br>These Gifts represent special abilities related to the The City <br>of Pigs Scenario and can be acquired once the requirements <br>are met. A Hunter can only have one Scenario Gift and if <br>they acquire a new one, they will have to forgo the previous <br>one.<br>The Meat of The God Under the Mine<br>Requirement: Obtain a piece of the flesh of the God at the <br>slaughterhouse or defeat a Spawn.<br>Y ou can consume the flesh of the God to temporarily gain <br>power. Once per Scene, you can heal 1 Wound and gain <br>1 Additional Success for all physical actions you take. Y ou <br>have to wait an entire Scene for the remaining flesh to <br>regenerate. If you use this Gift in 2 consecutive Scenes, the <br>flesh is consumed and you won’t be able to use it anymore.<br>The Brand of Greed<br>Requirement: To gain the trust and respect of Bardolf <br>Greed.<br>Bardolf trusts only those who demonstrate cunning and <br>ability, granting such people a special pass called The Brand <br>of Greed. With the Brand you get free access to any place in <br>the city, without the person in charge being able to object to <br>your entrance. Get 1 Additional Success when you exploit <br>the Mark’s importance against a city dweller.<br>There Is No House That Can Stop <br>Me (Special Gift for Garou the Old <br>Wolf)<br>Requirement: Clash with one of the brothers who has <br>made use of the Leader of the Gang of Pigs Gift.<br>Those damned pigs get on your nerves and you can’t stand <br>them running away from your wrath. Y ou get 2 Additional <br>Successes when you take action to destroy or overcome an <br>environmental obstacle that stands between you and one <br>of the three Pigs at the head of the gang. Y ou hate to lose <br>to them. If you have to leave or flee from a place without <br>eliminating them, you lose 1 Soma.<br>The Scenario The <br>City of Pigs in <br>Scenes<br>FIRST SCENE –  The interview <br>with Bardolf Greed<br>It’s the same one you find on page 204.<br>End of Scene:  Bardolf asks the Hunters to gather <br>information in the city and its factories, go to the SECOND <br>SCENE - Visit to the city.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":21400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ggEA6qCrwSqcMCrg","name":"Pagina 215","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 215</h2><p>2<br>3a<br>3b<br>214<br>SECOND SCENE – Visit to the city<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: Whitehaven is the ultimate <br>representation of what intellectuals in drawing rooms call <br>the “industrial revolution. ” The small brick houses fade <br>in the presence of the large factories which, in a few years, <br>have completely changed the appearance of what was once <br>little more than a peasant village. Busy workers run like <br>industrious ants,    among them old people and children. <br>Whitehaven no longer has anything to offer to those unable <br>to work.<br>Place: The alleys of the city of Whitehaven, amongst <br>workers and people who live for the day.<br>Time: It is late afternoon, and a faint rain begins to fall. In <br>just over an hour, night will fall.<br>Information: Between the back alleys of the city and <br>the factory workers, the Hunters receive all 3 pieces of <br>information found at the factories location (page 206). <br>After gathering these, it will be dark, and a group of Pig <br>Heads equal to twice the number of Hunters will ambush <br>them. Once the fight is resolved, the Hunters will see that <br>one of the attackers is wearing a butcher’s coat and another <br>is dressed as a beggar.<br>End of Scene:  The Hunters can decide to investigate <br>the slaughterhouse (THIRD SCENE OPTION A - The <br>Slaughterhouse) or the orchard (THIRD SCENE OPTION <br>B - The Orchard).<br>THIRD SCENE OPTION A – <br>The Slaughterhouse<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  The city’s slaughterhouse is <br>perhaps one of the largest buildings the Hunters have ever <br>seen, and from the smell of blood that saturates the air it <br>seems that it works at full capacity day and night. A rusty, old <br>gate is all that separates you from the main door, but the bars <br>on the windows and the many “No Trespassing” signs suggest <br>that it is not a place where outsiders are welcome.<br>Place: The great slaughterhouse of Whitehaven.<br>Time: It is now night even if, from the lights in the <br>windows, the slaughterhouse does not seem to have ceased <br>its activities.<br>Information: The Hunters explore the place following <br>the list in ascending order (page 208). Once they arrive at <br>the salting room, they will find Frank intent on mixing the <br>flesh of the God with the meat for the miners’ meals. Frank <br>will fight to the death. Having knocked out the middle <br>brother, and upon searching the room, the Hunters will <br>find the flesh of the God and a map representing a specific <br>area of the mine. <br>End of Scene: Hunters can also go to the orchard (THIRD <br>SCENE OPTION B - The Orchard ) or go to the mine, <br>where it is clear that something is happening to the miners <br>(FOURTH SCENE - The Mine).<br>THIRD SCENE OPTION B – <br>The Orchard<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  You walk for about ten <br>minutes before you reach a large apple orchard, clearly <br>abandoned. Old wooden sheds and rusty tools left out in the <br>rain confirm your suspicions. Among the shadows you can <br>see the silhouettes of the beggars and other poor people who <br>rest in the only place in the city where money is not required <br>to live.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":21500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"r6yqTxRwPAZmhnek","name":"Pagina 216","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 216</h2><p>4<br>5<br>215<br>Place: The orchard, a few minutes’ walk from Whitehaven.<br>Time: It is night and has stopped raining. A timid full <br>moon appears among the open clouds.<br>Information: Clarence will approach the Hunters <br>trying to figure out who they are and, once he realizes <br>that they pose a danger to the gang, will seek to mislead <br>them. He will attempt to highlight Greed’s shady business <br>and that his loyal lawyer William has all the evidence of <br>the industrialist’s illicit trafficking. If cornered, Clarence <br>will fight with the support of the Pig Heads, but not to the <br>death. Clarence will reveal everything that happens at the <br>mine if that can save his life. In his shack, it is possible to <br>find a map of the mine with a mark on a specific point.<br>End of Scene: Hunters can also go to the slaughterhouse <br>(THIRD SCENE OPTION A - The Slaughterhouse) or go to <br>the mine, where it is clear that something is happening to <br>the miners (FOURTH SCENE - The Mine).<br>FOURTH SCENE – The Mine<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  When you arrive at the <br>mine, you avoid the main entrance and, following the map, <br>you come to a played-out vein of coal. Following the railroad <br>tracks, now in disuse, you enter the darkness.<br>Place: The abandoned area of the Whitehaven Mine.<br>Time: It is night and the mine is completely dark.<br>Information: The Hunters will find Frank or Clarence <br>(determined by which location they haven’t visited yet) <br>heading for a meeting with Arthur. If both brothers have <br>been eliminated, old Martha will be the one to visit her son. <br>If not discovered, the Hunters will see the family member <br>receive a piece of meat by pulling it up from the well. If the <br>Hunters somehow reveal themselves, the <br>threatened family member will activate <br>the power of the God’s flesh to create a <br>Spawn.<br>End of Scene:  The Hunters have <br>discovered Arthur’s hideout, go to the <br>FIFTH SCENE - The God Under the <br>Mine.<br>FIFTH SCENE – The <br>God Under the Mine<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  From the <br>narrow well you see a light and hear a man <br>talking to himself. A long, low, prolonged moan <br>seems to come from who-knows-what strange <br>creature.<br>Place: The cave where Arthur is trapped.<br>Time: The time of reckoning.<br>End of Scene:  At this point, it will be up to the <br>Hunters to decide which path to take, but it will soon <br>become clear to them that Arthur is now insane and <br>cannot control his obsession with Bardolf Greed’s ruin. <br>If the Hunters waste too much time Frank, Clarence, or <br>other Pig Heads could arrive, depending on how much of <br>a challenge you want.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":21600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241726,"modifiedTime":1783973241726,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"20If8bO5JDBC1HPA","name":"Pagina 217","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 217</h2><p>216<br>Saint George <br>the Dragon Slayer<br>A special Scenario inspired by St. George <br>and the Dragon<br>Safety Keywords: Religious zeal / Persecution</p>","markdown":""},"sort":21700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"NQ7C1bT7iVLPPrwq","name":"Pagina 218","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 218</h2><p>217<br>Once upon a <br>time…<br>There was a brave and devoted fighter who <br>made the fight against monsters his reason <br>for living. Saint George is perhaps the most <br>important and powerful member of the <br>Order, but his zeal in punishing the Broken <br>Tales can be a threat to the Hunters too... <br>Perhaps the real enemy does not hide in the <br>shadows, but walks beside them...<br>The story that led us here…<br>Saint George the Dragon Slayer is a special Scenario <br>that can be used during any Campaign or for a short game. <br>In fact, once Saint George has been included as a support to <br>the Hunters, he will have several methods of foiling plans, <br>whether laid by friends or foes. Saint George will fight <br>alongside the Hunters, but his stern gaze and inquisitorial <br>spirit must be kept at bay so that the Saint does not unleash <br>the fury of the Church against its own agents.<br>How to use Saint George<br>Saint George will join the group of Hunters as soon as they <br>have solved a few Scenarios and earned a bit of fame. As an <br>Ally Dark Presence, Saint George will support the Hunters <br>on their travels. However, it will soon become clear that <br>his zeal for everything Broken Tales-related will make him <br>difficult to manage. <br>Saint George possesses a Gift called The Judgment of <br>the Saint. When enough Suspicion Tokens have been <br>accumulated, the Saint will become an Opponent Dark <br>Presence and will try to arrest the Hunters as he sees them <br>as representing the darkness that the Church fights.<br>Saint George  <br>(Ally Dark Presence)<br>Once upon a time there was a cheerful child named George <br>who often wandered away from home to run and play in the <br>woods. One day, George fell into the river and in the blink <br>of an eye, he was drowning. On the verge of death, the child <br>felt an incredible force pushing him to the surface and soon <br>found himself on the bank of the river, soaked to the bones <br>but still alive. His savior was a strange, lizard-like creature <br>with incredibly human eyes. A Dragon! thought the child, <br>throwing himself on the creature’s neck, and a deep friendship <br>was born between the two. In the following years, George <br>took every opportunity to meet his secret friend and learn <br>from him the wonders of magic, and what is hidden from <br>the eyes of ordinary people. Then, a plague struck the village <br>where George lived, killing his parents. The lad’s appeals for <br>the Dragon’s help fell on deaf ears, despite the creature being</p>","markdown":""},"sort":21800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"WwOUOOhRWn21o9Ns","name":"Pagina 219","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 219</h2><p>218<br>capable of healing any disease. The Dragon, out of fear of being discovered <br>and killed, refused to heal the people of the village. Twenty years passed <br>and George took his vows, becoming a Holy fighter in the service of the <br>Papacy. He led more than one battle against the forces of evil. When the <br>Saint returned to his old village, he walked into the forest in search of <br>his old friend. The Dragon was happy to see George again after such <br>a long time and came out... only to realize that he had come before his <br>executioner.<br>OL Medium 5 – (4 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a Holy knight in the service of the Church. I am skilled <br>at hunting and defeating any monster. Nothing escapes my inquisitive gaze.<br>Agenda: Find every creature linked to the Broken Tales and exterminate <br>them so that they can do no harm / Truly understand the nature of the Broken <br>Tales.<br>Gift - The Holy Dragon Slayer:  Saint George starts the Scenario with 1 Fervor <br>Token. When facing an enemy that is visibly monstrous, he can spend 1 Fervor Token <br>to allow an allied Hunter to inflict 1 additional Wound. When such an enemy unveils one <br>of their Gifts, Saint George can spend 1 Fervor Token to grant 2 Additional Successes on <br>a Defense Check to any allied Hunter. Whenever he suffers 1 Wound, Saint George <br>receives 1 Fervor Token.<br>Gift - The Judgment of the Saint:  Saint George keeps everyone under <br>observation, even the Hunters he accompanies. During a Scene, if a Hunter <br>activates their Dark Ego or uses any Gift that allows them to employ <br>magic or terrorize ordinary people in the presence of Saint George, add <br>1 Suspicion Token on this Gift. During a Scene, Saint George can keep a <br>Hunter under observation, making them uncomfortable. When <br>he does, the Storyteller may spend 1 Suspicion Token to <br>impose 1 Penalty to a Hunter Check. Suspicion Tokens <br>carry over from one Scenario to another. When there <br>are Suspicion Tokens equal to twice the number of <br>Hunters, Saint George engages in a Witch Hunt <br>and becomes an Opponent Dark Presence.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":21900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"6mNhiH9eGqLrplmh","name":"Pagina 220","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 220</h2><p>219<br>How to manage Saint George<br>Once introduced in the Campaign or in the single Scenario, <br>Saint George will be a recurring presence to whom the <br>Hunters must be accountable. As the highest representative <br>of the Papacy, the Saint has full authority over all members <br>of the Order.<br>For the Hunters, it will be clear that Saint George could be <br>a good ally, but that under his stern gaze not everything is <br>permitted.<br> ◆ The Storyteller can add Saint George to the party <br>throughout the Scenario. Even if he has the authority <br>to make all the decisions, it wouldn’t be fun to play the <br>Session with an NPC leading the Hunters by a leash. The <br>Saint will therefore remain in the background, curious <br>to observe the Hunters and their work as members of <br>the Order. The Storyteller must immediately make it <br>clear that the Saint is at their disposal with his Gifts, <br>but that The Judgment of the Saint can quickly turn <br>him into an enemy.<br> ◆ The Storyteller can add Saint George to the party, <br>but the Saint will act independently and appear <br>only in some Scenes. In this way, the Saint will apply <br>more pressure on the Hunters, judging behaviors that <br>he considers unbecoming for a member of the Order. <br>He will always give support with his Gifts, but the <br>Storyteller will be able to use him more as a nuisance <br>than anything else.<br> ◆ The Storyteller will only let Saint George step in <br>when it is clear that a monstrous creature is featured <br>in the Scenario. For example, in Red-Hood Iskra he <br>could come after the appearance of Greskar (page <br>125) or due to the presence of The Ancient Enemy <br>as a Dark Presence (page 49). Saint George will <br>arrive driven by a premonition that there is a monster <br>to hunt down and smite. The Saint will be open and <br>supportive towards the Hunters, at least until he has <br>accumulated the first Suspicion Token. This is a good <br>way to introduce Saint George to a Campaign for the <br>first time.<br> ◆ Once the Suspicion Tokens accrued are twice the <br>number of Hunters, Saint George will launch a <br>Witch Hunt, and will become an Opponent Dark <br>Presence with the corresponding profile. From that <br>moment on, like any Opponent, the Storyteller will be <br>able to use him to impede the Hunters and to create a <br>special Scenario leading to the final confrontation with <br>Saint George.<br>Saint George <br>(Opponent Dark Presence)<br>The Holy Fighter who eradicates darkness in all its forms. <br>There are skilled Paladins in his service, ready to carry out <br>his every command.<br>OL Medium 5 – (4 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a devout knight in the service of <br>the Church. I am adept at hunting and capturing any <br>manifestation of darkness. I know every Hunter in the Order <br>and I know how to defeat them.<br>Agenda: Find the Hunters who have shown to be linked to <br>the Broken Tales and lock them up in the Church’s prisons. <br>Whoever opposes my sentence will perish, suffering the <br>judgment of God himself.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":22000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"dRlMWiqGixKbEacf","name":"Pagina 221","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 221</h2><p>220<br>Gift - Witch Hunt:  When he becomes an Opponent <br>Dark Presence, Saint George acquires a number of Fervor <br>Tokens equal to the number of Hunters. When facing a <br>Hunter he’s been tracking down, he can spend 1 Fervor <br>Token to inflict 1 additional Wound on top of the normal <br>one, or just 1 Wound if the Hunter succeeds on their <br>Defense Check. The only way to avoid this Wound is to <br>have an Outcome with Increment and spend it to nullify <br>the Gift’s effect. Saint George can spend 1 Fervor Token to <br>transform any Position Check’s result for an action against <br>him into a Failure so long as the Hunter performing it has <br>at least one Descriptor related to magic or a monstrous <br>characteristic.    Saint George regenerates Fervor Tokens <br>equal to the number of Hunters at the beginning of each <br>Scenario.<br>Gift - The Judgment of the Saint: Saint George keeps <br>everyone under observation, even when hunting down <br>Hunters. During a Scene, if a Hunter activates their Dark <br>Ego to perform a good deed or uses any Gift that allows <br>them to use magic or manipulate ordinary people to do <br>a good deed in the presence of Saint George, he adds 1 <br>Judgment Token on this Gift. Judgment Tokens carry over <br>from one Scenario to the next. When a number of Judgment <br>Tokens equal to the number of Hunters are staked on this <br>Gift, Saint George will make amends, declaring that he was <br>wrong in his judgment, putting an end to the Witch Hunt.<br>Paladins of the Church<br>A group of faithful Paladins in the service of Saint George.<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a Paladin in the service of the great Saint <br>George himself and his word, for me, is law. Years of training <br>have made me adept at fighting the Broken Tales.<br>Note: Each Paladin has a different Downside, indicated in <br>the Paladin Gift.<br>Gift - Paladins: Each Paladin has a name and a dedicated <br>Gift, and a Downside to add to the standard Descriptor. <br>The Storyteller rolls 1 die to decide which Paladin follows <br>Saint George in the Witch Hunt. Saint Geoge has a number <br>of Paladins equal to that of the Hunters he hunts.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":22100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"oujbDgiEhbYNHO0q","name":"Pagina 222","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 222</h2><p>221<br>Roll First Name Downside Paladin Gift<br>1<br>Trebizond, the <br>princess of a <br>Distant Country.<br>Sometimes, I am seized <br>by an unshakeable <br>curiosity about new <br>things.<br>From a Far Country: Trebizond can make use of weapons and exotic <br>objects with which to surprise opponents. Once per Scene, she can create a <br>Descriptor that represents a special belonging, such as Magic-Finding Dust or <br>A Whip as Sharp as a Blade. When using her special equipment, Trebizond <br>increases her Opposition Level by 1.<br>2 Saint Demetrius<br>I put the defense of my <br>companions before my <br>own life.<br>Guardian: Once per Exchange, Demetrius can take 1 Wound in place of one <br>of his allies. When he does, he increases his Opposition Level by 1 for the rest <br>of the Scene.<br>3 Saint Theodore<br>The ecstasy of battle is <br>for me the sweetest of <br>pleasures.<br>Furious: Theodore always inflicts 1 Additional Wound when raging against <br>an enemy. He still inflicts 1 Wound even if the Defense Check is a successful <br>Outcome. The only way to avoid the effect of this Gift is to spend an <br>Increment to cancel the Wound.<br>4 Saint Martha<br>I do not think that the <br>Broken Tales should <br>be eradicated, but only <br>understood.<br>Friendly: Any Hunter who acts against Martha when there are other Paladins <br>as potential targets will receive 2 Penalties on their action.<br>5 Saint Syrus<br>I am the oldest of the <br>Paladins and I only trust <br>my own judgment.<br>Veteran: Once per Scene, Syrus can negate the effect of a Gift activated by a <br>Hunter. The Saint will find a method to counter Gifts, drawn from his great <br>experience.<br>6 Saint Margaret<br>I want to affirm my <br>role in the Church and <br>overthrow that arrogant <br>Saint George.<br>Ambition: Margaret increases her Opposition Level by 1 for each Wound <br>that Saint George has suffered. Once per Scene, when Saint George suffers 1 <br>Wound, Margaret can immediately perform 1 additional action.<br>Saint George in a Broken <br>Tales Campaign<br>By his very recursive nature, Saint George is a great addition <br>to a Broken Tales Campaign. In the list of clues on page 246 <br>there are also indications to link him to the story of the Child <br>Savior and of the One Who Plots in the Shadows. As written <br>in his Agenda, Saint George is torn between his duty to the <br>Church and the memory of when, as a child, he formed a <br>sincere bond with The Ancient Enemy.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":22200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"SUHXpbH81JwtQqR0","name":"Pagina 223","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 223</h2><p>222<br>OZena  <br>the Suffering and Desperate<br>A Scenario inspired by <br>the Wonderful Wizard of OZ (Lyman Frank Baum)<br>Part One – The Yellow Village<br>Safety Keywords: Disfiguring Illness / Mental Illness / Deformity / Plagiarism</p>","markdown":""},"sort":22300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"fLAMAfFIQz0qbas2","name":"Pagina 224","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 224</h2><p>223<br>OZena the Suffering and Desperate is a special Scenario <br>divided into three parts, which when played consecutively <br>completes the story of the unfortunate Dorothea. All <br>Scenarios are built as a Scene Tree (see page 89) and <br>are great for introductory Sessions or a mini-Campaign. <br>A Storyteller who prefers an emerging storytelling style <br>will still find Events and information useful for managing <br>a freer playstyle for the Hunters.<br>Once upon a <br>time…<br>Freiburg, West of the great Black Forest, <br>Germany. The regent of the city, Nils Schulz, <br>has invited the Order to investigate the <br>activities of Margareta Westen, a renowned <br>“witch” who is said to carry out strange <br>experiments in a small village nearby. <br>Although there is no apparent evidence of <br>any heresy, the village of Gelb is shunned <br>by all. Its inhabitants are deemed “strange” <br>and it has, over the years, welcomed all <br>manner of freaks and sick people looking <br>for a safe place to live. Thus, the Hunters <br>must go to Gelb and find out if Margareta <br>is really the terrible witch that Nils fears.<br>The story that led us here…<br>Dorothea is a young American girl from the <br>1900s who suffers from a very acute form of ozena. Under <br>the care of the charlatan “Dr. ” Norman Henkle, she took <br>part in a strange magical rite, and both were catapulted <br>into the Black Forest of 1780. Here, under the guidance <br>of Henkle, Dorothea took the name of OZena (a name <br>that has not yet been made official for her disease). She’s <br>hunting witches to procure ingredients and potions for <br>her master, with the doctor promising to find a cure for <br>the disease. Dorothea brought the Doctor other lost, <br>ill people found along the way: Lowe, a scoundrel with <br>Leontiasis; Dose, a thug suffering from leprosy who <br>covers his skin with metal; and Hirnloser, a mental <br>patient who believes he has no brain. <br>After eliminating the witch Johanne in Schiltach (east of <br>the Black Forest) from which she got her magic shoes, <br>Dorothea arrived in Gelb with her companions. Here, <br>pursuing the promise of her cure, she sent Lowe and <br>Hirnloser to the village as spies to observe Margareta’s <br>activities. The old witch is actually both learned and <br>benevolent. She uses her magical knowledge to provide a <br>home and support to many sick or deformed people who <br>would otherwise have no place to live. <br>Note: Nasal ozena (also known as chronic atrophic <br>rhinitis) is a particular form of chronic rhinitis, <br>characterized specifically by a marked and widespread <br>atrophy of the nasal mucosa, so that the structure of <br>the nose wastes away. The disease disfigures the face <br>in a permanent way, affecting the appearance of those <br>affected with devastating effects.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":22400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"XMWpq3g3vVD1cvAk","name":"Pagina 225","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 225</h2><p>1<br>224<br>The story at the arrival of the Hunters<br>Margareta Westen is a capable and experienced witch, <br>who served at many noble courts as a fortune teller and <br>counselor from a young age. Affected by a very serious form <br>of deforming osteitis, which has ruined her legs and arms, <br>Margareta has experienced the unreasoning prejudice of <br>society herself. She was marginalized and abandoned by <br>everyone. The witch has thus decided to found a small <br>community, where all those like her would be welcome. In <br>Gelb, Margareta cares for those unfortunate enough not to <br>have a place in society, and most of the villagers would give <br>their lives for her. <br>Margareta is part of a coven of witches called the Compass <br>Rose. Johanne, the witch of Schiltach (east of the Black <br>Forest), was also part of the same coven. The death of her <br>companion has put Margareta on alert, aware that it must <br>have been someone who knew the secrets of the coven <br>who killed Johanne. Dorothea has long since crept into <br>Gelb, hiding at the edge of the small village. Hirnloser has <br>instead openly joined the community, though everyone is <br>wary of his mental illness. Lowe serves as eyes and arms for <br>Dorothea around town, while Dose, hidden in the swamp <br>to the east, awaits a signal from Dorothea to spring into <br>action.<br>FIRST SCENE – Approaching <br>the village of Gelb<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  Before your eyes you see <br>the great Black Forest in all its splendor, a refuge for animals <br>and supernatural beings from the slow expansion of civilized <br>life. A wide beaten path leads through the trees. Near a sign <br>with directions to the village of Gelb, you see two motionless <br>figures, as if they’re awaiting your arrival. One is a man, old <br>and hunched over by who-knows-what disease, while the <br>other is a child with a disfigured face. The two hold hands <br>like father and son. The man nods to you and you understand <br>that he is a villager sent to guide you.<br>Place: The road that winds its way from the west into the <br>great Black Forest.<br>Time: It is early in the morning. A cart has brought the <br>Hunters from Freiburg to the edge of the forest and the <br>driver is now anxious to leave.<br>Initial Situation:  Henrich and Klaus approach the <br>Hunters and introduce themselves as emissaries on <br>Margareta’s behalf. The witch was formally notified by <br>Nils that he was sending some of his agents to check on <br>Gelb’s activities, but the regent took great care not to reveal <br>the true nature of the Hunters. Henrich offers to lead the <br>Hunters along the road to the village.<br>Information: Walking towards Gelb with Henrich and <br>Klaus you can get the following clues and information.<br> ◆ The village of Gelb is a safe place for anyone with a <br>disease or a deformity that makes them an outcast in <br>usual society. Margareta welcomes anyone without <br>asking questions about their past and with the aid of her <br>potions, she soothes the suffering of all the inhabitants. <br>Although Henrich is a poorly educated farmer, he will</p>","markdown":""},"sort":22500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"1I76J11KgXEA1Nz2","name":"Pagina 226","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 226</h2><p>225<br>do nothing but praise Margareta’s goodness throughout <br>the journey with sincere conviction.<br> ◆ Little Klaus is affected by Ozena and his nose is nothing <br>more than a clump of rotten meat. Despite the disease, <br>he has the lively and curious eyes of a child, and he will <br>ask the Hunters a thousand questions.<br> ◆ The road the group is traveling on was created to <br>facilitate commercial trips to Gelb. However, Henrich <br>will regretfully inform the Hunters that once merchants <br>arrive in the village, they are so frightened by the <br>sight of the inhabitants, they hurriedly leave without <br>conducting any business. <br> ◆ Halfway to the village, the Hunters will realize that <br>someone is following them. It’s Lowe, who hides among <br>the foliage and tries to figure out who the newcomers <br>are.<br>End of Scene:  The Hunters arrive at the village of Gelb. <br>Go to SECOND SCENE - The Village of Gelb.<br>Henrich the Father<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am one of the many people Margareta <br>saved from the miserable life of an outcast. My son Klaus is <br>everything to me, which is why I don’t want the village of <br>Gelb to be suspected of witchcraft.<br>Klaus, the Ozena-<br>Afflicted Son<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC  <br>(1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a curious child. I <br>love foreigners because they always have <br>interesting stories to tell. I know I have a <br>dreadful disease, but I have learned to live <br>with it.<br>Lowe the Coward <br>Henchman<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC  <br>(2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I’m an eternal coward <br>who has been given a monstrous aspect <br>by fate. I can adapt to any situation <br>and am quick to jump to the winning <br>side.<br>Agenda: To help Dorothea in her <br>mission, with the hope of recovering <br>from my condition / Save my life, no <br>matter who I have to betray.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":22600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"jDTUCgcNKQjkXu0a","name":"Pagina 227","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 227</h2><p>2<br>226<br>SECOND SCENE – The Village <br>of Gelb<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  When you arrive at the <br>entrance to the village, the spectacle that appears before you <br>is incredible. People with all kinds of diseases and deformities <br>walk in the streets, occupied performing a variety of tasks. In <br>reality, what you see is nothing more than an ordinary village <br>in Bavaria, inhabited solely by people who, in any other place, <br>would be considered monsters.<br>Place: The small village of Gelb.<br>Time: It is morning, and all the inhabitants are busy with <br>their work activities.<br>Information: Henrich will tell the Hunters that Margareta <br>will soon arrive in the town square to dispense her medicines. <br>While waiting for the witch, several things will happen.<br> ◆ Hirnloser will appear, dancing and chanting of distant <br>worlds that overlap each other. Adults look at him with <br>pity, children walk around him amused. If the Hunters <br>get close, he will try to interact with them. If the Hunters <br>ignore him, he will be the one to approach. Whatever <br>happens, when Margareta arrives in the square, <br>Hirnloser will leave.<br> ◆ When Margareta arrives all the inhabitants will stop <br>working to run to her. The witch dispenses strange vials <br>among happy and grateful faces. After the distribution <br>of the medicines, Henrich will lead the Hunters to <br>Margareta.<br> ◆ In the crowd you can spot Lowe, who gazes at the potions <br>with dreamy eyes.<br> ◆ Dorothea is in the crowd too, her face covered with <br>a heavy green hood, the smell of her illness clearly <br>distinguishable. The girl will disappear using her shoes <br>at the slightest hint of a problem.<br> ◆ Margareta will speak to the Hunters, saying she fears for <br>her life. A week ago, she received news of the murder <br>of the witch Johanne who lived in Schiltach, in the <br>eastern part of the Black Forest. Margareta is convinced <br>that someone is trying to eliminate all 4 witches of the <br>Black Forest, each of which holds part of a powerful <br>artifact. She believes someone is gathering the pieces to <br>reassemble the artifact, no matter the cost.<br> ◆ The conversation will be interrupted by Lowe who <br>screams desperately: Hirnloser has kidnapped Klaus <br>and is taking him to the great swamp near the village! <br>Margareta will ask the Hunters to save the child. In <br>exchange, she will reveal to the Hunters what she knows <br>of the artifact. In the woman’s eyes, the Hunters will see <br>only a sincere concern for the fate of little Klaus.<br>Margareta the Good Witch<br>OL Hard 7 – Main NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a capable witch who has devoted her life to <br>caring for the unfortunate. My body is wracked with disease, <br>but that doesn’t make me any less fearsome.<br>Agenda: Keep Gelb and everyone who lives there safe.<br>Gift - Witch:  Margareta can draw on her witch power <br>to create a Descriptor to represent the effect of her magic. <br>Her abilities are related to manipulating emotions, such as <br>instilling fear or bestowing calm. The Descriptor thus created <br>remains for the entire duration of a Scene. Alternatively, <br>Margareta can move objects with the power of thought. These <br>abilities can be used to hit someone from a distance, knock <br>objects out of someone’s hand, and generally manipulate the <br>environment.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":22700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"rXLLyigqZmL5TdL9","name":"Pagina 228","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 228</h2><p>3<br>227<br>Hirnloser the Scarecrow<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: Everyone thinks I’m crazy and maybe they’re <br>right. I don’t feel any fear and I can see beneath the surface of <br>those who pretend they are normal.<br>Agenda: I follow OZena because I can see past her pain. <br>There is another world, the one where she comes from and <br>where I want to go too.<br>End of Scene:  Margareta asks the Hunters to save little <br>Klaus, offering to reveal all her secrets in exchange for the <br>little one’s safety. If the Hunters set out to save Klaus go <br>to SCENE THREE - In the Swamp . If, on the other hand, <br>they decide to stay in the village or split up, for those who <br>remain, go to the FOURTH SCENE - OZena’s Attack.<br>THIRD SCENE – In the Swamp<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  You don’t have to go too <br>far into the swamp before you hear little Klaus scream. You <br>run to a small clearing where Hirnloser puts a sickle to the <br>child’s throat. He is near an old, abandoned shed from which <br>suddenly emerges a huge figure covered in grotesque armor <br>made of debris. Hirnloser stares at you, his eyes pools of pure <br>madness. “ And while we dance here in our little puppet show, <br>the real performance unfolds in the village, ” the madman <br>cries and smiles maliciously, as you realize that you have <br>been lured into a trap.<br>Place: A clearing in the swamp twenty minutes’ walk from <br>Gelb.<br>Time: It is late morning and the sun filters through the <br>trees.<br>Information: Hirnloser and Dose want to engage the <br>Hunters to give Dorothea time to kill Margareta. <br> ◆ Hirnloser is insane but he doesn’t really want to kill <br>Klaus. It will soon become clear that he uses the child <br>as a shield and lever to keep the Hunters busy.<br> ◆ If Lowe is present, he will try to surprise the Hunters <br>from behind but will flee at the slightest sign of danger.<br>Dose The Tin Man<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: Leprosy has destroyed my appearance, but <br>my body is still that of the Mountain, the name by which <br>I performed as a street artist in shows of strength and <br>endurance. Under my heavy armor I fear nothing.<br>Agenda: I am in love with OZena, disfigured by the disease <br>just like me. I am aware that she will never return my feelings <br>and that is why the only thing I can do is serve her, even to <br>my death.<br>Gift - The Tin Man: Dose is completely covered in thick <br>armor made of metal and other salvaged materials, such as <br>a large stove and the hull of a boat. The only unarmored spot <br>is a small door in the stove that was once used to remove <br>embers, which is located above his heart. It is not possible <br>to hurt Dose unless one first finds a way to penetrate his <br>armor or uses an attack that can clearly overcome his <br>defenses.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":22800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"un7SslJx2ybUlOEZ","name":"Pagina 229","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 229</h2><p>4<br>228<br>Gift - Giant:  Dose stands nearly seven feet tall and <br>possesses extraordinary strength. The disease consumed <br>his nerves making him immune to pain. Once per Scene he <br>can inflict 1 additional Wound with one hit of his mighty <br>ax.<br>End of Scene: After the fight, Klaus will tell the Hunters <br>that the real leader of the scoundrels is a girl with a green <br>cape they called OZena. She told her accomplices to buy <br>her time, while she would take care of the witch. Klaus did <br>not see the girl’s face, but by the smell he recognized his <br>own illness. Go to FOURTH SCENE - OZena’s Attack.<br>FOURTH SCENE – OZena’s <br>Attack<br>This Scene concludes the first part of the Scenario <br>and will change based on whether the Hunters <br>choose to leave someone in the village while they <br>go to rescue little Klaus. Dorothea will attempt <br>to kill Margareta in her house. If no Hunter <br>is present, the witch will succumb to <br>the blows of the young assassin. If <br>any or all the Hunters are present, <br>Dorothea will flee as soon as it <br>becomes clear that she is at a <br>distinct disadvantage.<br>Place: Margareta’s house. <br>A large circular house built <br>around a centuries-old oak.<br>Time: It is late morning and the village of Gelb has resumed <br>its activity. Many inhabitants remain waiting tensely in the <br>Town Square to discover the fate of little Klaus.<br>Information:<br> ◆ During the fight, Dorothea’s hood will slide back and <br>reveal her face. She is a young blonde girl, eyes of an <br>intense blue and a suppurating chasm in place of her <br>nose. <br> ◆ When Dorothea escapes and disappears, it will be clear <br>to the Hunters that her slippers are magical.<br> ◆ After the battle, if still alive, Margareta will reveal <br>details on the Compass Rose. If she was killed by <br>Dorothea, the Hunters will be able to obtain some of <br>the information by examining the witch’s house.<br>OZena (Dorothea)<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a young girl who wants to return to <br>her world. The disease that afflicts me has ruined my face <br>and with it all the hopes of a normal life. I am willing to do <br>anything to heal, which is why I became a witch killer.<br>Agenda: Kill every witch Henkle points out to me and <br>retrieve all four pieces of the Compass Rose.<br>Gift - The Silver Slippers:  The wearer of this magical <br>artifact can move through folds in space, disappearing and <br>reappearing in a flash. Dorothea can move freely up to a <br>maximum distance of thirty feet without anyone preventing <br>her, but she must be able to see the point of arrival. Once <br>per Scene, Dorothea can take a longer journey and reappear <br>in any place she has seen at least once.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":22900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"gdrKqSUuyW2iOgxq","name":"Pagina 230","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 230</h2><p>229<br>Epilogue<br>The Hunters will discover that OZena’s goal is the Compass <br>Rose, a powerful artifact capable of summoning storms that <br>are said to be able to throw people and objects into other <br>worlds. The four Black Forest witches - Johanne (East), <br>Margareta (West), Helga (South) and Karina (North) - split <br>the artifact into four parts so that no one could abuse its <br>power. Karina possessed the first piece of the Rose. Johanne <br>had the second, as well as being famous for her magic <br>slippers. For this reason, it is quite clear that OZena has <br>already attacked and killed the first two witches. The next <br>target will then be Helga, who lives in the village of Rot <br>south of the Forest.<br>If Margareta is still alive, she will reveal some additional <br>information. Helga is the cruelest and most powerful of the <br>coven. Her magic is based on blood and, for this reason, <br>the Hunters will have to be careful not to be injured in her <br>presence. There is a potion that can break Helga’s blood <br>curse, but Margareta doesn’t know its ingredients, apart <br>from knowing it contains Burdock.<br>Note to the Storyteller:  OZena’s story continues with <br>the Second Part, The Red Village. Keep track of who among <br>Hirnloser, Dose and Lowe survived the Scenario. They will <br>return in the third part, The Emerald Village.<br>Scenario Events<br>In this Scenario, there are five Events. As a Storyteller, feel <br>free to create new ones in response to the actions of the <br>Hunters.<br>When the Hunters are in conversation with <br>Margareta: Hirnloser will take the opportunity to <br>kidnap Klaus and take him to the nearby swamp, creating a <br>diversion to get the Hunters away from the village.<br>If the Hunters head to the swamps to save Klaus:  <br>Lowe will offer to “guide them” to try to waste more time <br>and give Dorothea more leeway to kill Margareta.<br>If someone has wasted time interacting and <br>getting to know Hirnloser in the village:  when the <br>madman has Klaus with him, he will try to use the child <br>as a lever to talk to his new friend again, forgetting about <br>the plan.<br>If Dorothea is cornered:  she will flee thanks to her <br>silver slippers. Dorothea cannot afford to risk being <br>captured. This event occurs as soon as the situation turns <br>in favor of the Hunters.<br>If Dorothea manages to kill Margareta:  she <br>will recover the piece of the Compass Rose and then <br>immediately escape thanks to her magical shoes.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":23000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ZJuIgC8I9cakM96s","name":"Pagina 231","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 231</h2><p>230<br>Part Two – The <br>Red Village<br>Safety Keywords: Rituals / Nudity / Blood / Body <br>horror<br>Once upon a <br>time…<br>Rot, South of the great Black Forest, Germany. <br>After investigating Margareta Westen’s activities <br>and discovering the secret of Gelb’s village, the <br>Hunters are now aware of the threat from OZena, <br>a young witch killer who is trying to rebuild a <br>powerful magical artifact called the Compass Rose. <br>As described by Margareta herself, whoever owns <br>the Rose can invoke a storm so powerful, it can <br>throw those who are swept up into other worlds and <br>dimensions. OZena’s next target is Helga, a powerful <br>witch who lives south of the great forest. Helga <br>founded the cult of the Crimson Kiss, surrounded <br>by faithful and devoted servants. The village of Rot, <br>where Helga has made her home, is shunned even <br>by state officials, who fear they won’t be able to <br>leave that cursed place. But before going to Rot, the <br>Hunters received a special invitation...<br>Principality of Transylvania, fortified church of <br>Valea Viilor. Since the young OZena can move <br>in space and time simply by clicking her magic <br>shoes, the Hunters need an asset that allows them <br>to anticipate the movements of the enemy. And <br>the Order’s Treasury will surely have something <br>suitable...<br>For this Scenario the Hunters will receive the support of <br>the Order in the form of one of the many treasures kept in <br>Valea Viilor.<br>The Mirror of a Thousand Wishes <br>(Inspired by Snow White)<br>Gift - Mirror Mirror on the Wall: Those who use the <br>Mirror of a Thousand Wishes can ask to see the near past <br>or the imminent future of a subject they have met at least <br>once. After spending 1 Soma, the Mirror will show a few <br>moments of the target by displaying them on its surface. <br>The observer will not know if what they see is the past or the <br>future. The Storyteller secretly rolls a die: with 1-3 they will <br>see the past, with 4-6 the future. The same subject cannot <br>be observed more than once during a Scene. Alternatively, <br>before attempting a specific task, the owner of the mirror <br>can look into it and spend 1 Soma. Roll a die. If it’s a 4+ they <br>will see a few moments of their imminent future. Thanks to <br>this premonition they will receive 3 Additional Successes <br>for the first action attempting to perform the task. <br>Note to the Storyteller: The Order’s Treasure is an extra <br>Gift that can be taken by one of the Hunters. The Broken <br>Ones expansion book features complete rules for managing <br>the Order’s Treasures and a long list of Treasures to choose <br>from.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":23100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241727,"modifiedTime":1783973241727,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"yJ9DUrxsaiqgF8sg","name":"Pagina 232","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 232</h2><p>1<br>231<br>The story that led us here…<br>After the events in Gelb, Dorothea moved to Rot as the <br>first step in eliminating Helga. The Red Witch, however, <br>took the young woman by surprise. Thanks to the witches’ <br>faithful servants, Helga captured the girl, holding her in <br>her fortified villa. On the first night of the full moon, Helga <br>intends to sacrifice Dorothea by performing a blasphemous <br>rite which consists of drinking the victim’s blood to <br>assimilate her memories. By doing so, Helga would learn <br>of Henkle’s hiding place, where the other pieces of the <br>Compass Rose are already located. <br>Of course, the Hunters arrive only hours before the sun sets <br>and a full moon rises, setting the stage for the ritual.<br>The story at the arrival of the Hunters…<br>Helga is a powerful witch who has never had any qualms <br>about using dark magic. Through blood magic, she kept her <br>appearance young (despite her eighty-eight years) and over <br>time she built a true cult, whose foolish devotees would <br>do anything for her. Through her blood Helga can control <br>plants and people, moving them like puppets. Although the <br>village of Rot has acquired a grim reputation, Helga knows <br>it is only a matter of time before some obsessed clergyman <br>decides to attack her to eradicate the evil she represents. <br>The witch aims to obtain the Compass Rose to escape to a <br>safe place, where she can rebuild her kingdom of fanatical <br>servants.<br>FIRST SCENE – Towards the <br>Village of Rot<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  You have finally arrived in <br>the deep south of the Black Forest. Along the way, there are <br>numerous signs warning that the village of Rot is a cursed <br>place. Dolls of wood and rag, crosses and mounds of salt, all <br>bear witness to the pointless, superstitious spells of protection <br>attempted by the inhabitants of the area. As you follow the <br>small path to the village, the forest thickens more and more, <br>while the branches of the trees lower as if to grab you.<br>Place: The small path that leads to Rot.<br>Time: It is late afternoon and the last rays of sunlight are <br>struggling to pass between the branches of the trees.<br>Initial Situation: The branches seem to stretch lower and <br>lower, until it becomes clear to the Hunters that something <br>is wrong. Shortly after, the animated trees will try to catch <br>the Hunters and imprison them.<br>Information: If a Hunter has some understanding of <br>magic, they will quickly understand that what animates the <br>trees is an arcane power. Observing the branches’ motions <br>for a while, it will be possible to see a figure not far away <br>bathing the trees in a liquid which apparently animates <br>them.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":23200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241728,"modifiedTime":1783973241728,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"1558HCRgbgdQ4VdY","name":"Pagina 233","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 233</h2><p>2<br>232<br>If the mirror is used to understand where <br>OZena is:<br> ◆ Past - Dorothea sneaks up to a large greenhouse, <br>where she sees men dressed in white tending to <br>plants and herbs. The mirror fills with the form of a <br>nightmare creature that resembles a spider made up <br>of people’s bodies, which scares Dorothea away from <br>the greenhouse. In the ensuing chaos Dorothea grabs a <br>sprig from a plant (Elderberry, which a Hunter with a <br>relevant Descriptor will recognize).<br> ◆ Future - Dorothea introduces herself to a beautiful <br>young woman, dressed in an elegant red dress. The <br>young assassin agrees to take a sip of the wine that is <br>offered to her. Then, a trickle of blood runs down her <br>lips and she falls to her knees. The woman in red smiles <br>mockingly as a long knife falls from Dorothea’s hand.<br>Threat - The Animated Forest<br>OL Medium 5 <br>Descriptor: We grab and capture all intruders through the <br>magic that animates our branches and roots.<br>Wolfgang the “druid”<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: I am a skilled and renowned pharmacist, and <br>there is no herb or remedy that I am not familiar with.<br>Agenda: I am enslaved by Helga’s power. My body moves at <br>her will and therefore I sprinkle drops of her blood to animate <br>the forest to capture potential intruders.<br>End of Scene:  If captured, Wolfgang will reveal what <br>he knows to the Hunters. In the greenhouse, other poor <br>people like him work incessantly under Helga’s magical <br>control. In the village, a strange figure called the Porcelain <br>Princess ensures that no one can harm the witch. During <br>the interrogation, Wolfgang will be seized with sudden <br>spasms and drown in his own blood. If Wolfgang has been <br>eliminated, the Hunters will simply have to choose which <br>way to go.<br>If they go to the greenhouse, go to the SECOND SCENE - <br>The Greenhouse.<br>If they go to the Village go to the THIRD SCENE - The <br>Doll’s Court.<br>SECOND SCENE – The <br>Greenhouse<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: Following the path you reach <br>an old manor house which has been remade as a greenhouse. <br>Many men and women dressed in white, with tired and long-<br>suffering expressions, work on small gardens. Strong smells of <br>herbs and medicinal infusions fill the air.<br>Place: The greenhouse where the base for the Infusion of <br>Purity is produced.<br>Time: The sun is setting. <br>Information:<br> ◆ Pharmacists are working on a strange potion. Those <br>who are experts in herbs will recognize the plants as <br>Burdock, Nettle and Hyssop. <br> ◆ If the Hunters approach the greenhouse, Manycorpses <br>will drop from the ceiling to stop the intruders.<br> ◆ The Infusion of Purity cannot be completed, as the <br>Elderberry, which Dorothea took in her fight with <br>Manycorpses, is missing.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":23300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241728,"modifiedTime":1783973241728,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"fwGskTaywOS8YDXa","name":"Pagina 234","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 234</h2><p>3<br>233<br>If the mirror is used:<br> ◆ Past - Dorothea sneaks up to a large greenhouse, <br>where she sees men dressed in white tending to <br>plants and herbs. The mirror fills with the form of a <br>nightmare creature that resembles a spider made up <br>of people’s bodies, which scares Dorothea away from <br>the greenhouse. In the ensuing chaos, Dorothea grabs <br>a sprig from a plant (Elderberry, which a Hunter with a <br>relevant Descriptor will recognize).<br> ◆ Future - Dorothea is kneeling with her arms behind <br>her back. Her body is stiff, as if paralyzed, as she is <br>forced to look at herself in a mirror. She weeps for what <br>she sees reflected: her face disfigured by a disease that <br>has completely devoured her nose. <br>Manycorpses<br>OL Hard 7 – Minor NPC (4 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am an abomination created by Helga’s <br>experiments, in which she has united all her lovers into one. <br>I hate anyone who still has a normal body and I use my <br>incredible power to destroy them.<br>Agenda: Kill and dismember any human that comes within <br>range.<br>Gift - Aberration: Manycorpses can act twice during an <br>Exchange. Thanks to its multiple arms it can move on any <br>surface.<br>End of Scene: After being freed, the greenhouse workers <br>reveal that Helga is able to control people’s bodies with her <br>blood magic. Something called the Infusion of Purity, a <br>potion, can lift the curse. Helga is producing the Infusion <br>because she plans to sell the antidote to rich and powerful <br>nobles after poisoning them with her magical blood. To <br>complete the Infusion, however, Elderberry is required, <br>though the ingredient does not grow in this area. A strange <br>girl in a green cape has stolen the small stash Helga had <br>brought back from her last trip.<br>Go to the THIRD SCENE - The Dolls’ Court.<br>THIRD SCENE – The Dolls’ <br>Court<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  You come to a bleak, <br>dilapidated village made up of small, ruined houses and <br>brightly colored tents. Men and women in an evident state of <br>distress lie sprawled along the streets. From their tired eyes, <br>you understand that they are exhausted by the incessant work <br>Helga magically forces them to do. Suddenly, figures wearing <br>grotesque doll masks appear and head in your direction, <br>drawing their weapons.<br>Place: The dilapidated village of Rot.<br>Time: The sun is setting, but time seems to have stopped <br>in the small village.<br>Information:<br> ◆ The Porcelain Dolls are the only individuals worth <br>talking to. They will initially have their guard up, but if <br>the Hunters are convincing, they will be brought to the <br>Porcelain Princess.<br> ◆ The village is just an old, dilapidated logging settlement. <br>Not far away, it is possible to see a noble’s mansion <br>where Helga now resides.<br> ◆ No one can come before Helga without the approval of <br>the Porcelain Princess, her favorite.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":23400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241728,"modifiedTime":1783973241728,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"E7eUjSENxGHPVZ9f","name":"Pagina 235","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 235</h2><p>234<br>If the mirror is used:<br> ◆ Past - Dorothea introduces herself to a beautiful <br>young woman, dressed in an elegant red dress. The <br>young assassin agrees to take a sip of the wine that is <br>offered to her. Then, a trickle of blood runs down her <br>lips and she falls to her knees. The woman in red smiles <br>mockingly as a long knife falls from Dorothea’s hand..<br> ◆ Future - Dorothea is kneeling with her arms behind <br>her back. Her body is stiff, as if paralyzed, as she is <br>forced to look at herself in a mirror. She weeps for what <br>she sees reflected: her face disfigured by a disease that <br>has completely devoured her nose. <br>The Porcelain Princess<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a young noble who has fallen from grace. <br>My disfigured face is covered in a beautiful doll mask, and I <br>sadistically manage the cult of the Crimson Kiss on behalf of <br>my lady Helga.<br>Agenda: Carry out every order of Helga in the hope that she <br>will heal my face / I would do anything to get my face back.<br>Gift - Vials:  The Princess always has five or six vials of <br>Helga’s blood with her for newcomers to drink. She also has <br>1 vial of the Infusion of Purity.<br>Porcelain Dolls<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are the devoted guards of the Porcelain <br>Princess. Everyone fears us for our martial ability. <br>Agenda: Fulfill every wish of the Porcelain Princess.<br>Gift - Armed Guard:  Each Doll is armed differently. <br>Roll 1 die: 1. Spear, the Doll can make exceptional jumps <br>and can always keep an enemy at a distance; 2. Double <br>knife, 2 attacks per Exchange; 3. Great Blade, once per <br>Scene inflicts 1 additional Wound; 4. Whip, 9 feet range, <br>whoever fails the Defense Check becomes entangled; 5. <br>Blood, the blade of the weapon is soaked in Helga’s blood; <br>6. Shield, +1 OL to defend themselves or an ally.<br>End of Scene:  By defeating the Porcelain Princess or <br>persuading her away from Helga’s service, the Hunters will <br>obtain the key to enter Helga’s palace. When questioned, <br>the Princess will reveal that her lady intends to perform <br>an arcane rite during the night that involves sacrificing <br>Dorothea. Go to SCENE FOUR - The Red Witch of the <br>South.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":23500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241728,"modifiedTime":1783973241728,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"vRXhbmdzHsLCVqDt","name":"Pagina 236","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 236</h2><p>4<br>235<br>FOURTH SCENE – The Red <br>Witch of the South<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  Helga’s palace stands out <br>from the whole village because it is the only well-maintained <br>building. A heavy reinforced door and bars on the windows <br>make you immediately understand that it will not be easy <br>to enter. The soft sobbing of a girl catches your attention. It <br>comes from the second floor, where there is a large balcony.<br>Place: The old mansion where Helga lives.<br>Time: It is now night and only the light of lanterns borne <br>by the Hammerheads illuminate the mansion.<br>Information:<br> ◆ Entering the main door means encountering <br>Hammerheads equal to the number of Hunters +2.<br> ◆ Entering through the window will take the Hunters <br>to the room where OZena is held. If the Hunters have <br>an Infusion of Purity, they can free her from Helga’s <br>control. From Dorothea’s green cape, thrown carelessly <br>in a corner of the room, it is possible to retrieve the <br>Elderberry to complete a possible Infusion. Spending <br>time finishing the Infusion will cause a number of <br>Hammerheads equal to the number of Hunters +2 to <br>arrive in the room.<br> ◆ While the Hunters are busy in the mansion, Helga is <br>taking a blood bath in a tub to prepare for the ritual. As <br>soon as Dorothea is freed, Helga will understand that <br>there are intruders and will get ready to welcome them <br>with an escort of 8 Hammerheads.<br>If the mirror is used<br> ◆ Past - Dorothea is kneeling with her arms behind her <br>back. Her body is stiff, as if paralyzed, as she is forced <br>to look at herself in a mirror. She weeps for what she <br>sees reflected: her face disfigured by a disease that has <br>completely devoured her nose.<br> ◆ Future - Dorothea is naked and tied up on a large <br>wooden table. A woman with beautiful red hair, also <br>naked, utters strange arcane formulas, while she <br>prepares to gut the young assassin with a long knife.<br>Helga the Red Witch<br>OL Hard 7 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a powerful witch and I use blood to <br>perform my spells. Drinking one drop of my blood is enough <br>to become my slave.<br>Agenda: Accumulating power and collecting the four pieces <br>of the Compass Rose thanks to the information obtained <br>from OZena’s sacrifice / I am always willing to make an <br>advantageous deal, even if this leads me to revise my plans. I <br>would do anything to live forever.<br>Gift - Blood Magic:  Helga can unleash her powers to <br>affect the blood of one or more subjects, inflicting 1 Wound <br>or commanding their movements. Whoever has swallowed <br>Helga’s blood is totally subject to her will. It is possible to <br>resist the effects of Blood Magic with a Defense Check, <br>but this does not eliminate Helga’s magic. Drinking the <br>Infusion of Purity renders anyone immune to Blood Magic <br>for the course of a Scene and cancels the crowd control. <br>Those under the influence of the Blood Magic have a slight <br>crimson tinge to their eyes.<br>Gift - Blood Witch:  Helga is made young and immortal <br>by blood magic. At the end of each of her actions and if hurt,</p>","markdown":""},"sort":23600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241728,"modifiedTime":1783973241728,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"G58QxrM1vLgVsJM5","name":"Pagina 237","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 237</h2><p>236<br>Helga recovers 1 Wound. The flesh regenerates as the blood <br>returns to her body. When she is eliminated by suffering <br>her last Wound, the magic dissipates and the witch’s body <br>returns to being a shriveled old woman.<br>The Hammerheads<br>OL Medium 5 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We were once a ferocious team of skilled <br>mercenaries, but now we are in Helga’s service. We were <br>tamed by her magic and therefore we do anything and <br>everything for her.<br>Gift - Hammerhead Helmet: The heavy and distinctive <br>Hammerhead helmet opens like a flower on the shoulders <br>and grants total head and chest protection, making the <br>NPC immune to any Wound that can’t get past a thick layer <br>of metal. An enemy can aim at the lower parts of the NPC <br>to ignore the helmet. However, they receive 1 Penalty for <br>their Check.<br>OZena (Dorothea)<br>Dorothea’s profile is presented on page <br>228, only her Agenda changes.<br>Agenda: Free myself from the prison <br>where Helga locked me up.<br>End of Scene:  Helga’s threat is <br>ended, either through combat or by <br>convincing her to let Dorothea go free. <br>The girl surrenders to the Hunters, <br>revealing that everything she did was <br>ordered by Norman Henkle, a doctor <br>who, like her, comes from another <br>world. Henkle settled in the center of the Black Forest, <br>in a village called Smaragd. Henkle’s goal is to gather all <br>the pieces of the Compass Rose to summon the magical <br>tornado. Dorothea realizes that Henkle is insane and reveals <br>to the Hunters that even though she has been stopped, the <br>man will still try to activate the half-reassembled artifact, <br>certainly with devastating results. Only Dorothea knows <br>the location of the village and she is willing to accompany <br>the Hunters, expressing sincere repentance.<br>Scenario Events<br>In this Scenario, there are three Events. As a Storyteller, feel <br>free to create new ones in response to the actions of the <br>Hunters.<br>If the Hunters get the better of Wolfgang: Helga will <br>let him speak for a while so she can observe the Hunters <br>closely and then kill the man by drowning him in his own <br>blood.<br>When the Hunters start to get the better of a conflict <br>with Helga’s minions: the witch will detonate one of her <br>minions in each Exchange to cover <br>the Hunters in her blood. Y ou can <br>try to control them later.<br>If Dorothea is saved by the <br>Hunters: she will stay by their <br>side as an ally to take revenge on <br>Helga. She will try to kill her even <br>if the Hunters intend to negotiate.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":23700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241728,"modifiedTime":1783973241728,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ShyVgdRvo42ie2WW","name":"Pagina 238","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 238</h2><p>237<br>Part Three – The <br>Emerald Village<br>Safety Keywords: Body horror<br>Once upon a <br>time…<br>Smaragd, in the center of the great Black Forest. <br>The Hunters are on the trail of Norman Henkle, <br>a doctor and charlatan who apparently is the <br>mastermind behind the young witch killer who <br>goes by the name of OZena. The girl, whose real <br>name is Dorothea, claims Henkle is actually <br>a powerful wizard who fulfills wishes. His <br>ultimate goal is to activate the Compass Rose <br>to summon a storm and return to his own time. <br>Given the young woman’s failure to retrieve the <br>last two pieces, Dorothea fears that Henkle will <br>activate the artifact anyway. Dorothea, however, <br>remembers the first witch she killed saying that <br>using the Compass Rose without all the pieces <br>would be disastrous, opening a passage to <br>another world, but at a very high price...<br>The story that led us here…<br>Norman Henkle has been settled in a small and remote <br>village for a month, where he halted an epidemic thanks <br>to the Penicillin in his doctor’s bag, brought back from the <br>year 1900. <br>Raised to the status of holy man, Norman began to believe <br>himself a magician, giving free rein to his madness. In the <br>center of Smaragd there is a small well whose true nature the <br>inhabitants have always ignored. It is in fact a wishing well, <br>which after centuries of inactivity, has awakened thanks to <br>the desire of Henkle himself to become a magician. <br>Now possessing new powers, Henkle is truly capable of <br>making people’s wishes come true. However, his madness <br>twists every wish and the results are always tainted. <br>Determined to return to his time and become famous, <br>Henkle lured young Dorothea into his service, promising <br>to fulfill her one desire, to heal the disease that disfigures <br>her face. <br>Aware that he can’t really do it without risking some worse <br>effect, Henkle is waiting for OZena’s return to retrieve the <br>last two pieces of the Compass Rose so he can leave Smaragd, <br>escaping in his hot-air balloon. In the meantime, Henkle <br>has “experimented” with his power on the inhabitants of <br>Smaragd, creating monsters and aberrations that now hope <br>to earn a new wish to return to normal, unaware that they <br>are locked in an endless cycle of warped wishes.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":23800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241728,"modifiedTime":1783973241728,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"lTWiBn8tDFHXUnsd","name":"Pagina 239","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 239</h2><p>1<br>238<br>The story at the arrival of the Hunters…<br>Henkle fortified Smaragd against any possible intruder, <br>garrisoned by the villagers now corrupted by their wishes, <br>as well as the former companions of Dorothea who <br>survived the first encounter with the Hunters. While the <br>hot-air balloon is almost done, Henkle awaits Dorothea’s <br>arrival to complete the Compass Rose and escape.<br>Note to the Storyteller: This part of the Scenario differs <br>from the first two parts, as many enemies and encounters <br>will depend on what the Hunters have done previously. For <br>this reason, you’ll find only three Scenes leading up to the <br>Hunters meeting Henkle. It is possible to drop one or more <br>of the NPCs presented in each Scene to provide a challenge <br>for the Hunters. At the end of each Scene, or during a Scene <br>itself, if the Hunters face NPCs in a conflict, place 1 Time <br>Token on Henkle’s Hot-Air Balloon Gift. Until the hot-air <br>balloon is revealed, the Hunters will only know the name <br>of the Tokens that are accumulated by the Storyteller, but <br>not their purpose.<br>FIRST SCENE – Approaching <br>the Village of Smaragd<br>Read aloud to the Hunters: Finally, you reach the center <br>of the great Black Forest. A small path, now <br>almost completely lost among    weeds, is the <br>only point of reference to find your way. <br>Dorothea precedes you by a few steps, <br>visibly nervous. Suddenly you see the <br>girl stop and she wavers for a moment, <br>suddenly finding herself on the edge <br>of a huge ravine. “This wasn’t here <br>the last time I was here, ” exclaims <br>the amazed girl. A moat over <br>sixty feet deep and thirty wide surrounds a small village that <br>you can glimpse through the foliage. The fact that there is <br>no bridge suggests that it was created for the sole purpose of <br>keeping intruders away.<br>Place: A huge circular pit that Henkle created in order to <br>secure Smaragd<br>Time: It is early morning. The sun is high in the cloudless <br>sky.<br>Initial Situation:  It will be clear to the Hunters that <br>the moat must be crossed somehow. Dorothea can use <br>her silver slippers if she still has them, but she won’t do so <br>without the consent of the Hunters. The girl is convinced <br>that the Order can help her and will not betray the trust of <br>the Hunters, unless she sees a possibility of returning to the <br>future (see Events).<br>Information:  Henkle’s plan is to hit the Hunters as <br>they cross the pit, so he has deployed some underlings to <br>ambush them. Choose one of the following:<br> ◆ Hirnloser will have discovered a good position from <br>which to target the Hunters at a distance with the help <br>of 6 Villagers. <br> ◆ Lowe will go to meet the Hunters to challenge them <br>in the open field, bringing with him 3 Villagers and 3</p>","markdown":""},"sort":23900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241728,"modifiedTime":1783973241728,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"g3ycZuToLnEXiuQo","name":"Pagina 240","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 240</h2><p>2<br>3<br>239<br>Canine Tigers. <br> ◆ Dose will very simply attack the Hunters as soon as <br>they cross the Pit.<br> ◆ 4 Villagers with 4 Canine Tigers<br>Threat - The Pit<br>OL Medium 5<br>Descriptor: A large, deep pit with strangely smooth walls.<br>End of Scene:  The Hunters cross the pit to enter the <br>village of Smaragd. Go to SECOND SCENE - The Emerald <br>Village.<br>SECOND SCENE – The <br>Emerald Village<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  Once you cross the Pit you <br>find yourself in a small village of houses, built amongst the <br>trees. It only takes a few steps to understand that something <br>is wrong. You feel disoriented and it is difficult for you to keep <br>track of which direction you are moving. The small village <br>now looks like a labyrinth, huge and intricate.<br>Place: The small village of Smaragd which, by a wish <br>made by Henkle, appears as an infinite labyrinth.<br>Time: It is impossible to mark the passage of time <br>as day and night alternate every minute.<br>Information:  Henkle’s plan is <br>to waste the Hunters’ time and <br>prevent them from getting to <br>the center of the village. For <br>this he has deployed some <br>subordinates to set up an <br>ambush. Choose one of the following:<br> ◆ Hirnloser will plan an ambush with the help of 4 <br>Villagers. He and his men can move freely without <br>being affected by the Illusory Labyrinth Threat. <br> ◆ Lowe will go to meet the Hunters to challenge them <br>in the open field, bringing with him 3 Villagers and 3 <br>Canine Tigers. <br> ◆ Dose will very simply attack the Hunters as soon as <br>they enter the village.<br> ◆ 4 Villagers with 4 Canine Tigers<br>Threat - Illusory Labyrinth<br>OL Hard 7<br>Descriptor: A maze of trees and houses that change every <br>minute, making it impossible to find your way around.<br>End of Scene:  The Hunters arrive at the center of the <br>village. Go to the THIRD SCENE - The Magician’s Fake <br>Castle.<br>THIRD SCENE – The <br>Magician’s Fake Castle<br>Read aloud to the Hunters:  Finally in the center of the <br>village, you find yourself in front of a huge oak that has been <br>molded into the shape of a grotesque castle. Inside the tree, <br>you can see a hot-air balloon made of patched fabric that is <br>slowly inflating. You have never seen anything like it, but you <br>understand it will not be good.<br>Place: Henkle’s workshop house in the center of the <br>village, where the hot-air balloon is set up.<br>Time: The morning sun is high in a cloudless sky.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":24000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241728,"modifiedTime":1783973241728,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"SsLFf9WPIO9Aso4J","name":"Pagina 241","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 241</h2><p>4<br>240<br>Information: Henkle’s plan is to waste the Hunters <br>time while he makes preparations for the hot-air balloon. <br>For this he has deployed some subordinates to set up an <br>ambush. Choose one of the following:<br> ◆ Hirnloser will plan an ambush with the help of 4 <br>Villagers and 4 Canine Tigers. Hirnloser will order his <br>underlings to focus on the most injured or physically <br>weaker Hunters. <br> ◆ Lowe will go to meet the Hunters to challenge them <br>in the open field, bringing with him 3 Villagers and 3 <br>Canine Tigers. <br> ◆ Dose will very simply attack the Hunters as soon as <br>they enter the castle.<br> ◆ 4 Villagers with 4 Canine Tigers<br>End of Scene: The Hunters arrive at Henkle’s Castle, go to <br>FOURTH SCENE - The End of OZena’s Sad Story.<br>FOURTH SCENE – The End of <br>OZena’s Sad Story<br>The final battle with Henkle can go in many different ways. <br>If he manages to activate the incomplete Compass Rose, <br>a huge tornado will hit the whole Black Forest, affecting <br>everyone and taking Henkle away to a place unknown to <br>the Hunters.<br>Whatever happens, the fate of young Dorothea will be in <br>their hands.<br>Lowe the Brave Fighter<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I became a proud warrior and realized my <br>heroic potential. I never back down and set an example for <br>my teammates.<br>Agenda: Stop the invaders and protect the village of <br>Smaragd, which has elected me as its hero.<br>Gift - Hero: Lowe fears nothing and is immune to all forms <br>of fear and magical control. After he acts, his allies receive <br>+1 to their OL, inspired by their hero’s courage and words.<br>Hirnloser the Genius<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: My mind has become infallible, and I can <br>calculate and check any variable in seconds. I have a strategy <br>for every situation.<br>Agenda: Solve any potential problems that plague my <br>benefactor Norman Henkle.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":24100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241728,"modifiedTime":1783973241728,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"lEHodGDdJUcMFEfr","name":"Pagina 242","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 242</h2><p>241<br>Gift - Genius: When someone uses a Gift, Hirnloser can <br>prevent it from activating by deploying a countering system <br>or strategy. This Gift can be used up to 3 times during a <br>Scene, but only 1 time per Exchange. <br>Dose the Giant in Love<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (3 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: My body has become pure metal and only the <br>power of love can bring me back to flesh and blood. I fight <br>and destroy anything that can threaten my sweet OZena.<br>Agenda: I am in love with OZena and I want her to loyally <br>serve Henkle once more. I know that imprisonment in the <br>hands of the enemy may have made her reluctant to trust us. <br>I have to save her, whether she wants it or not.<br>Gift - Of Steel and Love: Dose is made of pure metal and <br>cannot suffer any kind of physical Wound. The only way to <br>get him to return to flesh and blood for a few moments is <br>to make his heart beat with love. Seeing OZena in danger <br>or well disposed towards him will change him back for <br>one Exchange. Seeing OZena, Dose can’t help but declare <br>his love as he fights, making his infatuation for the young <br>assassin clear.<br>The Canine Tigers<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: We are the village dogs, turned into monsters <br>by the desire of one of the children. Once the tiger’s ferocity <br>takes over, we can no longer be controlled.<br>Gift - Fierce as a Tiger:  When a Canine Tiger suffers <br>a Wound, it goes mad with rage and its Opposition Level <br>rises to Hard 7. At the mercy of anger, the Tiger will attack <br>the closest target without distinguishing between allies and <br>enemies.<br>Norman  Henkle <br>The Powerful Wizard Who <br>Makes Wishes Come True<br>OL Medium 5 – Main NPC (2 Wounds)<br>Descriptor: I am a powerful wizard and what I desire <br>becomes reality. My skill as a barker always charms everyone <br>to my side.<br>Agenda: I want to go back to my time alone and become a <br>celebrity thanks to the power of magic.<br>Gift - Hot-Air Balloon: As soon as it is ready, Henkle will <br>board and release his hot-air balloon into the air to activate <br>the Compass Rose. As indicated by the Scenario, based on <br>the actions of the Hunters this Gift will accumulate Time <br>Tokens. When the third Time Token is placed, the hot-air <br>balloon is ready to go.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":24200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241728,"modifiedTime":1783973241728,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"8Y7wtlcC840474PI","name":"Pagina 243","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 243</h2><p>242<br>The Villagers of Emerald<br>OL Easy 3 – Minor NPC (1 Wound)<br>Descriptor: We are poor villagers changed by a wish we <br>made. <br>Agenda: We hate Henkle for what he did to us, but we serve <br>him in the hope that we can make another wish.<br>Gift - Careful What you Wish For:  Each Villager has <br>made a wish, but it has not had the desired effects. Roll 1 die <br>to see what mutation has developed: 1. Wish for Wealth: <br>The NPC spits out gold coins mixed with bile. With a single <br>action, they can hit up to 3 targets at a distance of 15 feet; <br>2. Wish for Beauty:  The NPC warps their body so as <br>always to look beautiful in the eyes of the beholder. When <br>there is more than one subject in view, their body changes <br>constantly. Whoever witnesses the show receives 1 Penalty <br>on their Checks out of disgust; 3. Wish for Health:  The <br>NPC’s body regenerates as their hair and body hair grow <br>out of proportion. The NPC recovers 1 Wound as soon as it <br>loses 1, making them effectively immortal. The effect of the <br>Wound suffered is applied, so the NPC can be defeated, but <br>will regenerate on its turn to act; 4. Wish for Skill: The <br>NPC raises their OL to Medium; 5. The NPC can no longer <br>sleep because they are obsessed with the idea of working, <br>and will constantly be chattering nonsense; 5. Wish to <br>Grow Up: The NPC is a child with a body of a giant while <br>their head has remained the same as before. They can take <br>2 extra Wounds and inflict 1 additional Wound when they <br>unleash their strength; 6. Wish for Love:  The NPC has <br>merged with the one they love, literally obtaining the desire <br>to “become one. ” As a double body the NPC can act twice.<br>Scenario Events<br>In this Scenario, there are two Events. As a Storyteller, feel <br>free to create new ones in response to the actions of the <br>Hunters.<br>When Henkle realizes that Dorothea does not have <br>the missing pieces of the Compass Rose with her:  <br>he will take off on the balloon as soon as it is ready, and <br>then activate the power of the incomplete Rose.<br>If Dorothea realizes that Henkle is willing to <br>abandon her to return to the future:  she will do <br>anything to reach the man, begging him not to abandon <br>her.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":24300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241728,"modifiedTime":1783973241728,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"38p2lcy1v6BpaJyu","name":"Pagina 244","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 244</h2><p>243<br>Playing a Broken Tales <br>Campaign<br>Broken Tales is particularly suitable for episodic <br>games, where the group of Hunters can change its <br>composition from Scenario to Scenario to always <br>experience different stories. That said, it is entirely possible <br>to play a Broken Tales Campaign. In fact, a campaign is the <br>perfect opportunity to explore the story of the One Who <br>Plots in the Shadows and uncover the secret behind the <br>Broken Tales.<br>To organize a Campaign, it is necessary to <br>follow the following steps:<br> ◆ Create a group of Hunters. Y ou can choose them from <br>pre-generated options or create them from scratch <br>with the rules on page 69. Even though a Campaign <br>allows a different and more detailed development of a <br>Hunter through experience, between one Scenario and <br>the next in a campaign a Player can decide to change <br>their Hunter. The newcomer will begin with an amount <br>of XP to spend equivalent to that accumulated (even <br>those already spent) by the Hunter who leaves the story.<br> ◆ The Storyteller places the Map of Broken Europe at <br>the center of the table, then asks the Hunters where <br>they want to start their story from. The Storyteller can <br>choose to offer only a few possibilities, based on the <br>Scenarios they prefer to initially bring to the table.<br> ◆ The first Session opens with a Scenario and with the <br>Hunters intent on solving the investigation. During <br>each Scenario, the Storyteller can decide to introduce <br>one of the Clues  that will lead to the One Who Plots <br>in the Shadow (page 246). Once the Scenario is over, <br>the Hunters are free to move to any destination on the <br>Map.<br> ◆ Moving from one place to another takes a few days <br>of travel. The journeys (page 111) are managed by a <br>series of Encounters in which the Storyteller can detail <br>the world of Broken Europe and introduce the Dark <br>Presences.<br> ◆ Once at the new location, the Hunters will encounter <br>the corresponding Scenario and, by facing it, they will <br>be able to obtain a potential new Clue about the One <br>Who Plots in the Shadows.<br> ◆ Once they discover his true intentions and where the <br>One Who Plots in the Shadows is hiding, the Hunters <br>will be able to meet him for the final confrontation.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":24400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241728,"modifiedTime":1783973241728,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"0K7UZpvyTzPi1gz9","name":"Pagina 245","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 245</h2><p>244<br>The whole (true) story of <br>the Broken Tales<br>The One Who Plots in the Shadows and the Child Savior <br>are one and the same, two sides of the same coin who will <br>never meet. The Child Savior, pure and innocent, who saved <br>the world of fairytales with his love for stories, as an adult, <br>became The Writer to Whom No One Gave Credit, driven <br>desperately insane by all the rejection he had experienced. <br>When the Child Savior made the wish, an echo of his future <br>self had already burrowed into his heart. Without knowing <br>it, the child had made a wish that destroyed everything <br>he loved. As the years went by, the Child Savior grew up, <br>and tried to save the fairytales from what he had done. <br>But the more he wrote, the darker and more repulsive the <br>stories became. Every refusal, every reader who mocked his <br>creativity pushed him further towards his future self: The <br>One Who Plots in the Shadows.<br>Broken Europe, the Hunters, and the whole world of the <br>Broken Tales are nothing more than a giant shattered <br>fairytale, constantly written by the One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows, who breaks and reshapes every story that has <br>ever been told. Safe in his hiding place, he has started with <br>his own favorite fairytales. The Child Savior is now but a <br>ghost, a faded memory of a lost innocence that wanders <br>through Broken Europe in search of someone who can save <br>the One Who Plots in the Shadows from the darkness of <br>his own heart.<br>In all this, the Hunters are just puppets, distorted heroes <br>created to bring justice to a world that shouldn’t exist, <br>an immense machine that works despite the lack of a <br>fundamental gear: the difference between good and evil, so <br>dear to the fairytales of yore.<br>Finding the One Who Plots in the Shadows and confronting <br>him with his errant ways is the only way to put an end to <br>an infinite cycle that will inevitably bring every story to its <br>breaking point. But once the truth is revealed, what will the <br>Hunters choose? <br>Returning to the status quo will mean returning to their <br>lives as villains, shunned and destined to lose, spinning <br>evil forever. In preserving all that has been created by all <br>the adventures of Broken Europe, they condemn all other <br>fairytales to be forever broken.<br>Fragments of a shattered mirror, still capable of reflecting <br>an image, but distorted and incomplete.<br>TRUE</p>","markdown":""},"sort":24500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241729,"modifiedTime":1783973241729,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"e957JDUL1KmkQ4BZ","name":"Pagina 246","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 246</h2><p>245<br>The Clues that lead to <br>the One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows<br>The One Who Plots in the Shadows lives in Borgo <br>Maleanime, a remote mountain village located in Northern <br>Italy. Safe inside a large mansion, the One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows continues to break new fairytales day after day, <br>feeding the dark world that he himself has created. Nobody <br>knows who he really is and his face doesn’t linger in any <br>of the villagers’ memories. Not even the oldest among <br>the villagers can say when he appeared exactly, and the <br>youngest assure each other he has been there at least since <br>forever.<br>Only those who know the truth will be able to see him for <br>what he truly is: a middle-aged gentleman with sad eyes, <br>surrounded by deeply dark circles.<br>By gathering information along their travels, the Hunters <br>will become more and more aware of the presence of the <br>One Who Plots in the Shadows, until they can clearly <br>distinguish him from among the inhabitants of Maleanime.<br>During or at the end of a Scenario, the Storyteller may <br>introduce one or more Clues related to the One Who <br>Plots in the Shadows so that over time it becomes clear to <br>the Hunters that a strange, hidden opponent is scheming <br>against the Order from the shadows. By studying the Map, <br>the Hunters will be able to see Borgo Maleanime, but until <br>they find the Clue of the Road of Memories, they will not <br>be able to reach the mansion where the One Who Plots in <br>the Shadows lives. <br>Borgo Maleanime itself cannot be reached unless you are <br>led there by someone who has already visited it at least <br>once.<br>The order and the way in which the Clues are found are <br>deliberately left open, to allow the Storyteller to develop <br>stories and events without restraint. However, there are a <br>few things to remember to keep the Campaign on track:<br> ◆ The Clue the Road of Memories represents the way to <br>find the mansion of the One Who Plots in the Shadows <br>in Borgo Maleanime. It should only emerge when the <br>Hunters have an idea of who is hiding in the small <br>village.<br> ◆ Borgo Maleanime’s name should only appear when the <br>Hunters have realized that a dark and dangerous force <br>is acting against the Order. But to get there they will <br>need the guidance of someone who has already been <br>there, such as the Hunter Niklaus von Krampus.<br> ◆ If the Hunters decide to visit Borgo Maleanime before <br>knowing what they are looking for, they will realize <br>that it is impossible to reach the town and that the <br>small road that leads to the mountain where the village <br>is located will magically take them beyond it. Speaking <br>with a wandering merchant along the road, they will <br>discover that he himself goes to the village every now <br>and then, but only if someone leads him, because Borgo <br>Maleanime is a strange place, always lost in the mists. <br>Unfortunately, for over a year now, no one has come <br>or gone from the village. The Storyteller should make <br>it clear to the Hunters that it is impossible to reach the <br>town without a guide and that such a person will not <br>be easy to find. Too much procrastination around the <br>town will only be a waste of time.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":24600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241729,"modifiedTime":1783973241729,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"9lQGKtZ4Ix5PurqP","name":"Pagina 247","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 247</h2><p>246<br>The Clues<br>The following is a series of Clues that the Storyteller must <br>drop during the course of the Campaign.<br> The Road of Memories<br>The Hunters find a diary written in a child’s handwriting. <br>The little book has a powerful magical aura, from which <br>emanates sadness and echoes of the past. The written pages <br>clearly illustrate an incredible passion for fairytales and for <br>all the characters who are part of them. The diary is full <br>of drawings sketched with a child’s hand. They represent <br>imaginary adventures starring the Hunters themselves, <br>painted as heroes who save the world of fairytales. The last <br>page of the diary is a drawing representing a large mansion <br>at the end of a tree-lined avenue.<br>If the Hunters have already been to Borgo Maleanime they <br>will recognize the avenue, but they will not remember <br>having seen the mansion. If they have never been there, they <br>will have the clear perception that the diary is a magical key <br>to get to a hidden place. <br>If they open the diary to the drawing of the mansion facing <br>the tree-lined avenue in Borgo Maleanime, they will see the <br>house.<br> The Child Savior<br>A strange child wanders at night, crossing the path of the <br>Hunters. His expression is sad and he never speaks. He can <br>come and go anywhere he wants, appearing and disappearing <br>in the blink of an eye. Sometimes he watches the Hunters, <br>sometimes he helps them for no obvious reason. It will soon <br>be clear to the Hunters that this figure is endowed with great <br>power, but that he acts towards inscrutable ends.<br>The Child Savior is but a ghost, a reminder of who the One <br>Who Plots in the Shadows once was. He does, however, <br>still share some of the power that led to the creation of the <br>world of Broken Tales. The Child Savior will approach the <br>Hunters to study them, trying to understand if they can <br>be the “heroes” who could bring peace to the heart of the <br>One Who Plots in the Shadows. After their first meeting, <br>the Child Savior could come to their aid using his ability <br>to come and go from stories as he pleases. It is not possible <br>to communicate with him in a normal way, but only by <br>trying to interpret his actions. The use of certain Gifts, at <br>the Storyteller’s discretion, may allow a Hunter to meet or <br>speak with the Child Savior for a short time. <br>Through his messages, the Child Savior can impart the <br>following information:<br> ◆ The Broken Tales are not really evil, but someone is <br>warping their destiny.<br> ◆ Someone pulls the strings of the Hunters’ fate.<br> ◆ The Hunters find an original fairytale that tells the true <br>story behind one of the Scenarios they have already <br>faced.<br> ◆ The location of the Diary (see The Road of Memories).<br> Sherazade the Weaver of Tales<br>Sherazade threatens the Hunters thanks to her power to <br>make nightmares real. As the agent of the One Who Plots <br>in the Shadows, the Weaver of Tales wants to prevent the <br>Hunters from uncovering the truth behind the Broken Tales.<br>Sherazade will act as described in the relevant Scenario on <br>page 196. In the Campaign, the Weaver of Tales resides <br>in Italy, in the Kingdom of Naples, as a guest of the noble</p>","markdown":""},"sort":24700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241729,"modifiedTime":1783973241729,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ioaaYfXCX7Fjb7Iu","name":"Pagina 248","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 248</h2><p>247<br>Bourbon family. The clues that her Shadows will leave must, <br>therefore, lead the Hunters to the city of Naples. Some <br>examples may be: the Bourbon coat of arms on a precious <br>ring, a small lava stone from Vesuvius, or a key with a finely <br>worked head depicting the royal palace of Caserta.<br>Once defeated, Sherazade will tell her story and how a <br>strange man whose face she can’t remember gave her the <br>power to take revenge for her sister’s death. Sherazade has <br>tried several times to tell a story with this strange figure <br>as the protagonist, but each time her power fizzled when <br>doing so.<br> ◆ All she has seen is an old mansion at the end of a tree-<br>lined avenue. <br> ◆ In another story, the mysterious figure did nothing <br>but write, as if obsessed with the idea of modifying his <br>stories. <br> ◆ In the past, Sherazade has seen a strange child appear <br>in some stories, able to put an end to the magic of her <br>nightmares.<br> ◆ If the Storyteller thinks the time is right, Sherazade <br>will describe having visited Borgo Maleanime the first <br>time she received her powers and can lead the Hunters <br>there.<br> Saint George the Dragon Slayer<br>Saint George puts pressure on the Hunters by judging their <br>integrity. As the unwitting pawn of the One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows, the Dragon Slayer becomes a threat to Hunters who <br>have gone too far, considering them villains.<br>Saint George will act as described in the relevant Scenario <br>on page 216. In the Campaign, the Saint will have received <br>his assignment from the Pope himself, but will clearly <br>remember that at the side of the pontiff there was a strange <br>adviser that no one had ever seen before. Investigating in <br>Rome, it will be obvious that no one has any memory of <br>this person except for his frequent speeches on the danger <br>of the Hunters, a weapon in the hands of the Order that <br>has always risked turning into a greater threat than what <br>it fights.<br>After making amends, Saint George will vow to help the <br>Hunters by setting out in search of this strange figure. Later, <br>the Saint will be able to bring various information to the <br>attention of the Hunters by acting as an intermediary for <br>other Clues. For example, he could suggest that Niklaus <br>von Krampus has already been to Borgo Maleanime.<br> Memories of the Old Exorcist<br>Niklaus von Krampus has already been to Borgo Maleanime, <br>where an encounter with a mysterious demon convinced him <br>to become a Hunter. What Niklaus does not know is that his <br>whole story is but the umpteenth creation of the One Who <br>Plots in the Shadows, to remove Niklaus from the game before <br>he can reveal too much. The old priest has always had the <br>strong feeling of having left an unfinished exorcism behind in <br>Borgo Maleanime.<br>Niklaus is known in Borgo Maleanime and the villagers will <br>be well disposed towards him. They will show him kindness <br>that they would not to any other foreigner. If Niklaus is <br>not among the Hunters played, the Hunters will be able to <br>learn what he did in Borgo Maleanime when reporting to <br>the Pope in Rome, or from Saint George once he is on their <br>side. The Hunters will discover that the old exorcist is on <br>a mission for the Order and the Storyteller will be able to <br>introduce a new Scenario with von Krampus as an NPC.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":24800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241729,"modifiedTime":1783973241729,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"GBecWj8jzcOOhy8E","name":"Pagina 249","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 249</h2><p>248<br> The Confession<br>At the end of an investigation, one of the Hunters’ opponents <br>confesses that they were led to do evil or that they received <br>their powers from a strange figure whose face they do not <br>remember.<br>One of the Scenario opponents will reveal to the Hunters <br>that they received some kind of help that led them to <br>perform the actions at the core of the Scenario.<br>An example: Iskra will describe fleeing, cold and without <br>strength, through the great Białowieża forest, with wolves on <br>her trail ready to devour her. The little girl remembers a caress <br>on the head and a male voice behind her that whispered, “I <br>will give you the power you need to take revenge on your <br>mother. ” After that, the little girl will say that she woke up <br>stained with blood and found many dead wolves at her feet.<br>Over the course of various Scenarios, it will become clear <br>to the Hunters that this mysterious figure is the one who <br>acts as a catalyst for the events that require the Order’s <br>intervention. However, the Storyteller will have to give <br>this information at the end of the Scenario, so that the <br>presence of the One Who Plots in the Shadows does not <br>divert the Hunters from the events of the Scenario itself. <br>From interrogations it will be possible to obtain, from time <br>to time, some additional information on the strange figure:<br> ◆ He has a strong Italian accent. <br> ◆ His hands are stained with ink and he claims to be a <br>humble writer.<br> ◆ He carries a book in which he takes notes and writes <br>stories.<br> Close Enough to Feel His Breath<br>The One Who Plots in the Shadows begins to perceive the <br>Hunters as a potential threat and therefore observes them <br>closely. In the most frantic scenes, a Hunter will always notice <br>the silhouette of a man, safely hidden behind some shadows.<br>The One Who Plots in the Shadows appears when the <br>Hunters are focused on something else, trying to better <br>understand what they have discovered about him. If <br>approached, he will disappear into thin air and it will be <br>clear to the Hunters that no matter how hard they try, <br>the face of the man is wiped from their memories. If the <br>“Confession” Clue has already been found, the connection <br>can be made. <br>While it will not be possible for the Hunters to catch the <br>One Who Plots in the Shadows, a good plan or a good <br>Position Check in the attempt could knock some important <br>object out of the opponent’s hands before he disappears:<br> ◆ A notebook in which characters and facts of a Scenario <br>still to be played are written. The Storyteller will prepare <br>some Clues such as the Agenda of an NPC, the power <br>of some Gift or some information that the Hunters <br>will read from the notebook, and that therefore they <br>will already know if they go to the indicated place. <br>The Storyteller must be careful that the information is <br>useful but does not reveal too much of the plot of the <br>Scenario. That way, the Hunters will understand that <br>the figure who lost the notebook plays an active role in <br>pulling the strings of what is happening.<br> ◆ An old and worn diary (see “The Road of Memories”).<br>After revealing two Clues in this way, the One Who Plots <br>in the Shadows will no longer dare to follow the Hunters.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":24900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241729,"modifiedTime":1783973241729,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"dkQtEU0x9SS4otQd","name":"Pagina 250","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 250</h2><p>249<br> The Assassin<br>The One Who Plots in the Shadows sends a Dark Presence to <br>thwart the Hunters.<br>The Dark Presence will aim to impede the Hunters and, if <br>defeated, will lead to a Clue taken from “The Confession. ”<br> The Prophecy<br>A powerful group (such as the Zugarramurdi witches) or a <br>Dark Presence (such as Ambrose, for example) will reveal to <br>the Hunters a prophecy about a dark creator who gives birth <br>to all the evil in Broken Europe.<br>The prophecy speaks of a human who became God and <br>believes he holds the whole world in his hands. The prophecy <br>will also reveal that the Child Savior, the protagonist of an <br>ancient fairytale, has the power to stop the One Who Plots <br>in the Shadows. This prophecy will reveal to the Hunters <br>the name of their enemy and a place where the Child <br>Savior was last seen. By choosing a location on the Map, <br>the Storyteller will be able to drop the “Child Savior Clue” <br>into the relevant Scenario.<br> The Epilogue<br>Once the necessary Clues have been obtained, the Hunters <br>will be able to see the path that leads to the mansion where <br>the One Who Plots in the Shadows lives. The villain will <br>unleash a group of Dark Presences against the Hunters, <br>created ad hoc for the final confrontation. The Dark <br>Presences must be equal to the number of Hunters and <br>each must be linked to a Hunter’s personal story. These <br>Dark Presences must have a background and an Agenda <br>that leads them to hate the Hunters. <br>Once the Dark Presences are defeated, the Hunters will face <br>the One Who Plots in the Shadows. He is an anonymous <br>man hunched over a large desk, scribbling incessantly on <br>the pages of a book before tearing them out in anger. The <br>One Who Plots in the Shadows will explain the whole true <br>story of the Child Savior and how the world as the Hunters <br>know it is nothing more than his creation.<br>The poor writer is now only a madman, prey to his own <br>delirium of omnipotence. However, what will be clear to <br>the Hunters is that his death will erase the history of Broken <br>Europe. A story of which they are, in spite of themselves, <br>the protagonists.<br>Killing the One Who Plots in the Shadows and bringing all <br>the fairytales back to what they were will turn the Hunters <br>back into being the villains, the losers, the ones everyone <br>hates.<br>Leaving the One Who Plots in the Shadows alive will mean <br>accepting a new world ruled by a mad God. But, it will be <br>a world where Hunters have the free will to be whatever <br>they want.<br>What will the Players choose?</p>","markdown":""},"sort":25000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241729,"modifiedTime":1783973241729,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"ltDt05GyLWBmUHLU","name":"Pagina 251","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 251</h2><p>250<br>The Map of Broken <br>Europe<br>During the Campaign, the Hunters will move across <br>the Map of Broken Europe. Some places will have a <br>corresponding Scenario, while in others it will be possible <br>to drop Dark Presences or encounters of various kinds. The <br>Storyteller can modify at will the Scenarios and situations <br>of each place according to the progress of the Campaign, <br>but the following information is to be considered canon for <br>how the general story of the Broken Tales was conceived.<br> Black Forest<br>Here the Hunters can face a Scenario in three acts called <br>OZena the Suffering and Desperate. Once the final scenario <br>is completed, OZena could become a Hunter of the Order. <br>OZena the Afflicted’s sheet is featured in the expansion <br>book The Broken Ones.<br> Borgholm<br>In this location, the Hunters will face the Scenario A <br>Soldier’s Duty.<br> Borgo Maleanime<br>Here, the Hunters can track the One Who Plots in the <br>Shadows if they have collected enough Clues. It will also be <br>the place of the final confrontation. Borgo Maleanime can <br>only be accessed if led by someone who has already visited <br>the town in the past.<br> Devil’s Bridge<br>Europe is littered with bridges that manifest strange powers <br>and that the local population always associate with the <br>Devil. One Devil’s Bridge can lead Hunters to another such <br>Bridge. Devil’s Bridges are spread across Europe, allowing <br>the Hunters to cover great distances in no time. There is <br>also a Devil’s Bridge in Borgo Maleanime, which could be <br>an alternative way for the Hunters to get to the hideout of <br>the One Who Plots in the Shadows.<br> Durfort<br>In this place the Hunters will face the Scenario Red-Hood <br>Iskra. Once the Scenario is resolved, Iskra could become <br>a Hunter of the Order. Iskra the Y oung Wolf ’s sheet is <br>featured in the expansion book The Broken Ones.<br> Martana Island<br>In this place the Hunters will face the Scenario The House <br>of Roses, featured in the expansion book The Broken Ones. <br>Once this Scenario is completed, Beauty and her Beast <br>could become Hunters of the Order. The sheet for Beauty <br>and her Beast is featured in the expansion book The <br>Broken Ones.<br> Lohr<br>In this place the Hunters will face the Scenario <br>Bloodwhite’s Heart, featured in the expansion book <br>The Broken Ones. Once this Scenario is completed, <br>Bloodwhite could become a Hunter of the Order. <br>Bloodwhite’s sheet is featured in the expansion book <br>The Broken Ones.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":25100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241729,"modifiedTime":1783973241729,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"n5syI52xqkw7SD6U","name":"Pagina 252","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 252</h2><p>251<br> London <br>In this place the Hunters will face the Scenario I Don’t <br>Believe, featured in the expansion book The Broken Ones.<br> Malbork<br>This city is home to the Order of the Teutonic Knights, who <br>have been in open conflict with the Church for years. The <br>Teutonic Knights believe the Hunters have strayed from the <br>straight path that should define a servant of God. <br>Some possible situations related to the Knights:<br> ◆ A Hunter of the Order has been taken prisoner (it <br>could be Krampus, whom the Hunters may be hoping <br>can lead them to Borgo Maleanime). <br> ◆ A Treasure linked to the Broken Tales has been found <br>by the Knights and is jealously guarded in a stronghold. <br> ◆ The Knights are preparing an attack on Valea Viilor, <br>with the intent of penetrating the fortified church and <br>discovering its secrets.<br> Naples <br>In this city, the Hunters will be able to track down Sherazade <br>and put an end to the threat she poses. Once the Scenario <br>is resolved, Sherazade the Weaver of Tales could become <br>a Hunter of the Order. Sherazade’s sheet is featured in the <br>expansion book The Broken Ones.<br> Nijmegen <br>Here the Hunters can meet the last druids in all of Broken <br>Europe. The druids are secretly in the service of the Dark <br>Presence Ambrose the Sorcerer, known as Merlin. The <br>druids are always ready to help the Hunters, but only <br>because they secretly try to gather information about the <br>Broken Tales to share with Merlin. <br>Some possible situations related to Nijmegen:<br> ◆ The druids ask for the Hunters’ help in driving the <br>Dark Presence Oakheart from the forest. The spirit <br>is in Nijmegen because she has fallen in love with a <br>young druid.<br> ◆ The druids ask the Hunters to capture a young novice <br>who has betrayed their order and is on his way to <br>Malbork to denounce the coven to the Teutonic <br>Knights. If the Hunters help them, the druids will reveal <br>the location of a Devil’s Bridge around Nijmegen.<br> Paris <br>In this location, the Hunters will face the Scenario The <br>Smile in the Darkness. Once the Scenario is completed, <br>Yvonne could become a Hunter of the Order. Yvonne of <br>the Dark’s sheet is featured in the expansion book The <br>Broken Ones.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":25200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241729,"modifiedTime":1783973241729,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"58fGGP3n8iSppcpO","name":"Pagina 253","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 253</h2><p>252<br> Prague<br>In this city the Hunters will face the Scenario I Will Stay <br>with You Always, available in the expansion book The <br>Broken Ones.<br> Rome<br>In the Church capital, Hunters can gather information <br>from other Hunters, receive assignments, or hire new party <br>members. Rome can also be a connection point for the <br>Clues of the Campaign and a place to return to regularly <br>to receive useful information. The Storyteller can use Rome <br>as a connecting point during the Campaign. When talking <br>with the Pope, the Hunters can learn useful information <br>and receive suggestions on what to do next.<br> Sinalunga<br>In this place, the Hunters will face the Scenario Of Flesh <br>and Wood. Once the Scenario completed, Carlo the Puppet <br>could become a Hunter of the Order. Carlo the Living <br>Puppet’s sheet is featured in the expansion book The <br>Broken Ones.<br> Stegeborg <br>In this place, the Hunters will face the Scenario Stegeborg’s <br>Quiet, available in the expansion book The Broken Ones. <br>Once the Scenario is completed, Talia the Sleeper could <br>become a Hunter of the Order. Talia the Sleeper’s sheet is <br>featured in the expansion book The Broken Ones.<br> Valea Viilor<br>In this fortified church lies the Treasury of the Order. This <br>is where the Hunters will have to return each time they <br>want to pick up a Treasure to bring on a mission. Too much <br>use of the Order’s Treasures may anger Karen. The Treasury <br>of the Order and Karen the Mannequin are featured in the <br>expansion book The Broken Ones.<br> Vigo<br>In this place, the Hunters will face the Scenario In your <br>Eyes, with your Feet, available in the expansion book The <br>Broken Ones.<br> Vík í Mýrdal<br>In this place, the Hunters will face the Scenario Hunger <br>Island, featured in the expansion book The Broken Ones.<br> Whitehaven<br>In this town, the Hunters will face the Scenario The City of <br>Pigs. Once the Scenario is completed, the Gang of Three <br>Pigs could become a Hunter of the Order. The Gang of <br>Three Pigs’ sheet is featured in the expansion book The <br>Broken Ones.<br> York <br>In this place, the Hunters will face the Scenario <br>Wonderbedlam. Once the Scenario is completed, Alice of <br>Other Worlds and Hatta Carter could become Hunters of <br>the Order. Alice of Other Worlds and Hatta Carter’s sheets <br>are featured in the expansion book The Broken Ones.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":25300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241729,"modifiedTime":1783973241729,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"csem8RIFRc49HI6d","name":"Pagina 254","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 254</h2><p>253<br> Zugarramurdi<br>In this small town, a powerful coven of witches has always <br>been hiding. Led by the sorceress Gabrina Furetta, who <br>fled from Italy after attracting too much attention from <br>the Papacy, the witches are available to provide power and <br>information. However, they always charge a price for their <br>help.<br> <br>Some possible situations related to Zugarramurdi:<br> ◆ Saint George arrives in the small town with his Paladins <br>to capture Gabrina.<br> ◆ The Hunters arrive during a magical challenge between <br>Baba Y aga and Gabrina. The two witches have a strong <br>mutual dislike (also because Baba Y aga never misses an <br>opportunity to mock her rival) and the consequences <br>of the many spells cast threaten to shed a bad light on <br>the Order.<br>Encounters<br>Encounters are Game Scenes that are outside a Scenario <br>and come into play when the Hunters move from one place <br>to another along the Map. The purpose of the Encounters <br>is to give variety to the Campaign game, highlighting the <br>stories and details of Broken Europe. <br>When the Hunters travel, based on the distance between <br>the place of departure and the place of arrival, the <br>Storyteller prepares 1 to 3 Encounters. This proportion is <br>purely subjective and only serves to give a perception of <br>distance, but it isn’t intended to be realistic. Simply put, it <br>will be clear to the Hunters that the longer a journey, the <br>more situations will arise along the way.<br>An Encounter follows the normal rules for Scenes but <br>ends when the Storyteller believes it has run its course. <br>Hunters are entitled to a Scenario’s end Interlude after each <br>Encounter. This is a good incentive for them, as Encounters <br>are a good way to earn XP without having to face the risks <br>of a full Scenario. <br>When planning the Encounters, the Storyteller can be <br>inspired by one of these 3 options:<br>Encounter with a Dark Presence<br>The Hunters stumble upon one of the Dark Presences <br>featured on page 41. Roll a die or pick from the list:<br>Ambrose the Sorcerer, known as the Old Merlin <br>1-2 The Hunters see an old, ruined tower in the mists. It is <br>the current home of Ambrose. The old wizard will welcome <br>them if they knock at his door. 3-4 A monstrous beast sows <br>panic in the square of a small village. In reality, the beast <br>was unleashed by Ambrose, curious to see the Hunters at <br>work. 5-6 Ambrose approaches the Hunters in the guise of <br>an old farmer named Kurt. The man is desperate because a <br>fairy creature destroys his crops every night. Ambrose hopes <br>the Hunters will eliminate the creature (which is actually <br>innocent and just upset by the wizard’s presence) because its <br>skin is useful for some arcane preparations.<br>Frog Face<br>1-2 Frog Face falls in love with one of the Hunters. 3-4 The <br>Hunters run into a young girl on the run. Frog Face and his <br>trusty Heinrich watch the encounter from a distance, waiting <br>to be able to retrieve their prey. 5-6 Heinrich approaches <br>the Hunters to request their services. His lord offers immense <br>riches if they manage to break a curse that hangs on him...<br>1</p>","markdown":""},"sort":25400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241729,"modifiedTime":1783973241729,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"Y1e6R4QslrjRLcRd","name":"Pagina 255","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 255</h2><p>254<br>Hua Mulan the Sword Demon  <br>1-2 The sound of a fight draws the attention of the Hunters. <br>A very skilled warrior faces more than ten brigands alone. <br>Will she need help? 3-4 Hua Mulan is on the trail of one of <br>the Hunters to avenge an injustice they inflicted to a former <br>Scenario NPC. 5-6 The Hunters find a half-dead deserter. <br>After recovering, the young man will say his name is Patrick <br>and will tell of having escaped the fury of an invincible warrior <br>who is hunting him down to punish him for his desertion. <br>Patrick will weep, saying that he was forced to enlist and that <br>he is just trying to reunite with his wife and daughter.<br>The Periwinkle Peer<br>1-2 The Peer tracks down the Hunters to challenge the most <br>skilled among them to a duel. 3-4 The Hunters meet the Peer <br>at a village celebration, and amidst music and libations, the <br>NPC will use his Gift of Divine Charm on one of the Hunters. <br>5-6 The Hunters meet Isabella, a young woman with a sad <br>look. She is a noble who has forsaken her family to follow the <br>Periwinkle Peer, who has now abandoned her for another <br>woman. If only someone would recover the necklace that <br>Isabella gave him as a promise of marriage, the young woman <br>would be free from all bonds and could return to her family.<br>The Ancient Enemy<br>1-2 A group of desperate farmers approaches the Hunters. A <br>large beast comes out every night and eats the cattle, and no <br>one is able to stop it. 3-4 The Ancient Enemy approaches the <br>Hunters in the guise of a small squirrel. He wants to observe <br>them in the next Scenario they will face, to understand if they <br>can be true allies who could save him from Saint George and <br>his Paladins. 5-6 A little girl named Sara asks the Hunters <br>to deliver a flower necklace to the “big lizard” who saved <br>her from drowning in the lake near the village. None of the <br>adults believe her story, but she would love to repay her savior. <br>Details in Sara’s description will give the Hunters the distinct <br>impression that this encounter actually happened.<br>The Wild Swans Gang<br>1-2 The Hunters arrive in a village where the church has <br>been set on fire by a group of fierce young people. Anton, the <br>parish priest, will say that there were eleven criminals and <br>that he heard them boast of their deep hatred for the papacy. <br>Now Anton fears that the gang is headed for the church in a <br>nearby village. 3-4 The Hunters stumble upon a dilapidated <br>house that everyone says is the home of a witch. Traces of <br>blood which lead into the nearby forest and disappear do not <br>bode well. 5-6 Arriving in the city, the Hunters discover that <br>another Hunter of the Order has arrived before them but has <br>mysteriously disappeared without a trace.<br>The Silent<br>1-2 The Hunters come across a traveling circus. Gustav, the <br>director, is desperate because the previous night someone <br>kidnapped Lucina, an unusual young woman with the power <br>to control insects, and someone he thinks of as a daughter. <br>Lucina has no control over her ability and now Gustav fears it <br>will cause genuine harm. 3-4 In a small village, a rumor has <br>spread that a beautiful young girl often baths in the nearby <br>river. Many bold young people went to see, but none came <br>back. 5-6 Marina the Sea Explorer contacts the Hunters via <br>a magical seagull. The bird reveals to the Hunters that, in the <br>village they are heading to, a dangerous killer with whom she <br>has unfinished business is hiding. As a reward for eliminating <br>this threat, Marina will be willing to donate one of her prized <br>treasures.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":25500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241729,"modifiedTime":1783973241729,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"teF2LU6zBotFoR1Y","name":"Pagina 256","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 256</h2><p>255<br>The Wise Fox<br>1-2 In a smallpox-stricken village, the Hunters receive a call <br>for help from the parents of a dying child. A fox spirit who has <br>often helped the village can be found in a nearby mountain <br>spring, but no one has the strength for such a difficult journey. <br>3-4 The Hunters find along their way a bag full of coins and, <br>shortly after, a poor blind man who claims to have lost them. <br>Doing the right or wrong thing will inform the Fox’s judgment <br>of the Hunters. 5-6 The Hunters find a wounded, old fox <br>being chased by a hunter named Galvan. The man will say <br>that the creature is an evil spirit and that it must die. The Fox <br>will take cover behind the Hunters.<br>Fire Eater the Puppeteer<br>1-2 Marilena, a desperate mother, runs through the town <br>streets. Her two beloved twin children, Rosa and Rosario, <br>disappeared from the bed they slept in without leaving a <br>trace. And to think that, just the night before, the family had <br>enjoyed the show of an itinerant puppeteer... 3-4 Wandering <br>around a large market, the Hunters notice a disturbing <br>puppet with a sad look that seems to be watching them. <br>5-6 The Hunters stumble upon Fire Eater’s street show and <br>realize that his amazing wireless puppets are animated by <br>dark magic.<br>The Masked Swashbuckler<br>1-2 The Hunters witness the duel between the Masked <br>Swashbuckler and a local noble, who is guilty of killing the <br>goat of a poor peasant family for fun. 3-4 The Masked <br>Swashbuckler, hired by an NPC from a past Scenario, <br>tries to assassinate one of the Hunters. 5-6 The Masked <br>Swashbuckler, drunk in the tavern, remembers the past and <br>the betrayals he suffered. If the Hunters keep him company, <br>between one slurred word and the next, the swordsman will <br>let slip a Clue about the One Who Plots in the Shadows.<br>Orcus the Guardian<br>1-2 The Hunters learn that a fearsome monster is garrisoning <br>a bridge across the river and killing anyone who doesn’t pay <br>him a toll. In reality, Orcus has settled under the bridge to live <br>far from the village and avoid doing harm. But when he went <br>out to ask for alms from a passing merchant, the situation as <br>always ended badly... and the rumor of a ferocious creature <br>guarding the bridge spread. 3-4 The Hunters arrive in <br>a square where an execution is about to take place. Orcus <br>unintentionally killed the arrogant son of the local noble <br>and was arrested. But the villagers plead for the good giant’s <br>fate, who over the years has always done his utmost to help <br>everyone. 5-6 The Hunters come across a criminal called <br>Vizzini, who keeps the Masked Swashbuckler and the gigantic <br>Orcus the Guardian in his service.<br>Goldilocks and her War Bears<br>1-2 The Hunters encounter a band of savagely slaughtered <br>mercenaries. Jacques, their leader, will tell them of a young <br>girl with three Bears who were able to hold their ground <br>alone against thirty of his men. 3-4 The Hunters encounter <br>Goldilocks while she is desperately seeking a cure for one of <br>her Bears, who has fallen ill. 5-6 The Hunters are in a tavern <br>when their waitress accidentally pours soup on a girl’s hair. <br>But the waitress’ apologies are far from enough to appease <br>Goldilocks’ ire.<br>Sinbad the Traveler of a Thousand Seas<br>1-2 In an old village tavern, Sinbad delights patrons with <br>tales of his adventures in the Far East. All his specific and <br>detailed references to magic and fantastic creatures lead <br>the Hunters to understand that Sinbad isn’t merely telling <br>tales. 3-4 The Hunters will encounter Sinbad in the palace <br>of a local noble. The Traveler boasts of having brought the <br>talented Chronicler Sherazade to Europe, and of knowing</p>","markdown":""},"sort":25600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241729,"modifiedTime":1783973241729,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"OqDsUvJMCApnaWoP","name":"Pagina 257","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 257</h2><p>256<br>which court she is gracing with her services. Sinbad is willing <br>to reveal this information, but only if someone can relieve <br>him of his boredom. 5-6 Sinbad contacts the Hunters for <br>help. He released a fire spirit out of curiosity, but now the <br>being is putting the whole region to fire and the sword. Sinbad <br>has the jar to seal the spirit away, but obviously he will want <br>to go with the Hunters himself to “lend a hand” and relieve <br>boredom.<br>Event<br>An Event is a series of Scenes that the Storyteller can <br>introduce to act as a “link” to the general plot of the <br>Campaign. These Scenes are great for:<br> ◆ Introducing opponents such as Sherazade and Saint <br>George.<br> ◆ Introducing the One Who Plots in the Shadows.<br> ◆ Letting the Hunters meet the ghost of the Child Savior.<br> ◆ Having the Hunters meet another Hunter or a <br>Dark Presence with useful information for their <br>investigation.<br>Some Events will be simple Scenes, such as meeting in an <br>inn with a Hunter to exchange information. In this case, the <br>Storyteller can take advantage of the setting to give color <br>and depth to the world of Broken Europe, and to the stories <br>of other Hunters or to Dark Presences.<br>Events with Sherazade or Saint George as protagonists, <br>on the other hand, could generate meaningful Scenarios <br>that must be resolved before the Hunters can resume their <br>journey.<br>Tackling a Hunter-specific issue <br>The Hunters encounter a situation related to one of their <br>own. Roll a die or pick from the list:<br>Baba Yaga the Child Witch<br>1-2 A witch who claims to have killed the famous Baba <br>Yaga. 3-4 A family that mistakes little Yaga for their dead <br>daughter. 5-6 A lady who knows of Morgana’s secret and of <br>Yaga and Merlin’s sins.<br>Babai the Judge<br>1-2 A corrupt judge who uses the law for personal gain. <br>3-4 A feud between two villages that has not been settled <br>for over a hundred years because no one is willing to act as a <br>judge between the parties. 5-6 An elusive murderer named <br>Mormo, who is said to walk in the shadows to escape the law.<br>Garou the Old Wolf<br>1-2 A young wolf from the North named Fenrir who wants to <br>beat the famous Garou. 3-4 An old hunter who is after the <br>trophy he most desires, the skin of the wolf that has terrified <br>humans for decades. 5-6 A ruthless brigand who uses the big <br>bad wolf as a cautionary tale to prey on the weak.<br>James the Swordsman<br>1-2 A crew of smugglers who want to avenge their captain, <br>killed in a duel. 3-4 A monstrous beast that persecutes an <br>innocent, just as it happened to James. 5-6 A famous duelist <br>who, however, wins his encounters through deceit.<br>The Astonishing Pied Piper Without a Name<br>1-2 A small village where all the animals have rebelled <br>against man. 3-4 A young apprentice who has heard the <br>2<br>3</p>","markdown":""},"sort":25700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241729,"modifiedTime":1783973241729,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"VE5q0lM6feBWgbKt","name":"Pagina 258","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 258</h2><p>257<br>Piper play and now wants him to become his teacher. 5-6 <br>The famous composer Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart has heard <br>the Pied Piper play a melody to cheer some street children <br>and now he cannot get such perfection out of his mind. The <br>musician has hired a group of bounty hunters to find the <br>Pied Piper and bring him to Salzburg so they can compose a <br>symphony together.<br>The Immortal <br>1-2 The grave of the only person the Immortal ever loved.  <br>3-4 The consequences of the Immortal’s past raids are the <br>source of daily suffering for an entire village. Is it time to <br>right the old wrongs? 5-6 A young boy who is identical to the <br>Immortal in his prime. He is in fact a homunculus created by <br>the Immortal himself and since forgotten. <br>The Woman from the Wood <br>1-2 A gang of street orphans being hunted by an avid meat <br>trader, famous for the “special” taste of some of his delicacies. <br>3-4 An old house in the woods, which is said to literally <br>devour those who enter it. 5-6 A young woman, very strong <br>and without memory, with the same physical features as the <br>Woman from the Wood.<br>Marina the Sea Explorer<br>1-2 A magical item that she absolutely needs to add to her <br>collection, but which an old nobleman does not want to let <br>go of, as it is the sole memento of his deceased wife.  3-4 A <br>child who has lost his sight and cannot be fooled by Marina’s <br>disguises. 5-6 Katrina, an old customer who wants to take <br>revenge on Marina for the gift she received, as it did not have <br>the desired effects.<br>Niklaus von Krampus <br>1-2 A young peasant woman seems to be possessed by a <br>dangerous demon, who turns out to be the brother of the one <br>trapped within Niklaus. 3-4 A devil wreaks havoc at night in <br>a terrified village, kidnapping children. 5-6 An old traveler <br>from Borgo Maleanime unlocks Krampus’ mind, letting his <br>memories pour out.<br>Regina, the Thief of Hearts<br>1-2 A prominent general whose heart Regina broke. 3-4 <br>A judge who wants Regina to stand trial for her past sins.  <br>5-6 Ace, Jack, and Spades, a group of former servants of <br>Regina who are demanding revenge for having been left for <br>the gallows. <br>Saint George the Dragon Slayer<br>1-2 Many villages live in fear of a “Dragon” who is taking <br>cattle and careless peasants. 3-4 An injustice perpetrated <br>by the Church against the peasants: a greedy priest who uses <br>his fake promises of Holy redemption to fill his belly. 5-6 A <br>Paladin in the service of George who betrayed the Church for <br>a good cause. <br>Sun Wukong the Amazing Monkey<br>1-2 The animals of a traveling circus are forced to perform <br>often deadly routines and weep at their wretched life. 3-4 A <br>raging spirit out of control awakened from a Chinese stone. <br>5-6 Angus, a survivor of Wukong’s anger when he escaped <br>from his first circus, who now wants the head of the monkey <br>warrior.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":25800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241730,"modifiedTime":1783973241730,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"iXHHfk0Fqij3r6CB","name":"Pagina 259","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 259</h2><p>258<br>Verdoux Bluebeard <br>1-2 Beatrix, Verdoux’s second wife, is not really dead, but <br>has rebuilt a life with the spy Anton, one of Bluebeard’s <br>historical enemies. The man faked Beatrix’s death to hurt his <br>rival, hiding her in an abandoned tower. Over time, however, <br>Anton fell in love with the sweetness of Beatrix, whose <br>memory was shattered by the pain of being away from her <br>beloved. 3-4 An old door in an abandoned building which, <br>apparently, no key can open. 5-6 A secret that, if revealed, <br>triggers a powerful curse, which kills whoever revealed the <br>secret within a week.<br>Yukie Onn the Traveling Artist<br>1-2 One of the brothers of Akihiro, her lost love, has come <br>to the West as part of a diplomatic mission. He was the <br>only one who never opposed the love between Yukie Onn <br>and Akihiro. Will he now hate Yukie for what she did to his <br>family? 3-4 The young lover Romeo mourns his impossible <br>love with Juliet, opposed by her parents, who do not consider <br>him worthy due to an old family feud. 5-6 A famous dancer, <br>envious of the attention that Yukie attracts, denounces her as <br>a foreign spy to the local government.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":25900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241730,"modifiedTime":1783973241730,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"DWJ6m88ldHiiUzmM","name":"Pagina 260","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 260</h2><p>259<br>Experience in a <br>Campaign game<br>During a Campaign, there are two types of Interludes that <br>significantly alter the general rules.<br>Scenario Interludes<br>They are exactly like those presented on page 11, with the <br>only exception that it is not possible to evolve a Descriptor <br>into a Specialization.<br>Scenario’s end Interlude<br>These occur automatically at the end of each Scenario <br>or after an Encounter if the Storyteller believes it was <br>important to the Campaign. Each Hunter receives 3 XP <br>for the end of the Scenario and 1 XP for an Encounter. <br>They also recover all their Soma points and remove all the <br>Wounds they suffered.<br>Y ou can spend 5 XP to get one of the following Advance-<br>ments.<br> Permanently acquire a Scenario Gift<br>The Hunter gains the Gift earned during the Scenario or <br>can purchase it now if the requirements have been met <br>during the story. Using the Gift as a starting point, they will <br>have to create a relevant Descriptor.<br> Permanently acquire an Order’s <br>Treasure<br>The Hunter gains an Order’s Treasure as a special <br>equipment. They will have to create a relevant Descriptor <br>for the Treasure.<br> Acquire a new Gift<br>The Hunter gets a new Gift related to their story, which will <br>be created with the rules on page 73. Together with the <br>Gift, they will have to create a relevant Descriptor.<br> Evolve a Descriptor into a Specialization<br>The Hunter can rewrite a Descriptor to make it more <br>effective and powerful. Once per Scene, when they bring <br>up the Descriptor in an action, they can decide to get 4 Base <br>Successes instead of 3.<br> Obtain 1 additional Wound<br>The Hunter can take 4 Wounds before being knocked out.<br> Increase the Soma value by 1<br>The Hunter receives 1 permanent Soma point. This <br>Progression can be acquired up to 3 times.<br> Have an apprentice Hunter in tow<br>After resolving an investigation, one who was an enemy <br>could become a future member of the Order. To take this <br>Advancement, an NPC encountered during a Scenario <br>must have been defeated or convinced to join the Order, <br>and there must be a corresponding Hunter Sheet. Having <br>an apprentice Hunter grants the following benefits:<br> ◆ The Player gets a second Hunter to use during Sessions. <br>At each Scene they can decide which of the two Hunters <br>will be leading, and will therefore act directly in the <br>Scene, and which will be backstage, and will therefore</p>","markdown":""},"sort":26000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241730,"modifiedTime":1783973241730,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"d3sRN3juXXNPd4pO","name":"Pagina 261","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 261</h2><p>260<br>work behind the scenes to grant bonuses.<br> ◆ The Storyteller can manage the Hunter backstage by <br>creating ad hoc Scenes for them, or by making them <br>return to “report” to the lead Hunter at the beginning <br>of the following Scene. This way, the Hunter may <br>have achieved all or part of the assigned task and the <br>Storyteller, in keeping with the narrative, will be able to <br>inflict Wounds, retrieve Soma or activate Gifts.<br> Forge a Bond with another Hunter<br>Going through the investigation together created a <br>special relationship between two Hunters. To take this <br>Advancement, the Player of the Hunter affected by the <br>Bond must agree.<br>Having a Bond with another Hunter grants the following <br>benefits:<br> ◆ Once per Scenario, a Hunter can come to the rescue of <br>their Bond wherever they are, appearing in the Scene <br>when needed most.<br> ◆ Once per Scene, a Hunter can give 1 or more Soma to <br>their Bond to help them out in a situation.<br> ◆ Once per Scene, a Hunter can take 1 Wound in place <br>of their Bond, but only if it makes sense in the story for <br>them to be able to stand between them and the threat.<br>For a two-way Bond, each affected Hunter must purchase <br>the Advancement.<br> Forge a Bond with a Dark Presence<br>A Hunter can create a special relationship with a Dark <br>Presence they have encountered on their travels. The <br>conditions for creating the Bond must be established by the <br>Player in agreement with the Storyteller. Once the Bond <br>is created, the Dark Presence will become an ally of the <br>Hunter, following them on their adventures.<br> ◆ If the Dark Presence was an Opponent or Neutral, the <br>Storyteller will have to consider whether to modify <br>some of their Gifts to make them more suitable for <br>their new role.<br> ◆ The Hunter must create a Descriptor to represent their <br>Bond with the Dark Presence. This Descriptor can be <br>brought into play during actions and marked to obtain <br>XP like all the others.<br> ◆ The Dark Presence will do their best to support the <br>Hunter, within the limits of what the Bond Descriptor <br>states. However, the NPC remains under the <br>Storyteller’s control.<br>Limitations when choosing Advancements<br>With the exception of Increase the Soma value by 1, each <br>Advancement can only be chosen once. A Hunter can never <br>have more than 4 Gifts (with the exception of those obtained <br>temporarily during a Scenario), so upon obtaining the fifth <br>Gift the Hunter must choose which one is being replaced <br>from among those they already have. The Dark Ego Gift  <br>can never be replaced in any way, but its Descriptor can be <br>evolved through a Specialization.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":26100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241730,"modifiedTime":1783973241730,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"P2WSb9LfkKSb0DdX","name":"Pagina 262","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 262</h2><p>Hunter’s Sheet<br>PLAYER:<br>Hunter:<br>Description:<br> <br> <br> <br> <br>Descriptor:<br>• Gift:<br> <br> <br> <br> <br>Descriptor:<br>• Gift:<br> <br> <br> <br> <br>Descriptor:<br>• Dark Ego:<br> <br> <br> <br> <br>ACTIVATOR:<br> Descriptors and Gifts <br> <br> Equipment <br>1.<br>2.<br>3.<br>EXTRA WOUND:<br> Wounds <br>XPSoma</p>","markdown":""},"sort":26200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241730,"modifiedTime":1783973241730,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"K4z10N5xinhZ7x7O","name":"Pagina 263","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 263</h2><p>Bookmark<br>Additional Descriptors<br>Story Gifts<br>Wounds<br>Notes<br>Soma    XP<br>Once upon a time...<br>Sheet<br> ←<br> ←<br>Additional Descriptors<br>Story Gifts<br>Wounds<br>Notes<br>Soma    XP<br>Once upon a time...<br>Sheet<br> ←<br> ←</p>","markdown":""},"sort":26300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241730,"modifiedTime":1783973241730,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"F6D4MhaZEQkBMIff","name":"Pagina 264","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 264</h2><p>Scenario Summary Sheet<br>BROKEN FAIRYTALE:<br>SAFETY KEYWORDS: <br>Keywords:<br> The story so far<br> Setting<br> The story when the Hunters arrive<br> Events &amp; Notes <br> Scenario Gifts <br>Gift:<br> <br>Gift:<br> <br>Gift:</p>","markdown":""},"sort":26400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241730,"modifiedTime":1783973241730,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"maG9DzkNxOHSWKNI","name":"Pagina 265","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 265</h2><p>NPC:   OL:              Wounds:  <br>Descriptor:<br>Agenda:<br>Gift:<br>Gift:<br> <br> NPC:   OL:              Wounds:  <br>Descriptor:<br>Agenda:<br>Gift:<br>Gift:<br> <br> NPC:<br>OL:                                                      Wounds:   <br>  <br>   <br>   <br>   <br>   <br>Descriptor:<br>Agenda:<br>Gift:<br> <br> NPC:<br>OL:                                                      Wounds:   <br>  <br>   <br>   <br>   <br>   <br>Descriptor:<br>Agenda:<br>Gift:<br> <br> NPC:<br>OL:                                                      Wounds:   <br>  <br>   <br>   <br>   <br>   <br>Descriptor:<br>Agenda:<br>Gift:<br> <br>Place:<br>Descriptor:<br>Gift:<br> <br>Other:<br>Place:<br>Descriptor:<br>Gift:<br> <br>Other:<br>Place:<br>Descriptor:<br>Gift:<br> <br>Other:<br>Place:<br>Descriptor:<br>Gift:<br> <br>Other:<br>Place:<br>Descriptor:<br>Gift:<br> <br>Other:<br>Place:<br>Descriptor:<br>Gift:<br> <br>Other:<br> Places <br> NPCs</p>","markdown":""},"sort":26500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241730,"modifiedTime":1783973241730,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"TIhkfwbgG6iTzh7i","name":"Pagina 266","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 266</h2><p>Map<br>Broken Europe<br>City<br>Settlement<br>Bridge<br>Forest<br>Naples<br>Rome<br>Paris Prague<br>London<br>York<br>Martana Island<br>Sinalunga<br>Borgo <br>Maleanime<br>Valea Viilor<br>Durfort<br>Whitehaven<br>Vík í Mýrdal<br>Borgholm<br>Stegeborg<br>Malbork<br>Lohr<br>Nijmegen<br>ZugarramurdiVigo<br>Devil's <br>Bridge<br>Black <br>Forest<br>Devil's <br>Bridge<br>Devil's <br>Bridge<br>BEAUTIFUL A SUNNY <br>DAY! THE SPELL IS BROKEN A SMALL ROAD IN THE WOODS DARK BEARD MEMORIES WHY?<br> FAIRYTALE A GENTLE CARESS A SMALL TOY SOMETHING OF VALUE</p>","markdown":""},"sort":26600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241730,"modifiedTime":1783973241730,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"k65SNwvFtsjZgYgx","name":"Pagina 267","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>bt-corebook-1-eng-final-screen-fixed - Pagina 267</h2><p>4uarto, A Smart Odyssey, a-irok, A. Choi, A. Gedeon, A. N. C. Mazor, A. Willett, Aaron Besson, Aaron D. Schneider, Aaron Sheehan, Aaron Starbird, Aaron Upchurch, Aaron Webster, Abe Scheppler, Abhishek Ray, <br>ABurrage, acolyte, Adam Burns, Adam Fisher, Adam Gerecke, Adam Jung, Adam Krump, Adam McCourt, Ad